{"title_page": "Leslie Lee (playwright)", "text_new": "'''Leslie Lee''' (1930 \u2013 January 20, 2014) was an American [[playwright]] and professor of playwriting.\n\n==Life and work==\nLeslie Lee grew up in [[West Conshohocken]], [[Pennsylvania]]. He earned a bachelor's degree from the [[University of Pennsylvania]] and a master's degree from [[Villanova University]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/23/theater/leslie-lee-playwright-of-black-life-dies-at-83.html|title=Leslie Lee, Playwright Who Enlarged Black Life Onstage, Dies at 83|date=January 22, 2014|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 23, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nLee's early theatre experience was at [[Ellen Stewart]]'s [[La MaMa Experimental Theatre Club|La Mama Experimental Theatre Club]] in the [[East Village, Manhattan]]. His play ''Elegy for a Down Queen'' was produced at La MaMa in 1970<ref>La MaMa Archives Digital Collections. [http://catalog.lamama.org/index.php/Detail/Occurrence/Show/occurrence_id/332 \"Production: ''Elegy for a Down Queen'' (1970)\"]. Retrieved May 23, 2018.</ref> and in 1972<ref>La MaMa Archives Digital Collections. [http://catalog.lamama.org/index.php/Detail/Occurrence/Show/occurrence_id/308 \"Production: ''Elegy for a Down Queen'' (1972)\"]. Retrieved May 23, 2018.</ref> by [[John Vaccaro]]'s [[Playhouse of the Ridiculous]]. ''Cops and Robbers'' was produced at La MaMa in 1971 by La MaMa GPA Nucleus Company.<ref>La MaMa Archives Digital Collections. [http://catalog.lamama.org/index.php/Detail/Occurrence/Show/occurrence_id/822 \"Production: ''Cops and Robbers'' (1971)\"]. Retrieved May 23, 2018.</ref> His play ''Love In the Eyes of Hope Dies Last'' was produced at La MaMa in 1997,<ref>La MaMa Archives Digital Collections. [http://catalog.lamama.org/index.php/Detail/Occurrence/Show/occurrence_id/3535 \"Production: ''Love, in the eyes of hope, dies last'' (1997)\"]. Retrieved May 23, 2018.</ref> and he directed [http://www.sophiamurashkovsky.com Sophia Murashkovsky]'s ''Coyote Take Me There'' at La MaMa in 1999.<ref>La MaMa Archives Digital Collections. [http://catalog.lamama.org/index.php/Detail/Occurrence/Show/occurrence_id/3537 \"Production: ''Coyote Take Me There'' (1999)\"]. Retrieved May 23, 2018.</ref>\n\nLee also worked with the [[Negro Ensemble Company]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Signature-Theatre-and-The-Negro-Ensemble-Company-to-Honor-Late-Playwright-Leslie-Lee-324-20140313|title=Signature Theatre and The Negro Ensemble Company to Honor Late Playwright Leslie Lee, 3/24|last=Desk|first=BWW News|work=BroadwayWorld.com|access-date=May 23, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHis significant work includes his [[history play]] ''Colored People's Time'', a production of which featured [[Angela Bassett]] and [[Samuel L. Jackson]], and ''Hannah Davis.'' He received   a 1975 [[Obie Award]] for Best Play, a 1976 [[Tony Award]] nomination for Best Play, and a [[Outer Critics Circle Award|Outer Circle Critics Award]] for his play ''First Breeze of Summer''.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} In 2006, the [[Negro Ensemble Company]] produced his play ''Sundown Names and Night Gone Things'', based on [[Richard Wright (author)|Richard Wright]]'s life in 1930s Chicago, featuring [[Stephen Tyrone Williams]] and [[Dewanda Wise]]. In 2008, the [[Signature Theatre Company]] produced a revival of ''First Breeze of Summer'', directed by [[Ruben Santiago-Hudson]] and starring [[Leslie Uggams]], [[Brandon J. Dirden]] and Jason Dirden, and [[Yaya DaCosta]].{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nLee's film credits include ''Almos' A Man'', an adaptation starring [[LeVar Burton]] of a [[Richard Wright (author)|Richard Wright]] story; ''[[The Killing Floor (1984 film)|The Killing Floor]],'' which won first prize at the National Black Film Consortium; and an adaptation (with Gus Edwards) of [[James Baldwin]]'s novel ''[[Go Tell It on the Mountain (film)|Go Tell It On The Mountain]],'' starring [[Paul Winfield]] and [[Rosalind Cash]].{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\n==Teaching and grants==\nLee taught playwriting at the [[State University of New York at Old Westbury|College of Old Westbury]] on [[Long Island]], [[New York University]]'s [[Tisch School of the Arts]], [[The New School]]'s [[Eugene Lang College of Liberal Arts]], and the Frederick Douglass Creative Arts Center in Manhattan. He was as a [[Artist-in-residence|playwright-in-residence]] at the [[University of Pennsylvania]], and received grants from the Shubert Foundation, the [[Rockefeller Foundation]], and the National Foundation of the Arts.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nHe received a playwriting fellowship from the [[Eugene O'Neill Theater Center]] in Connecticut.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nIn 2009, he was sponsored by a Likhachev Foundation grant to travel to [[Russia]] and complete a screenplay on [[Alexander Pushkin]].{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\n==Death and legacy==\nLee died on January 20, 2014, due to complications of [[Congestive heart failure|heart failure]]. He is survived by a brother and sisters, and several nieces and nephews.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/leslie-lee-playwright-of-the-african-american-experience-dies-at-83-com-214155|title=Leslie Lee, Playwright of the African-American Experience, Dies at 83 |website=Playbill|language=en|access-date=May 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Negro Ensemble Company]] and [[Signature Theatre Company]] held a memorial celebration of his life and work in March 2014.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.leslieleelegacy.org/menu/ Leslie Lee Legacy Foundation]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rsnTs9sRFw8 \"Remembering Leslie Lee\" (YouTube)] [[Signature Theatre Company]]\n* [http://blogs.lib.uconn.edu/archives/2016/08/15/black-experience-in-the-arts-playwright-leslie-lee/ \"Black Experience in the Arts: Playwright Leslie Lee\"] [[University of Connecticut]] Archives and Special Collections Blog \n* [http://catalog.lamama.org/index.php/Detail/Entity/Show/entity_id/962 Lee's page on La MaMa Archives Digital Collections]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lee, Leslie}}\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Villanova University alumni]]\n[[Category:Tisch School of the Arts faculty]]\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American dramatists and playwrights]]\n", "text_old": "'''Leslie Lee''' (1930 \u2013 January 20, 2014) was an American [[playwright]] and professor of playwriting.\n\n==Life and work==\nLeslie Lee grew up in [[West Conshohocken]], [[Pennsylvania]]. He earned a bachelor's degree from the [[University of Pennsylvania]] and a master's degree from [[Villanova University]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/23/theater/leslie-lee-playwright-of-black-life-dies-at-83.html|title=Leslie Lee, Playwright Who Enlarged Black Life Onstage, Dies at 83|date=January 22, 2014|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 23, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nLee's early theatre experience was at [[Ellen Stewart]]'s [[La MaMa Experimental Theatre Club|La Mama Experimental Theatre Club]] in the [[East Village, Manhattan]]. His play ''Elegy for a Down Queen'' was produced at La MaMa in 1970<ref>La MaMa Archives Digital Collections. [http://catalog.lamama.org/index.php/Detail/Occurrence/Show/occurrence_id/332 \"Production: ''Elegy for a Down Queen'' (1970)\"]. Retrieved May 23, 2018.</ref> and in 1972<ref>La MaMa Archives Digital Collections. [http://catalog.lamama.org/index.php/Detail/Occurrence/Show/occurrence_id/308 \"Production: ''Elegy for a Down Queen'' (1972)\"]. Retrieved May 23, 2018.</ref> by [[John Vaccaro]]'s [[Playhouse of the Ridiculous]]. ''Cops and Robbers'' was produced at La MaMa in 1971 by La MaMa GPA Nucleus Company.<ref>La MaMa Archives Digital Collections. [http://catalog.lamama.org/index.php/Detail/Occurrence/Show/occurrence_id/822 \"Production: ''Cops and Robbers'' (1971)\"]. Retrieved May 23, 2018.</ref> His play ''Love In the Eyes of Hope Dies Last'' was produced at La MaMa in 1997,<ref>La MaMa Archives Digital Collections. [http://catalog.lamama.org/index.php/Detail/Occurrence/Show/occurrence_id/3535 \"Production: ''Love, in the eyes of hope, dies last'' (1997)\"]. Retrieved May 23, 2018.</ref> and he directed [http://www.sophiamurashkovsky.com Sophia Murashkovsky]'s ''Coyote Take Me There'' at La MaMa in 1999.<ref>La MaMa Archives Digital Collections. [http://catalog.lamama.org/index.php/Detail/Occurrence/Show/occurrence_id/3537 \"Production: ''Coyote Take Me There'' (1999)\"]. Retrieved May 23, 2018.</ref>\n\nLee also worked with the [[Negro Ensemble Company]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Signature-Theatre-and-The-Negro-Ensemble-Company-to-Honor-Late-Playwright-Leslie-Lee-324-20140313|title=Signature Theatre and The Negro Ensemble Company to Honor Late Playwright Leslie Lee, 3/24|last=Desk|first=BWW News|work=BroadwayWorld.com|access-date=May 23, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHis significant work includes his [[history play]] ''Colored People's Time'', a production of which featured [[Angela Bassett]] and [[Samuel L. Jackson]], and ''Hannah Davis.'' He received   a 1975 [[Obie Award]] for Best Play, a 1976 [[Tony Award]] nomination for Best Play, and a [[Outer Critics Circle Award|Outer Circle Critics Award]] for his play ''First Breeze of Summer''.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} In 2006, the [[Negro Ensemble Company]] produced his play ''Sundown Names and Night Gone Things'', based on [[Richard Wright (author)|Richard Wright]]'s life in 1930s Chicago, featuring [[Stephen Tyrone Williams]] and [[Dewanda Wise]]. In 2008, the [[Signature Theatre Company]] produced a revival of ''First Breeze of Summer'', directed by [[Ruben Santiago-Hudson]] and starring [[Leslie Uggams]], [[Brandon J. Dirden]] and Jason Dirden, and [[Yaya DaCosta]].{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nLee's film credits include ''Almos' A Man'', an adaptation starring [[LeVar Burton]] of a [[Richard Wright (author)|Richard Wright]] story; ''[[The Killing Floor (1984 film)|The Killing Floor]],'' which won first prize at the National Black Film Consortium; and an adaptation (with Gus Edwards) of [[James Baldwin]]'s novel ''[[Go Tell It on the Mountain (film)|Go Tell It On The Mountain]],'' starring [[Paul Winfield]] and [[Rosalind Cash]].{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\n==Teaching and grants==\nLee taught playwriting at the [[State University of New York at Old Westbury|College of Old Westbury]] on [[Long Island]], [[New York University]]'s [[Tisch School of the Arts]], [[The New School]]'s [[Eugene Lang College of Liberal Arts]], and the Frederick Douglass Creative Arts Center in Manhattan. He was as a [[Artist-in-residence|playwright-in-residence]] at the [[University of Pennsylvania]], and received grants from the Shubert Foundation, the [[Rockefeller Foundation]], and the National Foundation of the Arts.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nHe received a playwriting fellowship from the [[Eugene O'Neill Theater Center]] in Connecticut.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nIn 2009, he was sponsored by a Likhachev Foundation grant to travel to [[Russia]] and complete a screenplay on [[Alexander Pushkin]].{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\n==Death and legacy==\nLee died on January 20, 2014 due to complications of [[Congestive heart failure|heart failure]]. He is survived by a brother and sisters, and several nieces and nephews.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/leslie-lee-playwright-of-the-african-american-experience-dies-at-83-com-214155|title=Leslie Lee, Playwright of the African-American Experience, Dies at 83 |website=Playbill|language=en|access-date=May 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Negro Ensemble Company]] and [[Signature Theatre Company]] held a memorial celebration of his life and work in March 2014.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.leslieleelegacy.org/menu/ Leslie Lee Legacy Foundation]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rsnTs9sRFw8 \"Remembering Leslie Lee\" (YouTube)] [[Signature Theatre Company]]\n* [http://blogs.lib.uconn.edu/archives/2016/08/15/black-experience-in-the-arts-playwright-leslie-lee/ \"Black Experience in the Arts: Playwright Leslie Lee\"] [[University of Connecticut]] Archives and Special Collections Blog \n* [http://catalog.lamama.org/index.php/Detail/Entity/Show/entity_id/962 Lee's page on La MaMa Archives Digital Collections]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lee, Leslie}}\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Villanova University alumni]]\n[[Category:Tisch School of the Arts faculty]]\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American dramatists and playwrights]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDeath and legacy:replaced: January 20, 2014 \u2192 January 20, 2014,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leslie_Lee_(playwright)"}
{"title_page": "Manhwa", "text_new": "{{short description|comics created in Korea}}\n{{For|Chinese comics|Manhua}}\n{{More citations needed|date=August 2019}}\n{{Expand French|Manhwa|date=January 2011}}\n[[File:Noblesse Ep. 2.png|thumb|200x200px|A scene from [[Noblesse (manhwa)|''Noblesse'']], an example of the ''manhwa'' or Korean comics]]\n{{Comics navbar}}\n{{Culture of Korea}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|title=Manhwa\n|hangul={{linktext|\ub9cc\ud654}}\n|hanja={{linktext|\u6f2b\u756b}}\n|rr=manhwa\n|mr=manhwa\n|}}\n'''Manhwa''' ([[Hangul]]: \ub9cc\ud654, [[Hanja]]: \u6f2b\u7575 {{IPA-ko|manhwa}}) is the general [[Korean language|Korean]] term for [[comics]] and print [[cartoon]]s (common usage also includes [[animated cartoon]]s). Outside Korea, the term usually refers to South Korean comics,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mangaka.co.uk/?page=manga-abc|title=Mangaka|author=|date=|website=www.mangaka.co.uk|access-date=2009-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110505174018/http://www.mangaka.co.uk/?page=manga-abc|archive-date=2011-05-05|url-status=dead}}</ref> although the comics industry is emerging in North Korea as well.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stahler|first=Kevin|url=https://piie.com/blogs/north-korea-witness-transformation/comics-north-korea|title=Comics in North Korea|publisher=[[Peterson Institute for International Economics]]|date=September 29, 2013|accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History of the term==\n[[File:Manhwa-Yu.Gil-jun-Yahak-01.jpg|thumb|160px|The first woodcut ''manhwa'', published in 1908<!--this picture will go into history section-->]]\nLinguistically, {{lang|ja|\u6f2b\u753b}} ([[manga]]), {{lang|zh|\u6f2b\u753b}} ([[manhua]]), and \ub9cc\ud654 (\u6f2b\u7575 manhwa) all mean comics in [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], and [[Korean language|Korean]] respectively. The Korean term \ub9cc\ud654 (\u6f2b\u7575 manhwa), along with the Japanese term {{lang|ja|\u6f2b\u753b}} ([[manga]]), are [[cognates]] of the Chinese phrase [[manhua]] (literally:\"impromptu sketches\").<ref>{{cite book |last=Petersen |first=Robert S. |title=Comics, Manga, and Graphic Novels: A History of Graphic Narratives |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hr7aZh6oonoC&pg=PA120 |year=2011 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |isbn=9780313363306}}</ref> The current usage of the terms \"manhwa\" and \"manhua\" in English is largely explained by the international success of the Japanese manga. Although in a traditional sense, in these languages the terms manga/manhua/manhwa had a similar meaning of comical drawing in a broad way, in English the terms manhwa and manhua generally designate the manga-inspired comic strips. \n<br>\nThe term manhwa came into popular use in Korea during the 1920s<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://professorlatinx.osu.edu/comics/manhwa/|title=Manhwa|last=Qui|first=Shelley|website=Professor LatinX|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref>, when it was applied to cartoons. Korea was under Japanese occupation from 1910 to 1945 and during this time elements of Japanese language and culture were incorporated into Korean society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.history.com/news/japan-colonization-korea|title=How Japan Took Control of Korea|last=Blakemore|first=Erin|website=HISTORY|language=en|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref> By the mid 1920s, most political newspapers were shut down<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://idp.calpoly.edu/idp/profile/cas/login?execution=e1s1|title=Cal Poly Web Login Service - Stale Request|website=idp.calpoly.edu|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref>, and political and social cartoons were abandoned in favor of children\u2019s and humorous illustrations.\n\nPolitical cartoons slowly reemerged following the establishment of the Republic of Korea (commonly known as South Korea) in 1948.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/South-Korea|title=South Korea - History|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref> During the early years of Japanese occupation, newspaper comics featured a great deal of social criticism. Popular artist Kim Yong-hwan started Korea\u2019s first comic magazine, Manhwa Haengjin, in 1948<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gftM5SjLwV8C&pg=PT402&lpg=PT402&dq=when+was+sunjeong+manhwa+made+in+south+korea&source=bl&ots=dylW7Vm_v2&sig=ACfU3U0HZROWsfJsDDEgvf2OUQsvBl8g5A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwizqNHh1anmAhVuFjQIHap9CywQ6AEwDHoECAkQAg#v=onepage&q=when%20was%20sunjeong%20manhwa%20made%20in%20south%20korea&f=false|title=Pop Goes Korea: Behind the Revolution in Movies, Music, and Internet Culture|last=Russell|first=Mark James|date=2012-10-20|publisher=Stone Bridge Press|isbn=978-1-61172-542-1|language=en}}</ref>, but it was quickly shut down because the authorities disapproved of the cover. \n\nThe popularity of comics rose during the 1950s and 1960s<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://professorlatinx.osu.edu/comics/manhwa/|title=Manhwa|last=Qui|first=Shelley|website=Professor LatinX|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref>, and the diversity of styles and subject matter led to the creation of new genres such as sunjeong (or soonjung)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gftM5SjLwV8C&pg=PT402&lpg=PT402&dq=when+was+sunjeong+manhwa+made+in+south+korea&source=bl&ots=dylW7Vm_v2&sig=ACfU3U0HZROWsfJsDDEgvf2OUQsvBl8g5A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwizqNHh1anmAhVuFjQIHap9CywQ6AEwDHoECAkQAg#v=onepage&q=when%20was%20sunjeong%20manhwa%20made%20in%20south%20korea&f=false|title=Pop Goes Korea: Behind the Revolution in Movies, Music, and Internet Culture|last=Russell|first=Mark James|date=2012-10-20|publisher=Stone Bridge Press|isbn=978-1-61172-542-1|language=en}}</ref>, romantic stories aimed at young women (equivalent to the Japanese genre [[Shoujo manga|Shoujo]]). [[Manhwabang]], [[Manga cafe|comics caf\u00e9s]] and stores that allowed readers to pay a set rate to sit and read comics, were also introduced to the public.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WcYex0sGmQ0C&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=when+were+manhwabangs+introduced+into+south+korea&source=bl&ots=uUWBsfNNj5&sig=ACfU3U2cELgvPrH4UFJbjTo4ckeWXY6IKQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi6_bP53KnmAhUPnZ4KHU04DuoQ6AEwC3oECAoQAg#v=onepage&q=when%20were%20manhwabangs%20introduced%20into%20south%20korea&f=false|title=The Rough Guide to Manga|last=Yadao|first=Jason S.|date=2009-10-01|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-1-4053-8423-0|language=en}}</ref> In response to the increasing publication of comics, as well as social and political changes within South Korea, the government began to enforce [[Censorship in South Korea|censorship laws]] and, by the mid-1960s, created a comics distribution monopoly that further censored manhwa.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SWdhAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA41&lpg=PA41&dq=park+chung+hee+and+manhwa+censorship&source=bl&ots=1EcnC-msFX&sig=ACfU3U2XPnjLlXZ3uBI-VE73iFvVXVTxKQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiH8_2116nmAhViJTQIHYNlC44Q6AEwAXoECAcQAg#v=onepage&q=park%20chung%20hee%20and%20manhwa%20censorship&f=false|title=The Korean Popular Culture Reader|last=Kim|first=Kyung Hyun|last2=Choe|first2=Youngmin|date=2014-03-07|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=978-0-8223-7756-6|language=en}}</ref>\n\nManga influenced manhwa from the medium\u2019s beginnings during the Japanese occupation of Korea and continued to exert a powerful influence as the manga industry became a major force within Japanese culture and began to export comics abroad. The author or artist of a manhwa is called a manhwaga (\ub9cc\ud654\uac00, \u6f2b\u7575\u5bb6). Manhwaga were not culturally isolated, and the influx of manga into the Korean comics market had a strong effect on the art and content of many artists\u2019 manhwa.<ref>Sugiyama, Rika. Comic Artists\u2014Asia: Manga, Manhwa, Manhua. New York: Harper, 2004. Introduces the work of comics artists in Japan, Korea, and Hong Kong through artist profiles and interviews that provide insight into their processes.\n</ref>\n\n===Adaptation of term===\nThe relative obscurity of Korean culture in the Western world has caused the word \"manhwa\" to remain somewhat unknown in the English-speaking world.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} English translations of manhwa have achieved success by targeting the manga and [[anime]] community, to the extent that manhwa were marketed as \"manga\" by the American publisher [[Tokyopop]].{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\n==Webtoons==\n{{Main article|Webtoons}}\n[[Webtoons]] first came into popularity in the early 2000s due to their free access and availability on the internet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/what-is-webtoons-2016-2|title=Millions in Korea are obsessed with these revolutionary comics \u2014 now they're going global|last=Acuna|first=Kirsten|website=Business Insider|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref> Since their creation, webtoons have gained popularity around the globe and have even been adopted outside of Korea as another form of comic publication.<ref>{{cite web|title=Webtoon, Why So Popular?|url=http://www.dgupost.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=1247|accessdate=2014-09-15}}</ref> This is credited to their unique format and pay model.\n\n==Korean manhwa publishers==\nNote: select publishers only\n\n*[[Daewon C.I.]]\n*[[Haksan Culture Company]]\n*[[Seoul Culture Corporation]]\n*[[Shinwon Agency Corporation]]\n*[[Ecomix Media Company]] / [[Netcomics]]\n\n==Manhwa in the United States==\n[[Sanho Kim]] was the first manhwa artist working in the States. During the 1960s and 70s, he worked for publishers [[Charlton Comics]], [[Warren Publishing]], Iron Horse Publishing, [[Skywald Publications]] and [[Marvel Comics]].<ref name=\"Comiclopedia\">[http://lambiek.net/artists/k/kim_san-ho.htm Kim entry], Lambiek's Comiclopedia. Accessed June 9, 2011.</ref>\n\nAccording to journalist [[Paul Gravett]], in 1987 Eastern Comics published the first original manhwas in the United States.<ref>[[Paul Gravett]]. [http://www.paulgravett.com/articles/article/make_mine_manhwa Make Mine Manhwa!: Exporting Korean Comics]</ref>\n\nDue to the explosion of manga's popularity in the Americas, many of the licensed titles acquired for the American market seek to emulate the popular elements of other successful series.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.time.com/time/columnist/arnold/article/0,9565,1152700,00.html | work=Time | title=Life and Literature Without Robots | first=Andrew D. | last=Arnold | date=2006-01-25 | accessdate=2010-05-12}}</ref> Recently, long-running webtoons serialized via [[web portal|Internet portal sites]] (e.g. by Daum Media)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cartoon.media.daum.net|title=Daum \uc6f9\ud230|author=|date=|website=Daum \uc6f9\ud230}}</ref>, like Lehzin Comics<ref>[[Lezhin Comics]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=August 2019}}, like Netcomics, and personal homepages have become both the creative and popular destination among the younger generation in Korea.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\nWith manga proving to be both popular and commercially successful in Europe and the United States, a number of publishers imported and translated manhwa titles in the hope of reaching the same audience. The readability and left-to-right orientation of manhwa contributed to its growing popularity, as did the realism of the characters and the combination of Eastern and Western styles and mythologies. Popular manhwa in the U.S. and European markets include Ragnarok, Priest, Island, and Tarot Caf\u00e9.<ref>Johnson-Woods, Toni. Manga: An Anthology of Global and Cultural Perspectives. New York: Continuum, 2010. Discusses manhwa\u2019s cultural context as well as the influence of manga on the Korean cartooning industry, focusing in particular on the 1980s and 1990s.\n</ref>\n\n===Direction of text===\nManhwa is read in the same direction as English books, horizontally and from left to right, because [[hangul]] is normally written and read horizontally, although it can also be written and read vertically from right to left, top to bottom.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n==North American manhwa imprints==\n*[[ADV Manga]]\n*[[Dark Horse Comics|Dark Horse Manhwa]]\n*[[DramaQueen]]\n*[[DrMaster Publications]]\n*[[Media Blasters]]\n*[[Netcomics]]\n*[[NBM ComicsLit]]\n*[[Seven Seas Entertainment]]\n*SuperAni\n*[[UDON's Korean Manhwa]]\n*[[Yen Press]]\n\n==Animation and live-action adaptations==\nAnimation based on Korean comics are still relatively rare (though there were several major hits in the late 1980s and early 90s with titles such as ''[[Dooly the Little Dinosaur]]'' and ''Fly! Superboard''). However, live-action drama series and movie adaptations of manhwa have occurred more frequently in recent years. ''[[Full House (2004 TV series)|Full House]]'' in 2004 and ''[[Goong (manhwa)|Goong]]'' (\"Palace\" or \"Princess Hours\") in 2006 are prominent examples, as both have been counted as the best dramas of their respective years.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}\n\nIn 2004, ''[[Blade of the Phantom Master]]'' was adapted into an animated film by a joint Korean-Japanese animation team.\n\n''SamBakZa'' produced ''[[There she is!!]]'' in 2006, which is about the developing relationship between a rabbit and a cat.\n\n''[[The Great Catsby]]'', ran as an onstage musical in 2006. In 2007, the award-winning Korean webtoon was adapted into a live-action drama. The title was also planned to be adapted into a [[feature film]] in late 2007.<ref name=\"catsby\">{{cite web|title=The Great Catsby: Hit Korean Internet Comic Drama-tized into TV form debuts in 4 days|url=http://www.clumproll.com/2007/07/01/the-great-catsby-hit-korean-internet-comic-drama-tized-into-tv-form-debuts-in-4-days/|accessdate=2007-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923194311/http://clumproll.com/2007/07/01/the-great-catsby-hit-korean-internet-comic-drama-tized-into-tv-form-debuts-in-4-days/|archive-date=2017-09-23|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n''[[War of Money]]'', a dramatized (adapted version) manhwa that aired in 2007, garnered much attention for its soundtrack and actors.\n\n''[[Priest (manhwa)|Priest]]'', a manhwa by [[Hyung Min-woo]] that has been translated to English, was adapted into the 2011 American sci-fi action horror film [[Priest (2011 film)|of the same name]] by [[Screen Gems]]. Released in 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/31084/paul-bettany-join-screen-gems-priest|title=Corrosion: Cold Winter Waiting Available for Digital Download - Dread Central|author=|date=|website=www.dreadcentral.com}}</ref> it was produced by [[Michael DeLuca]], directed by [[Scott Charles Stewart|Scott Stewart]], and stars [[Paul Bettany]] as the title character.<ref name=\"priest\">Olsen, Kevin Noel (January 25, 2007). [http://www.silverbulletcomicbooks.com/news/113822568629699.htm \"Amityville Director Set to Direct Priest Film Based on Tokypop Graphic Novel\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012181255/http://www.silverbulletcomicbooks.com/news/113822568629699.htm |date=2007-10-12 }}. Silver Bullet Comics.</ref><ref name=\"priest2\">Fischer, Martha (June 26, 2006). [http://www.cinematical.com/2006/06/26/butler-to-priest/ \"Butler to Priest\"]. Cinematical.com.</ref>\n\n''[[Secretly, Greatly]]'', a film based on a manhwa webtoon, became a top-grossing film in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ph.omg.yahoo.com/news/secretly-greatly-becomes-top-grossing-manhwa-to-film-101400409.html|title=Celebrity - Yahoo Lifestyle Singapore|author=|date=|website=ph.omg.yahoo.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://twitchfilm.com/2013/06/korean-box-office-not-so-secret-secretly-greatly-break-records.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-06-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304074735/http://twitchfilm.com/2013/06/korean-box-office-not-so-secret-secretly-greatly-break-records.html |archive-date=2016-03-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2013/06/10/2013061001331.html|title='Secretly Greatly' Blazes Trail at Box Office by Tapping Teen Audience|author=|date=|website=chosun.com}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of manhwa]]\n*[[Sunjung manhwa]]\n*[[Myeongnang manhwa]]\n*[[Manhwabang]]\n*[[Culture of South Korea]]\n*[[Korean Wave]]\n*[[Korean animation]]\n*[[Webtoon]]\n*[[Video gaming in South Korea]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{cite book|title=\ud55c\uad6d\ub9cc\ud654\ud1b5\uc0ac 1 (General History of Manwha 1) |author=Son Sang-ik |isbn=89-7259-890-9 |publisher=Sigongsa |year=1999 |language=Korean}}\n*{{cite book |last=Hart|first=Christopher|authorlink=Christopher Hart (artist)|title=Manhwa mania : how to draw Korean comics|year=2004|publisher=Watson-Guptill Publications|location=New York|isbn=0-8230-2976-X}}\n*{{cite web|title=\uac1c\ud654\uae30 \uc77c\uc81c\uc758 \uc2dc\uc0ac\ub9cc\ud654 \ud0c4\uc555 (The Japanese oppression on Sisa manhwa)|author=Kim Jinsu |url=http://www.chammalo.com/sub_read.html?uid=7283&section=section3&section2= |language=Korean |publisher=Chammalo |date=2007-06-02}}\n*{{cite web|script-title=ko:\ub9cc\ud654 |url=http://100.empas.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?i=136069#T3 |publisher=[[Empas]]/ [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]] |language=Korean }}\n*{{cite web|title=Manhwa |url=http://100.empas.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=284131&v=46 |publisher=Empas/ [[EncyKorea]] |language=Korean }}\n*{{cite web|title=Korea Manhwa Museum |author=Sim Ji-hoon |work=INISteel Webzine |url=http://www.inisteel.com/news/webzine/200401/webzine_iniinfromation01.html |publisher= |language=Korean }}\n*{{cite book |last=Sugiyama|first=Rika|title=Comic artists \u2014 Asia : manga, manhwa, manhua|year=2004|publisher=Harper Design International|location=New York|isbn=0-06-058924-8}}\n\n*[http://www.katavila.com/articles/jade/manhwa-p1.pdf \"Korean Comics in the U.S., Part 1, Comic-Con International 2004,\"] Jade Magazine.com, Sep. 2004\n*[http://www.katavila.com/articles/jade/manhwa-p2.pdf \"Korean Comics in the U.S., Part 2, Manhwa Sampler,\"] Jade Magazine.com, Sep. 2004\n*[http://www.sequentialtart.com/archive/aug04/art_0804_6.shtml \"Sang-Sun Park, ''Les Bijoux'' Comic Artist,\"] Sequential Tart.com, Aug. 2004\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060409171130/http://demon.mireene.com/ Manhwa site for \"Demon Diary\" (\ub9c8\uc655\uc77c\uae30)]\n*[http://www.katavila.com/articles/anime-tourist/infinity-studios.pdf \"Infinity Studios and Manhwa,\"] Anime Tourist.com, 16 June 2004\n*[http://www.koreasociety.org/dmdocuments/2008-3-25-park-taekwonv.mp3 Our Toys, Our Selves: Robot Taekwon V and South Korean Identity]\n*Cain, Geoffrey. [http://www.feer.com/jaunt-through-asia/2009/november51/will-the-internet-kill-the-manhwa-star \"Will the Internet Kill the Manhwa Star?\"] ''[[Far Eastern Economic Review|The Far Eastern Economic Review]]'', November 6, 2009\n\n===Popular manhwa artists===\n*[http://hyung-taekim.org Hyung-tae Kim]\n*[https://www.kimjunggi-shop.net Kim Jung-Gi]\n\n===Festivals===\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051123103107/http://www.cartooncity.co.kr/eng/index.aspx Bucheon Manhwa Information Center]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050308184814/http://www.bicof.com/2004/index.asp Bucheon International Manhwa festival]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20010331144344/http://www.sicaf.or.kr/ Seoul International Comics and Animation Festival]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051106033810/http://difeca.donga.com/ Dong-a/LG International festival of comics and animation]\n\n===Manhwa on mobiles===\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070313145428/http://www.moonk.co.kr/ Moonk Mobile Cartoon]\n\n===Associations===\n*[http://www.urimana.com/ Cartoon & Animation Society in Korea]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/19991129023829/http://www.cartoonpia.co.kr/ Seoul Cartoon]\n*[http://www.cartoon.or.kr/ The Korean Cartoonist Association]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051118031535/http://www.kwca.or.kr/ Korean Women Cartoonist Association]\n*[http://www.aca2000.com/ Amateur Comics Association]\n*[http://www.kacl.co.kr/ Korea Amateur Comic Land]\n\n===Information and studies===\n*[http://www.koscas.or.kr/ Korean Society of Cartoon & Animation Studies]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111009082216/http://www.ani.seoul.kr/eng/ Seoul Animation Center]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051106005532/http://cartooncity.co.kr/ Puchon Cartoon Information Center]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070107021256/http://www.koreasociety.org/content/view/88/39/ The Korea Society Manhwa Exhibit]\n\n{{Comics}}\n\n[[Category:Manhwa| ]]\n[[Category:South Korean manhwa| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|comics created in Korea}}\n{{For|Chinese comics|Manhua}}\n{{More citations needed|date=August 2019}}\n{{Expand French|Manhwa|date=January 2011}}\n[[File:Noblesse Ep. 2.png|thumb|200x200px|A scene from [[Noblesse (manhwa)|''Noblesse'']], an example of the ''manhwa'' or Korean comics]]\n{{Comics navbar}}\n{{Culture of Korea}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|title=Manhwa\n|hangul={{linktext|\ub9cc\ud654}}\n|hanja={{linktext|\u6f2b\u756b}}\n|rr=manhwa\n|mr=manhwa\n|}}\n'''Manhwa''' ([[Hangul]]: \ub9cc\ud654, [[Hanja]]: \u6f2b\u7575 {{IPA-ko|manhwa}}) is the general [[Korean language|Korean]] term for [[comics]] and print [[cartoon]]s (common usage also includes [[animated cartoon]]s). Outside Korea, the term usually refers to South Korean comics,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mangaka.co.uk/?page=manga-abc|title=Mangaka|author=|date=|website=www.mangaka.co.uk|access-date=2009-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110505174018/http://www.mangaka.co.uk/?page=manga-abc|archive-date=2011-05-05|url-status=dead}}</ref> although the comics industry is emerging in North Korea as well.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stahler|first=Kevin|url=https://piie.com/blogs/north-korea-witness-transformation/comics-north-korea|title=Comics in North Korea|publisher=[[Peterson Institute for International Economics]]|date=September 29, 2013|accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History of the term==\n[[File:Manhwa-Yu.Gil-jun-Yahak-01.jpg|thumb|160px|The first woodcut ''manhwa'', published in 1908<!--this picture will go into history section-->]]\nLinguistically, {{lang|ja|\u6f2b\u753b}} ([[manga]]), {{lang|zh|\u6f2b\u753b}} ([[manhua]]), and \ub9cc\ud654 (\u6f2b\u7575 manhwa) all mean comics in [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], and [[Korean language|Korean]] respectively. The Korean term \ub9cc\ud654 (\u6f2b\u7575 manhwa), along with the Japanese term {{lang|ja|\u6f2b\u753b}} ([[manga]]), are [[cognates]] of the Chinese phrase [[manhua]] (literally:\"impromptu sketches\").<ref>{{cite book |last=Petersen |first=Robert S. |title=Comics, Manga, and Graphic Novels: A History of Graphic Narratives |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hr7aZh6oonoC&pg=PA120 |year=2011 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |isbn=9780313363306}}</ref> The current usage of the terms \"manhwa\" and \"manhua\" in English is largely explained by the international success of the Japanese manga. Although in a traditional sense, in these languages the terms manga/manhua/manhwa had a similar meaning of comical drawing in a broad way, in English the terms manhwa and manhua generally designate the manga-inspired comic strips. \n<br>\nThe term manhwa came into popular use in Korea during the 1920s<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://professorlatinx.osu.edu/comics/manhwa/|title=Manhwa|last=Qui|first=Shelley|website=Professor LatinX|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref>, when it was applied to cartoons. Korea was under Japanese occupation from 1910 to 1945 and during this time elements of Japanese language and culture were incorporated into Korean society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.history.com/news/japan-colonization-korea|title=How Japan Took Control of Korea|last=Blakemore|first=Erin|website=HISTORY|language=en|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref> By the mid 1920s, most political newspapers were shut down<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://idp.calpoly.edu/idp/profile/cas/login?execution=e1s1|title=Cal Poly Web Login Service - Stale Request|website=idp.calpoly.edu|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref>, and political and social cartoons were abandoned in favor of children\u2019s and humorous illustrations.\n\nPolitical cartoons slowly reemerged following the establishment of the Republic of Korea (commonly known as South Korea) in 1948.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/South-Korea|title=South Korea - History|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref> During the early years of Japanese occupation, newspaper comics featured a great deal of social criticism. Popular artist Kim Yong-hwan started Korea\u2019s first comic magazine, Manhwa Haengjin, in 1948<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gftM5SjLwV8C&pg=PT402&lpg=PT402&dq=when+was+sunjeong+manhwa+made+in+south+korea&source=bl&ots=dylW7Vm_v2&sig=ACfU3U0HZROWsfJsDDEgvf2OUQsvBl8g5A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwizqNHh1anmAhVuFjQIHap9CywQ6AEwDHoECAkQAg#v=onepage&q=when%20was%20sunjeong%20manhwa%20made%20in%20south%20korea&f=false|title=Pop Goes Korea: Behind the Revolution in Movies, Music, and Internet Culture|last=Russell|first=Mark James|date=2012-10-20|publisher=Stone Bridge Press|isbn=978-1-61172-542-1|language=en}}</ref>, but it was quickly shut down because the authorities disapproved of the cover. \n\nThe popularity of comics rose during the 1950s and 1960s<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://professorlatinx.osu.edu/comics/manhwa/|title=Manhwa|last=Qui|first=Shelley|website=Professor LatinX|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref>, and the diversity of styles and subject matter led to the creation of new genres such as sunjeong (or soonjung)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gftM5SjLwV8C&pg=PT402&lpg=PT402&dq=when+was+sunjeong+manhwa+made+in+south+korea&source=bl&ots=dylW7Vm_v2&sig=ACfU3U0HZROWsfJsDDEgvf2OUQsvBl8g5A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwizqNHh1anmAhVuFjQIHap9CywQ6AEwDHoECAkQAg#v=onepage&q=when%20was%20sunjeong%20manhwa%20made%20in%20south%20korea&f=false|title=Pop Goes Korea: Behind the Revolution in Movies, Music, and Internet Culture|last=Russell|first=Mark James|date=2012-10-20|publisher=Stone Bridge Press|isbn=978-1-61172-542-1|language=en}}</ref>, romantic stories aimed at young women (equivalent to the Japanese genre [[Shoujo manga|Shoujo]]). [[Manhwabang]], [[Manga cafe|comics caf\u00e9s]] and stores that allowed readers to pay a set rate to sit and read comics, were also introduced to the public.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WcYex0sGmQ0C&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=when+were+manhwabangs+introduced+into+south+korea&source=bl&ots=uUWBsfNNj5&sig=ACfU3U2cELgvPrH4UFJbjTo4ckeWXY6IKQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi6_bP53KnmAhUPnZ4KHU04DuoQ6AEwC3oECAoQAg#v=onepage&q=when%20were%20manhwabangs%20introduced%20into%20south%20korea&f=false|title=The Rough Guide to Manga|last=Yadao|first=Jason S.|date=2009-10-01|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-1-4053-8423-0|language=en}}</ref> In response to the increasing publication of comics, as well as social and political changes within South Korea, the government began to enforce [[Censorship in South Korea|censorship laws]] and, by the mid-1960s, created a comics distribution monopoly that further censored manhwa.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SWdhAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA41&lpg=PA41&dq=park+chung+hee+and+manhwa+censorship&source=bl&ots=1EcnC-msFX&sig=ACfU3U2XPnjLlXZ3uBI-VE73iFvVXVTxKQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiH8_2116nmAhViJTQIHYNlC44Q6AEwAXoECAcQAg#v=onepage&q=park%20chung%20hee%20and%20manhwa%20censorship&f=false|title=The Korean Popular Culture Reader|last=Kim|first=Kyung Hyun|last2=Choe|first2=Youngmin|date=2014-03-07|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=978-0-8223-7756-6|language=en}}</ref>\n\nManga influenced manhwa from the medium\u2019s beginnings during the Japanese occupation of Korea and continued to exert a powerful influence as the manga industry became a major force within Japanese culture and began to export comics abroad. The author or artist of a manhwa is called a manhwaga (\ub9cc\ud654\uac00, \u6f2b\u7575\u5bb6). Manhwaga were not culturally isolated, and the influx of manga into the Korean comics market had a strong effect on the art and content of many artists\u2019 manhwa.<ref>Sugiyama, Rika. Comic Artists\u2014Asia: Manga, Manhwa, Manhua. New York: Harper, 2004. Introduces the work of comics artists in Japan, Korea, and Hong Kong through artist profiles and interviews that provide insight into their processes.\n</ref>\n\n===Adaptation of term===\nThe relative obscurity of Korean culture in the Western world has caused the word \"manhwa\" to remain somewhat unknown in the English-speaking world.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} English translations of manhwa have achieved success by targeting the manga and [[anime]] community, to the extent that manhwa were marketed as \"manga\" by the American publisher [[Tokyopop]].{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\n==Webtoons==\n{{Main article|Webtoons}}\n[[Webtoons]] first came into popularity in the early 2000s due to their free access and availability on the internet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/what-is-webtoons-2016-2|title=Millions in Korea are obsessed with these revolutionary comics \u2014 now they're going global|last=Acuna|first=Kirsten|website=Business Insider|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref> Since their creation, webtoons have gained popularity around the globe and have even been adopted outside of Korea as another form of comic publication.<ref>{{cite web|title=Webtoon, Why So Popular?|url=http://www.dgupost.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=1247|accessdate=2014-09-15}}</ref> This is credited to their unique format and pay model.\n\n==Korean manhwa publishers==\nNote: select publishers only\n\n*[[Daewon C.I.]]\n*[[Haksan Culture Company]]\n*[[Seoul Culture Corporation]]\n*[[Shinwon Agency Corporation]]\n*[[Ecomix Media Company]] / [[Netcomics]]\n\n==Manhwa in the United States==\n[[Sanho Kim]] was the first manhwa artist working in the States. During the 1960s and 70s, he worked for publishers [[Charlton Comics]], [[Warren Publishing]], Iron Horse Publishing, [[Skywald Publications]] and [[Marvel Comics]].<ref name=\"Comiclopedia\">[http://lambiek.net/artists/k/kim_san-ho.htm Kim entry], Lambiek's Comiclopedia. Accessed June 9, 2011.</ref>\n\nAccording to journalist [[Paul Gravett]], in 1987 Eastern Comics published the first original manhwas in the United States.<ref>[[Paul Gravett]]. [http://www.paulgravett.com/articles/article/make_mine_manhwa Make Mine Manhwa!: Exporting Korean Comics]</ref>\n\nDue to the explosion of manga's popularity in the Americas, many of the licensed titles acquired for the American market seek to emulate the popular elements of other successful series.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.time.com/time/columnist/arnold/article/0,9565,1152700,00.html | work=Time | title=Life and Literature Without Robots | first=Andrew D. | last=Arnold | date=2006-01-25 | accessdate=2010-05-12}}</ref> Recently, long-running webtoons serialized via [[web portal|Internet portal sites]] (e.g. by Daum Media)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cartoon.media.daum.net|title=Daum \uc6f9\ud230|author=|date=|website=Daum \uc6f9\ud230}}</ref>, like Lehzin Comics<ref>[[Lezhin Comics]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=August 2019}}, and personal homepages have become both the creative and popular destination among the younger generation in Korea.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\nWith manga proving to be both popular and commercially successful in Europe and the United States, a number of publishers imported and translated manhwa titles in the hope of reaching the same audience. The readability and left-to-right orientation of manhwa contributed to its growing popularity, as did the realism of the characters and the combination of Eastern and Western styles and mythologies. Popular manhwa in the U.S. and European markets include Ragnarok, Priest, Island, and Tarot Caf\u00e9.<ref>Johnson-Woods, Toni. Manga: An Anthology of Global and Cultural Perspectives. New York: Continuum, 2010. Discusses manhwa\u2019s cultural context as well as the influence of manga on the Korean cartooning industry, focusing in particular on the 1980s and 1990s.\n</ref>\n\n===Direction of text===\nManhwa is read in the same direction as English books, horizontally and from left to right, because [[hangul]] is normally written and read horizontally, although it can also be written and read vertically from right to left, top to bottom.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n==North American manhwa imprints==\n*[[ADV Manga]]\n*[[Dark Horse Comics|Dark Horse Manhwa]]\n*[[DramaQueen]]\n*[[DrMaster Publications]]\n*[[Media Blasters]]\n*[[Netcomics]]\n*[[NBM ComicsLit]]\n*[[Seven Seas Entertainment]]\n*SuperAni\n*[[UDON's Korean Manhwa]]\n*[[Yen Press]]\n\n==Animation and live-action adaptations==\nAnimation based on Korean comics are still relatively rare (though there were several major hits in the late 1980s and early 90s with titles such as ''[[Dooly the Little Dinosaur]]'' and ''Fly! Superboard''). However, live-action drama series and movie adaptations of manhwa have occurred more frequently in recent years. ''[[Full House (2004 TV series)|Full House]]'' in 2004 and ''[[Goong (manhwa)|Goong]]'' (\"Palace\" or \"Princess Hours\") in 2006 are prominent examples, as both have been counted as the best dramas of their respective years.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}\n\nIn 2004, ''[[Blade of the Phantom Master]]'' was adapted into an animated film by a joint Korean-Japanese animation team.\n\n''SamBakZa'' produced ''[[There she is!!]]'' in 2006, which is about the developing relationship between a rabbit and a cat.\n\n''[[The Great Catsby]]'', ran as an onstage musical in 2006. In 2007, the award-winning Korean webtoon was adapted into a live-action drama. The title was also planned to be adapted into a [[feature film]] in late 2007.<ref name=\"catsby\">{{cite web|title=The Great Catsby: Hit Korean Internet Comic Drama-tized into TV form debuts in 4 days|url=http://www.clumproll.com/2007/07/01/the-great-catsby-hit-korean-internet-comic-drama-tized-into-tv-form-debuts-in-4-days/|accessdate=2007-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923194311/http://clumproll.com/2007/07/01/the-great-catsby-hit-korean-internet-comic-drama-tized-into-tv-form-debuts-in-4-days/|archive-date=2017-09-23|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n''[[War of Money]]'', a dramatized (adapted version) manhwa that aired in 2007, garnered much attention for its soundtrack and actors.\n\n''[[Priest (manhwa)|Priest]]'', a manhwa by [[Hyung Min-woo]] that has been translated to English, was adapted into the 2011 American sci-fi action horror film [[Priest (2011 film)|of the same name]] by [[Screen Gems]]. Released in 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/31084/paul-bettany-join-screen-gems-priest|title=Corrosion: Cold Winter Waiting Available for Digital Download - Dread Central|author=|date=|website=www.dreadcentral.com}}</ref> it was produced by [[Michael DeLuca]], directed by [[Scott Charles Stewart|Scott Stewart]], and stars [[Paul Bettany]] as the title character.<ref name=\"priest\">Olsen, Kevin Noel (January 25, 2007). [http://www.silverbulletcomicbooks.com/news/113822568629699.htm \"Amityville Director Set to Direct Priest Film Based on Tokypop Graphic Novel\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012181255/http://www.silverbulletcomicbooks.com/news/113822568629699.htm |date=2007-10-12 }}. Silver Bullet Comics.</ref><ref name=\"priest2\">Fischer, Martha (June 26, 2006). [http://www.cinematical.com/2006/06/26/butler-to-priest/ \"Butler to Priest\"]. Cinematical.com.</ref>\n\n''[[Secretly, Greatly]]'', a film based on a manhwa webtoon, became a top-grossing film in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ph.omg.yahoo.com/news/secretly-greatly-becomes-top-grossing-manhwa-to-film-101400409.html|title=Celebrity - Yahoo Lifestyle Singapore|author=|date=|website=ph.omg.yahoo.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://twitchfilm.com/2013/06/korean-box-office-not-so-secret-secretly-greatly-break-records.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-06-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304074735/http://twitchfilm.com/2013/06/korean-box-office-not-so-secret-secretly-greatly-break-records.html |archive-date=2016-03-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2013/06/10/2013061001331.html|title='Secretly Greatly' Blazes Trail at Box Office by Tapping Teen Audience|author=|date=|website=chosun.com}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of manhwa]]\n*[[Sunjung manhwa]]\n*[[Myeongnang manhwa]]\n*[[Manhwabang]]\n*[[Culture of South Korea]]\n*[[Korean Wave]]\n*[[Korean animation]]\n*[[Webtoon]]\n*[[Video gaming in South Korea]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{cite book|title=\ud55c\uad6d\ub9cc\ud654\ud1b5\uc0ac 1 (General History of Manwha 1) |author=Son Sang-ik |isbn=89-7259-890-9 |publisher=Sigongsa |year=1999 |language=Korean}}\n*{{cite book |last=Hart|first=Christopher|authorlink=Christopher Hart (artist)|title=Manhwa mania : how to draw Korean comics|year=2004|publisher=Watson-Guptill Publications|location=New York|isbn=0-8230-2976-X}}\n*{{cite web|title=\uac1c\ud654\uae30 \uc77c\uc81c\uc758 \uc2dc\uc0ac\ub9cc\ud654 \ud0c4\uc555 (The Japanese oppression on Sisa manhwa)|author=Kim Jinsu |url=http://www.chammalo.com/sub_read.html?uid=7283&section=section3&section2= |language=Korean |publisher=Chammalo |date=2007-06-02}}\n*{{cite web|script-title=ko:\ub9cc\ud654 |url=http://100.empas.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?i=136069#T3 |publisher=[[Empas]]/ [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]] |language=Korean }}\n*{{cite web|title=Manhwa |url=http://100.empas.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=K&i=284131&v=46 |publisher=Empas/ [[EncyKorea]] |language=Korean }}\n*{{cite web|title=Korea Manhwa Museum |author=Sim Ji-hoon |work=INISteel Webzine |url=http://www.inisteel.com/news/webzine/200401/webzine_iniinfromation01.html |publisher= |language=Korean 