.co.kr/ Moonk Mobile Cartoon]\n\n===Associations===\n*[http://www.urimana.com/ Cartoon & Animation Society in Korea]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/19991129023829/http://www.cartoonpia.co.kr/ Seoul Cartoon]\n*[http://www.cartoon.or.kr/ The Korean Cartoonist Association]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051118031535/http://www.kwca.or.kr/ Korean Women Cartoonist Association]\n*[http://www.aca2000.com/ Amateur Comics Association]\n*[http://www.kacl.co.kr/ Korea Amateur Comic Land]\n\n===Information and studies===\n*[http://www.koscas.or.kr/ Korean Society of Cartoon & Animation Studies]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111009082216/http://www.ani.seoul.kr/eng/ Seoul Animation Center]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051106005532/http://cartooncity.co.kr/ Puchon Cartoon Information Center]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070107021256/http://www.koreasociety.org/content/view/88/39/ The Korea Society Manhwa Exhibit]\n\n{{Comics}}\n\n[[Category:Manhwa| ]]\n[[Category:South Korean manhwa| ]]\n", "name_user": "Maria97531", "label": "safe", "comment": "Netcomics was missing as a manhwa publisher in the U.S. and was added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manhwa"}
{"title_page": "George Harcourt Vanden-Bampde-Johnstone, 3rd Baron Derwent", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n[[File:George Harcourt Johnstone.jpg|thumb|right|Baron Derwent]]\n'''George Harcourt Vanden-Bampde-Johnstone, 3rd Baron Derwent''' (22 October 1899 \u2013 13 January 1949), was a [[United Kingdom|British]] author, diplomat and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician.\n\n==Early life==\nDerwent was born in [[London]] on 22 October 1899, the son of Hon. Edward Henry Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone, younger son of [[Harcourt Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone, 1st Baron Derwent]].<ref name=\"obit\" /> Derwent was educated at [[Charterhouse School|Charterhouse]] and [[Merton College, Oxford]] where he won the [[Newdigate Prize]] in 1920.<ref name=\"obit\" /><ref name=\"MCreg\">{{cite book|editor1-last=Levens|editor1-first=R.G.C.|title=Merton College Register 1900-1964|date=1964|publisher=Basil Blackwell|location=Oxford|page=113}}</ref> He succeeded as the third Baron Derwent on the death of his uncle in 1929.<ref name=\"obit\" />\n\n==Diplomatic and war service==\nOn leaving Merton he joined the diplomatic service and served as an honorary attach\u00e9 from 1929 at Warsaw, Brussels and Madrid. At the start of the Second World War he was in Berne before he returned to the United Kingdom in 1942 to serve in the [[Royal Air Force]] until 1944.<ref name=\"obit\" /><ref name=\"MCreg\" />\n\n==Author and poet==\nAs an author and poet Derwent wrote under his own name but also the pen name ''George Vanden''.<ref name=\"obit\" /> Two volumes of poetry were published in 1931 (''Fifty Poems'') and 1943 (''Before Zero Hour'').<ref name=\"obit\" />\n\n==Politician==\nDerwent was a [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] party politician and president of the Yorkshire Liberal Federation.<ref name=\"obit\" />\n\n==Family life==\nDerwent married Countess Sabine Czaykowska Iliesco in 1929, the daughter of Romanian General Iliesco.<ref name=\"peerage\" /> She died in 1941 and they had no children so when Derwent died aged 49 in Paris on his way back from a health visit to Switzerland, he was succeeded by his younger brother [[Patrick Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone, 4th Baron Derwent|Patrick]].<ref name=\"obit\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"obit\">\n{{Cite newspaper The Times\n|articlename=  Lord Derwent\n|section=Obituaries\n|day_of_week=Friday\n|date=14 January 1949\n|page_number=7\n|issue=51279\n|column=E\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"peerage\">[http://thepeerage.com/p7189.htm#i71890 thepeerage.com]</ref>\n}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Baron Derwent]] | before= [[Francis Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone, 2nd Baron Derwent|Francis Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone]] | after=[[Patrick Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone, 4th Baron Derwent|Patrick Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone]] | years=1929\u20131949 }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Derwent, George Harcourt Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone, 3rd Baron}}\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:1949 deaths]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Charterhouse School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Merton College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic peers]]\n[[Category:British diplomats]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) hereditary peers]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:English male poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century English poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n[[File:George Harcourt Johnstone.jpg|thumb|right|Baron Derwent]]\n'''George Harcourt Vanden-Bampde-Johnstone, 3rd Baron Derwent''' (22 October 1899 \u2013 13 January 1949), was a [[United Kingdom|British]] author, diplomat and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician.\n\n==Early life==\nDerwent was born in [[London]] on 22 October 1899, the son of Hon. Edward Henry Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone, younger son of [[Harcourt Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone, 1st Baron Derwent]].<ref name=\"obit\" /> Derwent was educated at [[Charterhouse School|Charterhouse]] and [[Merton College, Oxford]] where he won the [[Newdigate Prize]] in 1920.<ref name=\"obit\" /><ref name=\"MCreg\">{{cite book|editor1-last=Levens|editor1-first=R.G.C.|title=Merton College Register 1900-1964|date=1964|publisher=Basil Blackwell|location=Oxford|page=113}}</ref> He succeeded as the third Baron Derwent on the death of his uncle in 1929.<ref name=\"obit\" />\n\n==Diplomatic and war service==\nOn leaving Merton he joined the diplomatic service and served as an honorary attach\u00e9 from 1929 at Warsaw, Brussels and Madrid. At the start of the Second World War he was in Berne before he returned to the United Kingdom in 1942 to serve in the [[Royal Air Force]] until 1944.<ref name=\"obit\" /><ref name=\"MCreg\" />\n\n==Author and poet==\nAs an author and poet Derwent wrote under his own name but also the pen name ''George Vanden''.<ref name=\"obit\" /> Two volumes of poetry were published in 1931 (''Fifty Poems'') and 1943 (''Before Zero Hour'').<ref name=\"obit\" />\n\n==Politician==\nDerwent was a [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] party politician and president of the Yorkshire Liberal Federation.<ref name=\"obit\" />\n\n==Family Life==\nDerwent married Countess Sabine Czaykowska Iliesco in 1929, the daughter of Romanian General Iliesco.<ref name=\"peerage\" /> She died in 1941 and they had no children so when Derwent died aged 49 in Paris on his way back from a health visit to Switzerland, he was succeeded by his younger brother [[Patrick Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone, 4th Baron Derwent|Patrick]].<ref name=\"obit\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"obit\">\n{{Cite newspaper The Times\n|articlename=  Lord Derwent\n|section=Obituaries\n|day_of_week=Friday\n|date=14 January 1949\n|page_number=7\n|issue=51279\n|column=E\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"peerage\">[http://thepeerage.com/p7189.htm#i71890 thepeerage.com]</ref>\n}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Baron Derwent]] | before= [[Francis Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone, 2nd Baron Derwent|Francis Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone]] | after=[[Patrick Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone, 4th Baron Derwent|Patrick Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone]] | years=1929\u20131949 }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Derwent, George Harcourt Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone, 3rd Baron}}\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:1949 deaths]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Charterhouse School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Merton College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic peers]]\n[[Category:British diplomats]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) hereditary peers]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:English male poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century English poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Alpinu", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFamily Life:\u2192 Family life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Harcourt_Vanden-Bampde-Johnstone,_3rd_Baron_Derwent"}
{"title_page": "Disappearance of Don Lewis", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Disappearance of Don Lewis\n| image = Don Lewis disappearance portrait.jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption =\n| birth_name = Jack Donald Lewis\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1938|4|30|df=yes}}\n| birth_place =[[Dade City, Florida|Dade City]], [[Florida]], U.S.\n| other_names = Bob Martinez<ref name=\"Charley\">{{cite web|url=http://charleyproject.org/case/jack-donald-lewis|title=Jack Donald Lewis \u2013 The Charley Project|accessdate=April 1, 2020|date=September 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927192040/http://charleyproject.org/case/jack-donald-lewis|archive-date=September 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| death_date = August 18, 2002 ([[legal death]])\n| disappeared_date = {{Disappeared date and age|df=yes|1997|8|18|1938|4|30}}\n| disappeared_place =[[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], Florida, U.S.\n| disappeared_status = {{Missing for|1997|8|18}}\n| spouse             = {{Plainlist|\n* Gladys Lewis Cross<br />({{abbr|div.|divorce}} 1990)\n* {{marriage|[[Carole Baskin]]|1991|2002|end={{abbr|legal d.|legal death}}}}}}\n| children           = 4\n}}\n\n'''Jack Donald Lewis''' (April 30, 1938 \u2013 {{abbr|legal d.|legal death}} August 18, 2002) disappeared on August 18, 1997, after leaving his home in [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], [[Florida]], United States.<ref name=\"WTSP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/extras/disappearance-on-easy-street/67-396338130|title=Disappearance on Easy Street|website=WTSP|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The investigation into his disappearance has stretched from Lewis' [[Big Cat Rescue]] sanctuary in Tampa, co-owned by his second wife [[Carole Baskin]], to land owned by Lewis in [[Costa Rica]]. No evidence of Lewis being killed has surfaced, and investigators believe that it is unlikely that he disappeared on his own. Lewis was declared [[legal death|legally dead]] in 2002. As of 2020, the case is still open. Lewis' disappearance was covered in 2020 crime documentary series ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', which focused on a feud between Baskin and private zoo owner [[Joe Exotic]].\n\n==Background==\nDon Lewis was a native of [[Dade City, Florida|Dade City]], [[Florida]], United States.<ref name=\"People\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/too-purrfect-vol-50-no-21/|title=Too Purrfect|date=December 7, 1998|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|first=Pam |last=Lambert|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329014604/https://people.com/archive/too-purrfect-vol-50-no-21/|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Lewis was a self-made millionaire by 1981 through the [[real estate]] and [[used car]]s businesses.<ref name=\"People\"/> By that time, Lewis was married to his first wife Gladys Lewis Cross<ref name=\"Kiro\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/trending/tiger-king-sheriff-seeking-leads-1997-disappearance-carole-baskins-2nd-husband/FCSINAFMEZD7TD6B64DBHL6GZA/|title='Tiger King': Sheriff seeking leads in 1997 disappearance of Carole Baskin's 2nd husband|website=[[KIRO-TV|KIRO 7]]|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> and had three daughters and an adopted son.<ref name=\"People\"/> That year, Lewis first met [[Carole Baskin]] on Nebraska Avenue in Tampa when she was nineteen years old.<ref name=\"Intel\">{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/09/joe-exotic-and-his-american-animals.html|title= Joe Exotic bred lions, tigers, and ligers at his roadside zoo. He was a modern Barnum who found an equally extraordinary nemesis.|first=Robert |last=Moor|date=September 3, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[New York (magazine)|Intelligencer]]}}</ref><ref name=\"TheSecret\">{{Cite episode|title=The Secret|series=[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]|season=1|number=3|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Baskin and Lewis engaged in an affair while both were still married.<ref name=\"TheSecret\"/> Baskin became one of Lewis' many girlfriends and she substantially grew his wealth by helping him buy and sell real estate in 1984.<ref name=\"People\"/> The couple divorced each of their spouses and married in 1991.<ref name=\"DBeast\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/joe-exotic-built-a-wild-animal-kingdom-he-was-the-most-dangerous-predator-of-them-all|title=Joe Exotic Built a Wild Animal Kingdom. He Was the Most Dangerous Predator of Them All.|website=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=June 22, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|first=Sean |last=Williams}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, Lewis and Baskin co-founded Wildlife on Easy Street (now called [[Big Cat Rescue]]), a [[big cat]]s [[animal sanctuary]] in Tampa. According to Baskin and the 2020 crime documentary series ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', Lewis would take monthly flights to [[Costa Rica]] to deal with his [[Sexual addiction|sex addiction]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxygen.com/crime-news/what-happened-to-carole-baskins-ex-husband-don-lewis-from-tiger-king|title=What Happened To Carole Baskin's Former Husband, Who Vanished In 1997?|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]]|first=Gina |last=Tron}}</ref><ref name=\"Bible\">{{Cite web|url=https://brobible.com/culture/article/carole-baskin-boyfriend-restraining-order/|title=Carole Baskin\u2019s Boyfriend After Her Husband Disappeared Also Filed For A Chilling Restraining Order Against Her|first=Douglas |last=Charles|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=BroBible}}</ref> Lewis told family members and friends that he was planning to eventually move to Costa Rica.<ref name=\"People\"/> In early 1997, Lewis began transferring ownership of his properties in Florida to a Costa Rican company he controlled.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> In July 1997, Lewis filed a [[restraining order]] against Baskin, claiming that Baskin had threatened to kill him; the restraining order was rejected.<ref name=DonLewisMetro>{{Cite news |title=Tiger King: Who is Carole Baskin\u2019s first husband Jack 'Don' Lewis and when did he disappear? |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |website=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326151850/https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |archive-date=March 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lewis continued to live with Baskin afterwards.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> Lewis told Baskin multiple times that he wanted a [[divorce]], but she did not think he was ever serious.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> In the days leading up to his disappearance, Lewis bought a plane ticket to Costa Rica and was loading equipment on a truck destined for [[Miami]], Florida.<ref name=\"Tampa2005\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tampabay.com/archive/1998/08/23/mysterious-millionaire-still-missing/|title=Mysterious millionaire still missing|date=September 13, 2005|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[Tampa Bay Times]]|first=David |last=Karp}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\n[[File:Pilot Country Airport Gateway.jpg|thumb|left|Lewis' van was found at the Pilot Country Airport (pictured in 2016).<ref name=\"WTSP\"/>]]\nLewis disappeared on August 18, 1997, at around 6:00 a.m.<ref name=\"Charley\"/><ref name=\"WTSP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/extras/disappearance-on-easy-street/67-396338130|title=Disappearance on Easy Street|website=WTSP|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> On August 20, 1997, Lewis' white 1989 Dodge van was found at the Pilot Country Airport in Springhill, Florida, {{convert|40|mile|km}} away from the sanctuary.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/><ref name=\"People\"/> At the time of his disappearance, Lewis was known to own several planes and would fly them even though his [[private pilot licence]] was suspended.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> The keys to the van were found on the floorboard and the van had been parked for a couple of days.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> No evidence was found within the van.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> The [[Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office (Florida)|Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office]] \"found no sign of foul play\" at the Big Cat Rescue sanctuary and visited [[Bagaces]], Costa Rica, where Lewis owned a {{convert|200|acre|ha|abbr=off}} park, as part of their investigation.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/><ref name=\"People\"/><ref name=\"Poly\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/tiger-king-carole-baskin-don-lewis.html|title='Tiger King': What Happened to Carole Baskin\u2019s Husband, Don Lewis?|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[The New York Times]]|first=Audra D. S. |last=Burch}}</ref> The investigation in Costa Rica lasted five days.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> In Costa Rica, investigators found indications that Lewis engaged in extramarital affairs and illegal business practices.<ref name=\"People\"/> Investigators also found that two of Lewis' [[ocelot]]s had recently been shipped out, but their whereabouts were not found.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> None of Lewis' [[credit card]]s have been used since his disappearance.<ref name=\"People\"/>\n\nLewis left behind holdings estimated at more than [[United States dollar|$]]5 million, leading to a legal dispute between Baskin and Lewis' children.<ref name=\"People\"/> Lewis was [[Legal death|declared legally dead]] in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Rosy|last=Cordero|url=https://ew.com/tv/tiger-king-carole-baskin-slams-netflix-documentary/|title='Tiger King' subject Carole Baskin slams Netflix doc, calls it 'salacious and sensational'|website=[[EW.com|Entertainment Weekly]]|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> Most of Lewis' estate was left to Baskin.<ref name=DonLewisMetro /> In 2004, Baskin refused to take a [[polygraph]] related to the investigation, as advised by her attorney.<ref name=\"Tampa2005\"/> Lewis' children have volunteered to take polygraphs.<ref name=\"Charley\"/><ref name=\"Tampa2005\"/> By 2005, authorities leaned away from the theory that Lewis disappeared on his own.<ref name=\"Tampa2005\"/> Hillsborough County Sergeant John Marsicano stated that, \"from an investigative standpoint\", it did not seem like Lewis ran off on his own.<ref name=\"Tampa2005\"/> In 2020, the ''Tiger King'' series became popular as many people stayed at home due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]]. Using the popularity of ''Tiger King'', Hillsborough County Sheriff Chad Chronister appealed to the public for legitimate leads or evidence.<ref name=TampaSheriff>{{cite news|title=Hillsborough sheriff says tips are coming in \u2018Tiger King\u2019 missing millionaire case |first=Christopher |last=Spata |url=https://www.tampabay.com/news/crime/2020/03/31/hillsborough-sheriff-says-tips-are-coming-in-tiger-king-missing-millionaire-case/ |website=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Since the release of the series, the Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office has received six [[Tip (law enforcement)|tip]]s a day related to the disappearance.<ref name=\"Poly\"/> Chronister reiterated that his department does not \"have any type of evidence, not one piece, that suggests that [Lewis] was killed.\"<ref name=\"Poly\"/> The case is still open as of 2020.<ref name=\"CBS\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/police-ask-for-new-leads-in-disappearance-of-don-lewis-husband-of-tiger-king-star-carole-baskin/|title=Police ask for new leads in disappearance of Don Lewis, husband of \"Tiger King\" star Carole Baskin|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[CBS News]]|first=Danielle|last=Garrand}}</ref>\n\n==Unofficial theories==\nIn December 1998, Pam Lambert of ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' wrote that there was \"a wealth of suspects and scenarios, but little precious evidence\".<ref name=\"People\"/> The third episode of ''Tiger King'', \"The Secret\", covered multiple theories surrounding Lewis' disappearance.<ref name=\"Kiro\"/> Lewis' children have pushed a theory that Baskin fed Lewis to the tigers, and have criticized investigators for not running a [[Genetic testing|DNA test]] on a [[meat grinder]] at the sanctuary.<ref name=\"People\"/> Baskin reacted to the allegations saying that there would be human bones as remains if the tigers would have eaten Lewis.<ref name=\"People\"/> Baskin expressed her disappointment about the theories to Lambert, saying \"Can you imagine having people think you killed your husband or wife and not being able to prove otherwise? Without a body, there is nothing I can do to clear my name.\"<ref name=\"People\"/> Baskin has a long-running feud with private zoo owner [[Joe Exotic]].<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Not Your Average Joe|series=[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]|season=1|number=1|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Exotic has promoted an unsubstantiated theory that Baskin was involved in the disappearance of Lewis.<ref name=\"CBS\"/> Exotic created a music video entitled \"Here Kitty Kitty\" that featured a Baskin-lookalike feeding raw meat to tigers.<ref name=\"Kiro\"/> After ''Tiger King'' was released, several [[Internet meme]]s targeted Baskin for her speculated involvement in Lewis' disappearance.<ref name=\"Kiro\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Tiger King}}\n\n[[Category:1990s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:August 1997 crimes]]\n[[Category:August 1997 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Unsolved crimes in the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Dade City, Florida|Lewis, Don]]\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Disappearance of Don Lewis\n| image = Don Lewis disappearance portrait.jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption =\n| birth_name = Jack Donald Lewis\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1938|4|30|df=yes}}\n| birth_place =[[Dade City, Florida|Dade City]], [[Florida]], U.S.\n| other_names = Bob Martinez<ref name=\"Charley\">{{cite web|url=http://charleyproject.org/case/jack-donald-lewis|title=Jack Donald Lewis \u2013 The Charley Project|accessdate=April 1, 2020|date=September 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927192040/http://charleyproject.org/case/jack-donald-lewis|archive-date=September 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| death_date = August 18, 2002 ([[legal death]])\n| disappeared_date = {{Disappeared date and age|df=yes|1997|8|18|1938|4|30}}\n| disappeared_place =[[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], Florida, U.S.\n| disappeared_status = {{Missing for|1997|8|18}}\n| spouse             = {{Plainlist|\n* Gladys Lewis Cross<br />({{abbr|div.|divorce}} 1990)\n* {{marriage|[[Carole Baskin]]|1991|2002|end={{abbr|legal d.|legal death}}}}}}\n| children           = 4\n}}\n\n'''Jack Donald Lewis''' (April 30, 1938 \u2013 {{abbr|legal d.|legal death}} August 18, 2002) disappeared on August 18, 1997, after leaving his home in [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], [[Florida]], United States.<ref name=\"WTSP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/extras/disappearance-on-easy-street/67-396338130|title=Disappearance on Easy Street|website=WTSP|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The investigation into his disappearance has stretched from Lewis' [[Big Cat Rescue]] sanctuary in Tampa, co-owned by his second wife [[Carole Baskin]], to land owned by Lewis in [[Costa Rica]]. No evidence of Lewis being killed has surfaced, and investigators believe that it is unlikely that he disappeared on his own. Lewis was declared [[legal death|legally dead]] in 2002. As of 2020, the case is still open. Lewis' disappearance was covered in 2020 crime documentary series ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', which focused on a feud between Baskin and private zoo owner [[Joe Exotic]].\n\n==Background==\nDon Lewis was a native of [[Dade City, Florida|Dade City]], [[Florida]], United States.<ref name=\"People\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/too-purrfect-vol-50-no-21/|title=Too Purrfect|date=December 7, 1998|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|first=Pam |last=Lambert|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329014604/https://people.com/archive/too-purrfect-vol-50-no-21/|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Lewis was a self-made millionaire by 1981 through the [[real estate]] and [[used car]]s businesses.<ref name=\"People\"/> By that time, Lewis was married to his first wife Gladys Lewis Cross<ref name=\"Kiro\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/trending/tiger-king-sheriff-seeking-leads-1997-disappearance-carole-baskins-2nd-husband/FCSINAFMEZD7TD6B64DBHL6GZA/|title='Tiger King': Sheriff seeking leads in 1997 disappearance of Carole Baskin's 2nd husband|website=[[KIRO-TV|KIRO 7]]|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> and had three daughters and an adopted son.<ref name=\"People\"/> That year, Lewis first met [[Carole Baskin]] on Nebraska Avenue in Tampa when she was nineteen years old.<ref name=\"Intel\">{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/09/joe-exotic-and-his-american-animals.html|title= Joe Exotic bred lions, tigers, and ligers at his roadside zoo. He was a modern Barnum who found an equally extraordinary nemesis.|first=Robert |last=Moor|date=September 3, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[New York (magazine)|Intelligencer]]}}</ref><ref name=\"TheSecret\">{{Cite episode|title=The Secret|series=[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]|season=1|number=3|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Baskin and Lewis engaged in an affair while both were still married.<ref name=\"TheSecret\"/> Baskin became one of Lewis' many girlfriends and she substantially grew his wealth by helping him buy and sell real estate in 1984.<ref name=\"People\"/> The couple divorced each of their spouses and married in 1991.<ref name=\"DBeast\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/joe-exotic-built-a-wild-animal-kingdom-he-was-the-most-dangerous-predator-of-them-all|title=Joe Exotic Built a Wild Animal Kingdom. He Was the Most Dangerous Predator of Them All.|website=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=June 22, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|first=Sean |last=Williams}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, Lewis and Baskin co-founded Wildlife on Easy Street (now called [[Big Cat Rescue]]), a [[big cat]]s [[animal sanctuary]] in Tampa. According to Baskin and the 2020 crime documentary series ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', Lewis would take monthly flights to [[Costa Rica]] to deal with his [[Sexual addiction|sex addiction]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxygen.com/crime-news/what-happened-to-carole-baskins-ex-husband-don-lewis-from-tiger-king|title=What Happened To Carole Baskin's Former Husband, Who Vanished In 1997?|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]]|first=Gina |last=Tron}}</ref><ref name=\"Bible\">{{Cite web|url=https://brobible.com/culture/article/carole-baskin-boyfriend-restraining-order/|title=Carole Baskin\u2019s Boyfriend After Her Husband Disappeared Also Filed For A Chilling Restraining Order Against Her|first=Douglas |last=Charles|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=BroBible}}</ref> Lewis told family members and friends that he was planning to eventually move to Costa Rica.<ref name=\"People\"/> In early 1997, Lewis began transferring ownership of his properties in Florida to a Costa Rican company he controlled.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> In July 1997, Lewis filed a [[restraining order]] against Baskin, claiming that Baskin had threatened to kill him; the restraining order was rejected.<ref name=DonLewisMetro>{{Cite news |title=Tiger King: Who is Carole Baskin\u2019s first husband Jack 'Don' Lewis and when did he disappear? |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |website=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326151850/https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |archive-date=March 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lewis continued to live with Baskin afterwards.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> Lewis told Baskin multiple times that he wanted a [[divorce]], but she did not think he was ever serious.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> In the days leading up to his disappearance, Lewis bought a plane ticket to Costa Rica and was loading equipment on a truck destined for [[Miami]], Florida.<ref name=\"Tampa2005\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tampabay.com/archive/1998/08/23/mysterious-millionaire-still-missing/|title=Mysterious millionaire still missing|date=September 13, 2005|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[Tampa Bay Times]]|first=David |last=Karp}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\n[[File:Pilot Country Airport Gateway.jpg|thumb|left|Lewis' van was found at the Pilot Country Airport (pictured in 2016).<ref name=\"WTSP\"/>]]\nLewis disappeared on August 18, 1997, at around 6:00 a.m.<ref name=\"Charley\"/><ref name=\"WTSP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/extras/disappearance-on-easy-street/67-396338130|title=Disappearance on Easy Street|website=WTSP|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> On August 20, 1997, Lewis' white 1989 Dodge van was found at the Pilot Country Airport in Springhill, Florida, {{convert|40|mile|km}} away from the sanctuary.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/><ref name=\"People\"/> At the time of his disappearance, Lewis was known to own several planes and would fly them even though his [[private pilot licence]] was suspended.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> The keys to the van were found on the floorboard and the van had been parked for a couple of days.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> No evidence was found within the van.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> The [[Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office (Florida)|Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office]] \"found no sign of foul play\" at the Big Cat Rescue sanctuary and visited [[Bagaces]], Costa Rica, where Lewis owned a {{convert|200|acre|ha|abbr=off}} park, as part of their investigation.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/><ref name=\"People\"/><ref name=\"Poly\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/tiger-king-carole-baskin-don-lewis.html|title='Tiger King': What Happened to Carole Baskin\u2019s Husband, Don Lewis?|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[The New York Times]]|first=Audra D. S. |last=Burch}}</ref> The investigation in Costa Rica lasted five days.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> In Costa Rica, investigators found indications that Lewis engaged in extramarital affairs and illegal business practices.<ref name=\"People\"/> Investigators also found that two of Lewis' [[ocelot]]s had recently been shipped out, but their whereabouts were not found.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> None of Lewis' [[credit card]]s have been used since his disappearance.<ref name=\"People\"/>\n\nLewis left behind holdings estimated at more than [[United States dollar|$]]5 million, leading to a legal dispute between Baskin and Lewis' children.<ref name=\"People\"/> Lewis was [[Legal death|declared legally dead]] in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Rosy|last=Cordero|url=https://ew.com/tv/tiger-king-carole-baskin-slams-netflix-documentary/|title='Tiger King' subject Carole Baskin slams Netflix doc, calls it 'salacious and sensational'|website=[[EW.com|Entertainment Weekly]]|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> Most of Lewis' estate was left to Baskin.<ref name=DonLewisMetro /> In 2004, Baskin refused to take a [[polygraph]] related to the investigation, as advised by her attorney.<ref name=\"Tampa2005\"/> Lewis' children have volunteered to take polygraphs.<ref name=\"Charley\"/><ref name=\"Tampa2005\"/> By 2005, authorities leaned away from the theory that Lewis disappeared on his own.<ref name=\"Tampa2005\"/> Hillsborough County Sergeant John Marsicano stated that, \"from an investigative standpoint\", it did not seem like Lewis ran off on his own.<ref name=\"Tampa2005\"/> In 2020, the ''Tiger King'' series became popular as many people stayed at home due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]]. Using the popularity of ''Tiger King'', Hillsborough County Sheriff Chad Chronister appealed to the public for legitimate leads or evidence.<ref name=TampaSheriff>{{cite news|title=Hillsborough sheriff says tips are coming in \u2018Tiger King\u2019 missing millionaire case |first=Christopher |last=Spata |url=https://www.tampabay.com/news/crime/2020/03/31/hillsborough-sheriff-says-tips-are-coming-in-tiger-king-missing-millionaire-case/ |website=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Since the release of the series, the Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office has received six [[Tip (law enforcement)|tip]]s a day related to the disappearance.<ref name=\"Poly\"/> Chronister reiterated that his department does not \"have any type of evidence, not one piece, that suggests that [Lewis] was killed.\"<ref name=\"Poly\"/> \n\nThe case is still open as of 2020.<ref name=\"CBS\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/police-ask-for-new-leads-in-disappearance-of-don-lewis-husband-of-tiger-king-star-carole-baskin/|title=Police ask for new leads in disappearance of Don Lewis, husband of \"Tiger King\" star Carole Baskin|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[CBS News]]|first=Danielle|last=Garrand}}</ref>\n\n==Unofficial theories==\nIn December 1998, Pam Lambert of ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' wrote that there was \"a wealth of suspects and scenarios, but little precious evidence\".<ref name=\"People\"/> The third episode of ''Tiger King'', \"The Secret\", covered multiple theories surrounding Lewis' disappearance.<ref name=\"Kiro\"/> Lewis' children have pushed a theory that Baskin fed Lewis to the tigers, and have criticized investigators for not running a [[Genetic testing|DNA test]] on a [[meat grinder]] at the sanctuary.<ref name=\"People\"/> Baskin reacted to the allegations saying that there would be human bones as remains if the tigers would have eaten Lewis.<ref name=\"People\"/> Baskin expressed her disappointment about the theories to Lambert, saying \"Can you imagine having people think you killed your husband or wife and not being able to prove otherwise? Without a body, there is nothing I can do to clear my name.\"<ref name=\"People\"/> Baskin has a long-running feud with private zoo owner [[Joe Exotic]].<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Not Your Average Joe|series=[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]|season=1|number=1|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Exotic has promoted an unsubstantiated theory that Baskin was involved in the disappearance of Lewis.<ref name=\"CBS\"/> Exotic created a music video entitled \"Here Kitty Kitty\" that featured a Baskin-lookalike feeding raw meat to tigers.<ref name=\"Kiro\"/> After ''Tiger King'' was released, several [[Internet meme]]s targeted Baskin for her speculated involvement in Lewis' disappearance.<ref name=\"Kiro\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Tiger King}}\n\n[[Category:1990s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:August 1997 crimes]]\n[[Category:August 1997 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Unsolved crimes in the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Dade City, Florida|Lewis, Don]]\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n", "name_user": "Nice4What", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInvestigation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disappearance_of_Don_Lewis"}
{"title_page": "Grapefruit", "text_new": "{{About|the fruit}}\n{{short description|citrus fruit}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Crazy Wikipedia it is letting me edit this article right now don\u2019t use Wikipedia!!!!!\nFreherheghdwtjhcddstfde\n| image = Grapefruit-Whole-&-Split.jpg\n| image_caption = Red grapefruit\n| genus = Citrus\n| species = {{hybrid}} paradisi\n| authority = Macfad.\n}}\n\nThe '''grapefruit ''' (''Citrus \u00d7 paradisi'') is a [[subtropics|subtropical]] [[citrus]] tree known for its relatively large sour to semi-sweet, somewhat bitter [[fruit]].<ref name=\"morton\">{{cite book |author=Morton, Julia Frances |title=Grapefruit, Citrus paradisi. In: Fruits of Warm Climates, p 152\u2013158|publisher=NewCROP, New Crop Resource Online Program, Center for New Crops and Plant Products, Department of Horticulture and Landscape Architecture, Purdue University |year=1987 |isbn=978-0-9610184-1-2 |oclc= 16947184 |url=http://www.hort.purdue.edu/newcrop/morton/grapefruit.html}}</ref> Grapefruit is a citrus [[hybrid (biology)|hybrid]] originating in [[Barbados]] as an accidental cross between the [[orange (fruit)|sweet orange]] (''C. sinensis'') and [[pomelo]] (or shaddock) (''C. maxima''), both of which were introduced from Asia in the seventeenth century.<ref name=\"Carrington & Fraser\">{{cite book |last1=Carrington |first1=Sean |last2=Fraser |first2=HenryC |title=A~Z of Barbados Heritage |edition= |series= |year=2003 |publisher=Macmillan Caribbean |location= |isbn=978-0-333-92068-8 |pages=90\u201391 |chapter=Grapefruit |quote=One of many citrus species grown in Barbados. This fruit is believed to have originated in Barbados as a natural cross between sweet orange (''C. sinesis'') and Shaddock (''C. grandis''), both of which originated in Asia and were introduced by Europeans in the seventeenth century. The grapefruit first appeared as an illustration entitled \"The Forbidden Fruit Tree\" in ''The Natural History of Barbados'' (1750) by Rev. Griffith Hughes. This accords with the scientific name which literally is \"citrus of paradise\". The fruit seems to have been fairly commonly available around that time, since George Washington in his Barbados Journal (1750-1751) mentions \"the Forbidden Fruit\" as one of the local fruit available at a dinner party he attended. The plant was later described in the 1837 ''Flora of Jamaica'' as the Barbados Grapefruit. The historical arguments and experimental work on leaf enzymes and oils from possible parents all support a Barbadian origin for the fruit.}}</ref> When found, it was nicknamed the \"[[forbidden fruit]]\".<ref name=morton/> Frequently, it is misidentified as the very similar parent species, [[pomelo]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Li|first=Xiaomeng|author2=Xie R.|author3=Lu Z.|author4=Zhou Z.|title=The Origin of Cultivated Citrus as Inferred from Internal Transcribed Spacer and Chloroplast DNA Sequence and Amplified Fragment Length Polymorphism Fingerprints|journal=Journal of the American Society for Horticultural Science|date=July 2010|volume=135|issue=4|page=341|url=http://journal.ashspublications.org/content/135/4/341.full|accessdate=27 February 2013|doi=10.21273/JASHS.135.4.341|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424191429/http://journal.ashspublications.org/content/135/4/341.full|archive-date=24 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe ''grape'' part of the name alludes to clusters of fruit on the tree that often appear similar to [[grape]] clusters.<ref name=\"loc.gov\">[https://www.loc.gov/rr/scitech/mysteries/grapefruit.html \"How did the grapefruit get its name?\"] [[Library of Congress]]. Science Reference Service, Everyday Mysteries. Retrieved August 2, 2009.</ref> The interior flesh is segmented and varies in color from white to yellow to red to pink.\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Grapefruit.ebola.jpeg|thumb|upright|Grapefruit growing in the grape-like clusters from which their name derives]]\nThe evergreen grapefruit trees usually grow to around {{convert|5|\u2013|6|m|ft|sp=us}} tall, although they may reach {{convert|13|\u2013|15|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=morton/> The leaves are glossy, dark green, long (up to {{convert|15|cm|in|sp=us}}), and thin. It produces {{convert|5|cm|in|0|abbr=on}} white four-petaled [[flower]]s. The fruit is yellow-orange skinned and generally, an [[oblate spheroid]] in shape; it ranges in diameter from {{convert|10|\u2013|15|cm|in|abbr=on}}. The flesh is segmented and [[acid]]ic, varying in color depending on the [[cultivar]]s, which include white, pink, and red pulps of varying sweetness (generally, the redder varieties are the sweetest).<ref name=morton/> The 1929 U.S. Ruby Red<ref name=morton/> (of the Redblush variety) has the first grapefruit [[patent]].<ref name=\"txsweet\">[http://www.texasweet.com/About-Texas-Citrus/Texas-Grapefruit-History Texas grapefruit history] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101128162502/http://texasweet.com/About-Texas-Citrus/Texas-Grapefruit-History |date=2010-11-28 }}, TexaSweet. Retrieved 2 July 2008.</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe genetic origin of the grapefruit is a hybrid mix.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Xiaomeng Li|author2=Rangjin Xie|author3=Zhenhua Lu|author4=Zhiqin Zhou|title=Genetic origin of cultivated citrus determined: Researchers find evidence of origins of orange, lime, lemon, grapefruit, other citrus species|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2011/01/110118101600.htm|website=Science Daily|accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref> One ancestor of the grapefruit was the Jamaican [[sweet orange]] (''Citrus sinensis''), itself an ancient hybrid of Asian origin; the other was the Indonesian [[pomelo]] (''C. maxima'').<ref name=morton/> One story of the fruit's origin is that a certain \"Captain Shaddock\"<ref name=morton/><ref name=\"Kumamoto\">{{cite journal|last=Kumamoto|first=J.|last2=Scora|first2=R. W.|last3=Lawton|first3=H. W.|last4=Clerx|first4=W. A.|date=1987-01-01|title=Mystery of the forbidden fruit: Historical epilogue on the origin of the grapefruit, Citrus paradisi (Rutaceae)|journal=Economic Botany|volume=41|issue=1|pages=97\u2013107|doi=10.1007/BF02859356|issn=0013-0001}}</ref> brought pomelo seeds to Jamaica and bred the first fruit,<ref name=\"culinaire\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20080502135258/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0JAW/is_87/ai_n25336559 Grapefruit: a fruit with a bit of a complex] in ''Art Culinaire'' (Winter, 2007)</ref> although it probably originated as a naturally occurring hybrid between the two plants some time after they had been introduced there.<ref name=morton/><ref name=\"Carrington & Fraser\"/>\n\n{{Quote box\n| align = right\n| title = Forbidden-Fruit-Tree\n| quote = <poem>\nThe Trunk, Leaves, and Flowers of this Tree, very much resemble\nthose of the Orange-tree.\nThe Fruit, when ripe, is something longer and larger than the largest\nOrange; and exceeds, in the Delicacy of its Taste, the Fruit of every\nTree in this or any of our neighbouring Islands.\nIt hath somewhat of the Taste of a Shaddock; but far exceeds that, as\nwell as the best Orange, in its delicious Taste and Flavour.\n</poem>\n| source = \u2014Description from Hughes' 1750 ''Natural History of Barbados''\n}}\nThe hybrid fruit, then called \"the forbidden fruit\", was first documented in 1750 by a [[Wales|Welshman]], Rev. [[Griffith Hughes]], who described specimens from Barbados in ''The Natural History of Barbados''.<ref name=morton/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldwidewords.org/qa/qa-gra3.htm|title=World Wide Words: Grapefruit|website=World Wide Words|access-date=2017-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.welchmanhallgullybarbados.com/index.php |title=Welchman Hall Gully, Barbados |author=Admin |year=2010 |publisher=[[Barbados National Trust]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100816070727/http://www.welchmanhallgullybarbados.com/index.php |archivedate=16 August 2010 |accessdate=11 July 2010 |quote=The Development of the Gully - The Gully was once part of a plantation owned by a Welshman called General William Asygell Williams over 200 years ago. Hence the name \"Welchman Hall\" gully. It was this man who first developed the gully with exotic trees and an orchard. Interestingly, the grapefruit is originally from Barbados and is rumoured to have started in Welchman Hall Gully. |url-status=dead }}</ref> Currently, the grapefruit is said to be one of the \"Seven Wonders of Barbados\".<ref>Barbados Seven Wonders: The Grapefruit Tree. [http://www.barbados.org/grapefrt.htm Abstract]</ref>\n\nThe grapefruit was brought to Florida by Count [[Odet Philippe]] in 1823 in what is now known as [[Safety Harbor]].<ref name=morton/> Further crosses have produced the [[tangelo]] (1905), the [[Minneola tangelo]] (1931), and the [[oroblanco]] (1984).\n\nThe grapefruit was known as the ''shaddock'' or ''shattuck'' until the nineteenth century.<ref name=morton/><ref name=\"Kumamoto\"/> Its current name alludes to clusters of the fruit on the tree, which often appear similar to that of [[grape]]s.<ref name=\"loc.gov\"/> Botanically, it was not distinguished from the pomelo until the 1830s, when it was given the name ''Citrus paradisi.'' Its true origins were not determined until the 1940s. This led to the official name being altered to ''Citrus \u00d7 paradisi,'' the \"\u00d7\" identifying its hybrid origin.<ref name=\"Texas_Citrus\">Texas Citrus: Puzzling Beginnings. [http://www.texasweet.com/texascitrus/grapefruit.html Article] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070125112342/http://www.texasweet.com/texascitrus/grapefruit.html |date=2007-01-25}}</ref><ref name=\"University_of_Florida\">University of Florida: IFAS Extension; The Grapefruit. {{cite web |url= http://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/pdffiles/CH/CH06300.pdf |title= Fact Sheet |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070628190748/http://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/pdffiles/CH/CH06300.pdf |archivedate= 2007-06-28 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:KC Atwood.jpg|thumb|upright|Kimball Atwood]]\nAn early pioneer in the American citrus industry was Kimball Atwood, a wealthy entrepreneur who founded the Atwood Grapefruit Company in the late nineteenth century. The Atwood Grove became the largest grapefruit grove in the world, with a yearly output of 80,000 boxes of fruit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20040816/NEWS/408160323?tc=ar |title=Manatee County a big part of citrus history |publisher=HeraldTribune.com |date=2004-08-16 |accessdate=2011-12-17}}</ref> It was there that pink grapefruit was first discovered in 1906.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hort.purdue.edu/newcrop/morton/grapefruit.html|title=Grapefruit|website=www.hort.purdue.edu|access-date=2017-03-30}}</ref>\n\n===Ruby Red===\n[[File:Citrus paradisi (Grapefruit, pink) white bg.jpg|thumb|\"Red\" grapefruit]]\nThe 1929 Ruby Red (or ''Redblush'') patent was associated with real commercial success, which came after the discovery of a red grapefruit growing on a pink variety.<ref name=morton/> [[Atomic gardening|Using radiation to trigger mutations]], new varieties were developed to retain the red tones which typically faded to pink.<ref>{{cite news |author=William J Broad |title=Useful Mutants, Bred With Radiation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/28/science/28crop.html?_r=1&pagewanted=print&oref=slogin |work=New York Times |date=28 August 2007}}</ref> The Rio Red variety is the current (2007) Texas grapefruit with registered trademarks Rio Star and Ruby-Sweet, also sometimes promoted as \"Reddest\" and \"Texas Choice\". The Rio Red is a [[mutation breeding|mutation bred]] variety that was developed by treatment of bud sticks with thermal neutrons. Its improved attributes of mutant variety are fruit and juice color, deeper red, and wide adaptation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mvgs.iaea.org/Search.aspx?ID=282|title=MVD|website=mvgs.iaea.org|access-date=2017-03-30}}</ref>\n\n===Star Ruby===\nThe Star Ruby is the darkest of the red varieties.<ref name=morton/> Developed from an [[irradiation|irradiated]] Hudson grapefruit,<ref>{{cite journal |last=Ahloowalia |first=B.S. |last2=Maluszynski |first2=M. |last3=Nichterlein |first3=K. |date=2004 |title=Global impact of mutation-derived varieties |journal=Euphytica |volume=135 |issue=2 |pages=187\u2013204 |doi=10.1023/B:EUPH.0000014914.85465.4f }}</ref> it has found limited commercial success because it is more difficult to grow than other varieties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aggie-horticulture.tamu.edu/citrus/grapefruit.htm|title=Home fruit Production-Grapefruit|last=Sauls|first=Julian W.|year=1998|accessdate=2013-07-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citrusvariety.ucr.edu/citrus/starruby.html|title=Star Ruby grapefruit|author=Citrus Variety Collection|accessdate=2013-07-22}}</ref>\n\n==Varieties==\nThe varieties of [[Texas]] and [[Florida]] grapefruit include: Oro Blanco, Ruby Red, Pink, Rio Star, Thompson, White Marsh, Flame, Star Ruby, Duncan, and Pummelo HB.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gofloridagrapefruit.com/florida-grown/ |title=Go Florida Grapefruit |publisher=Go Florida Grapefruit |accessdate=2011-12-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110910120645/http://www.gofloridagrapefruit.com/florida-grown/ |archivedate=2011-09-10 }}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nIn 2018, world production of grapefruits (combined with pomelos) was 9.4 million tonnes, led by China with 53% of the world total. Secondary producers were [[Vietnam]] and the United States.<ref name=fao18/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; clear:left; width:18em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=2|Grapefruit production in 2018\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ddf; width:25%;\"| Country\n! style=\"background:#ddf; width:15%;\"| Production <br /><small>(millions of [[tonne]]s)</small>\n|-\n| <center>{{CHN}} </center>|| <center>5.0</center>\n|-\n| <center>{{VIE}} </center>|| <center>0.7</center>\n|-\n| <center>{{USA}} </center>|| <center>0.6</center>\n|-\n| <center>{{MEX}} </center>|| <center>0.5</center>\n|-\n| <center>{{SAF}} </center>|| <center>0.4</center>\n|-\n| <center>{{IND}} </center>|| <center>0.3</center>\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#ccc;\"\n|<center>'''World''' </center>||<center> '''9.4'''</center>\n|-\n|colspan=2|<small>Source: [[FAOSTAT]] of the [[United Nations]]</small><ref name=\"fao18\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/faostat/en/#data/QC|title= Grapefruit production in 2018, Crops/Regions/World list/Production Quantity (pick lists)|date=2019|publisher=UN Food and Agriculture Organization, Corporate Statistical Database (FAOSTAT)|accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Colors and flavors==\n[[File:Grapefruit-mercaptan-2D-skeletal-vertical.png|80px|thumb|Grapefruit mercaptan]]\nGrapefruit varieties are differentiated by the flesh color of fruit they produce. Common varieties are [[red]], [[white]], and [[pink]] pulp colors. Flavors range from highly acidic and somewhat sour to sweet and tart, resulting from composition of sugars (mainly [[sucrose]]), [[organic acid]]s (mainly citric acid), and [[monoterpene]]s and [[sesquiterpene]]s providing aromas.<ref name=\"Zheng\">{{cite journal | last=Zheng | first=Huiwen | last2=Zhang | first2=Qiuyun | last3=Quan | first3=Junping | last4=Zheng | first4=Qiao | last5=Xi | first5=Wanpeng | title=Determination of sugars, organic acids, aroma components, and carotenoids in grapefruit pulps | journal=Food Chemistry | volume=205 | year=2016 | issn=0308-8146 | doi=10.1016/j.foodchem.2016.03.007 | pages=112\u2013121|pmid=27006221}}</ref>\n\n[[Grapefruit mercaptan]], a [[sulfur]]-containing [[terpene]], is one of the [[aroma compound]]s influencing taste and [[odor]] of grapefruit, compared with other citrus fruits.<ref name=\"Andrea_Buettner_and_Peter_Schieberle\">{{cite journal\n| title= Characterization of the Most Odor-Active Volatiles in Fresh, Hand-Squeezed Juice of Grapefruit (''Citrus paradisi Macfayden'')\n| author1=A. Buettner |author2=P. Schieberle |journal= J. Agric. Food Chem.\n| year= 1999\n| volume= 47\n| pages= 5189\u20135193\n| doi= 10.1021/jf990071l\n| pmid= 10606593\n| issue= 12}}</ref>\n\n==Drug interactions==\n{{Main|Grapefruit\u2013drug interactions}}\n\nGrapefruit and [[grapefruit juice]] have been found to [[drug interaction|interact]] with numerous [[drugs]] and in many cases, to result in adverse direct and/or side effects (if dosage is not carefully adjusted.)<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Bailey DG, Dresser G, Arnold JM |title=Grapefruit-medication interactions: forbidden fruit or avoidable consequences? |journal=CMAJ |volume=185 |issue=4 |pages=309\u201316 |date=March 2013 |pmid=23184849 |pmc=3589309 |doi=10.1503/cmaj.120951}}</ref>\n\nThis happens in two very different ways. In the first, the effect is from [[bergamottin]], a natural [[furanocoumarin]] in both grapefruit flesh and peel that inhibits the [[CYP3A4]] [[enzyme]], (among others from the [[P450]] enzyme family responsible for metabolizing 90% of drugs). The action of the CYP3A4 enzyme itself is to [[metabolism|metabolize]] many medications.<ref name=\"CYP3A4 inhibition\">{{cite web|last1=Renee|first1=Janet|title=Does Grapefruit Inhibit Liver Enzymes?|url=http://healthyeating.sfgate.com/grapefruit-inhibit-liver-enzymes-10445.html|website=sfgate.com|publisher=SF Gate|accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Mitchell May 2016\">{{cite web|last1=Mitchell|first1=Steve|title=Why Grapefruit and Medication Can Be a Dangerous Mix|url=http://www.consumerreports.org/health/grapefruit-and-medications-can-be-a-dangerous-mix/|website=Consumer Reports|accessdate=4 May 2016|date=19 February 2016}}</ref> If the drug's breakdown for removal is lessened, then the level of the drug in the blood may become too high or stay too long, leading to [[adverse effect]]s.<ref name=\"Mitchell May 2016\"/> On the other hand, some drugs must be broken down to become active, and inhibiting [[CYP3A4]] may lead to reduced drug effects.\n\nThe other effect is that grapefruit can block the absorption of drugs in the intestine.<ref name=\"Mitchell May 2016\"/> If the drug is not absorbed, then not enough of it is in the blood to have a therapeutic effect.<ref name=\"Mitchell May 2016\"/> Each affected drug has either a specific increase of effect or decrease.\n\nOne whole grapefruit, or a glass of {{convert|200|mL|usoz|abbr=on}} of grapefruit juice may cause drug overdose toxicity.<ref name=\"BaileyDresser2012\">{{cite journal|last1=Bailey|first1=D. G.|last2=Dresser|first2=G.|last3=Arnold|first3=J. M. O.|title=Grapefruit-medication interactions: Forbidden fruit or avoidable consequences?|journal=Canadian Medical Association Journal|volume=185|issue=4|year=2012|pages=309\u2013316|issn=0820-3946|doi=10.1503/cmaj.120951|pmid=23184849|pmc=3589309}}</ref> Typically, drugs that are incompatible with grapefruit are so labeled on the container or [[package insert]].<ref name=\"Mitchell May 2016\"/> People taking drugs should ask their health care provider or pharmacist questions about grapefruit and drug interactions.<ref name=\"Mitchell May 2016\"/>\n\n==Nutrition==\n{{Nutritional value\n| name=Grapefruit, raw, white, all areas\n| kJ=138\n| protein=.8 g\n| fat=0.10 g\n| water=90.48 g\n| carbs=8.41 g\n| fiber=1.1 g\n| sugars=7.31 g\n| glucose=\n| fructose=\n| iron_mg=0.06\n| manganese_mg=0.013\n| calcium_mg=12\n| magnesium_mg=9\n| phosphorus_mg=8\n| potassium_mg=148\n| zinc_mg=0.07\n| vitC_mg=33.3\n| pantothenic_mg=0.283\n| vitB6_mg=0.043\n| folate_ug=10\n| choline_mg=7.7\n| thiamin_mg=0.037\n| riboflavin_mg=0.020\n| niacin_mg=0.269\n| vitE_mg=0.13\n| source_usda=1\n| note=[http://ndb.nal.usda.gov/ndb/search/list?qlookup=09116&format=Full Link to USDA Database entry]\n}}\n\nRaw grapefruit is 90% water, 8% [[carbohydrate]]s, 1% [[protein]], and contains negligible [[fat]] (table). In a 100 gram reference amount, raw grapefruit provides 33 [[calorie]]s and is a rich source of [[vitamin C]] (40% of the [[Daily Value]]), with no other [[micronutrient]]s in significant content.\n\n===Citric acid===\nGrapefruit juice contains about half the [[citric acid]] of [[Lime (fruit)|lime]] or [[lemon]] juice, and about 50% more citric acid than [[Orange (fruit)|orange]] juice.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Penniston KL, Nakada SY, Holmes RP, Assimos DG | title=Quantitative Assessment of Citric Acid in Lemon Juice, Lime Juice, and Commercially-Available Fruit Juice Products | journal=Journal of Endourology | volume=22 | issue=3 | year=2008 | pmid=18290732 | pages = 567\u2013570 | doi = 10.1089/end.2007.0304 | pmc=2637791}}</ref>\n\n==Grapefruit sweets==\nIn [[Costa Rica]], especially in [[Atenas]], grapefruit are often cooked to remove their sourness, rendering them as [[Confectionery|sweets]]; they are also stuffed with ''[[dulce de leche]]'', resulting in a [[dessert]] called ''toronja rellena'' (stuffed grapefruit).<ref>{{cite book|editor=Ben Box|others=Sarah Cameron, Sebastian Ballard|title=1994 Mexico & Central America Handbook|edition=4|year=1993|publisher=Trade and Travel Publications Ltd|location=Bath, England|language=English|isbn=978-0900751462|page=682|chapter=Costa Rica - The Meseta Central}}</ref> In [[Haiti]], grapefruit is used primarily for its juice (''jus de Chad\u00e8que''), but also is used to make jam (''confiture de Chad\u00e8que'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memoireonline.com/03/09/2031/Standardisation-dune-formulation-de-confiture-de-chadeque-et-evaluation-des-parametres-physico-chim.html |title=Standardisation d'une formulation de confiture de chad\u00e8que et \u00e9valuation des param\u00e8tres physico-chimiques, microbiologiques et sensoriels |editor=Monrose, Gregory Salomon |publisher=Universit\u00e9 d'Etat d'Haiti (UEH / FAMV) - Ingenieur Agronome 2009|via=Memoire Online|accessdate=5 June 2017|language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor=Bidault, Blandine|editor2=Gattegno, Isabelle |page=46 |year=1984 |title=Le point sur la transformation des fruits tropicaux. |publisher=Groupe de recherche et d'echanges technologiques (GRET) |location=Paris |language=fr}}</ref>\n\n== Parasites ==\nGrapefruits are one of the most common hosts for fruit flies like ''[[Anastrepha suspensa|A. suspensa]]'', which will lay their eggs in overripe or spoiled grapefruits.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=van Whervin|first=L. Walter|date=March 1974|title=Some Fruitflies (Tephritidae) in Jamaica|journal=PANS Pest Articles & News Summaries|volume=20|issue=1|pages=11\u201319|doi=10.1080/09670877409412331|issn=0030-7793}}</ref> The larvae of these flies will then consume the fruit in order to gain nutrients until they can proceed into the pupae stage. This parasitism has led to millions in economic costs for nations in Central America and Southern North America.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Fruit fly pests : a world assessment of their biology and management|last=McPheron, Bruce A. Steck, Gary J.|date=1996|publisher=St. Lucie Press|isbn=1574440144|oclc=34343237}}</ref>\n\n==Other uses==\nGrapefruit has also been investigated in cancer medicine [[pharmacodynamics]]. Its inhibiting effect on the [[metabolism]] of some drugs may allow smaller doses to be used, which can help to reduce costs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/560026|title=Cut Cancer Drug Costs By Exploring Food Interactions|first=Allison|last=Gandey|date=July 18, 2007|work=[[Medscape]]|access-date=2017-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn aromatherapy, the fruity aroma of grapefruit is believed to have an uplifting and stimulating effect on the mind, inhaling the aroma of grapefruit can be used to help combat tiredness or mental exhaustion.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nLifestyle magazines and websites sometimes recommend grapefruit as a stain remover for porcelain and enamel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.wikihow.com/Clean-Your-Bathtub-with-Grapefruit-and-Salt?amp=1|title=How to Clean Your Bathtub with Grapefruit and Salt: 6 Steps|website=m.wikihow.com|access-date=2019-03-08}}{{user-generated inline|date=September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apartmenttherapy.com/how-to-clean-a-bathtub-naturally-with-grapefruit-salt-117590|title=How To Naturally Clean a Bathtub with Grapefruit and Salt|website=Apartment Therapy|access-date=2019-03-08}}</ref>\n\n==Grapefruit relatives==\n{{Main|Citrus taxonomy}}\nGrapefruit is a pomelo [[backcross]], a hybrid of [[pomelo]] \u00d7 [[sweet orange]], with sweet orange itself being a [[pomelo]] \u00d7 [[mandarin orange|mandarin]] hybrid.\n\nThe grapefruit is a parent to many hybrids:\n* A [[Tangelo]] is any hybrid of a [[tangerine]] and either a [[pomelo]] or a grapefruit\n** '[[Tangelo#Minneola|Minneola]]': [[Duncan grapefruit]] \u00d7 [[Dancy (fruit)|Dancy tangerine]]<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|date=1987|chapter=Tangelo|pages=158\u2013160|title=Fruits of warm climates|first=Julia F.|last=Morton|author-link=Julia Morton|location=Miami, FL. |isbn=0-9610184-1-0|chapter-url=https://www.hort.purdue.edu/newcrop/morton/tangelo.html|url=https://www.hort.purdue.edu/newcrop/morton/index.html}}</ref>\n** 'Orlando' (formerly 'Take'): [[Bowen grapefruit]] \u00d7 [[Dancy (fruit)|Dancy tangerine]](pollen parent)<ref name=\":0\"/>\n*** [[Fairchild (fruit)|Fairchild]] is a [[Clementine]] \u00d7 Orlando hybrid\n** 'Seminole': [[Bowen grapefruit]] \u00d7 [[Dancy (fruit)|Dancy tangerine]]<ref name=\":0\"/>\n** 'Thornton': [[tangerine]] \u00d7 grapefruit, unspecified<ref name=\":0\"/>\n** '[[Ugli fruit|Ugli]]': [[mandarin orange|mandarin]] \u00d7 grapefruit, probable (wild seedling)<ref name=\":0\"/>\n** 'Nova' is a second-generation hybrid: [[Clementine]] \u00d7 Orlando tangelo cross<ref name=\":0\"/>\n* The [[Oroblanco]] and [[Melogold]] grapefruits are hybrids between pummelo (''Citrus maxima'') and the grapefruit\n\nThe grapefruit's cousins include:\n* Common [[sweet orange]]: [[pummelo]] \u00d7 [[mandarin orange|mandarin]] hybrid\n* [[Bitter orange]]: a different [[pummelo]] \u00d7 [[mandarin orange|mandarin]] hybrid\n* [[Mandelo]]s: pummelo \u00d7 [[mandarin orange|mandarine]] (''[[Citrus maxima]]'')\n* [[Hyuganatsu]] may also be a pummelo hybrid\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Grapefruit knife]]\n* [[Grapefruit spoon]]\n* [[Grapefruit\u2013drug interactions]]\n* [[Naringenin]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Wiktionary|grapefruit}}\n{{Commons category|Citrus Paradisi group}}\n* {{Wikispecies-inline|Citrus paradisi}}\n\n{{Citrus}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q41350}}\n\n[[Category:Citrus hybrids]]\n[[Category:Citrus]]\n[[Category:Flora of Barbados]]\n[[Category:Flora of Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Grapefruit|*]]\n[[Category:Tropical agriculture]]\n[[Category:Fruit trees]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the fruit}}\n{{short description|citrus fruit}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Grapefruit\n| image = Grapefruit-Whole-&-Split.jpg\n| image_caption = Pink grapefruit\n| genus = Citrus\n| species = {{hybrid}} paradisi\n| authority = Macfad.\n}}\n\nThe '''grapefruit ''' (''Citrus \u00d7 paradisi'') is a [[subtropics|subtropical]] [[citrus]] tree known for its relatively large sour to semi-sweet, somewhat bitter [[fruit]].<ref name=\"morton\">{{cite book |author=Morton, Julia Frances |title=Grapefruit, Citrus paradisi. In: Fruits of Warm Climates, p 152\u2013158|publisher=NewCROP, New Crop Resource Online Program, Center for New Crops and Plant Products, Department of Horticulture and Landscape Architecture, Purdue University |year=1987 |isbn=978-0-9610184-1-2 |oclc= 16947184 |url=http://www.hort.purdue.edu/newcrop/morton/grapefruit.html}}</ref> Grapefruit is a citrus [[hybrid (biology)|hybrid]] originating in [[Barbados]] as an accidental cross between the [[orange (fruit)|sweet orange]] (''C. sinensis'') and [[pomelo]] (or shaddock) (''C. maxima''), both of which were introduced from Asia in the seventeenth century.<ref name=\"Carrington & Fraser\">{{cite book |last1=Carrington |first1=Sean |last2=Fraser |first2=HenryC |title=A~Z of Barbados Heritage |edition= |series= |year=2003 |publisher=Macmillan Caribbean |location= |isbn=978-0-333-92068-8 |pages=90\u201391 |chapter=Grapefruit |quote=One of many citrus species grown in Barbados. This fruit is believed to have originated in Barbados as a natural cross between sweet orange (''C. sinesis'') and Shaddock (''C. grandis''), both of which originated in Asia and were introduced by Europeans in the seventeenth century. The grapefruit first appeared as an illustration entitled \"The Forbidden Fruit Tree\" in ''The Natural History of Barbados'' (1750) by Rev. Griffith Hughes. This accords with the scientific name which literally is \"citrus of paradise\". The fruit seems to have been fairly commonly available around that time, since George Washington in his Barbados Journal (1750-1751) mentions \"the Forbidden Fruit\" as one of the local fruit available at a dinner party he attended. The plant was later described in the 1837 ''Flora of Jamaica'' as the Barbados Grapefruit. The historical arguments and experimental work on leaf enzymes and oils from possible parents all support a Barbadian origin for the fruit.}}</ref> When found, it was nicknamed the \"[[forbidden fruit]]\".<ref name=morton/> Frequently, it is misidentified as the very similar parent species, [[pomelo]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Li|first=Xiaomeng|author2=Xie R.|author3=Lu Z.|author4=Zhou Z.|title=The Origin of Cultivated Citrus as Inferred from Internal Transcribed Spacer and Chloroplast DNA Sequence and Amplified Fragment Length Polymorphism Fingerprints|journal=Journal of the American Society for Horticultural Science|date=July 2010|volume=135|issue=4|page=341|url=http://journal.ashspublications.org/content/135/4/341.full|accessdate=27 February 2013|doi=10.21273/JASHS.135.4.341|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424191429/http://journal.ashspublications.org/content/135/4/341.full|archive-date=24 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe ''grape'' part of the name alludes to clusters of fruit on the tree that often appear similar to [[grape]] clusters.<ref name=\"loc.gov\">[https://www.loc.gov/rr/scitech/mysteries/grapefruit.html \"How did the grapefruit get its name?\"] [[Library of Congress]]. Science Reference Service, Everyday Mysteries. Retrieved August 2, 2009.</ref> The interior flesh is segmented and varies in color from white to yellow to red to pink.\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Grapefruit.ebola.jpeg|thumb|upright|Grapefruit growing in the grape-like clusters from which their name derives]]\nThe evergreen grapefruit trees usually grow to around {{convert|5|\u2013|6|m|ft|sp=us}} tall, although they may reach {{convert|13|\u2013|15|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=morton/> The leaves are glossy, dark green, long (up to {{convert|15|cm|in|sp=us}}), and thin. It produces {{convert|5|cm|in|0|abbr=on}} white four-petaled [[flower]]s. The fruit is yellow-orange skinned and generally, an [[oblate spheroid]] in shape; it ranges in diameter from {{convert|10|\u2013|15|cm|in|abbr=on}}. The flesh is segmented and [[acid]]ic, varying in color depending on the [[cultivar]]s, which include white, pink, and red pulps of varying sweetness (generally, the redder varieties are the sweetest).<ref name=morton/> The 1929 U.S. Ruby Red<ref name=morton/> (of the Redblush variety) has the first grapefruit [[patent]].<ref name=\"txsweet\">[http://www.texasweet.com/About-Texas-Citrus/Texas-Grapefruit-History Texas grapefruit history] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101128162502/http://texasweet.com/About-Texas-Citrus/Texas-Grapefruit-History |date=2010-11-28 }}, TexaSweet. Retrieved 2 July 2008.</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe genetic origin of the grapefruit is a hybrid mix.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Xiaomeng Li|author2=Rangjin Xie|author3=Zhenhua Lu|author4=Zhiqin Zhou|title=Genetic origin of cultivated citrus determined: Researchers find evidence of origins of orange, lime, lemon, grapefruit, other citrus species|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2011/01/110118101600.htm|website=Science Daily|accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref> One ancestor of the grapefruit was the Jamaican [[sweet orange]] (''Citrus sinensis''), itself an ancient hybrid of Asian origin; the other was the Indonesian [[pomelo]] (''C. maxima'').<ref name=morton/> One story of the fruit's origin is that a certain \"Captain Shaddock\"<ref name=morton/><ref name=\"Kumamoto\">{{cite journal|last=Kumamoto|first=J.|last2=Scora|first2=R. W.|last3=Lawton|first3=H. W.|last4=Clerx|first4=W. A.|date=1987-01-01|title=Mystery of the forbidden fruit: Historical epilogue on the origin of the grapefruit, Citrus paradisi (Rutaceae)|journal=Economic Botany|volume=41|issue=1|pages=97\u2013107|doi=10.1007/BF02859356|issn=0013-0001}}</ref> brought pomelo seeds to Jamaica and bred the first fruit,<ref name=\"culinaire\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20080502135258/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0JAW/is_87/ai_n25336559 Grapefruit: a fruit with a bit of a complex] in ''Art Culinaire'' (Winter, 2007)</ref> although it probably originated as a naturally occurring hybrid between the two plants some time after they had been introduced there.<ref name=morton/><ref name=\"Carrington & Fraser\"/>\n\n{{Quote box\n| align = right\n| title = Forbidden-Fruit-Tree\n| quote = <poem>\nThe Trunk, Leaves, and Flowers of this Tree, very much resemble\nthose of the Orange-tree.\nThe Fruit, when ripe, is something longer and larger than the largest\nOrange; and exceeds, in the Delicacy of its Taste, the Fruit of every\nTree in this or any of our neighbouring Islands.\nIt hath somewhat of the Taste of a Shaddock; but far exceeds that, as\nwell as the best Orange, in its delicious Taste and Flavour.\n</poem>\n| source = \u2014Description from Hughes' 1750 ''Natural History of Barbados''\n}}\nThe hybrid fruit, then called \"the forbidden fruit\", was first documented in 1750 by a [[Wales|Welshman]], Rev. [[Griffith Hughes]], who described specimens from Barbados in ''The Natural History of Barbados''.<ref name=morton/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldwidewords.org/qa/qa-gra3.htm|title=World Wide Words: Grapefruit|website=World Wide Words|access-date=2017-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.welchmanhallgullybarbados.com/index.php |title=Welchman Hall Gully, Barbados |author=Admin |year=2010 |publisher=[[Barbados National Trust]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100816070727/http://www.welchmanhallgullybarbados.com/index.php |archivedate=16 August 2010 |accessdate=11 July 2010 |quote=The Development of the Gully - The Gully was once part of a plantation owned by a Welshman called General William Asygell Williams over 200 years ago. Hence the name \"Welchman Hall\" gully. It was this man who first developed the gully with exotic trees and an orchard. Interestingly, the grapefruit is originally from Barbados and is rumoured to have started in Welchman Hall Gully. |url-status=dead }}</ref> Currently, the grapefruit is said to be one of the \"Seven Wonders of Barbados\".<ref>Barbados Seven Wonders: The Grapefruit Tree. [http://www.barbados.org/grapefrt.htm Abstract]</ref>\n\nThe grapefruit was brought to Florida by Count [[Odet Philippe]] in 1823 in what is now known as [[Safety Harbor]].<ref name=morton/> Further crosses have produced the [[tangelo]] (1905), the [[Minneola tangelo]] (1931), and the [[oroblanco]] (1984).\n\nThe grapefruit was known as the ''shaddock'' or ''shattuck'' until the nineteenth century.<ref name=morton/><ref name=\"Kumamoto\"/> Its current name alludes to clusters of the fruit on the tree, which often appear similar to that of [[grape]]s.<ref name=\"loc.gov\"/> Botanically, it was not distinguished from the pomelo until the 1830s, when it was given the name ''Citrus paradisi.'' Its true origins were not determined until the 1940s. This led to the official name being altered to ''Citrus \u00d7 paradisi,'' the \"\u00d7\" identifying its hybrid origin.<ref name=\"Texas_Citrus\">Texas Citrus: Puzzling Beginnings. [http://www.texasweet.com/texascitrus/grapefruit.html Article] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070125112342/http://www.texasweet.com/texascitrus/grapefruit.html |date=2007-01-25}}</ref><ref name=\"University_of_Florida\">University of Florida: IFAS Extension; The Grapefruit. {{cite web |url= http://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/pdffiles/CH/CH06300.pdf |title= Fact Sheet |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070628190748/http://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/pdffiles/CH/CH06300.pdf |archivedate= 2007-06-28 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:KC Atwood.jpg|thumb|upright|Kimball Atwood]]\nAn early pioneer in the American citrus industry was Kimball Atwood, a wealthy entrepreneur who founded the Atwood Grapefruit Company in the late nineteenth century. The Atwood Grove became the largest grapefruit grove in the world, with a yearly output of 80,000 boxes of fruit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20040816/NEWS/408160323?tc=ar |title=Manatee County a big part of citrus history |publisher=HeraldTribune.com |date=2004-08-16 |accessdate=2011-12-17}}</ref> It was there that pink grapefruit was first discovered in 1906.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hort.purdue.edu/newcrop/morton/grapefruit.html|title=Grapefruit|website=www.hort.purdue.edu|access-date=2017-03-30}}</ref>\n\n===Ruby Red===\n[[File:Citrus paradisi (Grapefruit, pink) white bg.jpg|thumb|\"Red\" grapefruit]]\nThe 1929 Ruby Red (or ''Redblush'') patent was associated with real commercial success, which came after the discovery of a red grapefruit growing on a pink variety.<ref name=morton/> [[Atomic gardening|Using radiation to trigger mutations]], new varieties were developed to retain the red tones which typically faded to pink.<ref>{{cite news |author=William J Broad |title=Useful Mutants, Bred With Radiation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/28/science/28crop.html?_r=1&pagewanted=print&oref=slogin |work=New York Times |date=28 August 2007}}</ref> The Rio Red variety is the current (2007) Texas grapefruit with registered trademarks Rio Star and Ruby-Sweet, also sometimes promoted as \"Reddest\" and \"Texas Choice\". The Rio Red is a [[mutation breeding|mutation bred]] variety that was developed by treatment of bud sticks with thermal neutrons. Its improved attributes of mutant variety are fruit and juice color, deeper red, and wide adaptation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mvgs.iaea.org/Search.aspx?ID=282|title=MVD|website=mvgs.iaea.org|access-date=2017-03-30}}</ref>\n\n===Star Ruby===\nThe Star Ruby is the darkest of the red varieties.<ref name=morton/> Developed from an [[irradiation|irradiated]] Hudson grapefruit,<ref>{{cite journal |last=Ahloowalia |first=B.S. |last2=Maluszynski |first2=M. |last3=Nichterlein |first3=K. |date=2004 |title=Global impact of mutation-derived varieties |journal=Euphytica |volume=135 |issue=2 |pages=187\u2013204 |doi=10.1023/B:EUPH.0000014914.85465.4f }}</ref> it has found limited commercial success because it is more difficult to grow than other varieties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aggie-horticulture.tamu.edu/citrus/grapefruit.htm|title=Home fruit Production-Grapefruit|last=Sauls|first=Julian W.|year=1998|accessdate=2013-07-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citrusvariety.ucr.edu/citrus/starruby.html|title=Star Ruby grapefruit|author=Citrus Variety Collection|accessdate=2013-07-22}}</ref>\n\n==Varieties==\nThe varieties of [[Texas]] and [[Florida]] grapefruit include: Oro Blanco, Ruby Red, Pink, Rio Star, Thompson, White Marsh, Flame, Star Ruby, Duncan, and Pummelo HB.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gofloridagrapefruit.com/florida-grown/ |title=Go Florida Grapefruit |publisher=Go Florida Grapefruit |accessdate=2011-12-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110910120645/http://www.gofloridagrapefruit.com/florida-grown/ |archivedate=2011-09-10 }}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nIn 2018, world production of grapefruits (combined with pomelos) was 9.4 million tonnes, led by China with 53% of the world total. Secondary producers were [[Vietnam]] and the United States.<ref name=fao18/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; clear:left; width:18em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=2|Grapefruit production in 2018\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ddf; width:25%;\"| Country\n! style=\"background:#ddf; width:15%;\"| Production <br /><small>(millions of [[tonne]]s)</small>\n|-\n| <center>{{CHN}} </center>|| <center>5.0</center>\n|-\n| <center>{{VIE}} </center>|| <center>0.7</center>\n|-\n| <center>{{USA}} </center>|| <center>0.6</center>\n|-\n| <center>{{MEX}} </center>|| <center>0.5</center>\n|-\n| <center>{{SAF}} </center>|| <center>0.4</center>\n|-\n| <center>{{IND}} </center>|| <center>0.3</center>\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#ccc;\"\n|<center>'''World''' </center>||<center> '''9.4'''</center>\n|-\n|colspan=2|<small>Source: [[FAOSTAT]] of the [[United Nations]]</small><ref name=\"fao18\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/faostat/en/#data/QC|title= Grapefruit production in 2018, Crops/Regions/World list/Production Quantity (pick lists)|date=2019|publisher=UN Food and Agriculture Organization, Corporate Statistical Database (FAOSTAT)|accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Colors and flavors==\n[[File:Grapefruit-mercaptan-2D-skeletal-vertical.png|80px|thumb|Grapefruit mercaptan]]\nGrapefruit varieties are differentiated by the flesh color of fruit they produce. Common varieties are [[red]], [[white]], and [[pink]] pulp colors. Flavors range from highly acidic and somewhat sour to sweet and tart, resulting from composition of sugars (mainly [[sucrose]]), [[organic acid]]s (mainly citric acid), and [[monoterpene]]s and [[sesquiterpene]]s providing aromas.<ref name=\"Zheng\">{{cite journal | last=Zheng | first=Huiwen | last2=Zhang | first2=Qiuyun | last3=Quan | first3=Junping | last4=Zheng | first4=Qiao | last5=Xi | first5=Wanpeng | title=Determination of sugars, organic acids, aroma components, and carotenoids in grapefruit pulps | journal=Food Chemistry | volume=205 | year=2016 | issn=0308-8146 | doi=10.1016/j.foodchem.2016.03.007 | pages=112\u2013121|pmid=27006221}}</ref>\n\n[[Grapefruit mercaptan]], a [[sulfur]]-containing [[terpene]], is one of the [[aroma compound]]s influencing taste and [[odor]] of grapefruit, compared with other citrus fruits.<ref name=\"Andrea_Buettner_and_Peter_Schieberle\">{{cite journal\n| title= Characterization of the Most Odor-Active Volatiles in Fresh, Hand-Squeezed Juice of Grapefruit (''Citrus paradisi Macfayden'')\n| author1=A. Buettner |author2=P. Schieberle |journal= J. Agric. Food Chem.\n| year= 1999\n| volume= 47\n| pages= 5189\u20135193\n| doi= 10.1021/jf990071l\n| pmid= 10606593\n| issue= 12}}</ref>\n\n==Drug interactions==\n{{Main|Grapefruit\u2013drug interactions}}\n\nGrapefruit and [[grapefruit juice]] have been found to [[drug interaction|interact]] with numerous [[drugs]] and in many cases, to result in adverse direct and/or side effects (if dosage is not carefully adjusted.)<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Bailey DG, Dresser G, Arnold JM |title=Grapefruit-medication interactions: forbidden fruit or avoidable consequences? |journal=CMAJ |volume=185 |issue=4 |pages=309\u201316 |date=March 2013 |pmid=23184849 |pmc=3589309 |doi=10.1503/cmaj.120951}}</ref>\n\nThis happens in two very different ways. In the first, the effect is from [[bergamottin]], a natural [[furanocoumarin]] in both grapefruit flesh and peel that inhibits the [[CYP3A4]] [[enzyme]], (among others from the [[P450]] enzyme family responsible for metabolizing 90% of drugs). The action of the CYP3A4 enzyme itself is to [[metabolism|metabolize]] many medications.<ref name=\"CYP3A4 inhibition\">{{cite web|last1=Renee|first1=Janet|title=Does Grapefruit Inhibit Liver Enzymes?|url=http://healthyeating.sfgate.com/grapefruit-inhibit-liver-enzymes-10445.html|website=sfgate.com|publisher=SF Gate|accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Mitchell May 2016\">{{cite web|last1=Mitchell|first1=Steve|title=Why Grapefruit and Medication Can Be a Dangerous Mix|url=http://www.consumerreports.org/health/grapefruit-and-medications-can-be-a-dangerous-mix/|website=Consumer Reports|accessdate=4 May 2016|date=19 February 2016}}</ref> If the drug's breakdown for removal is lessened, then the level of the drug in the blood may become too high or stay too long, leading to [[adverse effect]]s.<ref name=\"Mitchell May 2016\"/> On the other hand, some drugs must be broken down to become active, and inhibiting [[CYP3A4]] may lead to reduced drug effects.\n\nThe other effect is that grapefruit can block the absorption of drugs in the intestine.<ref name=\"Mitchell May 2016\"/> If the drug is not absorbed, then not enough of it is in the blood to have a therapeutic effect.<ref name=\"Mitchell May 2016\"/> Each affected drug has either a specific increase of effect or decrease.\n\nOne whole grapefruit, or a glass of {{convert|200|mL|usoz|abbr=on}} of grapefruit juice may cause drug overdose toxicity.<ref name=\"BaileyDresser2012\">{{cite journal|last1=Bailey|first1=D. G.|last2=Dresser|first2=G.|last3=Arnold|first3=J. M. O.|title=Grapefruit-medication interactions: Forbidden fruit or avoidable consequences?|journal=Canadian Medical Association Journal|volume=185|issue=4|year=2012|pages=309\u2013316|issn=0820-3946|doi=10.1503/cmaj.120951|pmid=23184849|pmc=3589309}}</ref> Typically, drugs that are incompatible with grapefruit are so labeled on the container or [[package insert]].<ref name=\"Mitchell May 2016\"/> People taking drugs should ask their health care provider or pharmacist questions about grapefruit and drug interactions.<ref name=\"Mitchell May 2016\"/>\n\n==Nutrition==\n{{Nutritional value\n| name=Grapefruit, raw, white, all areas\n| kJ=138\n| protein=.8 g\n| fat=0.10 g\n| water=90.48 g\n| carbs=8.41 g\n| fiber=1.1 g\n| sugars=7.31 g\n| glucose=\n| fructose=\n| iron_mg=0.06\n| manganese_mg=0.013\n| calcium_mg=12\n| magnesium_mg=9\n| phosphorus_mg=8\n| potassium_mg=148\n| zinc_mg=0.07\n| vitC_mg=33.3\n| pantothenic_mg=0.283\n| vitB6_mg=0.043\n| folate_ug=10\n| choline_mg=7.7\n| thiamin_mg=0.037\n| riboflavin_mg=0.020\n| niacin_mg=0.269\n| vitE_mg=0.13\n| source_usda=1\n| note=[http://ndb.nal.usda.gov/ndb/search/list?qlookup=09116&format=Full Link to USDA Database entry]\n}}\n\nRaw grapefruit is 90% water, 8% [[carbohydrate]]s, 1% [[protein]], and contains negligible [[fat]] (table). In a 100 gram reference amount, raw grapefruit provides 33 [[calorie]]s and is a rich source of [[vitamin C]] (40% of the [[Daily Value]]), with no other [[micronutrient]]s in significant content.\n\n===Citric acid===\nGrapefruit juice contains about half the [[citric acid]] of [[Lime (fruit)|lime]] or [[lemon]] juice, and about 50% more citric acid than [[Orange (fruit)|orange]] juice.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Penniston KL, Nakada SY, Holmes RP, Assimos DG | title=Quantitative Assessment of Citric Acid in Lemon Juice, Lime Juice, and Commercially-Available Fruit Juice Products | journal=Journal of Endourology | volume=22 | issue=3 | year=2008 | pmid=18290732 | pages = 567\u2013570 | doi = 10.1089/end.2007.0304 | pmc=2637791}}</ref>\n\n==Grapefruit sweets==\nIn [[Costa Rica]], especially in [[Atenas]], grapefruit are often cooked to remove their sourness, rendering them as [[Confectionery|sweets]]; they are also stuffed with ''[[dulce de leche]]'', resulting in a [[dessert]] called ''toronja rellena'' (stuffed grapefruit).<ref>{{cite book|editor=Ben Box|others=Sarah Cameron, Sebastian Ballard|title=1994 Mexico & Central America Handbook|edition=4|year=1993|publisher=Trade and Travel Publications Ltd|location=Bath, England|language=English|isbn=978-0900751462|page=682|chapter=Costa Rica - The Meseta Central}}</ref> In [[Haiti]], grapefruit is used primarily for its juice (''jus de Chad\u00e8que''), but also is used to make jam (''confiture de Chad\u00e8que'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memoireonline.com/03/09/2031/Standardisation-dune-formulation-de-confiture-de-chadeque-et-evaluation-des-parametres-physico-chim.html |title=Standardisation d'une formulation de confiture de chad\u00e8que et \u00e9valuation des param\u00e8tres physico-chimiques, microbiologiques et sensoriels |editor=Monrose, Gregory Salomon |publisher=Universit\u00e9 d'Etat d'Haiti (UEH / FAMV) - Ingenieur Agronome 2009|via=Memoire Online|accessdate=5 June 2017|language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor=Bidault, Blandine|editor2=Gattegno, Isabelle |page=46 |year=1984 |title=Le point sur la transformation des fruits tropicaux. |publisher=Groupe de recherche et d'echanges technologiques (GRET) |location=Paris |language=fr}}</ref>\n\n== Parasites ==\nGrapefruits are one of the most common hosts for fruit flies like ''[[Anastrepha suspensa|A. suspensa]]'', which will lay their eggs in overripe or spoiled grapefruits.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=van Whervin|first=L. Walter|date=March 1974|title=Some Fruitflies (Tephritidae) in Jamaica|journal=PANS Pest Articles & News Summaries|volume=20|issue=1|pages=11\u201319|doi=10.1080/09670877409412331|issn=0030-7793}}</ref> The larvae of these flies will then consume the fruit in order to gain nutrients until they can proceed into the pupae stage. This parasitism has led to millions in economic costs for nations in Central America and Southern North America.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Fruit fly pests : a world assessment of their biology and management|last=McPheron, Bruce A. Steck, Gary J.|date=1996|publisher=St. Lucie Press|isbn=1574440144|oclc=34343237}}</ref>\n\n==Other uses==\nGrapefruit has also been investigated in cancer medicine [[pharmacodynamics]]. Its inhibiting effect on the [[metabolism]] of some drugs may allow smaller doses to be used, which can help to reduce costs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/560026|title=Cut Cancer Drug Costs By Exploring Food Interactions|first=Allison|last=Gandey|date=July 18, 2007|work=[[Medscape]]|access-date=2017-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn aromatherapy, the fruity aroma of grapefruit is believed to have an uplifting and stimulating effect on the mind, inhaling the aroma of grapefruit can be used to help combat tiredness or mental exhaustion.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nLifestyle magazines and websites sometimes recommend grapefruit as a stain remover for porcelain and enamel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.wikihow.com/Clean-Your-Bathtub-with-Grapefruit-and-Salt?amp=1|title=How to Clean Your Bathtub with Grapefruit and Salt: 6 Steps|website=m.wikihow.com|access-date=2019-03-08}}{{user-generated inline|date=September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apartmenttherapy.com/how-to-clean-a-bathtub-naturally-with-grapefruit-salt-117590|title=How To Naturally Clean a Bathtub with Grapefruit and Salt|website=Apartment Therapy|access-date=2019-03-08}}</ref>\n\n==Grapefruit relatives==\n{{Main|Citrus taxonomy}}\nGrapefruit is a pomelo [[backcross]], a hybrid of [[pomelo]] \u00d7 [[sweet orange]], with sweet orange itself being a [[pomelo]] \u00d7 [[mandarin orange|mandarin]] hybrid.\n\nThe grapefruit is a parent to many hybrids:\n* A [[Tangelo]] is any hybrid of a [[tangerine]] and either a [[pomelo]] or a grapefruit\n** '[[Tangelo#Minneola|Minneola]]': [[Duncan grapefruit]] \u00d7 [[Dancy (fruit)|Dancy tangerine]]<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|date=1987|chapter=Tangelo|pages=158\u2013160|title=Fruits of warm climates|first=Julia F.|last=Morton|author-link=Julia Morton|location=Miami, FL. |isbn=0-9610184-1-0|chapter-url=https://www.hort.purdue.edu/newcrop/morton/tangelo.html|url=https://www.hort.purdue.edu/newcrop/morton/index.html}}</ref>\n** 'Orlando' (formerly 'Take'): [[Bowen grapefruit]] \u00d7 [[Dancy (fruit)|Dancy tangerine]](pollen parent)<ref name=\":0\"/>\n*** [[Fairchild (fruit)|Fairchild]] is a [[Clementine]] \u00d7 Orlando hybrid\n** 'Seminole': [[Bowen grapefruit]] \u00d7 [[Dancy (fruit)|Dancy tangerine]]<ref name=\":0\"/>\n** 'Thornton': [[tangerine]] \u00d7 grapefruit, unspecified<ref name=\":0\"/>\n** '[[Ugli fruit|Ugli]]': [[mandarin orange|mandarin]] \u00d7 grapefruit, probable (wild seedling)<ref name=\":0\"/>\n** 'Nova' is a second-generation hybrid: [[Clementine]] \u00d7 Orlando tangelo cross<ref name=\":0\"/>\n* The [[Oroblanco]] and [[Melogold]] grapefruits are hybrids between pummelo (''Citrus maxima'') and the grapefruit\n\nThe grapefruit's cousins include:\n* Common [[sweet orange]]: [[pummelo]] \u00d7 [[mandarin orange|mandarin]] hybrid\n* [[Bitter orange]]: a different [[pummelo]] \u00d7 [[mandarin orange|mandarin]] hybrid\n* [[Mandelo]]s: pummelo \u00d7 [[mandarin orange|mandarine]] (''[[Citrus maxima]]'')\n* [[Hyuganatsu]] may also be a pummelo hybrid\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Grapefruit knife]]\n* [[Grapefruit spoon]]\n* [[Grapefruit\u2013drug interactions]]\n* [[Naringenin]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Wiktionary|grapefruit}}\n{{Commons category|Citrus Paradisi group}}\n* {{Wikispecies-inline|Citrus paradisi}}\n\n{{Citrus}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q41350}}\n\n[[Category:Citrus hybrids]]\n[[Category:Citrus]]\n[[Category:Flora of Barbados]]\n[[Category:Flora of Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Grapefruit|*]]\n[[Category:Tropical agriculture]]\n[[Category:Fruit trees]]\n", "name_user": "2601:883:4280:99b0:615d:6fef:3de3:bc46", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grapefruit"}
{"title_page": "Long Beach State Beach men's volleyball", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2010}}\n{{Infobox college volleyball team|AIAW=no\n|name = Long Beach State Beach\n|logo = Beach-Big.png\n|logo_size = 175\n|university = Long Beach State University\n|conference = Mountain Pacific Sports Federation\n|conference_short = Big West\n|division =\n|city = Long Beach\n|stateabb = CA\n|state = California\n|coach = [[Alan Knipe]]\n|tenure = 16th\n|arena = [[Walter Pyramid]], 2019\n|capacity = 5,000\n|nickname = LB 49ers\n|NCAAchampion = 1991, 2018, 2019\n|NCAArunnerup = 1970, 1973, 1990, 1999, 2004\n|NCAAfinalfour = 1970, 1973, 1990, 1991, 1999, 2004, 2008, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019\n|NCAAtourneys = 1970, 1971, 1972, 1973, 1978, 1981, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1990, 1991, 1999, 2004, 2008, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019\n|conference_tournament = 1973, 1990, 1991, 2017, 2018\n|conference_season = SCIVA: 1973 <br />WIVA: 1990, 1992 <br />MPSF: 1999, 2000, 2001, 2008, 2017 <br />Big West: 2018, 2019\n}}\n\nThe '''Long Beach State Beach men's volleyball''' team is the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] Division I men's volleyball team for the [[California State University, Long Beach|Long Beach State University]]. [[Alan Knipe]] is the current head coach of 14 years, though he's been with the program since 2001.\n\n==Program record and history==\n<small>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\"|Year\n! style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\"|Head Coach\n! style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\"|Overall <br /> Record\n! style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\"|Conference<br /> Record\n! style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\"|Conference<br /> Standing\n! style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\"|Postseason\n|-\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead|\n|name=\n|startyear=1970\n|conference=''[[SCIVA Conderence|SCIVA]]''\n|endyear=1978\n|}}\n|-\n| 1970\n| Randy Sandefur\n| 6\u20134\n| 3\u20132\n| 3rd\n| [[1970 NCAA Division I Men's Volleyball Tournament|NCAA]] Runners-up