Team facts==\n\n===Head coach===\n* 1970\u20131974: Randy Sandefur\n* 1975\u20131976: Miles Pabst\n* 1977\u20131980: Dick Montgomery\n* 1981: Don Paris\n* 1982\u20132000: Ray Ratelle\n* 2001\u2013present: Alan Knipe\n: Alan Knipe's win-loss record presently stands at 334-149 (.692 percentage).  He has been to the final four a total of eight times: twice as a player (1990, 1991) and six as a coach (2004, 2008, 2016, 2017, 2018 and 2019).  He was a member of Long Beach's\u20141991--[[NCAA]] Men's VB National Championship Team; coming up a game short in coaching the 2004 team to NCAA Runners-up, he coached the 49ers to its second and third [[NCAA]]championships in 2018 and 2019.  He was the head coach of the U.S. National Team, until 2012, and he returned to [[LBSU]] upon completing his service.\n\n===Conference===\n* 1970\u20131978: SCIVA\n** Overall Record (incomplete): 50\u201356\n* 1979\u20131985: CIVA\n** Overall Record: 114\u201382\n* 1986\u20131992: WIVA\n** Overall Record: 165\u201368\n* 1993\u20132017: [[Mountain Pacific Sports Federation]] (MPSF)\n** Overall Record: @Good, ~79.5%\n* 2018\u2013present: Big West Conference\n** Overall Record: 19-1\n\n===Home court===\nThe volleyball team played in the Goldmine gymnasium at CSULB until 1994.  Since November 30, 1994, the team has played at the [[Walter Pyramid]].  The 18-story tall complex has played host twice to the NCAA Men's Volleyball Championships (2001, 2003).  Its infrastructure utilizes 18,000 steel tubes and connection modules.  It cost approximately $22 million to build.\n\n===National championships===\n* 1991: NCAA by defeating [[University of Southern California|USC]]\n\nWith an overall record of 31 wins and just 4 losses, the 1991 NCAA Men's Volleyball Champions swept three out of their five post-season opponents.  In the WIVA Tournament (Irvine, CA) the 49ers beat [[UCSB]] and [[San Diego State University|SDSU]] 3\u20130 before overcoming county/national nemesis, the [[UCLA]] Bruins 3\u20132.  From there it was on to Hawaii for the '91 Final Four.  'the Beach' said [[aloha]] to Penn State in a clean sweep 3\u20130; they then needed an extra game winning 3\u20131 over longtime rival [[University of Southern California|USC]] for their first national championship to date.\n\n1991's team included these mentionable leaders: Alan Knipe, Brent Hilliard (NCAA Final Four MVP), Brett Winslow, Jason Stimpfig and Ray Ratelle (Asics/VB Mag. & AVCA C.O.Y.).  No other 'BEACH' Men's VB Team has ever won as many games as this singular team; they were a combined 89% in their win-lost ratio.\n\n* 2018: Won second NCAA title by defeating UCLA 3-2 (at Westwood, [[Los Angeles]]). They defeated Ohio State University (defending national champions) 3-1 in the semi-finals. \n\nWith co-Valuables Josh Tunaniga, JR-Setter AND TJ DeFalco, JR-Outside Hitter, eight thousand in the stands were treated to a thrilling five-setter match (in overtime) favoring the men of south L.A. county.\n* 2019: Won third NCAA title by defeating Hawaii 3-1 (at Long Beach). LB defeated Pepperdine University 3-1 in the semi-finals.\n\n==Notable players==\n* '''[[Taylor Crabb]]''' \u2013 2013 AVCA P.O.Y.; AVCA 2013 & 2014 1st Team All-American, 2012 Volleyball Magazine 3rd Team All-American \n* '''[[Bob Ctvrtlik]]''' \u2013 Asics/VB Mag. honorable mention All-American (1983), First U.S. Olympic Team Member/49er who won Olympic Medals in men's volleyball (1988, gold; 1992, bronze)\n* '''[[Torey Defalco]]''' \u2013 a.k.a. The Brethren, T.J. DeFalco; 2017 and 2019 AVCA Player of the Year. 4-time AVCA First Team All-American\n* '''Tyler Hildebrand''' \u2013 4 yr starter who simultaneously doubled as the U.S. National Team's setter (2003\u20132012), 3-time AVCA\u2014and Asics/VB Mag.--1st Team All-American (2004\u20132006), all 3rd team [[MPSF]] 15th Yr. Anniversary Team.  Current Associate Coach (2013\u2013present).\n* '''Tim Hill''' \u2013 2-time all SCIVA Conference Player, [[Association of Volleyball Professionals|AVP]] Hall of Famer\n* '''[[Brent Hilliard]]''' \u2013 4-time All-American (1990 Asics/VB Mag. Freshman; AVCA 1st Team: 1991, 1992; AVCA 2nd Team: 1993; Asics/VB Mag. 1st Team: 1991\u2013'93), 1992 AVCA National Player of the Year, all 1st team [[MPSF]] 15th Yr. Anniversary Team, U.S. Olympic Team Member (1992, Bronze Medalist)\n* '''[[Tom Hoff]]''' \u2013 2-time AVCA\u2014and Asics/VB Mag.--1st Team All-American (1995, 1996), U.S. Olympic Team Member (2000; 2004; 2008, gold medalist), all 2nd Team [[MPSF]] 15th Yr. Anniversary Team, Collegiate triple-doubles leader (K-B-D)\n* '''Mark Kerins''' \u2013 Asics/VB Mag. 1st Team All-American (1990), Asics/VB Mag. 2nd Team All-American (1989), [[Association of Volleyball Professionals|AVP]] Beach Pro (1993\u20132000), Senior captain of the most superior 49er men's team assembled in [[LBSU]] history.\n* '''Alan Knipe''' \u2013 2-time AVCA\u2014and Asics/VB Mag.--All-American (1991, 2nd team; 1992, 1st team), 2004 AVCA Coach of the Year (LBSU Men's VB), U.S. National Team Coach (2009\u20132012), 2017 MPSF C.O.Y.\n* '''[[David Lee (volleyball)|David Lee]]''' \u2013 2004 AVCA 1st Team All-American, 2008 Olympic gold medalist.\n* '''Paul Lotman''' \u2013 2008 AVCA 1st Team All-American & National Player of the Year\n* '''David McKenzie''' \u2013 3-time All-American (AVCA 2nd Team: 1999, AVCA 1st Team: 2000, 2001 & Asics/VB Mag. 2nd Team: 1999, Asics/VB Mag. 3rd Team: 2000), holds the NCAA record for kills in a game (58/106 attempts), all 3rd team [[MPSF]] 15th Yr. Anniversary Team, sibling to Joy Fuerbringer (class of 1993, NCAA National Women's VB Champion, AVCA All-American)\n* '''Miles Pabst''' \u2013 2-time All-American who led the team to the 1973 NCAA Final Four, U.S. National Team Member, First 49er to return to [[LBSU]] as head coach (1975\u20131976)\n* '''Dodge Parker''' \u2013 Pioneer from VB factory [[Punahou School]] ('69 class), 1986 [[LBSU]] Hall of Fame Inductee, NCAA Men's VB (1970, 1973) & [[International Volleyball Association]]'s Star, U.S. National Team Member (1973\u2013'80ish)\n* '''Josh Tuaniga''' \u2013 2018 NCAA MVB POY. Four-time AVCA All-American (2016\u20132019), 2016 Off the Block all-Freshman, inaugural 2018 BWCT MVP.    \n* '''[[Brett Winslow]]''' \u2013 1996 Olympian and team captain of the 1991 national title squad.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.longbeachstate.com/sports/m-volley/lbst-m-volley-body.html}}\n\n{{California State University, Long Beach}}\n\n[[Category:Long Beach State Beach men's volleyball|*]]\n", "name_user": "FeverishAxe0", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProgram record and history", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_Beach_State_Beach_men%27s_volleyball"}
{"title_page": "Eric Greitens", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Eric Greitens\n|image        = Eric Greitens 2018.jpg\n|order        = 56th [[List of governors of Missouri|Governor of Missouri]]\n|lieutenant   = Mike Parson\n|term_start   = January 9, 2017\n|term_end     = June 1, 2018\n|predecessor  = [[Jay Nixon]]\n|successor    = [[Mike Parson]]\n|birth_name   = Eric Robert Greitens\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1974|04|10}}\n|birth_place  = [[St. Louis]], [[Missouri]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] (2015\u2013present)\n|otherparty   = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] (before 2015)\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Sheena Chestnut|2011}}\n|children     = 2\n|education    = [[Duke University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br />[[Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]] ([[Master of Arts|MPhil]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|DPhil]])\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States|}}\n|branch       = {{naval|United States}}\n|serviceyears = 2001\u2013present\n|rank         = [[File:US-O4 insignia.svg|23px]] [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]]\n|mawards      = [[File:Bronze Star ribbon.svg|23px|border]] [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]]<br />[[File:Purple Heart BAR.svg|border|23px]] [[Purple Heart]] \n}}\n'''Eric Robert Greitens''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0261|r|a\u026a|t|\u0259|n|z}};<ref>{{cite AV media |people=Greitens, Eric |date=June 6, 2016 |title=Eric Greitens: Taking Aim |medium=video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Yf2Gai1uQYM |access-date= April 12, 2018}}</ref> born April 10, 1974) is an American politician, humanitarian, author, and former [[Navy SEAL]] who was the [[List of Governors of Missouri|56th]] [[governor of Missouri]] from January 2017 until his resignation in June 2018 after a string of corruption allegations and felony charges.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hancock|first=Jason|url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article212114314.html|title=Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens resigns, ending political career once aimed at presidency|date=May 29, 2018|work=The Kansas City Star|access-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live|last2=Lowry|first2=Bryan}}</ref>\n\nBorn and raised in [[St. Louis]], Greitens received a doctorate from [[Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]], as a [[Rhodes scholar]]. During his four tours of duty as a U.S. Navy SEAL officer, he rose to the rank of [[United States Navy officer rank insignia|lieutenant commander]], commanded a unit targeting [[Al-Qaeda]], and was awarded a [[Bronze Star]] and a [[Purple Heart]]. Later, after being a [[White House Fellow]], Greitens founded a nonprofit organization, [[The Mission Continues]], to benefit veterans. In 2013, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' included him in its [[Time 100|list]] of the 100 most influential people in the world.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://time100.time.com/2013/04/18/time-100/slide/eric-greitens|title=The 2013 ''TIME'' 100| first=Mike |last=Mullen|journal=Time |accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter having been a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] during his early life, Greitens announced in 2015 that he had become a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]. He ran for governor of Missouri as a Republican in 2016. Greitens prevailed over three opponents in the [[2016 Missouri gubernatorial election#Republican primary|Republican primaries]] and then defeated Democratic state [[Attorney General of Missouri|Attorney General]] [[Chris Koster]] in the [[2016 Missouri gubernatorial election|general election]]. One of Greitens's signature accomplishments in office was signing Missouri's [[Right-to-work law|right-to-work]] law,<ref name=\":7\" /> which was later repealed by statewide referendum.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\nIn February 2018, St. Louis Circuit Attorney [[Kimberly Gardner]] charged Greitens with felony [[invasion of privacy]]. Gardner later also charged him with campaign-related offenses. Greitens was indicted on felony charges of computer tampering in April 2018;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/20/politics/eric-greitens-computer-tampering-charge/index.html|title=Missouri Gov. Greitens indicted on felony computer-tampering charge|last=Berg|first=Rebecca|date=|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> all charges were dropped in May 2018. Greitens resigned from office on June 1<ref>{{cite news|last1=Suntrup|first1=Jack|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/judge-greitens-team-must-turn-over-documents-from-his-dark/article_b3674fa9-5972-529e-b0a2-4c6ca010dc42.html|title=Embattled Gov. Eric Greitens resigns|date=May 30, 2018|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|access-date=|url-status=live|last2=Erickson|first2=Kurt}}</ref> after the Missouri Legislature commenced a special session to consider impeachment.<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.riverfronttimes.com/newsblog/2018/04/11/greitens-blasts-political-witch-hunt-just-before-impeachment-report-drops|title=Greitens Blasts 'Political Witch Hunt' Just Before Impeachment Report Drops|last=Fenske|first=Sarah|website=Riverfront Times|language=en|access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> In June 2018, Special Prosecutor Gerard Carmody began investigating Gardner and announced a seven-count felony indictment against the prosecution's lead investigator.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref name=\":22\" /> In February 2020, the Missouri Ethics Commission reported that its campaign investigation did not find wrongdoing on Greitens's part individually, or that he knew of two reporting issues that it found with his campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/13/politics/eric-greitens-no-wrongdoing-investigation-missouri/index.html|title=Investigation into former Missouri governor finds 'no evidence of any wrongdoing'|first=Rebecca |last=Buck|website=CNN|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> Greitens and his supporters have denied any criminal wrongdoing and have repeatedly called the allegations a \"political witch hunt\".<ref name=\":23\" />\n\n==Early life==\nGreitens was born on April 10, 1974, in [[St. Louis, Missouri]], a son of Becky and Rob Greitens.<ref name=nyt1>[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/07/fashion/weddings/sheena-chestnut-eric-greitens-weddings.html \"Sheena Chestnut, Eric Greitens\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', August 5, 2011.</ref> He was raised in his mother's [[Jewish]] faith; his father is [[Catholic]].<ref name=\"thetower\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thetower.org/article/can-this-jewish-republican-outsider-change-the-face-of-missouri-eric-greitens|title=Can This Jewish Republican Outsider Change the Face of Missouri?|work=The Tower| accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/magazine/2017/07/10/eric-greitens-missouri-governor/|title=Eric Greitens's Rising Star|first=John J.|last=Miller|date=July 10, 2017|website=[[National Review]]}}</ref> Greitens's mother retired as an early childhood special education teacher in St. Ann, Missouri, for the Pattonville School District. His father, also retired, was an accountant in St. Louis for the Department of Agriculture.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/07/fashion/weddings/sheena-chestnut-eric-greitens-weddings.html|title=Sheena Chestnut, Eric Greitens: Weddings|date=August 5, 2011|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 28, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>  Greitens graduated from [[Parkway North High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parkwayalumni.org/participate/hof/charter/greitens.html|title=Home of the Parkway Alumni Association|work=Parkway Alumni Association|accessdate=May 11, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324120058/http://www.parkwayalumni.org/participate/hof/charter/greitens.html|archive-date=March 24, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> He grew up as a Democrat.<ref name=\"Fox News\">{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/opinion/former-navy-seal-why-i-am-no-longer-a-democrat|title=Former Navy SEAL: Why I am no longer a Democrat|author1=Eric Greitens|publisher=[[Fox News]]|date=July 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nGreitens was an [[Angier Buchanan Duke|Angier B. Duke]] Scholar at [[Duke University]], where he studied ethics, philosophy, and public policy and graduated [[Summa Cum Laude|''summa cum laude'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abduke.org/scholars/viewfeatured.aspx?id=6b7913cf-b136-41a8-9595-2d11e7ffbe04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081226125105/http://www.abduke.org/scholars/viewfeatured.aspx?id=6b7913cf-b136-41a8-9595-2d11e7ffbe04|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 26, 2008|title=Featured Profiles|publisher=A.B. Duke Foundation|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}</ref> At Duke he contributed photographs to a Save the Children Foundation project involving refugees from the [[Rwandan genocide]] and the war in Bosnia. Some of his work appeared in the publication ''Children in War: Community Strategies for Healing''.<ref>[http://www.eric.ed.gov/PDFS/ED412009.pdf ''Children in War: Community Strategies for Healing''], ed.gov; accessed May 11, 2017.</ref><ref name=Beacon />\n\nBefore graduating from Duke in 1996, Greitens was selected as a [[Rhodes Scholar|Rhodes]]<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1995/12/11/us/32-are-named-rhodes-scholars.html?scp=1&sq=greitens&st=cse 32 Are Named Rhodes Scholars] AP National Desk, nytimes.com, December 11, 1995.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/1995/12/two-receive-rhodes |title=Two receive Rhodes |date=December 11, 1995 |last=Allen |first=Misty |work=dukechronicle.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510212008/http://dukechronicle.com/node/107778 |archive-date=May 10, 2010 |accessdate=November 1, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and a [[Truman Scholar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.truman.gov/meet-our-scholars?Year=1995|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929033242/http://www.truman.gov/meet-our-scholars?Year=1995|url-status=dead|title=Meet Our Scholars, 1995 Truman Scholars|archivedate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> He went on to attend [[Lady Margaret Hall]], a constituent college of the [[University of Oxford]], where he earned a [[MPhil|master's degree in philosophy]] in development studies in 1998 and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|doctorate in philosophy]] in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|title=Public service focus of Greitens' talk|url=https://source.wustl.edu/2010/03/public-service-focus-of-greitens-talk/|date=March 17, 2010}}</ref> Greitens is a former Senior Fellow at the Harry S. Truman School of Public Affairs at the [[University of Missouri]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://truman.missouri.edu/People/EricGreitens|title=Archived copy|accessdate=May 24, 2011|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110324095601/http://truman.missouri.edu/People/EricGreitens|archivedate=March 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Athletics ===\nGreitens is a sub-three-hour marathon runner and a winner of Shamrock Marathon at Camp Fallujah, Iraq. A boxer, he won two Oxford University Boxing Blues and the gold medal at the British Universities Sports Association's National Boxing Championships.<ref name=\":2\" /> Greitens has a black belt in [[Taekwondo]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.navytimes.com/news/your-navy/2017/12/12/missouri-gov-eric-greitens-a-former-navy-seal-touts-his-physical-feats/|title=Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens, a former Navy SEAL, touts his physical feats|last1=Balantine|first1=Summer|date=December 11, 2017|newspaper=Navy Times|access-date=June 28, 2019|agency=Associated Press|last2=Stafford|first2=Margaret}}</ref>\n\n=== Humanitarian work ===\nGreitens has done international humanitarian work in Rwanda, Cambodia, Albania, Mexico, India, the Gaza Strip, Croatia, and Bolivia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bigthink.com/videos/eric-greitens-why-i-became-a-navy-seal|title=Eric Greitens: Why I Became a Navy SEAL|date=September 4, 2011|website=Big Think|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> During his 2016 campaign for governor, he said, \"I have worked in Cambodia with kids who lost limbs to land mines and are survivors of polio. I\u2019ve worked in Bolivia with children of the street. I\u2019ve worked in one of Mother Teresa\u2019s homes for the destitute and dying.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/883fae53a7864ae89abe1f5e9a9bb94a|title=Missouri gubernatorial candidates on social issues|last=Press|first=The Associated|date=October 9, 2016|website=AP NEWS|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFor six weeks as a college student, Greitens worked at two refugee camps, the Puntizela camp outside Pula, Croatia, and the Gasinci camp outside Osijek, Croatia. Both are described in his book. Refugee camps in Croatia were temporary homes for Bosnians crossing the border.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.columbiamissourian.com/news/politifact_missouri/fact-check-greitens-worked-with-bosnian-refugees-but-location-less/article_f1b362f0-85a8-11e6-917e-e386578ae76b.html|title=FACT CHECK: Greitens worked with Bosnian refugees but location less clear|last=Alamdari|first=Natalia|website=Columbia Missourian|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> Greitens also traveled to Rwanda and Zaire as a volunteer U.N. photographer.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==Career==\nGreitens has taught public service at the Truman School of Public Affairs and was an adjunct professor of business ethics in the MBA program at the [[Olin School of Business]] at [[Washington University in St. Louis]].<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|title=Eric Greitens |url=http://now.tufts.edu/commencement-2012/eric-greitens|work =Tufts Now|date=May 20, 2012|publisher=[[Tufts University]]|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Faculty News:Bookshelf|work=Olin Business |url=https://olin.wustl.edu/docs/Communication/OlinBusinessMagazine_2011.pdf|issue=Fall 2011|page=11|publisher=[[Olin Business School]]|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=records>{{cite news|title=Records shed light on Missouri candidate Eric Greitens' income, sources|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article111904197.html|author=Hancock, Jason |date=November 1, 2016|work =[[Kansas City Star]]|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Armed services===\nGreitens matriculated at the [[Officer Candidate School (United States Navy)|United States Navy's Officer Candidate School]] in [[Pensacola, Florida]], in January 2001, graduating in May of that year as an ensign in the [[United States Navy Reserve]].{{sfn|Greitens|2011|p=133}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.veteransadvantage.com/cms/content/herovet-eric-greitens|title=Eric Greitens profile|last=Asfar|first=Roy|date=April 1, 2011|publisher=Veterans Advantage|accessdate=April 28, 2014}}</ref> He then began [[Basic Underwater Demolitions/SEAL]] (BUD/S) training in [[Coronado, California]],{{sfn|Greitens|2011|p=143\u201345}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navyseals.com/life-service| title=Archived copy| accessdate=May 24, 2011|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722154323/http://www.navyseals.com/life-service|archivedate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> graduating with Class 237 in February 2002.{{sfn|Greitens|2011|p=201}}\n\nGreitens rose to be a [[lieutenant commander]] in the [[United States Navy Reserve]]. During his active duty career, he was deployed four times, to [[Iraq]], [[Afghanistan]], the [[Horn of Africa]], and [[Southeast Asia]]. He was the commander of a joint special operations task unit, a [[Mark V Special Operations Craft]] detachment,{{sfn|Greitens|2011|p=235}} and an al-Qaeda targeting cell.{{sfn|Greitens|2011|p=271}} He was awarded the [[Bronze Star]], [[Purple Heart]], and the [[Combat Action Ribbon]].<ref name=\"Beacon\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://now.tufts.edu/commencement-2012/eric-greitens |title=Eric Greitens |publisher=Tufts University |website=Tufts Now |access-date=April 13, 2018 |year=2012 }}</ref> In 2011 the Association of the U.S. Navy named Greitens its Naval Reserve Junior Officer of the Year.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://now.tufts.edu/commencement-2012/eric-greitens|title=Eric Greitens|date=October 16, 2013|website=Tufts Now|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe has criticized the [[Veterans Administration]], saying of its employees, \"Even if you\u2019re only 40 percent disabled, they\u2019ll give you 100 percent disability in some cases.\" \"You have to think about the incentives of government workers. Guys in the VA don\u2019t get paid to help veterans lead productive lives. Their metrics are on how many people sign up for benefits.\" He feels such overuse strains the VA system and prevents vets from reintegrating into general society.<ref name=\"Beacon\">[http://freebeacon.com/politics/the-great-jewish-hope/ The Great Jewish Hope], ''[[Free Beacon]]'', Bill McMorris, February 19, 2015. Retrieved April 12, 2018.</ref>\n\nDuring a deployment in Thailand, Greitens learned of drug use by Navy personnel and initiated an investigation that led to their removal. In the Philippines Greitens's crew effectively shut down a transit site for a terrorist organization, according to an evaluation report.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/76bc2050643a49edbef75bae6f8fedd5|title=Greitens' displayed ambition, from childhood through career|last=Lieb|first=David a|date=May 13, 2018|website=AP NEWS|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> Greitens spent three months in charge of a 50-person unit in Manda Bay, Kenya, near the Somali border. He left full-time active duty to take a one-year White House fellowship, where he developed a program to get architecture and engineering students involved in rebuilding efforts after Hurricane Katrina.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.columbiatribune.com/e6d628f8-08cb-568f-80ec-31b7fa4ff9b2.html|title=Military records laud Missouri Senate, governor candidates|website=Columbia Daily Tribune|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> Greitens simultaneously remained in the Navy Reserves, leading a program that recruited high-level advisers for special military operations around the world.<ref name=\":4\" /> After his fellowship, he volunteered for a six-month tour in Iraq that began in October 2006.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==== Fallujah truck bombing ====\nOn March 28, 2007, two suicide bombers detonated trucks carrying chlorine gas at the Fallujah government complex where Greitens and other military personnel were sleeping. The attack was the seventh [[Chlorine bombings in Iraq|chlorine bombing]] in the [[Al Anbar Governorate|Al Anbar]] province of [[Iraq]] by [[Al-Qaeda|al Queda]]. Greitens was among about 15 who were wounded.<ref name=\":5\" /> \"The attack began at 6:33 a.m. with mortar fire, followed by two truck bombs and small arms fire. Iraqi Police identified the first suicide attacker and fired on the truck, causing it to detonate before reaching the compound,\" according to a [[Multi-National Force West|Multinational Forces West]] press release. \"Iraqi Army soldiers spotted the second suicide truck approaching the gate and engaged it with small arms fire, causing it to also detonate near the entrance of the compound.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2007/03/fallujah_government.php|title=Fallujah government center struck by chlorine suicide attack {{!}} FDD's Long War Journal|date=March 28, 2007|website=longwarjournal.org|language=en-US|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> Greitens received a [[Purple Heart]] after sustaining injuries from the bombing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2017/05/29/greitens-explains-navy-seal-leadership-style-vs-political-leadership-style/|title=Greitens explains Navy SEAL leadership style vs. political leadership style|date=May 29, 2017|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===White House fellowship===\n[[File:Eric Greitens 2011-5.jpg|thumb|Greitens speaking in 2011]]\nIn 2005 President [[George W. Bush]] appointed Greitens as a [[White House Fellow]].<ref>[http://www.whitehouse.gov/fellows/alumni/2005-06.html White House Fellows: Class of 2005-2006\" Online Article] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080616101956/http://www.whitehouse.gov/fellows/alumni/2005-06.html |date=June 16, 2008 }}, WhiteHouse.gov, July 16, 2008.</ref> As a White House Fellow he worked in the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development|Department of Housing and Urban Development]] (HUD)<ref>Hinman, Kristen. [http://www.riverfronttimes.com/2008-04-09/news/navy-seal-eric-greitens-has-come-home-to-st-louis-to-help-fellow-iraq-vets \"Captain America\"], ''Riverfront Times'', April 9, 2008.</ref> and developed a new program to assist with rebuilding efforts after [[Hurricane Katrina]]: the Universities Rebuilding America Partnership (URAP),<ref>\"Volume 3 Number 5: Universities Rebuilding America\", PD&R Periodicals: Research Works, May 1, 2006.{{cite web|url= http://www.huduser.org/periodicals/ResearchWorks/may_06/RW_vol3num5t1.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=April 27, 2008|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080502214837/http://www.huduser.org/periodicals/ResearchWorks/may_06/RW_vol3num5t1.html|archivedate=May 2, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huduser.org/periodicals/ResearchWorks/may_06/RW_vol3num5t1.html|title=Internet Archive Wayback Machine |date=September 27, 2015|accessdate=May 18, 2017|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130504100943/http://www.huduser.org/periodicals/Researchworks/may_06/RW_vol3num5t1.html|archivedate=May 4, 2013}}</ref> a $5.6 million effort to engage architecture and engineering students in the continued effort to rebuild [[New Orleans]]. During his time as a White House Fellow he co-founded the President's Higher Education Community Service Honor Roll Program.<ref>[http://truman.missouri.edu/wp-content/uploads/eric-greitens-cv.pdf \"Profile: Eric Greitens\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220191347/http://truman.missouri.edu/wp-content/uploads/eric-greitens-cv.pdf |date=February 20, 2015 }}, The Truman School of Public Affairs webpage, February 20, 2015.</ref>\n\n===Nonprofit work===\nAfter returning from Iraq, Greitens used his combat pay and the disability pay of two friends to start [[The Mission Continues]], a nonprofit organization whose goal is to \"challenge veterans to serve and lead in communities across America\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.missioncontinues.org/About/About_Us|title=Archived copy|accessdate=May 23, 2011| url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110528042213/http://www.missioncontinues.org/About/About_Us|archivedate=May 28, 2011}}</ref> It encourages veterans to heal themselves through public service by engaging in volunteer organizations across the country.<ref>Klein, Joe [http://time.com/3707640/clay-hunts-legacy-for-veterans \"Clay Hunt's Legacy for Veterans\"], ''Time'', February 16, 2015.</ref><ref>Shane III, Leo [http://www.militarytimes.com/story/veterans/careers/civilian/2014/11/20/mission-continue-jobs/19320641 Study: Volunteer work could help vets' careers], ''Military Times'', February 16, 2015.</ref> In 2014 it won the CLASSY Award for its effectiveness in active-duty and veteran services.<ref>\"[http://www.classyawards.org/exchange/the-mission-continues-drives-progress-for-active-duty-veteran-services The Mission Continues Drives Progress for Active Duty & Veteran Services] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220191247/http://www.classyawards.org/exchange/the-mission-continues-drives-progress-for-active-duty-veteran-services/ |date=February 20, 2015 }}\", CLASSY Award, February 16, 2015.</ref> Greitens stepped down as CEO in July 2014 and resigned from the board of directors in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.missioncontinues.org/about/our-board|title=Our Board - Mission Continues |publisher= Mission Continues|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newprofit.com/cgi-bin/iowa/do/invest/37.html?page=leadership |title=New Profit Inc.: The Mission Continues|publisher= Mission Continues|accessdate=May 11, 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105211219/http://newprofit.com/cgi-bin/iowa/do/invest/37.html?page=leadership |archive-date=November 5, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.draperrichards.org/fellows/mission.html|title=Internet Archive Wayback Machine|date=September 28, 2015| accessdate =May 18, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120103015210/http://www.draperrichards.org/fellows/mission.html|archivedate=January 3, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.missioncontinues.org/About/OurTeam/details/11 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522084346/http://www.missioncontinues.org/About/OurTeam/details/11 |archivedate=May 22, 2011 |df= }}</ref><ref>Brennan, Vince [http://www.bizjournals.com/stlouis/news/2014/07/02/the-mission-continues-greitens-steps-down.html \"The Mission Continues' Greitens steps down\"], ''St. Louis Business Journal'', February 20, 2015.</ref>\n\nAs CEO of The Mission Continues, Greitens worked without a salary in 2007\u201308. Later he received compensation between $150,000 and $200,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/organizations/208742553|title=Nonprofit Explorer|work =ProPublica| accessdate= May 11, 2017}}</ref> Daniel Borochoff, president and founder of [[CharityWatch]], which evaluates nonprofit organizations, said that Greitens's wages \"seem within a reasonable range\"; the AP reported that his salary was about one-third higher than the $131,000 median compensation for chief executives of 237 medium-sized charities in the Midwest.<ref>[http://bigstory.ap.org/article/20824a15eb914e2694e1d4e102d909da/missouri-governor-candidates-salary-charity-questioned Missouri governor candidate's salary from charity questioned], [[Associated Press]], September 12, 2016.</ref> In a 2016 interview Borochoff cited Greitens's PhD and military experience as a possible reason for his slightly above-average salary. Borochoff said Greitens's wages \"seem within a reasonable range. The leaders of the Mission Continues have a big responsibility with this program, dealing with kind of a complicated population, so people shouldn't make that comparison to their own salary.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rebootcamp.militarytimes.com/education-transition/2016/09/08/the-mission-continues-founder-s-salary-questioned-amid-candidacy-for-missouri-governor/|title=The Mission Continues founder's salary questioned amid candidacy for Missouri governor|last=Lieb|first=David A.|date=April 2, 2018|website=Reboot Camp|language=en-US|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 [[New Profit Inc.|New Profit]] added The Mission Continues to its portfolio of the fastest-growing and highest-impact nonprofits in the sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.newprofit.org/amplify/honoring-the-mission-continues-on-veterans-day|title=Honoring The Mission Continues on Veterans Day|last=Admin|website=blog.newprofit.org|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> The [[Associated Press]] reported in March 2018 that Greitens had used the charity's email account to arrange political meetings about his intended gubernatorial campaign, which may not be allowed by federal tax law.<ref>[http://fox2now.com/2018/03/01/greitens-sent-political-invite-on-charity-email/ Greitens sent political invite on charity email], ''[[KTVI]]'', March 1, 2018. Retrieved March 20, 2018.</ref> He was also accused of using the charity's list of donors to raise money for his political campaign, a violation of campaign finance law.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news-leader.com/story/news/politics/2018/04/20/eric-greitens-indicted-again-he-suspected-stealing-charity-he-created/535650002/|title=Eric Greitens was indicted again. He is suspected of stealing from the charity he created.|work=Springfield News-Leader|access-date=September 9, 2018|language=en}}</ref> On December 28, 2018, the Missouri Attorney General informed The Mission Continues that, after a review of \u201chundreds of thousands of pages\u201d and several depositions, there was not enough evidence to support enforcement action against the nonprofit.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vockrodt |first1=Steve |title=Hawley drops Greitens-related investigations as he prepares to leave AG's office |url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article223692540.html |newspaper=Kansas City Star |accessdate=December 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018 The Mission Continues president Spencer Kympton posted an open letter informing its members that \"Regardless of someone's [Greitens's] history with The Mission Continues, we do not stand by actions that violate the core values we all strive to embody. And as uncomfortable as it may be, we must not fail to pronounce that.\" The letter also apologized to the volunteers and community leaders with The Mission Continues for any unwarranted attention from media and civic leaders they experienced.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.missioncontinuesblog.org/letter-veterans-thank-continuing-make-nations-communities-stronger/ |title=A Letter to Our Veterans: Thank You for Continuing to Make Our Nation's Communities Stronger |publisher=The Mission Continues |access-date=July 12, 2018 |date=July 10, 2018 |first=Spencer |last=Kympton }}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010 to 2012, [[Washington University in St. Louis]]'s [[Center for Social Development]], in collaboration with The Mission Continues, conducted a study involving nearly 500 veterans in more than 400 nonprofit organizations in 42 states. Its aim was to assess the perceived personal, social and family impacts of participating in the organization's Fellowship Program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://csd.wustl.edu/items/the-mission-continues-national-initiative-2/|title='The Mission Continues' National Initiative {{!}} Center for Social Development {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=csd.wustl.edu|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> \u201cThe results show that volunteering with The Mission Continues can help vets reengage in their communities and can increase their well-being,\" wrote Nancy Morrow-Howell, co-author and Faculty Associate, Center for Social Development, Washington University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://csd.wustl.edu/new-survey-shows-redeploying-veterans-to-serve-at-home-eases-reintegration-challenges/|title=New survey shows redeploying veterans to serve at home eases reintegration challenges {{!}} Center for Social Development {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=csd.wustl.edu|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Author===\n[[File:SD meets with Missouri governor 170327-D-GO396-222 (32870938313).jpg|thumb|left|Greitens with U.S. Secretary of Defense [[James Mattis]] in March 2017]]\nGreitens's first book, ''Strength and Compassion'' (2008), is a collection of photographs and essays with a foreword by Rwandan humanitarian [[Paul Rusesabagina]] and an introduction by [[Bobby Muller]], cofounder of the [[International Campaign to Ban Landmines]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.creativewell.com/pdf/muller.pdf|title=''Strength and Compassion''|publisher=creativewell.com|accessdate=May 11, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304074201/http://www.creativewell.com/pdf/muller.pdf|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Strength and Compassion: Photographs and Essays by Eric Greitens|date=September 23, 2008|isbn=978-0971007802|last1=Greitens|first1=Eric}}</ref> Photographs by Greitens were placed on display in the exhibition \u201cStrength and Compassion\u201d at the [[:fi:International Photography Hall of Fame and Museum|International Photography Hall of Fame]] (IPHF) in December 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/entertainment/arts-and-theatre/former-navy-seal-s-photos-come-to-international-photography-hall/article_7e960a88-fe17-5e83-80e0-38da5b8e968f.html|title=Former Navy SEAL's photos come to International Photography Hall of Fame|last=Miller|first=Sarah Bryan|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> ''Strength and Compassion'' was recognized as ''ForeWord'' magazine's Photography Book of the Year and the grand prize winner of the 2009 New York Book Festival.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOn April 11, 2011, [[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]] published Greitens's second book, ''The Heart and the Fist: The Education of a Humanitarian, the Making of a Navy SEAL''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.houghtonmifflinbooks.com/catalog/titledetail.cfm?titleNumber=1431563|title=Book Detail Page - HMH Books|work=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt |accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/39344692/Spring-2011-Adult-Frontlist-Catalog|title=Spring 2011 Houghton Mifflin Harcourt Adult Frontlist Catalog|publisher=scribd.com|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref> ''The Heart and the Fist'' is Greitens's memoir, featuring stories of his humanitarian work, his training as a naval officer and SEAL and the military experiences that led him to adopt the philosophy that one has to be strong to do good but also has to do good to be strong. The book ranked 10th on the ''New York Times'' bestseller list for hardcover nonfiction in May 2011,<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/22/books/review/InsideList-t.html?_r=1&ref=books|work=The New York Times|first=Jennifer|last=Schuessler|title=Inside the List|date=May 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2011-05-29/hardcover-nonfiction/list.html|work=The New York Times|first=Jennifer|last=Schuessler|title=Print & E-Books|date=May 29, 2011|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref> debuting on the St. Louis Independent Bookstore Alliance Best Sellers list at No. 1 for the week of April 17, 2011.<ref>[http://www.stlindiebook.com/node/41 \"St. Louis Independent Bookstore Alliance\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911121720/http://www.stlindiebook.com/node/41 |date=September 11, 2011 }}, stlindiebook.com; accessed May 10, 2017.</ref> The following year, Houghton Mifflin Harcourt also released a [[Young adult fiction|young adult]] edition, ''The Warrior's Heart''.<ref>Powers, Kevin, [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/11/books/review/the-warriors-heart-by-eric-greitens.html \"Acts of Valor\"], ''New York Times'', November 11, 2012; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\nIn March 2015 Houghton Mifflin Harcourt released Greitens's book ''[[Resilience: Hard-Won Wisdom for Living a Better Life]]''. It draws on letters Greitens wrote to a fellow SEAL struggling with [[PTSD]].<ref>Nelson, Marcia [http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/new-titles/adult-announcements/article/65354-spring-2015-announcements-lifestyle-death-and-dieting.html Spring 2015 Announcements: Lifestyle: Death and Dieting], ''Publishers Weekly'', February 16, 2015.</ref><ref>Naughton, Julie [http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/authors/interviews/article/65363-rising-after-a-fall-pw-talks-with-eric-greitens.html \"Rising After a Fall: PW Talks with Eric Greitens\"], ''Publishers Weekly'', February 16, 2015.</ref>\n\nAs an author and former SEAL, Greitens was a popular speaker before his political career.<ref name=\"records\" /> In 2016 an anonymous group charged in a [[YouTube]] video that he had exaggerated his record and was unduly benefiting from his time in the SEALs; Greitens responded to the claims by releasing his military records and publishing a video he uploaded to his channel with testimonials from SEALs and Marines with whom he had served.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/03/us/navy-seals-split-over-members-benefiting-from-hard-earned-brand.html|title=Rift Among Navy SEALs Over Members Who Cash In on Brand|date=April 3, 2016|work=The New York Times| accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Governor of Missouri==\nIn 2015, Greitens\u2014who was a Democrat in his early years\u2014wrote a [[Fox News]] editorial announcing that he had become a Republican. He said he had been raised in the tradition of [[Harry Truman]] and had even been recruited as a Democratic candidate for Congress, but was pushed rightward after seeing the [[Department of Veterans Affairs]] fail to help many of his brothers in arms. He recalled being angered at how the Democrats' only solution was to \"spend more money\" on the VA. \"The problem is that most Democrats seem to think more money and bigger government are the solutions to virtually every single problem,\" he wrote. He said he believed Democrats no longer had the right ideas to stand up for the middle class.<ref name=\"Fox News\"/>\n\n===2016 election===\n{{main|2016 Missouri gubernatorial election}}\n[[File:Eric Greitens for Governor.png|thumb|Gubernatorial election campaign logo]]\nOn September 26, 2015, Greitens announced his candidacy for [[List of Governors of Missouri|governor of Missouri]]<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/government-politics/article36693603.html|title=Former Navy SEAL Greitens running as Republican for Missouri governor|website=kansascity.com|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref> as a Republican.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/greitens-casts-himself-renegade-he-joins-gop-crowd-running-governor|title=Greitens casts himself as a renegade as he joins GOP crowd running for governor|author=Jo Mannies|work=stlpublicradio.org|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref> Shortly after a June 30, 2016, quarterly deadline for filing campaign contributions, he received the largest ever single contribution in a Missouri campaign, $1.975 million, which meant he did not have to reveal it until October, months after the primary. The source was a previously unknown [[Superpac]], \"SEALS for Truth\".<ref>[https://www.riverfronttimes.com/newsblog/2016/07/21/eric-greitens-nabs-single-largest-campaign-contribution-in-missouri-history Eric Greitens Nabs Single Largest Campaign Contribution in Missouri History], ''[[Riverfront Times]]'', Danny Wicentowski, July 21, 2016. Retrieved March 29, 2018.</ref> SEALS for Truth had received the money from the American Policy Coalition (APC), another Superpac, on the same day APC received the entire amount. Greitens had assured voters he intended to increase transparency while reducing corruption in state politics as a campaign focus.<ref name=\"Superpac\">[https://themissouritimes.com/34673/greitens-donors-donor-still-mystery/ Greitens donor\u2019s donor still a mystery], ''The Missouri Times'', Travis Zimpfer, October 17, 2016. Retrieved March 29, 2018.</ref> APC, about which there was almost no information online, was headed by Ohio lawyer David Langdon, who had incorporated it in Kentucky in 2015.<ref name=\"Superpac\" /> Between the 2010 election cycle and early 2015, at least 11 groups connected to Langdon spent at least $22 million on ballot initiatives against abortion and same-sex marriage and on federal and state elections around the country, as tabulated by the Center for Public Integrity.<ref>[https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2015/05/dark-money-ohio-elections-phantom-118268 Meet the Suburban Ohio Lawyer Behind the Right\u2019s Dark Money Machine], ''[[Politico]]'', Carrie Levine, May 26, 2015. Retrieved March 29, 2018.</ref> On March 12, 2017, the ''[[St. Louis Post Dispatch]]'' and ''[[The Kansas City Star]]'' editorial boards published a joint editorial criticizing Greitens for \"secret fundraising and secret spending\" and for tactics such as ordering that \"[s]ecurity staffers block reporters from getting close to him\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/opinion/columns/the-platform/editorial-attention-gov-greitens-our-joint-call-with-the-kansas/article_9a90c2e7-9aaa-5faf-886d-949420b1505c.html|title=Editorial: Attention, Gov. Greitens! Our joint call with ''The Kansas City Star'' for greater transparency, accountability|last=Star|first=the editorial boards of the St. Louis Post-Dispatch and The Kansas City|work=St. Louis Post Dispatch |accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref> In 2018 Missouri Attorney General [[Josh Hawley]], a Republican running for the U.S. Senate, announced the opening of an investigation of Greitens's 2016 campaign financing.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/23/mccaskill-missouri-greitens-republicans-senate-545393 |department=Elections |title='She's a lucky duck': GOP implodes again for McCaskill |newspaper=[[Politico]] |first=Daniel |last=Strauss |date=April 23, 2018 |access-date=April 30, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nGreitens won the August 2 Republican primary with 236,250 votes (34.6%) to businessman John Brunner's 169,425 (24.8%), Lieutenant Governor [[Peter Kinder]]'s 141,498 (20.7%), and former Speaker [[Catherine Hanaway]]'s 136,350 (19.9%).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kmbc.com/politics/eric-greitens-wins-missouri-gop-primary-to-face-chris-koster-in-fall/41023714|title=Eric Greitens wins Missouri GOP Primary, to face Chris Koster in fall|publisher=kmbc.com|accessdate=June 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/2016-election/results/map/governor/missouri|title=Missouri Governor Races Results|work=Politico|accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref> Democrat-turned-Republican Greitens faced Republican-turned-Democrat [[Chris Koster]] in the general election on November 8, 2016, and won with 51.3% of the vote to Koster's 45.4%.<ref name=\"General\">{{cite web|url=http://enr.sos.mo.gov/default.aspx |title=2016 General Election - Official Results |work=Missouri Secretary of State|date=November 8, 2016|accessdate=December 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 28, 2017, the Missouri Ethics Commission fined Greitens's campaign $1,000 for violating state campaign ethics rules regarding campaign disclosure. Greitens did not contest the fine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/in-latest-secrecy-issue-gov-greitens-is-fined-by-state/article_f08341ac-aea7-510e-b8fd-a1f5a872964e.html|title=In latest secrecy issue, Gov. Greitens is fined by state for undisclosed donor list|last=McDermott|first=Kevin|work=stltoday.com|accessdate=May 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title= 2016 Republican Primary for Governor of Missouri<ref>{{cite web |title=Missouri Gubernatorial Election, 2016 |url=https://ballotpedia.org/Missouri_gubernatorial_election,_2016 |website=ballotpedia.org |publisher=Ballotpedia |accessdate=November 18, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n |party = Republican Party (United States)\n |candidate = Eric Greitens \n |votes = 236,481\n |percentage = 34.56\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Republican Party (United States)\n |candidate = John Brunner\n |votes = 169,620\n |percentage = 24.79\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Republican Party (United States)\n |candidate = Peter Kinder\n |votes = 141,629\n |percentage = 20.70\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Republican Party (United States)|candidate=Catherine Hanaway|votes=136,521|percentage=19.95}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title= 2016 Missouri Gubernatorial Election<ref>{{cite web |title=2016 Missouri Governor Election Results |url=https://www.politico.com/2016-election/results/map/governor/missouri/ |website=politico.com |publisher=Politico |accessdate=November 18, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n |party = Republican Party (United States)\n |candidate = Eric Greitens \n |votes = 1,424,730\n |percentage = 51.3\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = Chris Koster\n |votes = 1,261,110\n |percentage = 45.4\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Cabinet===\n[[File:GreitensSEOC.jpg|thumb|Governor Greitens and DPS Director Drew Juden brief reporters during Winter Storm Jupiter at the State Emergency Operation Center on January 12, 2017.]]\nGreitens's cabinet began service on January 9, 2017, when he was inaugurated as the 56th governor of Missouri. Director of the Department of Corrections Anne Precythe was the first member of his cabinet, appointed on December 21, 2016. All but three members of his cabinet were confirmed by the Missouri Senate by the end of predecessor Jay Nixon's administration. Rob Dixon, Steve Corsi, and Anna Hui served as Acting Director of Economic Development, Acting Director of Social Services, and Acting Director of Labor and Industrial Relations, respectively, before being confirmed. The Greitens administration had a majority female cabinet.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Cabinet Position !! Name !! Appointment Date\n|-\n| Administrator of the [[Office of Administration]]||[[Sarah Steelman]]|| January 6, 2017\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Agriculture|Department of Agriculture]]|| Chris Chinn || December 27, 2017\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Corrections|Department of Corrections]]|| Anne Precythe || December 21, 2016\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Natural Resources|Department of Natural Resources]]|| Carol Comer || January 18, 2017\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Public Safety|Department of Public Safety]]|| Charles Juden || January 2, 2017\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Revenue|Department of Revenue]]|| Joel Walters || February 14, 2017\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Insurance, Financial Institutions, and Professional Registration]]|| Chlora Lindely-Myers || February 14, 2017\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Health and Senior Services|Department of Health and Senior Services]]||[[Randall W. Williams]]|| February 9, 2017\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Economic Development|Department of Economic Development]]|| Rob Dixon || June 2, 2017\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Social Services|Department of Social Services]]|| Steve Corsi || May 19, 2017\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Labor and Industrial Relations|Department of Labor and Industrial Relations]]|| Anna Hui || March 30, 2017\n|}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/whos-running-missouri-now-brief-look-greitens-cabinet-picks-date#stream/0|title=Who's running Missouri now? A brief look at Greitens' Cabinet picks to date|last1=Griffin|first1=Marshall|website=news.stlpublicradio.org|publisher=St Louis Public Radio|accessdate=November 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===First year===\n[[File:GreitensInaug.jpg|thumb|A B-2 stealth bomber flies over the Inauguration of Governor Eric Greitens on January 9, 2017 in Jefferson City, Missouri.]]\nGreitens took office as governor on January 9, 2017. His first two executive orders banned employees in the executive branch from accepting gifts from lobbyists and froze all new regulations through February 2017. He remained opposed to accepting a federal Medicaid expansion in Missouri.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/governor-elect-greitens-likely-to-make-missouri-a-right-to/article_678160f8-ceab-55da-9b94-28c643308b2e.html|title=Governor-elect Greitens likely to make Missouri a right-to-work state|first=Kevin|last=McDermott|publisher=stltoday.com|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref> In November 2018 a statewide referendum put heavy restrictions on lobbyist gifts, virtually banning them.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Griffiths |first1=Shawn |title=Missouri Voters Ban Most Lobbyist Gifts, Vote to End Gerrymandering |url=https://ivn.us/2018/11/07/missouri-voters-ban-lobbyist-gifts-vote-end-gerrymandering/ |website=ivn.us |publisher=IVN |accessdate=November 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn February 6, 2017, Greitens signed a bill making Missouri the 28th [[Right-to-work law|right-to-work state]].<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|last1 =Shaw| first1= Adam|title='Right-to-Work' Movement Claims Victory in Missouri, Eyes NH Next |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/02/06/right-to-work-movement-claims-victory-in-missouri-eyes-nh-next.html|date=February 6, 2017 |work=[[Fox News]]|accessdate=February 10, 2017}}</ref> In response, unions that opposed the law filed a referendum to overturn it,<ref>{{cite web |last1= Hancock| first1= Jason| title=Gov. Eric Greitens Signs Missouri Right-to-Work Bill, But Unions File Referendum to Overturn It|url =http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article130983664.html|date=February 6, 2017|work=[[The Kansas City Star]]|accessdate=February 10, 2017}}</ref> and on August 7, 2018, Missouri voters voted to overturn the right-to-work law.<ref name=\":15\">{{cite web|url=https://fox2now.com/2018/08/07/right-to-work-overturned-as-prop-a-fails/|title=Right-to-work overturned as Prop A fails|date=August 8, 2018|accessdate=August 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, 170 gravestones at the Chesed Shel Emeth Jewish Cemetery in [[University City, Missouri|University City]], [[Missouri]], were toppled and overturned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/02/21/us/jewish-cemetery-vandalized/index.html|title=Jewish cemetery vandalized; headstones damaged|author1=Dalila-Johari Paul |author2=Jason Hanna|website=CNN|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/02/22/politics/jewish-cemetery-muslims-fundraising-trnd/index.html|title=Pence, Missouri governor join cleanup at vandalized Jewish cemetery|author=Alexandra Larkin and Faith Karimi|website=CNN|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref> The vandalism drew national attention and occurred during a period when anonymous threats were being made against Jewish institutions nationwide.<ref name=\":0\" /> Greitens responded to the vandalism by announcing that he would lead a cleanup at the site. Greitens, who is Jewish, posted on Facebook a request for volunteers to help him clean up the cemetery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/EricGreitens/posts/10155034667679747|title=Eric Greitens|website=facebook.com|language=en|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref> On February 27, 2017, [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Mike Pence]] was already in Missouri for a small business roundtable, where he toured a small business in Fenton with Greitens, and he accepted Greitens's offer to join the cleanup efforts.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stljewishlight.com/news/local/pence-community-response-to-cemetery-vandalism-inspiring-the-nation/article_bd8b4474-f976-11e6-8ede-cf20a79c4c41.html|title=Pence: Community response to cemetery vandalism 'inspiring the nation'|last=Writer|first=Eric Berger, Staff|website=St. Louis Jewish Light|language=en|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref> The St. Louis Jewish Light reported, \u201cthe governor and vice president made their remarks atop a flatbed truck on a path inside the cemetery.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> CNN reported that President Trump called Greitens to \"thank the people of Missouri for standing up in the fight against anti-Semitism.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn August 22, 2017, Greitens granted a stay of execution to [[Murder of Felicia Gayle|Marcellus Williams]], who had been set to be executed that day. DNA tests, using technology unavailable at the time of the killing, on the knife used in the killing matched an unknown male, not Williams. Greitens appointed a board of five retired judges to investigate the case and recommend commutation or execution. The panel has no deadline for its report.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/greitens-stops-execution-after-questions-about-dna-evidence/article_edb01294-3d89-5bf6-823e-5a10f8747cc4.html|title=Greitens stops execution after questions about DNA evidence|last=Kohler| first= Jeremy| work=St. Louis Post Dispatch|access-date=August 22, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Missouri governor names panel to examine new DNA evidence in Marcellus Williams' case |url=http://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/missouri-governor-names-panel-examine-new-dna-evidence-marcellus-williams-case#stream/0|author=Mannies, Jo|date=September 12, 2017|publisher=stlpublicradio.org|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref>[[File:Mike Pence and Eric Greitens.jpg|thumb|Greitens meeting with Vice President [[Mike Pence]], January 2017]]On October 27, 2017, the governor's office announced that 30 women had been appointed to state boards and commissions, joining \"a majority-female cabinet\". First Lady Sheena Greitens had announced on October 3 that the Greitens administration would appoint 25 women in the next 25 days, in honor of the 25th anniversary of the Women's Foundation of [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Governor Greitens Appoints 30 Women to State Boards and Commissions|url=https://governor.mo.gov/news/archive/governor-greitens-appoints-30-women-state-boards-and-commissions|date=October 27, 2017|publisher=governor.mo.gov|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Judicial appointments====\nGreitens appointed Jackson County Circuit Judge W. Brent Powell to the Missouri Supreme Court in April 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/kansascity/news/2018/03/20/jackson-county-circuit-court-judge-cory-atkins.html |title=Greitens appoints 'Rising Star' as new Jackson County judge |newspaper=Kansas City Business Journal |date=March 20, 2018 |first=James |last=Dornbrook |access-date=August 13, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.joplinglobe.com/news/judge-w-brent-powell-appointed-to-missouri-supreme-court/article_8b4ef146-29e0-11e7-99ea-336e3939c698.html |title=Judge W. Brent Powell appointed to Missouri Supreme Court |date=April 25, 2017 |newspaper=Joplin Globe |first1=Summer |last1=Ballentine |first2=David A. |last2=Lieb |access-date=August 13, 2019 |agency=Associated Press }}</ref> He also made the following judicial appointments: Kevin Walden was appointed Circuit Judge for the 8th Judicial Circuit; Katherine (\"Katie\") M. Fowler as Circuit Court Judge for the 22nd Judicial Circuit; Lynne R. Perkins as Associate Circuit Court Judge for the 22nd Judicial Circuit; Brouck Jacobs as Circuit Judge for the 13th Judicial Circuit; and Melissa Lawyer as Circuit Judge for the 5th Judicial Circuit.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://themissouritimes.com/44913/greitens-announces-five-judicial-appointments/ |title=Greitens announces five judicial appointments |newspaper=The Missouri Times |date=October 13, 2017 |access-date=August 13, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n====Tort reform====\nIn 2017 [[Harris Insights & Analytics]] surveyed 1,300 corporate litigators and senior executives for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce's Institute for Legal Reform. Missouri's overall state liability system ranked 49th out of 50. As part of his \u201cMore Jobs, Higher Pay\u201d plan, Greitens pushed for more tort reform than any state in the country. In 2017 the [[American Tort Reform Association]] criticized St. Louis as the \"worst Judicial Hellhole\u2122\" in the country, and said \u201cjudicial hellholes\u201d like [[St. Louis]] are known for systematically misapplying the law in ways that expand liability and ratchet up the cost of doing business in the state. Greitens signed legislation that the Property Casualty Insurers Association of America said would help improve Missouri's legal climate by curbing abuses associated with \u00a7537.065 and the time-limited demand settlement process.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.insurancejournal.com/news/midwest/2017/07/13/457609.htm |title=Missouri Governor Signs Tort Reform Legislation |date=July 13, 2017 |journal=Insurance Journal |access-date=August 13, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nOther tort reform bills Greitens signed include:\n\nMissouri SB31, which makes changes to the collateral source rule (paid v. billed damages) so parties can introduce only evidence of the actual cost of the medical care rendered, not the value of that care.\n\nMissouri SB43, which brings standards for lawsuits in Missouri in line with 38 other states and the federal government. The bill requires the use of the \u201cmotivating factor\u201d standard for employment discrimination cases. The \u201cmotivating factor\u201d standard is used by the U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC) in analyzing claims under Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 (Title VII) and the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA).\n\nMissouri SB 88, which gives veterinarians the same malpractice coverage as doctors, dentists, and other medical professionals.\n[[File:GreitensRoyals.jpg|thumb|Greitens speaking to Fox 4 News at the 2017 MLB Opening Day for the Kansas City Royals in August 2017.]]\nMissouri HB 452, which says that, with certain exceptions, no healthcare provider shall be liable for the negligence of another entity or person who is not an employee of the healthcare provider.\n\nMissouri HB153, which creates a higher standard for expert evidence, improves the reliability of expert witness testimony, and puts Missouri in line with a majority of states regarding the standard used for expert testimony.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.news-leader.com/story/opinion/readers/2018/02/02/keep-reforming-missouri-lawsuit-abuse-2018/1087167001/ |title=Keep reforming Missouri lawsuit abuse in 2018 |newspaper=Springfield News-Leader |date=February 2, 2018 |first1=James R. |last1=Copland |first2=Rafael A. |last2=Mangual |access-date=August 13, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==== Ethics reform and government efficiency ====\nWithin an hour of his inauguration, Greitens signed an executive order banning state employees in his administration from accepting or soliciting gifts from lobbyists. The order also banned employees in the governor's office from lobbying the executive branch while Greitens was in office. The order was later loosened by Governor Mike Parson, who allowed gifts to members of the executive branch. As Lieutenant Governor, Parson received meals and gifts from lobbyists worth $2,752 in his first six months in office, the [[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] reported, citing Missouri Ethics Commission records.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox2now.com/2017/01/09/greitens-bans-lobbyist-gifts-to-executive-branch/|title=Greitens bans lobbyist gifts to executive branch|date=January 9, 2017|website=FOX2now.com|language=en|access-date=August 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFox 2 News St. Louis accused Greitens of \u201clashing out against two Republican senators who didn\u2019t vote against a pay raise for themselves and other elected officials.\u201d Only Republican State Senators Denny Hoskins and Paul Wieland cast votes to allow the raise to take effect, but six other senators recused themselves and didn't vote. Greitens had personally pressured lawmakers to vote down the raise. Hoskins and Wieland described their meetings with him as tense. Wieland described it as intimidation and said he felt insulted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox2now.com/2017/01/31/missouri-governor-slams-fellow-republicans-on-social-media/|title=Missouri governor slams fellow Republicans on social media|date=January 31, 2017|website=FOX2now.com|language=en|access-date=August 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGreitens approved a plan to reduce the number of people that can be appointed to political positions. A 2017 Boards and Commissions Task Force report outlined ways to eliminate 439 gubernatorial appointments and cut or merge numerous state boards and commissions, more than 200 of which currently exist. The recommendations aligned with Greitens's goal to make Missouri's government smaller and reduce state regulators' reach. The report included recommendations to cut more than two dozen commissions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news-leader.com/story/news/politics/2017/11/02/gov-greitens-gives-seal-approval-plan-eliminating-hundreds-missouri-appointees/822309001/|title=Gov. Greitens gives seal of approval to plan eliminating hundreds of Missouri appointees|last=Schmitt|first=Will|website=Springfield News-Leader|language=en|access-date=August 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring his 2017 State of the State address, Greitens announced: \"We found 30 cars the government didn't need, and we're getting rid of them. That's going to save Missourians over $500,000.\" Greitens sold one of the state's two passenger planes used by his predecessor, [[Jay Nixon]]. The 2018 [[Missouri Department of Public Safety|Department of Public Safety]] spending proposal called for a $37,000 reduction in aircraft maintenance costs due to the sale of the twin-engine, six-passenger plane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newstribune.com/news/local/story/2018/jan/14/state-cutting-30-vehicles-oa-fleet/708689/|title=State cutting 30 vehicles from OA fleet|website=News Tribune|access-date=August 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/missouri-governor-to-sell-one-state-airplane/article_ace2d746-f8c9-5964-adf7-a2f137ee5a77.html|title=Missouri governor to sell one state airplane|last=Erickson|first=Kurt|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=August 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGreitens released funding for biodiesel facilities that was originally withheld because of concerns that state revenues could fall short. The released $4 million was the amount necessary to pay off a backlog of subsidies called for under a 2002 state law that provided incentives for biodiesel plants that began operating by 2009. Fox 2 St. Louis reported that members of the soybean industry said that releasing the incentives \u201chelped launch the industry.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox2now.com/2018/05/17/missouri-governor-releases-final-biodiesel-subsidies/|title=Missouri governor releases final biodiesel subsidies|date=May 17, 2018|website=FOX2now.com|language=en|access-date=August 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Economic effect====\nOn November 21, 2017, Greitens announced that [[Sedalia, Missouri]], would be home to a $250 million [[Nucor]] steel-bar mill.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.komu.com/news/nucor-announces-new-steel-mill-in-sedalia/|title=Nucor announces new steel mill in Sedalia|website=KOMU|language=en|access-date=June 20, 2019|first=Mackenzie|last=Huck|date=November 21, 2017}}</ref> Missouri was chosen over Kansas, Nebraska, South Carolina and Florida for the facility, which created 255 jobs with a median annual salary of $65,000 in addition to 450 temporary construction jobs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/stlouis/news/2017/11/21/steel-company-picks-missouri-for-new-250-million.html|newspaper=St. Louis Business Journal|access-date=June 20, 2019|title=Steel company picks Missouri for new $250 million mill|first=Steph|last=Kukuljan|date=November 21, 2017}}</ref> Missouri moved up nine spaces, from 31st to 22nd, in [[CNBC]]'s annual list of America's Top States for Business published on July 11, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/07/11/top-states-for-business-22-missouri.html|title=22. Missouri|last=staff|first=CNBC com|date=July 11, 2017|website=www.cnbc.com|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref> In 2018 Missouri also had its lowest unemployment rate in 18 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/business/local/missouri-unemployment-drops-to-lowest-rate-since-june/article_01a69daf-6081-56d4-9f4d-963e722e85a2.html|title=Missouri unemployment drops to lowest rate since June 2000|last=Press|first=Associated|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Regulatory reform ====\nIn January 2017 Greitens signed Executive Order 17-03, which froze implementation of all new regulations for over 30 days and required each agency to review its rules and remove \"needless and burdensome regulations.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/greitens-signs-second-executive-order-freezing-new-regulations-for-businesses/article_2f0a09b8-c164-5021-8f69-f382d4586ca6.html|title=Greitens signs second executive order freezing new regulations for businesses|last=Bott|first=Celeste|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref> A 2017 audit of state regulations found more than seven million words of regulations on the books. Greitens declared plans to remove nearly one-third of these, equal to approximately 33,000 regulations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://krcgtv.com/news/local/gov-greitens-state-of-the-state-address|title=Gov. Greitens State of the State Address|last=Staff|first=KRCG 13 Web|date=January 10, 2018|website=KRCG|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGreitens signed into law a bill removing regulations on ride-sharing services like [[Uber]] and [[Lyft]], allowing them to work freely in Missouri. Uber said the legislation would lead to 10,000 additional jobs in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news-leader.com/story/news/politics/2017/04/24/greitens-signs-statewide-regulations-for-uber-lyft/100855590/|title=Greitens signs statewide regulations for Uber, Lyft|website=Springfield News-Leader|language=en|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref> Greitens posted on Facebook a video of himself signing the bill in a Lyft in a [[Taco Bell]] parking lot, which earned him a shout-out from Taco Bell.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article147109379.html|title=Greitens gets a shout-out from Taco Bell after his Chalupa bill-signing ceremony|last=By|website=kansascity|language=en|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSenior officials in Greitens's administration supported state and national agricultural advocacy groups\u2019 efforts to rewrite the Obama Administration's \"[[Waters of the United States]]\" (WOTUS) rule.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newstribune.com/news/news/story/2017/jun/28/missouri-leaders-applaud-epas-waters-change/679903/|title=Missouri leaders applaud EPA's 'waters' change|website=News Tribune|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref> Missouri [[American Farm Bureau Federation|Farm Bureau]] President Blake Hurst said, \"we appreciate Gov. Greitens' comments to [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] asserting that the WOTUS rule was too broad an interpretation of law and that it should be redefined.\"<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nIn March 2017 Greitens announced that the Missouri Board of Nursing approved the [[United States Air Force|Air Force]]'s practical nurse education program. He said the agreement, designed to allow military nurses to practice in the civilian sector following military service, would be the first of its kind in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://krcgtv.com/news/local/greitens-missouri-board-of-nursing-approves-air-force-practical-nurse-education-program|title=Greitens: Missouri Board of Nursing approves Air Force practical nurse education program|last=Dailey|first=Greg|date=March 22, 2017|website=KRCG|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:SteelMillRally.jpg|thumb|Hundreds of workers from southeast Missouri rally outside the Governor's Office in support of Greitens and the 2017 Steel Mill Bill.]]\n\n==== 2017 steel mill special session ====\nGreitens supported the Missouri Steel Mill Bill, legislation that allowed utility regulators to approve lower electricity rates for industrial companies using large amounts of energy.\n\nThe legislation was drafted in response to the March 2016 [[Noranda (mining company)|Noranda]] smelter closure, in which nearly 900 people lost their jobs and the average household income in [[New Madrid County, Missouri|New Madrid County]] fell by $6,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2018/09/26/theres-optimism-in-southeast-missouris-bootheel-about-jobs/|title=There's optimism in southeast Missouri's Bootheel about jobs|date=September 26, 2018|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref> During the final weeks of the regular 2017 legislative session, the Missouri House of Representatives passed an amendment by State Representative [[Don Rone Jr.|Don Rone]] designed to help bring industrial jobs to the state. The bill, however, was met with opposition in the Senate led by Senator Doug Libla, and ultimately failed. Greitens called a special legislative session in May 2017, bringing the Missouri General Assembly back to the Capitol one week after its regular session adjourned to pass the legislation.\n[[File:SenatorsDoor.jpg|thumb|Following a rally, Greitens led workers to the offices of state senators to urge them to pass the 2017 Steel Mill Bill.]]\n\u201cAnd people are sick of having to drive to Kentucky, having to drive to Tennessee, having to drive to Arkansas,\u201d Greitens said in an interview with MissouriNet. \u201cWatching their friends have to get in trucks and go across the border to find a quality job. And we promised during the (gubernatorial) campaign we were going to fight for them.\u201d<ref name=\"missourinet.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2017/05/22/missouri-legislatures-special-session-starts-monday-greitens-and-schaaf-clash-over-psc-language-issue/|title=Missouri Legislature's special session starts Monday; Greitens and Schaaf clash over PSC language issue|date=May 22, 2017|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter calling the session, Greitens held rallies in Southeast Missouri in [[New Madrid, Missouri|New Madrid]], [[Poplar Bluff, Missouri|Poplar Bluff]], [[Dexter, Missouri|Dexter]] and [[Sikeston, Missouri|Sikeston]] and hosted hundreds of Bootheel residents at the Capitol in Jefferson City for a rally urging lawmakers to approve the bill.<ref name=\"missourinet.com\"/> Following the rally, Greitens encouraged the crowd to join him in walking to every state senator's office. Participants taped messages to the doors of Senate offices, including phrases such as \u201cwe don\u2019t want welfare\u201d and \u201cbring back American jobs.\u201d<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2017/05/24/southeast-missouri-residents-rally-with-greitens-on-noranda-issue-rone-predicts-house-will-approve-bill-on-wednesday/|title=Missouri Bootheel residents rally with Greitens for jobs bill|date=May 24, 2017|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref> Rone praised Greitens, saying \u201cwe finally have a governor who knows where southeast Missouri is.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nUltimately, the General Assembly passed the legislation and Greitens signed the bill in to law on June 16, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.missouribusinessalert.com/industries/84500/2017/06/16/greitens-signs-steel-mill-bill/|title=Greitens signs steel mill bill passed in May special session \u2013 Missouri Business Alert|language=en-US|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref> Following the special session, Magnitude 7 Metals LLC announced that the firm would restart two of the plant's three production lines, which brought over 450 jobs to the region with an average salary of $95,000, with the potential for another 900 jobs in the future.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2017/05/25/missouri-house-approves-norandasteel-mill-bill-mccreery-describes-bill-as-giveaway-to-ameren/|title=Missouri House approves Noranda/steel mill bill|date=May 25, 2017|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.semissourian.com/story/2491628.html|title=Former smelter to reopen in May, plans to employ 450 people near term, as many as 900 with future expansions|last=Missourian|first=Mark Bliss ~ Southeast|date=March 10, 2018|website=seMissourian.com|language=en|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the announcement, Greitens accepted an invitation to meet with [[Donald Trump|President Donald Trump]] at the [[White House]] to discuss workforce development and job creation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2017/06/15/missouri-governor-signs-steel-mill-bill-heads-to-washington-to-talk-jobs/|title=Missouri governor signs steel mill bill, heads to Washington to talk jobs|date=June 15, 2017|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== 2017 pro-life special session ====\n[[File:ProLifeSession.jpg|thumb|Nearly a thousand supporters of the pro-life movement attend Governor Greitens' rally during the pro-life special session in June 2017.]]\nFollowing the extraordinary session on the Steel Mill Bill, Greitens called a second special session to pass pro-life legislation. He went on a statewide tour with former [[Arkansas Governor]] [[Mike Huckabee]] and said \"we had some radical politicians in St. Louis who passed legislation to make St. Louis an abortion sanctuary city, where it would make it illegal ... for organizations like Our Lady's Inn and other pro-life groups just to hire pro-life workers. So we're out here to protect pregnancy care centers.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/abortion-regulations-st-louis-anti-discrimination-law-focus-2nd-special-legislative-session|title=Abortion regulations, St. Louis anti-discrimination law focus of 2nd special legislative session|last2=Griffin|first2=Marshall|first1=Jo |last1=Mannies|website=St. Louis Public Radio|access-date=August 13, 2019|date=June 7, 2017}}</ref> The bill also required that doctors explain the risks of abortion to a patient 72 hours before performing an abortion, called for annual inspections of clinics, added new whistle-blower protections for clinic employees, and heightened requirements for pathologists who provide services to abortion facilities. Executive director of [[NARAL Pro-Choice America|NARAL Pro Choice Missouri]] Alison Dreith said the session was \"political theater.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/in-private-ceremony-greitens-signs-new-abortion-law/article_10c9ef36-688b-51c1-9aca-2386d9495187.html|title=In private ceremony, Greitens signs new abortion law|last=Erickson|first=Kurt|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|access-date=August 13, 2019|date=July 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn July 26, 2017, Greitens signed HCS SB 5, a wide-ranging pro-life measure, into law.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalrighttolifenews.org/2017/07/missouri-gov-greitens-signs-wide-ranging-pro-life-measure/|title=Missouri Gov. Greitens signs wide-ranging pro-life measure|last=Dave Andrusko|date=July 26, 2017|website=NRL News Today|access-date=August 13, 2019}}</ref> Missouri Right to Life said, \"We are especially grateful to Governor Greitens for calling this special session and for his support of this pro-life legislation.\" [[National Right to Life Committee|NRLC]]'s state affiliate called the measure \"one of the strongest pro-life bills to be passed by the Missouri Legislature in many years.\"<ref name=\":21\" />\n\nIn 2018 [[The Satanic Temple]] delivered oral arguments in front of the [[Missouri Court of Appeals|Missouri State Court Western Appellate District]] in an effort to challenge Greitens's pro-life legislation, claiming that it \"violated the religious beliefs of one of its members.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/satanic-temple-missouri-abortion-law_n_59bacd6de4b02da0e1403c82|title=Why The Satanic Temple Is Fighting Missouri's Restrictive Abortion Law|last=Blumberg|first=Antonia|date=September 14, 2017|website=HuffPost|access-date=August 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018 Greitens was featured in the [[Netflix]] documentary film \"''[[Reversing Roe]]''\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Reversing Roe (2018)|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt8948614/fullcredits|website=IMDb|access-date=August 13, 2019}}</ref>{{better source|date=August 2019}}\n\n==== Changes to Missouri's foster care system ====\n\nIn June 2017 Greitens signed Missouri's first Foster Care Bill of Rights, which outlined specific measures designed to improve the safety and quality of life of children in Missouri's foster care system.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/greitens-signs-foster-care-bill-rights#stream/0 |title=Greitens signs Foster Care Bill of Rights |publisher=St. Louis Public Radio |date=June 22, 2017 |first=Marshall |last=Griffin |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018 Greitens ordered that Missouri children in foster care no longer have to pay $15 to get copies of their birth certificates. The move was hailed as removing a key obstacle for many to apply for driver's licenses, jobs, or higher education. \u201cFor the children who are involved in this system, it\u2019s everything to them,\u201d said Colleen Polak, director of legal services for Voices for Children in St. Louis.<ref name=\"news.stlpublicradio.org\">{{cite news |url=https://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/missouri-foster-children-top-agenda-first-lady-sheena-greitens#stream/0 |title=Missouri foster children top agenda for first lady Sheena Greitens |date=January 3, 2018 |publisher=St. Louis Public Radio |first=Holly |last=Edgell |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017 Greitens appointed 27 advocates to the Child Abuse and Neglect Review Boards, Children's Trust Fund Board, and Missouri State Foster Care and Adoption Board. Many of those boards had been unable to operate because no one had been appointed to them to make quorum.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://themissouritimes.com/45902/greitens-appoints-27-members-to-child-protection-boards/ |title=Greitens appoints 27 members to child protection boards |date=November 17, 2017 |first=Benjamin |last=Peters |newspaper=The Missouri Times |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Sheena Greitens announced that the administration's Children's Division had enrolled in a new National Council For Adoption (NCFA) study of foster parent recruitment and retention. Its goal was to find ways to more effectively train and support foster parents.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.missourinet.com/2017/12/12/far-reaching-foster-care-study-announced-by-missouri-first-lady/ |title=Far reaching foster care study announced by Missouri First Lady |date=December 12, 2017 |first=Jason |last=Taylor |website=Missourinet |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref> Sheena Greitens also distributed over 3,200 books in state storage Missouri's foster families and foster children.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/stlouis/news/2018/01/30/q-a-with-sheena-greitens.html |title=Q&A with Sheena Greitens |magazine=St. Louis Business Journal |date=January 30, 2018 |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref> She then announced that Missouri had joined the National Electronic Interstate Compact Enterprise, a multistate collaboration designed to make adoption and fostering across state lines easier.<ref name=\"news.stlpublicradio.org\"/>\n\n==== Council of Governors ====\nIn May 2017 President Trump appointed Greitens to the Council of Governors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://themissouritimes.com/40176/greitens-named-council-governors-trump/|title=Greitens named to Council of Governors by Trump|date=May 2, 2017|website=The Missouri Times|language=en|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref> A bipartisan organization of state governors, the council advises on matters of national defense, the national guard and defense support to local authorities. Greitens served alongside [[Rick Scott]] of Florida, [[Bill Walker (American politician)|Bill Walker]] of Alaska, [[Mark Dayton]] of Minnesota, [[Steve Bullock (American politician)|Steve Bullock]] of Montana, [[Dannel Malloy]] of Connecticut, and [[Mary Fallin]] of Oklahoma. Greitens was the only newly elected governor Trump appointed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newstribune.com/news/missouri/story/2017/may/02/trump-intends-appoint-greitens-council-governors/672261/|title=Trump intends to appoint Greitens to council of governors|website=News Tribune|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Public safety and law enforcement support ====\n\nGreitens signed a \u201cBlue Alert\u201d law modeled after the Amber Alert system for missing children. He pursued the idea to allow public broadcasts with information that could assist in the apprehension of individuals who commit violence against police officers. The measure was part of a package of crime-related changes to state law the Missouri House and Senate approved in May 2017. It also enhanced penalties for assaults on law enforcement officers and created the crime of illegal re-entry. People deported from the United States for committing a crime who return and commit a felony would also be guilty of illegal re-entry in Missouri.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://themissouritimes.com/42367/greitens-signs-blue-alert-bill-into-law/ |title=Greitens signs Blue Alert bill into law |date=July 6, 2017 |newspaper=The Missouri Times |first=Benjamin |last=Peters |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.senate.mo.gov/17info/BTS_Web/Bill.aspx?SessionType=R&BillID=57095296 |publisher=Missouri State Senate |title=SB34 \u2013 Modifies and creates new provisions relating to criminal offenses |first=Scott |last=Svagera |date=July 6, 2017 |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nGreitens announced a special operations unit of the State Highway Patrol to target violent felons on interstate highways. The task force collected better intelligence to aid local police and pushed to stop drug trafficking. The Missouri Department of Public Safety worked with the FBI and the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration to go after violent criminals.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://fox4kc.com/2017/07/11/state-highway-patrol-to-help-address-violence-in-st-louis/ |title=State Highway Patrol to help address violence in St. Louis |agency=Associated Press |date=July 11, 2017 |publisher=[[WDAF-TV]] |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nGreitens changed the state's emergency response philosophy, adopting a \u201cgo early, go big\u201d approach in which the operating response was to go before disaster strikes and be overprepared throughout the emergency to minimize human casualties. He activated the State Emergency Operations Center prior to several major events, including instances of massive flooding, tornadoes, and winter storms. The center operates 24 hours a day to coordinate the response by the National Weather Service, The Department of Public Safety, the State Emergency Management Agency, Missouri State Highway Patrol, MoDOT, Electric Utilities and Power Companies/Power, and faith-based and volunteer response partners, including Convoy of Hope and the Red Cross.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.news-leader.com/story/news/local/missouri/2017/01/12/greitens-declares-state-emergency-winter-storm-approaches/96522264/ |title=Greitens declares state of emergency as winter storm approaches |date=January 12, 2017 |newspaper=Springfield News-Leader |publisher=USA Today Network |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nOfficials in the Greitens administration sent notices to 8,000 doctors who weren't following best practices for prescribing [[opioids]] within the state's Medicaid program, instructing them to change their prescribing patterns and consider referring people on long-term opioids to addiction programs. The ''Kansas City Star'' reported that Greitens also started filling vacancies on the medical licensing board with physicians who were \u201cwilling to get tough on colleagues who contribute to the opioid crisis.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/local/news-columns-blogs/the-buzz/article161759233.html |title=Gov. Eric Greitens orders prescription drug monitoring program for Missouri |date=July 17, 2017 |newspaper=The Kansas City Star |first1=Jason |last1=Hancock |first2=Andy |last2=Marso |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nGreitens issued an executive order to create a prescription drug monitoring program, addressing the concern that Missouri was the only state in the U.S. without a program. The order directed the Department of Health and Senior Services to build the database, which was designed to help identify suspicious patterns of prescriptions of controlled substances, including opioids.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/business/health-care/article203576419.html |title=Greitens announces opioid crackdown that could affect 8,000 Missouri doctors |date=March 5, 2018 |newspaper=The Kansas City Star |first=Andy |last=Marso |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nGreitens created the Firefighter Veterans Initiative to connect veterans to public safety careers. The program introduces participants to firefighting through physical skills training through basic classroom instruction and pairing students with mentors.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://krcgtv.com/news/local/photo-gallery-governors-initiative-trains-veterans-to-be-firefighters |title=Initiative trains veterans to be firefighters |date=February 18, 2018 |publisher=[[KRCG]] |first=Gabriella |last=Nu\u00f1ez |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Second year===\nOn February 24, 2018, Greitens declared a state of emergency and activated the Missouri National Guard in response to severe weather that began on February 23.<ref>{{cite web |title=Executive Order 2018-02 |url=https://governor.mo.gov/node/266 |website=governor.mo.gov |publisher=Missouri Governor |accessdate=November 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Tax reform====\n[[File:GreitensChiefs.jpg|thumb|Governor Greitens and Kansas City Chiefs Coach Andy Reid on the field at KC Chiefs Training Camp in St. Joseph, Missouri in July 2017.]]\nOn January 18, 2018, Greitens announced tax cuts to be proposed in the state legislature. More information on the cuts was released in the following weeks. The plan was to cut individual and corporate taxes by approximately $800 million. The overhaul would reduce the top individual income tax rate by 10% and the corporate income tax rate by nearly a third. The top individual income tax rate would drop from 5.9% to 5.3%. The proposal would also create a non-refundable state tax credit for low-income workers, which Greitens said would essentially eliminate income taxes for 380,000 people. He said the bill would drop taxes 51%, from $920 to $449 annually for a married couple with two children earning $40,000. Greitens also said the plan would drop taxes down 2.9%, from $6,917 to $6,716 annually, for a married couple with two children who earn $150,000. The plan also intended to cut corporate tax rates from 6.25% to 4.25%.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erickson |first1=Kurt |title=Greitens hopes $800 million in tax cuts will turbocharge the Missouri economy |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/greitens-hopes-million-in-tax-cuts-will-turbocharge-the-missouri/article_d6fbb4da-072f-5c40-a971-ce8a1995011f.html |newspaper=St Louis Post-Dispatch |accessdate=November 18, 2018 |date=January 30, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |title=Governor Greitens outlines principles for tax reform |url=https://themissouritimes.com/47460/governor-greitens-outlines-principles-for-tax-reform/ |newspaper=The Missouri Times |date=January 18, 2018 |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref> It simplified the tax code and eliminated special rules that rewarded companies that hired employees outside of Missouri. As a result, Missouri would have the country's second-lowest corporate tax rate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.columbiamissourian.com/news/state_news/greitens-plan-cuts-taxes-for-most-missourians/article_fa713de0-0527-11e8-ac09-6723216541b3.html|title=Greitens' plan cuts taxes for most Missourians|author=Missourian Staff|website=The Columbia Missourian|language=en|access-date=June 20, 2019 |date=January 29, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nGreitens's $28.8 billion fiscal 2019 budget proposal estimated a 2.5% growth rate in net general revenue, with 70% coming from personal income taxes. To balance the operating budget, Greitens also proposed changes to the tax code that would increase state revenue. One of these was removing the timely filing discount. The discount offers vendors up to a 2% discount for filing sales taxes on time. The Missouri Department of Revenue projected state savings of $57.4 million by eliminating the discount.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Henderson |first1=Matthew |title=Greitens proposes sweeping tax reform |url=http://sbj.net/stories/greitens-proposes-sweeping-tax-reform,57373 |website=sbj.net |publisher=SBJ |date=February 5, 2018 |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nGreitens signed legislation that simplified Missouri's tax code, eliminated special rules that rewarded companies that hired employees outside of Missouri, and reduced Missouri's business tax rate from 6.25% to 4.0%, making it the second lowest in the country.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.cchgroup.com/2018/06/05/missouri-enacts-corporate-tax-rate-cut-and-apportionment-changes/ |title=Missouri Enacts Corporate Tax Rate Cut and Apportionment Changes |website=CCHTaxGroup |date=June 5, 2018 |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==== ''Trinity Lutheran Church of Columbia v. Comer'' ====\nGreitens ended a longstanding state policy against using tax dollars to aid religious groups. His decision came a week before the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] heard arguments in the case of ''Trinity Lutheran Church of Columbia v. Comer''. The lawsuit challenged a 2012 decision by the Missouri Department of Natural Resources to deny the Columbia church a grant to replace the gravel on its playground with softer, safer material. Greitens instructed the Department of Natural Resources to allow religious organizations to apply for and be eligible to receive those grants.<ref>Greitens ended a long standing state policy of discrimination against religious organizations.  The policy prevented tax dollars from being used to aid religious groups. Greitens\u2019 decision came a week before the U.S. Supreme Court heard arguments in the case of ''Trinity Lutheran Church of Columbia v. Comer''. The lawsuit challenged a 2012 decision by the Missouri Department of Natural Resources to deny the Columbia church a grant to replace the gravel on its playground with softer, safer material. Greitens instructed the Department of Natural Resources to allow religious organizations to apply for and be eligible to receive those grants. {{cite news |url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article144497099.html |title=Gov. Greitens reverses state policy, allowing tax dollars to aid religious groups |newspaper=The Kansas City Star |date=April 13, 2017 |first=Jason |last=Hancock |access-date=August 12, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==== Jason Stockley protests ====\nOn September 15, 2017, St. Louis police officer [[Jason Stockley]] was found not guilty of first-degree murder for shooting [[Anthony Lamar Smith]] in 2011. Protests erupted in St. Louis. Prior to the verdict, a group of clergy publicly stated that an acquittal would result in \"mass disruption\" in the city. Greitens, who was openly critical of his predecessor Jay Nixon's response to the Ferguson unrest, preemptively activated the Missouri National Guard and scheduled 12-hour shifts for the St. Louis municipal police.\n\nBefore the judge's decision in Stockley's trial, Greitens and Smith's fianc\u00e9e, Christina Wilson, made a call for peace. \"If you feel like you want to speak out, speak how you feel and whatever comes to you,\"\n\nWilson said, \"Just do it in a peaceful way.\"<ref name=\"praises\">{{cite news |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/greitens-praises-police-response-to-st-louis-protests/article_4308bc80-da7d-5519-930a-d4645fd670ab.html |title=Greitens praises police response to St. Louis protests |newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=October 10, 2017 |first=Kurt |last=Erickson |access-date=August 13, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ksdk.com/article/news/local/gov-greitens-fiancee-of-anthony-lamar-smith-call-for-peace/63-474991744 |title=Gov. Greitens, fianc\u00e9e of Anthony Lamar Smith call for peace |publisher=KSDK |date=September 15, 2017 |first=Sam |last=Clancy |access-date=August 13, 2019 }}</ref> Greitens said, \"Whatever the verdict is, we will protect every single person's right to peacefully protest\". \"And whatever the verdict is, we will also protect people's lives, their homes and our communities.\"<ref name=\"praises\" /> Following the verdict, Greitens oversaw the Department of Public Safety's plan to protect city infrastructure like firehouses. After declaring the protests an \"unlawful assembly\", police officers were pelted with water bottles and rocks. Protesters also descended upon Mayor [[Lyda Krewson]]'s home, and threw bricks at and vandalized it. Police deployed tear gas to break up the crowd and two officers were injured by bricks thrown by protesters. Over the night, ten police officers were injured and 32 protesters arrested. Greitens said, \"In the past, our leaders let people break windows, loot, start fires. They let them do it. Not this time.\u201d Within 48 hours, major threats of violence were thwarted and it was reported that the St. Louis police made 300 arrests. Greitens garnered national attention for his response to the protest. \u201cWe had leaders who wanted to give people a safe space to loot and to burn,\u201d Greitens told Fox News. \u201cNow in Missouri if you loot the only safe space you\u2019re going to have is in a jail cell.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/gov-greitens-you-break-a-window-you-re-going-to/article_4e2ca012-aa46-50e8-a22e-37885318db8a.html |title=Gov. Greitens: 'You break a window, you're going to be behind bars.' |date=September 17, 2017 |newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |first=Erin |last=Heffernan |access-date=August 13, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==== Low-income housing tax credits ====\nIn 2017 the Missouri Housing Development Commission voted 8 to 2 to zero out the state's low-income housing tax credit for 2018.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/greitens-succeeds-push-halt-low-income-housing-tax-credits|title=Greitens succeeds in push to halt low-income housing tax credits|last=Griffin|first=Marshall|website=news.stlpublicradio.org|language=en|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref> Greitens phoned into the meeting and voted to zero out the tax credits while then Lt. Governor [[Mike Parson]] voted to keep them. Greitens said in a written statement that \"special interests abused low income housing tax breaks to make themselves rich.\"<ref name=\":13\" /> Following Greitens's appointments to the commission and the 2017 vote, Missouri did not issue $140 million in state low-income housing tax credits. The low-income housing tax credit program was cut from over $1.3 billion over the previous decade to zero. Greitens accused the low-income housing industry of conspiring to upend his political career though legal troubles and the threat of impeachment.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article232245482.html|title='Affordable housing crisis': Future of Missouri low-income tax credit still in flux|last=By|website=kansascity|language=en|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref> It was later determined that a month after he orchestrated the demise of the tax credit, local newspaper publisher Scott Faughn paid $50,000 in cash to the attorney for the ex-husband of the woman who accused Greitens of sexual misconduct.<ref name=\":14\" /> ''[[The Kansas City Star]]'' reported on July 8, 2019, that Faughn eventually paid the attorney another $70,000 in cash, keeping the transactions secret for months while continuing to cover Greitens both in his newspaper and on his TV show, which is sponsored by Sterling Bank, a Poplar Bluff-based bank highly involved in low-income housing tax credits. When the payments were eventually revealed, Faughn fled the state to avoid a subpoena from Greitens's lawyers. The attorney who received the payments testified that he was told the cash came from a GOP donor who wanted to oust Greitens.<ref name=\":14\" />[[File:GreitensFire.jpg|thumb|Greitens training with firefighters at the St. Louis Fire Academy in February 2017.]]When Parson took over as governor following Greitens's resignation in June 2018, he was adamant that the $150 million program remain dormant until the legislature passed reforms. In May 2019, after the legislature was unable to reconcile differences between the two chambers in a bill to restart the program, Parson's office announced that he would consider restoring the credits without the legislature, but he ultimately decided against doing so.\n\n====Changes to the Missouri National Guard and veterans' rights ====\nOn June 14, 2017, Greitens signed legislation (S.B. 108) guaranteeing state and federal reemployment rights to Missouri employees who are members of any reserve component of the U.S. Armed Forces called to active duty. The law also extended reemployment rights to Missouri employees who are members of the National Guard of another state called to active duty in that state.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thinkhr.com/blog/missouri-employment-law-update-june-2017/ |title=Missouri Employment Law Update |date=June 19, 2017 |website=ThinkHR |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nOn October 10, 2017, Greitens announced the Missouri Army National Guard would add nearly 800 soldiers by 2019. The expansion brought units to Missouri from around the country. The new units' economic impact was estimated around $15 million, including direct payroll and access to benefits for healthcare and education for the soldiers.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article178264206.html |title=Gov. Greitens announces 800 new National Guard jobs |agency=Associated Press |date=October 11, 2017 |newspaper=The Kansas City Star |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Greitens announced that members of the Missouri National Guard would train with the [[Israeli Home Front Command]]. Missouri is one of four states\u2014along with Colorado, Illinois and Massachusetts\u2014to train with the command, a branch of the [[Israel Defense Forces]] that focuses on civilian protection during a war or crisis.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stljewishlight.com/news/local/gov-greitens-missouri-national-guard-troops-to-train-with-israelis/article_bf3fbe72-11bb-11e8-a64c-e304a2a51eee.html |title=Gov. Greitens: Missouri National Guard troops to train with Israelis |website=St. Louis Jewish Light |date=February 14, 2018 |first=Eric |last=Berger |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://fox2now.com/2018/02/09/missouri-to-partner-with-israeli-home-front-command/ |title=Missouri to partner with Israeli Home Front Command |date=February 9, 2018 |agency=Associated Press |website=Fox2Now |publisher=[[KTVI]] |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Greitens signed into law legislation allowing those in the Missouri National Guard and the armed forces reserves to deduct their military income from their state taxes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://fox2now.com/2018/04/19/missouri-bill-lowers-income-taxes-for-national-guard-and-reserves/ |title=Missouri bill lowers income taxes for National Guard and reserves |date=April 19, 2018 |agency=Associated Press |website=Fox2Now |publisher=KTVI |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nOn April 27, 2018, Greitens announced an initiative in the Department of Natural Resources to recruit and hire more veterans at Missouri State Parks. DNR began recruiting veterans to serve in the department in June 2017. That effort was expanded by opening additional positions to veteran recruits including Park Ranger, Park/Historic Site Specialist and maintenance classifications. In response to the initiative, the [[Missouri Department of Natural Resources]] developed a new website devoted to veteran recruitment.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.kfvs12.com/story/38063168/gov-greitens-announces-effort-to-hire-vets-for-mo-state-parks/ |publisher=[[KFVS]] |date=April 27, 2018 |title=Gov. Greitens announces effort to hire vets for MO state parks |first=James |last=Long |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Confide app ruling===\nIn December 2017, Democrats accused Greitens and senior members of his staff of subverting Missouri's open records laws after the ''[[Kansas City Star]]'' reported that they used [[Confide]], a messaging app that erases texts after they have been read, on their personal phones.<ref name=\"penchant\">{{cite news |title=Greitens' penchant for secrecy goes digital with messaging app that leaves no trace |url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article188405944.html|author=Hancock, Jason|date=December 7, 2017| work=[[Kansas City Star]]|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref> Attorney General Hawley at first claimed conflict of interest, but on December 20 announced his office would investigate, saying that the matter was legally complex because the state [[Sunshine Law]] \"was written decades and decades ago and has not been updated to take into account\" technological changes.<ref name=\"answers\">{{cite news|title=Greitens answers question about his use of secret texting app by attacking media |url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/local/news-columns-blogs/the-buzz/article189204289.html|author=Hancock, Jason|date=December 11, 2017|newspaper=[[Kansas City Star]]|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Missouri attorney general will investigate Gov. Greitens' use of secret texting app|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article190772809.html|author=Hancock, Jason|date=December 20, 2017|work =[[Kansas City Star]]|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"seeks\">{{cite news|title=New lawsuit seeks to stop Missouri governor from using secretive phone app| url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/new-lawsuit-seeks-to-stop-missouri-governor-from-using-secretive/article%E2%80%94b22e94c7-6546-5eff-a93e-43f33fa6978a.html |author=Erickson, Kurt|date=January 2, 2018|newspaper=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref> In March 2018, Hawley cleared Greitens, finding no evidence of wrongdoing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/hawley-s-office-subpoenaed-for-greitens-confide-investigation-records/article_d4ea77f9-b984-53c1-add0-a4bef6ef8ed0.html|title=Hawley's office subpoenaed for Greitens Confide investigation records|last=Suntrup|first=Jack|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn late December, two attorneys filed suit, claiming that use of such \"self-immolating\" apps by elected officials and government employees violates Missouri's public records laws.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lawsuit alleges Gov. Greitens conspired to violate Missouri open records laws |url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article192544944.html|author=Hancock, Jason|date=January 2, 2018|work=[[Kansas City Star]]|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Organization files lawsuit against Greitens over use of app |url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/national/organization-files-lawsuit-against-greitens-over-use-of-app/article_468329d1-a491-5148-bf1f-17198125f02b.html|date=January 2, 2018|newspaper=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref> On January 3, 2018, Rep. Gina Mitten filed House Bill 1817, which would ban use of apps like Confide in conducting public business, and Speaker Richardson told the ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'' that in its 2018 session the legislature might consider modernizing the state's current open records laws.<ref name=\"seeks\" />\n\nOn July 9, 2019, [[Cole County, Missouri|Cole County]] Circuit Judge Jon Beetem sided with Greitens, dismissing the claims that Greitens's office had subverted or violated any laws. Beetem also ruled that as a private citizen, Sansone cannot sue Greitens over alleged Sunshine Law violations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kshb.com/news/state/missouri/missouri-judge-sides-with-ex-gov-eric-greitens-in-lawsuit-over-message-deleting-app|title=Judge sides with ex-Gov. Greitens in Sunshine Law suit|date=July 9, 2019|website=KSHB|language=en|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Affair and invasion of privacy charge ===\nOn January 10, 2018, ahead of an investigative report released by St. Louis [[CBS]] affiliate [[KMOV]] the same evening, Greitens publicly disclosed that he had engaged in an extramarital affair with his hairstylist in 2015.<ref name=\"kmov.com\">{{cite news |url=https://www.kmov.com/news/blackmail-alleged-as-governor-greitens-admits-to-extramarital-affair/article_f4d77b48-9d65-5fbc-8511-84002622188d.html  |title=Blackmail alleged as Governor Greitens admits to extramarital affair |date=January 10, 2018 |publisher=[[KMOV]] |first1=Lauren |last1=Trager |first2=John |last2=O'Sullivan |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref> Greitens and his wife issued a joint statement in which he acknowledged the affair, called it \"a deeply personal mistake\", and said that \"we dealt with this together honestly and privately.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-pol-missouri-governor-greitens-20180111-story.html|title=Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens' extramarital affair was 'the worst-kept secret in the world' |last=Pearce|first=Matt|date=January 11, 2018|work=L.A. Times|access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref> KMOV played a recording made by the hairstylist's then-husband in which she said that Greitens had invited her to his home, where she consented to having her hands taped to exercise rings above her head while she was undressed and blindfolded. In the recording, the hairstylist added that while she was blindfolded, Greitens took pictures of her without her consent and threatened to share them if she ever went public with the affair.<ref name=\"washingtonpost\">{{Cite news|first=Fred|last=Barbash|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2018/01/11/missouri-gov-eric-greitens-admits-extramarital-affair-but-denies-reports-he-blackmailed-woman/|title=Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens admits extramarital affair but denies reports he blackmailed woman with nude photo|work=[[Washington Post]] |publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|location=Washington DC|date=January 11, 2018|access-date=January 11, 2018|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\nGreitens denied the blackmail accusation.<ref name=\"washingtonpost\" /> After initially not commenting on the question, his attorney appeared to deny that any pictures were taken; in an email, he wrote, \"No violence. No picture taken. No threat of blackmail.\"<ref name=\"kmov.com\" /><ref>{{Cite news|first1=Kevin|last1=McDermott|first2=Jack |last2=Suntrup|first3=Celeste|last3=Bott|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/greitens-admits-affair-on-heels-of-television-report/article_b5f28d4d-72bd-512c-870b-da7dc7cd1fe3.html|title=Greitens admits affair, but denies allegation he blackmailed woman with photo |work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|publisher=[[Lee Enterprises]]|location=St. Louis, Missouri|date=January 11, 2018 |accessdate=February 24, 2018|quote=No violence. No picture taken. No threat of blackmail.}}</ref> Greitens also denied taking any such photos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/state-lawmaker-says-greitens-told-him-no-picture-ever-taken/article_13f90b72-a796-5cc5-a1b9-8b10f356d068.html|title=State lawmaker says Greitens told him 'no picture ever taken' of former lover|last=McDermott|first=Kevin|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=August 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter Attorney General [[Josh Hawley]]'s office said in a statement that it did not have jurisdiction to look into the matter, the [[district attorney|circuit attorney]] for the City of St. Louis opened an investigation into the blackmail allegations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fox4kc.com/2018/01/11/st-louis-circuit-attorney-launches-investigation-into-gov-greitens-following-affair-blackmail-allegations/|title=St. Louis circuit attorney launches investigation into Gov. Greitens following affair, blackmail allegations|last=Koch|first=Makenzie|date=January 11, 2018|access-date=January 11, 2018|publisher=fox4kc.com|agency=Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article194149869.html|title=Greitens faces criminal inquiry, calls for resignation after blackmail allegations|last1=Lowry|first1=Bryan|date=January 11, 2018|work=[[Kansas City Star]]|access-date=January 11, 2018|publisher=[[McClatchy Company]]|last2=Hancock|first2=Jason|location=Kansas City, Missouri}}</ref>\n\nOn January 20, 2018, [[CNN]] reported that two unnamed sources alleged that the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] was investigating Greitens. Following its usual practice, the FBI did not confirm or deny the existence of an inquiry, and the sources could not confirm whether the blackmail allegations were its focus.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Evan|last1=Perez|first2=MJ|last2=Lee|first3=Rebecca|last3=Berg|title=FBI opened inquiry into Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens|url=http://www.cnn.com/2018/01/19/politics/missouri-governor-eric-greitens-fbi-inquiry/index.html|work=[[CNN]]|date=January 19, 2018|accessdate=February 12, 2018}}</ref> In response, Greitens's attorney, Jim Bennett, said in an email that he and his colleagues had not seen any indication that an FBI investigation was underway. Bennett added that they saw nothing worthy of investigation, and that \"Governor Greitens has not been contacted at any time by the FBI and we are not aware of any interest by the FBI.\"<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news-leader.com/story/news/politics/2018/01/20/greitens-attorney-pushes-back-cnn-report-fbi-inquiry/1050784001/|title=Greitens' attorney pushes back on CNN report of FBI inquiry|last=Schmitt|first=Will|website=Springfield News-Leader|language=en|access-date=August 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n\"I have notified CNN that this story should be retracted,\" Bennett said. \"Without getting into the details, it is sufficient to say the named source has a history of profane and aberrant behavior toward people associated with Governor Greitens dating back to last year to such a degree that Governor Greitens\u2019 press secretary had to block his calls and other members of the Missouri Republican Party staff felt threatened to the degree that senior leadership attempted to intervene with his family.\" The named source was former Greitens supporter Eli Karabell.<ref name=\":20\" /> On January 20, 2018, Greitens told the AP he didn\u2019t know Karabell. Greitens\u2019s spokesman, Parker Briden, said Karabell was a \u201cserial liar\u201d who had called Briden multiple times \u201cacting crazy,\u201d including claiming he would donate millions to Greitens if he could meet with him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/4d51c51d43894faa994c71138a5bab07|title=Missouri governor: 'no blackmail,' 'no violence' in affair|last=Lieb|first=David a|last2=Ballentine|first2=Summer|date=January 20, 2018|website=AP NEWS|access-date=August 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Indictment====\nOn February 22, 2018, a St. Louis [[grand jury]] indicted Greitens on felony invasion of privacy charges.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=February 23, 2018|title=Missouri governor charged over nude photo|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-43164741|newspaper=BBC News|date=February 23, 2018}}</ref> He was released on [[personal recognizance|his own recognizance]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Missouri gov. indicted on invasion of privacy charge for allegedly taking compromising photo |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/eric-greitens-indicted-invasion-of-privacy-compromising-photo/|accessdate=February 27, 2018 |publisher=CBS News|date=February 23, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Kevin|last=Held|title=Gov. Eric Greitens indicted for invasion of privacy|url=http://fox2now.com/2018/02/22/gov-eric-greitens-indicted/|website=Fox 2 St. Louis|location=St. Louis, Missouri|date=February 22, 2018|accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref> and waived his first appearance.<ref>Joel Currier, [http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/greitens-waives-first-court-appearance-in-computer-tampering-case/article_0aa57c54-45dc-5999-ab32-473300365ca8.html Greitens waives first court appearance in computer tampering case], ''St. Louis Post-Dispatch'' (May 22, 2018).</ref> \n \nOn March 26, the judge denied defense motions to have a [[bench trial]] rather than a jury trial, refused to dismiss the assistant prosecutor, kept the jury trial date as scheduled, and refused to dismiss the indictment.<ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.nhregister.com/news/article/The-Latest-Judge-allows-charge-against-Missouri-12782763.php|title=The Latest: Judge allows charge against Missouri governor|date=March 27, 2018|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn April 9, 2018, ''Fox News'' reported that the woman with whom Greitens had the affair testified that she could not say whether she saw Greitens with a camera or phone on the day he allegedly took the photo. Court records say that the woman told prosecutors, \"I don't know if it's because I'm remembering it through a dream or I\u2014I'm not sure, but yes, I feel like I saw it after it happened, but I haven't spoken about it because of that\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/missouri-gov-greitens-ex-lover-said-illicit-photo-may-have-been-a-dream-documents-say|title=Missouri Gov. Greitens' ex-lover said illicit photo may have been 'a dream,' documents say|last=Chamberlain|first=Samuel|date=April 9, 2018|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn pre-trial depositions, William Tisaby, a former FBI agent who assisted Gardner with the Greitens investigations, affirmed to defense attorneys that he had taken notes during his interview of the woman. After attorneys pressed him to turn over the notes, he changed his testimony and asserted that he had not taken notes during the interview. Video footage, initially withheld from defense attorneys but later tendered, showed Tisaby taking notes during his interview with the woman while in Gardner's presence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/st-louis-prosecutor-s-investigator-greitens-case-charged-perjury-evidence-tampering|title=St. Louis Prosecutor's Investigator In Greitens Case Charged With Perjury, Evidence Tampering|last=Lippmann|first=Rachel|website=news.stlpublicradio.org|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 20, 2018, the circuit court attorney charged Greitens with a second felony for tampering with a computer in taking email and donor lists from The Mission Continues for fundraising purposes.<ref name=\"NewsTrib\">[http://www.newstribune.com/news/missouri/story/2018/apr/30/house-committee-release-supplemental-greitens-report/724225/ House committee investigating Greitens releases report comparing woman's testimony], ''[[Jefferson City News Tribune]]'', April 30, 2018. Retrieved May 1, 2018.</ref> The Associated Press first reported on the donor list in October 2016. Greitens initially denied using the list, but in April 2017 he acknowledged its use. Greitens said the list was provided by his then-campaign manager, but the former manager denied that.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/former-aide-says-greitens-relied-charity-donor-list-dark-money-kick-start-campaign |title=Former aide says Greitens relied on charity donor list, 'dark money' to kick-start campaign |first1=Jo |last1=Mannies |first2=Jason |last2=Rosenbaum |publisher=[[KWMU]] |date=May 9, 2018 |access-date=May 18, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n====Voluntary dismissal of criminal charges====\nBoth charges against Greitens were dropped in May 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Berg|first1=Rebecca|title=Charge dropped against Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/05/14/politics/eric-greitens-charge-dropped/index.html|work=CNN|date=May 14, 2018|accessdate=November 19, 2018}}</ref> Prosecutors withdrew the felony invasion of privacy charge on May 14, 2018, after investigators failed to find the alleged photo that formed the basis of the charge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2018/05/15/charge-against-missouri-gov-eric-greitens-is-dropped-but-prosecutors-plans-to-revisit/|title=Charge against Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens is dropped, but prosecutors plan to revisit|work=Washington Post|date=May 15, 2018|author=Samantha Schmidt}}</ref> The prosecutor's office agreed that if Greitens resigned, it would withdraw the felony charges relating to the charity email list.<ref name=\"The New York Times\">{{cite news |last1=Bosman |first1=Julie |last2=Smith |first2=Mitch |title=Gov. Eric Greitens of Missouri Resigns: 5 Takeaways |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/30/us/eric-greitens-missouri-takeaways.html |work=The New York Times |date=May 30, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Greitens resigned effective June 1, 2018.<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/embattled-missouri-gov-eric-greitens-says-he-will-resign/2018/05/29/5dc13386-6384-11e8-a69c-b944de66d9e7_story.html Embattled Missouri Governor Eric Greitens says he will resign], ''[[Washington Post]]'', Sean Sullivan, May 29, 2018. Retrieved May 30, 2018.</ref>\n\nThe circuit attorney referred the case to a special prosecutor, Jean Peters Baker of Kansas City. Baker declined to refile charges, citing the statutes of limitations and insufficient evidence.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vockrodt |first1=Steve |title=Baker declines to charge Greitens despite 'probable cause' for sexual assault |url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article212769354.html |newspaper=The Kansas City Star |accessdate=December 22, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.riverfronttimes.com/newsblog/2019/06/19/kim-gardner-cant-escape-the-shadow-of-greitens-investigation|title=Kim Gardner Can't Escape the Shadow of Greitens' Investigation|last=Wicentowski|first=Danny|website=Riverfront Times|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> ''The Kansas City Star'' confirmed that at the conclusion of Gardner's and Baker's investigations, evidence of an alleged photo was never produced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kansascity.com/opinion/editorials/article212861529.html|title=Jean Peters Baker declined to charge Greitens, but she did right by the victim|last=Sugg|first=Rich|website=kansascity|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn May 18, 2018, [[Cole County, Missouri|Cole County]] Prosecutor Mark Richardson announced he would not file any additional charges against Greitens, as suggested by Attorney General Hawley, related to how his gubernatorial campaign reported the receipt of a charity donor list used for political fundraising.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ksdk.com/article/news/local/missouri-prosecutor-says-he-wont-file-charges-against-governor-greitens/63-553896740 |title=Missouri prosecutor says he won't file charges against Governor Greitens |website=KSDK |language=en-US |access-date=May 18, 2018 |date=May 18, 2018 |agency=Associated Press }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/missouri-to-launch-special-session-on-greitens-allegations/2018/05/18/32580988-5a59-11e8-9889-07bcc1327f4b_story.html |title=Greitens won't be charged for finance report on donor list |last=Lieb|agency=Associated Press |first=David A. |date=May 18, 2018 |newspaper=Washington Post |language=en-US |access-date=May 18, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==== Special Investigative Committee report ====\nSeveral Republican members of the [[Missouri House of Representatives]] called on Greitens to resign after the allegations were made public.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Jack|last1=Suntrup|first2=Kurt|last2=Erickson|title=Missouri Republicans debate whether Greitens should stay or go|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/fourth-gop-house-member-says-greitens-should-resign/article_6838825d-5a63-5bfb-8d81-c17fb4c89ee4.html|work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|publisher=[[Lee Enterprises]]|date=January 17, 2018|accessdate=February 12, 2018}}</ref> Hawley, a Republican running for the U.S. Senate, called the situation \"very grave\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Benjamin|last=Peters |url=https://themissouritimes.com/49665/hawley-calls-situation-with-greitens-very-grave-in-fox-news-interview/|title=Hawley calls situation with Greitens 'very grave' in Fox News interview|work=The Missouri Times|publisher=Capitol Publishing Group |location=Jefferson City, Missouri|date=March 29, 2018|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> Illinois Governor [[Bruce Rauner]], a Greitens campaign contributor and ally, called on Greitens to resign.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/12/rauner-greitens-resignation-call-520858 |title=Illinois GOP governor calls for Missouri GOP governor to resign |newspaper=[[Politico]] |first=Natasha |last=Korecki |date=April 12, 2018 |access-date=April 30, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nOn April 11, 2018, a Special Investigative Committee (SIC) of the Missouri House of Representatives released an initial 24-page report detailing allegations against Greitens by the hairstylist with whom he had had an affair.<ref>{{cite report |title=Report of the Missouri House Special Investigative Committee on Oversight|publisher=Missouri House of Representatives |date=April 11, 2018}}</ref> The stylist accused him of unwanted kissing and sexual touching, violently slapping and spanking her, coercing her into performing oral sex on him, and threatening to blackmail her.<ref>{{cite news|first=John|last=Eligon |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/11/us/missouri-greitens-house-impeachment-inquiry.html|title=Sex Claims Against Missouri Governor Vividly Detailed in Report|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=New York Times Company|location=New York City|date=April 11, 2018 |accessdate=April 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Eli|last=Rosenberg |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2018/04/11/missouri-gov-eric-greitens-groped-and-initiated-unwanted-sexual-contact-with-woman-she-testifies/|title=Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens groped, hit and coerced woman into sexual contact, she testifies |work=[[Washington Post]]|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|location=Washington DC|date=April 11, 2018|accessdate=April 11, 2018}}</ref> In a four-page report issued on April 30, 2018 the SIC chair, Republican Representative Jay Barnes, said it found that the Greitens defense claims, that the woman's testimony was inconsistent, were groundless.<ref name=\"NewsTrib\" />\n\n====Impeachment session and resignation====\nOn May 3, the Missouri House and Senate collected enough signatures from members to call a special session to consider impeachment.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/05/03/politics/missouri-lawmakers-special-session-greitens-impeachment/index.html |title=Missouri lawmakers seeking special session for impeachment proceedings against Greitens |date=May 4, 2018 |first=Rebecca |last=Berg |access-date=May 5, 2018 |publisher=CNN }}</ref> House Speaker Todd Richardson, a Republican, said 29 senators and 138 House members, more than the three-fourths required in each chamber, supported convening a 30-day special session. It began on May 18, the last day of the regular session.<ref name=\"impeach\">[https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/03/eric-greitens-missouri-impeachment-special-session-568509 Missouri lawmakers agree to special session to weigh impeaching Gov. Eric Greitens], ''[[Politico]]'', Brent D. Griffiths, May 3, 2018. Retrieved May 7, 2018.</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://kcur.org/post/what-expect-during-missouri-s-special-session#stream/0 |title=Missouri's special session underway, here's what to expect |last=Griffin |first=Marshall |date=May 18, 2018 |work=[[KCUR]] |access-date=May 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn May 29, 2018, Greitens announced that he would resign effective June 1, 2018.<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\"/> The St. Louis prosecutor's office had made a deal with Greitens that if he resigned, it would withdraw the felony charges for using the veterans' charity email list in his campaign.<ref name=\"The New York Times\"/>\n\n====Aftermath====\nOn December 31, 2018, the Special Investigative Committee on Oversight that was investigating Greitens released its final report.<ref name=\"SuntrupReport\">{{cite web |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/committee-investigating-eric-greitens-releases-pages-of-documents-on-new/article_ec4525d1-f354-5729-860b-89821d75dd43.html |first=Jack |last=Suntrup |title=Committee investigating Eric Greitens releases 2,100 pages of documents on New Year's Eve |newspaper=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] |date=December 31, 2018}}</ref> The ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'' reported, \"Documents and testimony showed that Greitens ran an off-the-books gubernatorial campaign in 2014 and 2015, and lied about his campaign's acceptance of a charity donor list from the Mission Continues, a veterans charity Greitens founded in 2007.\"<ref name=\"SuntrupReport\" />\n\nOn July 18, 2019, [[KFVS-TV|KFVS]] televised an interview with Greitens about a leaked draft audit of former [[Missouri Department of Public Safety|Missouri Director of Public Safety]] Drew Juden by Democratic [[State Auditor of Missouri|State Auditor]] [[Nicole Galloway]], rumored to be planning a run for governor in 2020.<ref name=\":19\"/> Greitens can be seen leaving a building in his U.S. Navy uniform before changing clothes to speak to the station.<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kfvs12.com/2019/07/18/juden-defends-tenure-dps-draft-audits/|title=Juden defends tenure in DPS draft audits|last=Sweeney|first=Kathy|website=KFVS|access-date=July 24, 2019|date=July 18, 2019}}</ref> He appointed Juden in January 2017 as Director of Missouri Department of Public Safety. Governor [[Mike Parson]] announced that Juden would leave the department in August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2018/09/07/fired-missouri-official-takes-shots-at-parson-his-replacement/|title=Fired Missouri official takes shots at Parson, his replacement|date=September 7, 2018|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref> Shortly after the appointment of former State Patrol Superintendent Sandra Karsten as Juden's replacement, Auditor Nicole Galloway announced a departmental audit of DPS at Parson's request.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2018/11/28/galloway-to-audit-missouri-dps-directors-office-parson-and-karsten-called-for-audit/|title=Galloway to audit Missouri DPS director's office; Parson and Karsten called for audit|date=November 28, 2018|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref> KFVS's investigation found that Galloway's audit covered only Juden's time as Director.<ref name=\":19\" /> The first draft of the audit KFVS obtained alleged that Juden had taken unreported time off while Director.<ref name=\":19\" />\n\n===Final days in office===\nAt 508 days, Greitens's gubernatorial tenure is the 10th-shortest in Missouri history. Among elected governors, his tenure is the shortest of any Missouri governor since 1861, and the fourth-shortest overall (behind only [[Frederick Bates (politician)|Frederick Bates]], [[Claiborne Fox Jackson]], and [[Trusten Polk]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://editions.lib.umn.edu/smartpolitics/2018/05/31/eric-greitens-records-4th-shortest-tenure-by-an-elected-missouri-governor/|title=Eric Greitens Records 4th Shortest Tenure By An Elected Missouri Governor {{!}} Smart Politics|website=editions.lib.umn.edu|date=May 31, 2018|access-date=June 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the final days of his administration, Greitens signed 77 pieces of legislation into law. Among these was a bill that cut the corporate tax rate and changed how utility companies receive rate adjustments. He also signed a law making [[revenge porn]] illegal in Missouri. He banned lab-grown meats, provided a 5% rate reduction for utility companies, and allowed monopoly utility companies to increase fees for water services if they don't make the expected amount from utility rates. Greitens also signed bills to:\n\n* allow telephone companies to choose a different way to be taxed;\n* pare a program intended to entice developers to restore dilapidated buildings;\n* raise the minimum age to be tried as an adult from 17 to 18;\n* give state regulatory control over disposal of industrial waste;\n* codify consumer protections for Missourians to ensure they're not stuck with large bills for emergency services;\n* reclassify state workers as at-will employees;\n* allow businesses to grow and harvest hemp;\n* decrease the corporate tax rate from 6.25% to 4%; and\n* expand medicaid coverage for new mothers struggling with addiction.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erickson |first1=Kurt |title=Here are the bills Gov. Eric Greitens signed before leaving office |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/here-are-the-bills-gov-eric-greitens-signed-before-leaving/article_d2132b21-8db0-5d50-bed6-1d8ad4ec34b0.html |website=stltoday.com |publisher=St Louis Post-Dispatch |accessdate=November 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nGreitens also issued four commutations and five pardons.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greenwald |first1=Dan |title=Greitens issues several pardons and commutations on final day in office |url=https://www.kmov.com/news/greitens-issues-several-pardons-and-commutations-on-final-day-in/article_75ee3711-21e0-567c-a3bc-53ffe34db35e.html |website=kmov.com |publisher=KMOV4 |accessdate=November 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Pardon of Judy Henderson ====\nOn December 20, 2017, Judy Henderson was released from the Chillicothe Correctional Center in northwest Missouri after 35 years on Greitens's orders.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/nation-world/article215228235.html|title='I've not really talked about it.' Judy Henderson revisits Klein murder on crime show|last=Gutierrez|first=Lisa|date=July 21, 2018|website=The Kansas City Star|access-date=}}</ref> Greitens went to Chillicothe to meet with Henderson and sign the papers commuting her life sentence for her role in the July 1981 robbery-turned-murder of jeweler Harry Klein. Greitens's office said that Henderson could have been out of prison decades earlier.<ref name=\":17\" /> Following her release, the 68-year-old Henderson gave her version of the events on \"''The Real Story with [[Mar\u00eda Elena Salinas]]''.\"<ref name=\":17\" /> Authorities believe her boyfriend, Greg Cruzen, shot Klein and paid four witnesses to lie about Henderson's role, according to the ''[[Springfield News-Leader]]''.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news-leader.com/story/news/crime/2018/06/06/springfield-judy-henderson-eric-greitens-pardon-prison-release/559819002/|title=Eric Greitens still has fans, like the Springfield woman he pardoned after 35 years in prison|website=Springfield News-Leader|language=en|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref> At trial, Henderson and Cruzen were represented by the same defense attorney. \"I remember Jimmy McMullin, the attorney, telling us to not say a word, not to talk to anyone about anything. I was so confused, I felt like we were both going to be O.K. That's what Greg kept telling me,\" she told Salinas. Henderson claims she wanted to take the stand to defend herself \"but Jimmy McMullin said I cannot, and I did not know what my defense was until every witness walked in the courtroom and I would tell Jimmy when they would come in, I said, 'Who are they and why are they here?'\" She was found guilty. Cruzen was acquitted.<ref name=\":17\" />\n\nGreitens's office said it reviewed thousands of documents related to the case before Greitens commuted her sentence and subsequently pardoned her. She told the ''News-Leader'' that Greitens called her on his last day in office to tell her she was pardoned. \"The loss of a life and the pain that it caused his family is something that will stick with me for the rest of my life,\" Henderson said in June 2018.<ref name=\":18\" />\n\n===Appointment of special prosecutor to investigate St. Louis Circuit Attorney===\nFollowing the dismissal of all charges against Greitens, his defense attorneys filed a police report with the [[Metropolitan Police Department, City of St. Louis|St. Louis Metropolitan Police Department]] alleging criminal misconduct by Gardner's office in his case.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/stlouis/news/2018/05/15/greitens-lawyers-to-file-police-report-accusing.html|newspaper=St. Louis Business Journal|access-date=July 2, 2019|title=Greitens' lawyers to file police report accusing former lead investigator of perjury |date=May 15, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nOn June 29, 2018, St. Louis Circuit Judge Michael Mullen appointed Gerard Carmody as special prosecutor to investigate the alleged misconduct by Gardner's office.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kbia.org/post/special-prosecutor-appointed-william-tisaby-investigation|title=Special prosecutor appointed in William Tisaby investigation|last=Lippmann|first=Rachel|website=kbia.org|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/greitens-investigator-s-deposition-reveals-confrontation-confusion-but-did-he/article_a7250df9-7baa-5c9f-8e91-248406678286.html|title=Greitens investigator's deposition reveals confrontation, confusion. But did he commit perjury?|last=Currier|first=Robert Patrick, Joel|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> On June 17, 2019, a 7-count felony indictment of William Tisaby was unsealed. Tisaby had been charged with six counts of felony perjury and one count of felony tampering with evidence.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article231646258.html|title=Former FBI agent who investigated Greitens indicted for perjury, evidence tampering|last=By|website=kansascity|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> According to the ''St. Louis Post-Dispatch'', the 30-page indictment accused Tisaby of concealing a series of documents from defense attorneys and lying under oath during the deposition \u201cabout matters that could substantially affect, or did substantially affect, the course or outcome of the Greitens case.\"<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/former-fbi-agent-who-investigated-greitens-indicted-in-st-louis/article_147c2a69-b36e-5822-8e8c-e81ac81cfdf7.html|title=Former FBI agent who investigated Greitens indicted in St. Louis as part of perjury investigation|last=Patrick|first=Joel Currier, Robert|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> ''The Associated Press'' reported that Tisaby surrendered to authorities on the same day the indictment against him was unsealed. He pleaded not guilty at his arraignment and was released on his own recognizance on the conditions that he surrender his passport and inform a probation officer of any travel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/8172e48bb5f74427a315ab8322542338|title=Former Greitens' investigator indicted on 7 felonies|last=Hollingsworth|first=Heather|date=2019-06-17|website=AP NEWS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> In a press conference following Tisaby's release from custody on June 17, 2018, Tisaby's attorney, Jermaine Wooten, told reporters that \u201cMs. Gardner is probably the actual target here, not Mr. Tisaby.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox2now.com/2019/06/18/attorney-gardner-is-probably-the-actual-target-here-not-mr-tisaby/|title=Attorney: 'Gardner is probably the actual target here, not Mr. Tisaby'|date=June 18, 2019|website=FOX2now.com|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe indictment also lodged a series of claims against Gardner, stating \"that she failed to correct Tisaby\u2019s lies, failed to report them to police, and made incorrect statements to defense lawyers and the judge.\" The alleged misconduct in the unsuccessful prosecution of Greitens has placed Gardner at risk of losing her law license and facing criminal charges.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nOn July 10, 2019, the grand jury that indicted Tisaby disbanded without any other indictments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/grand-jury-disbands-without-charging-st-louis-circuit-attorney/article_e0894ff8-d44d-553c-8cb6-7822076aa626.html|title=Grand jury disbands without charging St. Louis Circuit Attorney|last=Currier|first=Joel|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref> The next day, Gardner held a press conference outside the St. Louis Circuit Attorney's Office denying any wrongdoing in Greitens's case. The press conference marked Gardner's first public statement on the matter since the appointment of the special prosecutor, as a gag order had been placed on the case for the duration of the grand jury. Fox 2 Now reported that Gardner claimed that it was time for the city to \"move on\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox2now.com/2019/07/11/after-grand-jury-term-ends-gardner-says-its-time-for-the-city-to-move-on/|title=After grand jury term ends, Gardner says it's time for the city to move on|date=July 11, 2019|website=FOX2now.com|language=en|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref> Following the press conference, Carmody took the unusual step of putting out a statement clarifying that the grand jury disbanded not because the investigation was complete but because it had reached its expiration and its term could not be extended.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://molawyersmedia.com/2019/07/16/investigation-involving-st-louis-prosecutor-kimberly-gardner-is-ongoing-2/|title=Investigation involving St. Louis prosecutor Kimberly Gardner is ongoing|last=Salter|first=Jim|date=July 16, 2019|website=Missouri Lawyers Media|language=en-US|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref> \u201cNotwithstanding the expiration of that Grand Jury\u2019s term, the investigation into possible criminal activity will continue,\u201d Carmody said in the statement.<ref name=\":16\" />\n\nDuring an August 15, 2019 hearing, Carmody said the ongoing probe was focused on the failed prosecution of Greitens and confirmed that Gardner was under \"active criminal investigation.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ksdk.com/article/news/local/criminal-investigation-into-failed-prosecution-of-former-missouri-governor-eric-greitens-remains-active/63-a23813c9-e272-4f63-b918-5f918214bc43|title=Criminal investigation into failed prosecution of former Missouri Governor Eric Greitens remains 'active'|website=KSDK|access-date=August 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation and conclusion==\n\nIn February 2020, after a nearly 18-month investigation into Greitens's 2016 gubernatorial campaign, the Missouri Ethics Commission (MEC) \"found no evidence of any wrongdoing\" by him, but required the campaign to update its reports with in-kind contributions from two groups, and to pay the commission about $178,000 in fees. In a statement, Greitens called the result an exoneration and vindication.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/13/politics/eric-greitens-no-wrongdoing-investigation-missouri/index.html |title=Investigation into former Missouri governor who resigned finds 'no evidence of any wrongdoing' |date=February 13, 2020 |first=Rebecca |last=Buck |publisher=CNN |access-date=February 14, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://krcgtv.com/news/local/no-evidence-of-any-wrongdoing-former-gov-eric-greitens-fully-exonerated|title=UPDATE: State ethics fines Greitens campaign $178,000 for failing to report contributions|date=February 13, 2020|publisher=KRCG|access-date=February 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nGreitens spoke publicly for the first time since his resignation with [[KTVI|Fox 2 St. Louis]]' Chris Hayes on February 13, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox4kc.com/news/no-evidence-of-any-wrongdoing-former-governor-eric-greitens-fully-exonerated-of-campaign-misconduct/|title='No evidence of any wrongdoing': Former Gov. Eric Greitens fully exonerated, campaign to pay $38k|date=February 13, 2020|website=FOX 4 Kansas City WDAF-TV {{!}} News, Weather, Sports|language=en-US|access-date=February 24, 2020}}</ref> Greitens claimed that the investigation was a result of \"false allegations made by a lawyer politician,\" presumably former State Rep. Jay Barnes, who filed the complaint. Barnes served as the Chairman of the Missouri House Special Committee on Oversight responsible for investigating the allegations against Greitens. Barnes publicly accused Greitens of running a \"criminal enterprise\" and of having committed \"literary fraud\" relating to Greitens' best-selling book, ''Resilience''. The MEC found no evidence to support Barnes' claims.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox2now.com/2020/02/13/were-fighting-back-eric-greitens-on-new-ethics-report-on-his-campaign/|title='We're fighting back' \u2013 Eric Greitens on new ethics report on his campaign|date=February 14, 2020|website=FOX2now.com|language=en|access-date=February 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn February 20, 2020, Greitens appeared on several radio shows to discuss a resolution introduced in the [[Missouri House of Representatives|Missouri House]] by Rep. Justin Hill calling on [[United States Attorney General|U.S. Attorney General]] [[William Barr]] and the [[Department of Justice]] to investigate several cash payments totaling $120,000 paid to witnesses in the Greitens case in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://971talk.radio.com/blogs/the-marc-cox-morning-show/former-missouri-governor-eric-greitens-on-federal-investigat|title=Greitens endorses call for federal investigation|date=February 20, 2020|website=FM NewsTalk 97.1|language=en|access-date=February 24, 2020}}</ref>  Hill, a former police officer with experience on a DEA task force responsible for large currency investigations, appeared on The Marc Cox Show prior to Greitens. Hill characterized the cash payments delivered by convicted felon and Missouri journalist Scott Faughn as a \"criminal effort to un-elect a duly elected Governor.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://971talk.radio.com/blogs/the-marc-cox-morning-show/missouri-rep-justin-hill-on-governor-eric-greitens|title=Rep Justin Hill wants AG Barr to investigate the Greitens take down|date=February 19, 2020|website=FM NewsTalk 97.1|language=en|access-date=February 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Post-gubernatorial career==\nOn June 2, 2019, the ''St. Louis Post-Dispatch'' reported that Greitens had returned to the U.S. Navy as a Naval Reserve Officer. Since leaving office, he has worked on a book about his Jewish faith.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/getting-his-sea-legs-back-after-resigning-from-office-greitens/article_0b797d35-842b-56aa-ad2f-77f046890dd4.html|title='Getting his sea legs back.' After resigning from office, Greitens tries to steady his life \u2014 in private|last=Suntrup|first=Kurt Erickson, Jack|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== COVID-19 Response ====\nDuring a [[Fox News]] interview on [[America's Newsroom]], Greitens called the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] outbreak a \"serious issue\" and said that \"fear is also contagious\", calling for a level-headed response from elected officials.<ref>{{Citation|title=America's Newsroom|url=https://www.facebook.com/EricGreitens/videos/1396498820558747/|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, 2020, Greitens solicited donations and then purchased $80,000 worth of [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE) for first responders in the [[Greater St. Louis|St. Louis]], [[Kansas City metropolitan area|Kansas City]], and [[St. Joseph, Missouri|St. Joseph]] areas. He provided nearly 15,000 protective masks to numerous agencies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kmox.radio.com/articles/news/former-gov-eric-greitens-delivers-masks-to-first-responders|title=Former Gov. Eric Greitens delivers $80,000 protective masks to St. Louis first responders|date=2020-03-30|website=KMOX-AM|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox2now.com/news/missouri/former-missouri-governor-gets-donors-to-raise-money-for-masks-for-first-responders/|title=Former Missouri governor gets donors to raise money for masks for first responders|date=2020-03-30|website=FOX2now.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Sheena Greitens.jpg|thumb|upright|Sheena Greitens in 2017]]\n[[File:Inauguration of Eric Greitens 12.jpg|thumb|Eric and Sheena Greitens dancing at the inaugural ball]]\nGreitens's marriage to his first wife ended in divorce in 2003.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article194096374.html|title=Gov. Greitens admits to extramarital affair, denies threatening to blackmail the woman|work=The Kansas City Star|date=January 10, 2018|first=Jason|last=Hancock|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe married Sheena Elise Chestnut on August 7, 2011, in [[Spokane, Washington]],<ref name=\"nyt1\" /> and they have two sons.<ref name=\"MizzStateU\">[http://publicaffairs.missouristate.edu/Convocation/Eric-Greitens.htm 2014 Convocation Lecture] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220191705/http://publicaffairs.missouristate.edu/Convocation/Eric-Greitens.htm |date=February 20, 2015 }} February 16, 2015</ref><ref>Hollerman, Joe [http://www.stltoday.com/lifestyles/columns/joe-holleman/stl-s-eric-greitens-steps-down-as-veterans-group-chief/article_1efe6a36-7515-5ac0-bd7d-8fc111c83c55.html STL's Eric Greitens steps down as veterans group chief], ''St. Louis Post-Dispatch'', February 16, 2015.</ref><ref name=\"nyt1\" /> Sheena Greitens is an [[assistant professor]] of [[political science]] at the [[University of Missouri]], focused primarily on China and North Korea.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ksl.com/article/46234810 |title=Missouri governor admits having affair but denies blackmail |first1=Summer |last1=Ballentine |first2=Jim |last2=Salter |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=January 11, 2018 |access-date=February 28, 2019 |website=[[KSL.com]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Greitens had an extramarital affair with his hairstylist.<ref name=\"kmov.com\"/>\n\nThe first Jewish governor of Missouri, Greitens attends the Reform B\u2019nai El synagogue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/meet-the-first-jewish-governor-of-missouri-a-former-navy-seal/|title=Meet the first Jewish governor of Missouri, a former Navy SEAL|last=Friedman|first=Gabe|website=timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stljewishlight.com/news/local/q-a-with-eric-greitens-who-will-be-first-jewish/article_2201014b-2727-5f86-b345-130fa9837055.html|title=Q&A with Eric Greitens, who will be first Jewish governor of Missouri|last=JTA|first=Gabe Friedman|website=St. Louis Jewish Light|language=en|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, before Greitens took office, Sheena Greitens was robbed at gunpoint at a St. Louis-area coffee shop. She was unharmed. Three suspects, ages 14, 15 and 19, were arrested a short time later. Eric Greitens said at the time that he was glad \u201cthe men and women of law enforcement found these young men before I did.\u201d<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/4416854ada4f4957ba61e514b8ede13c|title=3 in custody in robbery of wife of Missouri governor-elect|last=Salter|first=Jim|date=2016-12-06|website=AP News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> After the incident, [[Missouri State Highway Patrol]] Captain John Hotz said the patrol would begin providing security for Sheena Greitens. The patrol provided security for the governor-elect immediately after the election, but Hotz said security detail for the spouse typically begins only after a governor takes office.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n==Honors and awards==\nOn October 3, 2008, [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush]] awarded Greitens the [[President's Volunteer Service Award]] outside [[Air Force One]] at [[Lambert International Airport]] in St. Louis, Missouri, for his work at [[The Mission Continues]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/greitens-said-it-memorable-quotes-that-marked-his-candidacy-governorship/article_aa4c6678-2482-56ff-af43-c7c13ec8cfe4.html |title=Greitens said it: Memorable quotes that marked his candidacy, governorship |date=June 1, 2018 |newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |access-date=February 28, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://latimesblogs.latimes.com/washington/2009/01/post-1.html |title=Who were those unfamiliar audience faces at Bush's farewell address? |date=January 15, 2009 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=February 28, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Greitens received the HOOAH Award, commissioned by the Major George A. Smith Memorial Fund and presented by the [[National Conference on Citizenship]] to recognize \"a notable veteran who defines their citizenship through service to our country\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncoc.net/index.php?tray=content&tid=top45&cid=2kc27|title=Presentation of the HOOAH Award to Lt. Eric Greitens |publisher=[[National Conference on Citizenship]]|access-date=April 28, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100929060411/http://www.ncoc.net/index.php?tray=content&tid=top45&cid=2kc27 |archive-date=September 29, 2010 |date=October 2, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.slideshare.net/civicvoice/ncoc-event-program-2009 |title=Event Program: HOOAH Award |date=September 9, 2009 |publisher=[[National Conference on Citizenship]] |at=slide 5 |via=[[SlideShare]] |access-date=February 28, 2019 }}</ref> He was also named the 2010 Reader of the Year by ''[[Outside (magazine)|Outside]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nyberg|first=Justin|url=http://outsideonline.com/outside/culture/200912/altruism-all-stars-eric-greitens.html|title=Adventure Altruism All-Stars|work =Outside Online |date=December 3, 2009|accessdate=April 28, 2014 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110507012215/http://outsideonline.com/outside/culture/200912/altruism-all-stars-eric-greitens.html|archivedate=May 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=Sam|last1=Moulton|first2=Kyle|last2=Dickman|first3=Justin |last3=Nyberg|first4=Ryan|last4=Krogh|first5=Abe|last5=Streep|url=http://www.outsideonline.com/1874971/adventure-altruism-all-stars |title=Adventure Altruism All-Stars|work=[[outside (magazine)|Outside Online]]|publisher=Mariah Media|location=Santa Fe, New Mexico |date=December 2, 2009|accessdate=May 24, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2010, [[Major League Baseball]] and ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' announced Greitens as a winner in ''People's All-Stars Among Us'' competition. He was selected to represent the city of St. Louis and the Cardinals at the 2010 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] in [[Anaheim, California]].<ref>[http://newyork.yankees.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20100601&content_id=10674702&vkey=pr_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl \"MLB, ''PEOPLE'' Magazine & Cardinals announce three finalists for 'People All-Stars Among Us' national campaign\"], New York Yankees, June 1, 2010.</ref><ref>[http://mlb.mlb.com/peopleallstarsamongus \"People All-Stars Among Us\"], MLB.com, June 20, 2010.</ref>\n\nOn May 20, 2012, Greitens was awarded an honorary Doctor of Humane Letters degree from [[Tufts University]] when he gave the commencement speech at the school's 156th commencement.<ref>[http://now.tufts.edu/articles/meaningful-adventure \"A Meaningful Adventure\"], Tufts University, May 20, 2012.</ref> That same year he received the Bronfman Prize, which recognizes dynamic leaders whose innovation and impact serve as inspiration for the next generations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecharlesbronfmanprize.com/recipients/2012-eric-greitens|title=Eric Greitens profile|work=Charles Bronfman Prize|date=February 16, 2015|accessdate=April 11, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807065905/http://thecharlesbronfmanprize.com/recipients/2012-eric-greitens|archive-date=August 7, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn April 18, 2013, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' named Greitens to its list of the 100 Most Influential People in the World.<ref name=TIME>{{cite magazine|first=Mike|last=Mullen|url=http://time100.time.com/2013/04/18/time-100/slide/eric-greitens|title=The 2013 TIME 100: Eric Greitens|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|location=New York City|date=February 18, 2015 |accessdate=April 11, 2018}}</ref> In 2014 ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' featured him as one of the World's 50 Greatest Leaders.<ref>{{cite web|first=Geoff|last=Colvin|url=http://money.cnn.com/gallery/leadership/2014/03/20/worlds-best-leaders.fortune/38.html|title=Eric Greitens - Fortune ranks the World's 50 Greatest Leaders|work=[[CNNMoney]]|publisher=[[CNN]] |date=March 20, 2014|accessdate=April 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Military award ribbons and badges ===\n\n[[File:United_States_Navy_Special_Warfare_insignia.png|200x200px]]\n\n[[File:United_States_Navy_Parachutist_Badge.png|200x200px]]\n\n[[File:NavySmallBoatOfficerPin.jpg|alt=|100x100px]]\n\n[[File:Bronze_Star_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Bronze Star Medal]]\n\n[[File:Purple_Heart_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Purple Heart]]\n\n[[File:Joint_Service_Commendation_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Commendation Medal|Joint Service Commendation Medal]]\n\n[[File:Navy_and_Marine_Corps_Commendation_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Commendation Medal|Navy and Marine Corps Commendation Medal]]\n\n[[File:Combat_Action_Ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Combat Action Ribbon|Navy Combat Action Ribbon]]\n\n[[File:Us_jointservachiev_rib.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Achievement Medal|Joint Service Achievement Medal]]\n\n[[File:Navy_and_Marine_Corps_Achievement_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Achievement Medal|Navy and Marine Corps Achievement Medal]]\n\n[[File:National_Defense_Service_Medal_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[National Defense Service Medal]]\n\n[[File:Afghanistan_Campaign_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Afghanistan Campaign Medal]]\n\n[[File:Iraq_Campaign_Medal_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Iraq Campaign Medal]]\n\n[[File:Global_War_on_Terrorism_Expeditionary_Medal_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary Medal]]\n\n[[File:Global_War_on_Terrorism_Service_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]]\n\n[[File:Sea_Service_Deployment_Ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Sea Service Deployment Ribbon|Navy Sea Service Deployment Ribbon]]\n\n[[File:ResMedRib.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Armed Forces Reserve Medal]]\n\n[[File:Outstanding_Volunteer_Service_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Military Outstanding Volunteer Service Medal|Outstanding Volunteer Service Medal]]\n\n[[File:United_States_Navy_Rifle_Marksmanship_Ribbon_with_expert_device.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Marksmanship Medal|Navy Expert Rifleman Medal]]\n\n[[File:United_States_Navy_Pistol_Marksmanship_Ribbon_with_expert_device.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Marksmanship Medal|Navy Expert Pistol Shot Medal]]\n\n==Publications==\n*{{cite thesis|type=AB|last=Greitens|first=Eric R.|date=1996|title=On Courage|publisher=Duke University|degree=|url=https://find.library.duke.edu/catalog/DUKE002133696|doi=}}\n*{{cite thesis|type=M.Phil|last=Greitens|first=Eric R.|date=1998|title=Intervening on Behalf of Children in War: Challenges for Humanitarian Assistance|publisher=Oxford University|degree=|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Intervening_on_Behalf_of_Children_in_War.html?id=-qhEPAAACAAJ|doi=}}\n*{{cite thesis|type=PhD|last=Greitens|first=Eric R.|date=2000|title=Children First: Ideas and the Dynamics of Aid in Western Voluntary Assistance Programs for War-Affected Children Abroad|publisher=Oxford University|degree=|url=https://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?uin=uk.bl.ethos.365669|doi=}}\n*{{Cite book| last=Greitens| first=Eric|title=Strength & Compassion: Photographs and Essays|publisher=Leading Authorities Press|year=2008|isbn=978-0971007802}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Greitens|first=Eric|title=The Heart and the Fist: The Education of a Humanitarian, the Making of a Navy SEAL|publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]]|year=2011|isbn=978-0547424859|ref=harv|location=New York|url=https://archive.org/details/heartfisteducati0000grei|url-access=registration}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Greitens|first=Eric|title=The Warrior's Heart: Becoming a Man of Compassion and Courage|publisher=[[HMH Books for Young Readers]]|year=2012|isbn=978-0547868523|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/warriorsheartbec0000grei}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Greitens|first=Eric|title=Resilience: Hard-Won Wisdom for Living a Better Life|publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]]|year=2015|isbn=978-0544323988|title-link=Resilience: Hard-Won Wisdom for Living a Better Life}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{C-SPAN|ericgreitens}}\n* {{Charlie Rose view|15618}}\n* {{Worldcat id|lccn-n2008-39452}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dave Spence]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[Governor of Missouri]]|years=[[2016 Missouri gubernatorial election|2016]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jay Nixon]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Governors of Missouri|Governor of Missouri]]|years=2017\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mike Parson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of Missouri}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Politics|War}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Greitens, Eric}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American male taekwondo practitioners]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:American military writers]]\n[[Category:American Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:Angier B. Duke Scholars]]\n[[Category:Duke University alumni]]\n[[Category:Governors of Missouri]]\n[[Category:Jewish American military personnel]]\n[[Category:Jewish American state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from St. Louis]]\n[[Category:Missouri Democrats]]<!-- Switched parties -->\n[[Category:Missouri Republicans]]\n[[Category:Republican Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Truman Scholars]]\n[[Category:United States Navy SEALs personnel]]\n[[Category:University of Missouri faculty]]\n[[Category:Washington University in St. Louis faculty]]\n[[Category:White House Fellows]]\n[[Category:Writers from Missouri]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Eric Greitens\n|image        = Eric Greitens 2018.jpg\n|order        = 56th [[List of governors of Missouri|Governor of Missouri]]\n|lieutenant   = Mike Parson\n|term_start   = January 9, 2017\n|term_end     = June 1, 2018\n|predecessor  = [[Jay Nixon]]\n|successor    = [[Mike Parson]]\n|birth_name   = Eric Robert Greitens\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1974|04|10}}\n|birth_place  = [[St. Louis]], [[Missouri]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] (2015\u2013present)\n|otherparty   = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] (before 2015)\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Sheena Chestnut|2011}}\n|children     = 2\n|education    = [[Duke University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br />[[Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]] ([[Master of Arts|MPhil]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|DPhil]])\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States|}}\n|branch       = {{naval|United States}}\n|serviceyears = 2001\u2013present\n|rank         = [[File:US-O4 insignia.svg|23px]] [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]]\n|mawards      = [[File:Bronze Star ribbon.svg|23px|border]] [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]]<br />[[File:Purple Heart BAR.svg|border|23px]] [[Purple Heart]] \n}}\n'''Eric Robert Greitens''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0261|r|a\u026a|t|\u0259|n|z}};<ref>{{cite AV media |people=Greitens, Eric |date=June 6, 2016 |title=Eric Greitens: Taking Aim |medium=video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Yf2Gai1uQYM |access-date= April 12, 2018}}</ref> born April 10, 1974) is an American politician, humanitarian, author, and former [[Navy SEAL]] who was the [[List of Governors of Missouri|56th]] [[governor of Missouri]] from January 2017 until his resignation in June 2018.\n\nBorn and raised in [[St. Louis]], Greitens received a doctorate from [[Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]], as a [[Rhodes scholar]]. During his four tours of duty as a U.S. Navy SEAL officer, he rose to the rank of [[United States Navy officer rank insignia|lieutenant commander]], commanded a unit targeting [[Al-Qaeda]], and was awarded a [[Bronze Star]] and a [[Purple Heart]]. Later, after being a [[White House Fellow]], Greitens founded a nonprofit organization, [[The Mission Continues]], to benefit veterans. In 2013, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' included him in its [[Time 100|list]] of the 100 most influential people in the world.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://time100.time.com/2013/04/18/time-100/slide/eric-greitens|title=The 2013 ''TIME'' 100| first=Mike |last=Mullen|journal=Time |accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter having been a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] during his early life, Greitens announced in 2015 that he had become a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]. He ran for governor of Missouri as a Republican in 2016. Greitens prevailed over three opponents in the [[2016 Missouri gubernatorial election#Republican primary|Republican primaries]] and then defeated Democratic state [[Attorney General of Missouri|Attorney General]] [[Chris Koster]] in the [[2016 Missouri gubernatorial election|general election]]. One of Greitens's signature accomplishments in office was signing Missouri's [[Right-to-work law|right-to-work]] law,<ref name=\":7\" /> which was later repealed by statewide referendum.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\nIn February 2018, St. Louis Circuit Attorney [[Kimberly Gardner]] charged Greitens with felony [[invasion of privacy]]. Gardner later also charged him with campaign-related offenses. Greitens was indicted on felony charges of computer tampering in April 2018;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/20/politics/eric-greitens-computer-tampering-charge/index.html|title=Missouri Gov. Greitens indicted on felony computer-tampering charge|last=Berg|first=Rebecca|date=|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> all charges were dropped in May 2018. Greitens resigned from office on June 1<ref>{{cite news|last1=Suntrup|first1=Jack|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/judge-greitens-team-must-turn-over-documents-from-his-dark/article_b3674fa9-5972-529e-b0a2-4c6ca010dc42.html|title=Embattled Gov. Eric Greitens resigns|date=May 30, 2018|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|access-date=|url-status=live|last2=Erickson|first2=Kurt}}</ref> after the Missouri Legislature commenced a special session to consider impeachment.<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.riverfronttimes.com/newsblog/2018/04/11/greitens-blasts-political-witch-hunt-just-before-impeachment-report-drops|title=Greitens Blasts 'Political Witch Hunt' Just Before Impeachment Report Drops|last=Fenske|first=Sarah|website=Riverfront Times|language=en|access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> In June 2018, Special Prosecutor Gerard Carmody began investigating Gardner and announced a seven-count felony indictment against the prosecution's lead investigator.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref name=\":22\" /> In February 2020, the Missouri Ethics Commission reported that its campaign investigation did not find wrongdoing on Greitens's part individually, or that he knew of two reporting issues that it found with his campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/13/politics/eric-greitens-no-wrongdoing-investigation-missouri/index.html|title=Investigation into former Missouri governor finds 'no evidence of any wrongdoing'|first=Rebecca |last=Buck|website=CNN|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> Greitens and his supporters have denied any criminal wrongdoing and have repeatedly called the allegations a \"political witch hunt\".<ref name=\":23\" />\n\n==Early life==\nGreitens was born on April 10, 1974, in [[St. Louis, Missouri]], a son of Becky and Rob Greitens.<ref name=nyt1>[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/07/fashion/weddings/sheena-chestnut-eric-greitens-weddings.html \"Sheena Chestnut, Eric Greitens\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', August 5, 2011.</ref> He was raised in his mother's [[Jewish]] faith; his father is [[Catholic]].<ref name=\"thetower\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thetower.org/article/can-this-jewish-republican-outsider-change-the-face-of-missouri-eric-greitens|title=Can This Jewish Republican Outsider Change the Face of Missouri?|work=The Tower| accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/magazine/2017/07/10/eric-greitens-missouri-governor/|title=Eric Greitens's Rising Star|first=John J.|last=Miller|date=July 10, 2017|website=[[National Review]]}}</ref> Greitens's mother retired as an early childhood special education teacher in St. Ann, Missouri, for the Pattonville School District. His father, also retired, was an accountant in St. Louis for the Department of Agriculture.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/07/fashion/weddings/sheena-chestnut-eric-greitens-weddings.html|title=Sheena Chestnut, Eric Greitens: Weddings|date=August 5, 2011|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 28, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>  Greitens graduated from [[Parkway North High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parkwayalumni.org/participate/hof/charter/greitens.html|title=Home of the Parkway Alumni Association|work=Parkway Alumni Association|accessdate=May 11, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324120058/http://www.parkwayalumni.org/participate/hof/charter/greitens.html|archive-date=March 24, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> He grew up as a Democrat.<ref name=\"Fox News\">{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/opinion/former-navy-seal-why-i-am-no-longer-a-democrat|title=Former Navy SEAL: Why I am no longer a Democrat|author1=Eric Greitens|publisher=[[Fox News]]|date=July 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nGreitens was an [[Angier Buchanan Duke|Angier B. Duke]] Scholar at [[Duke University]], where he studied ethics, philosophy, and public policy and graduated [[Summa Cum Laude|''summa cum laude'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abduke.org/scholars/viewfeatured.aspx?id=6b7913cf-b136-41a8-9595-2d11e7ffbe04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081226125105/http://www.abduke.org/scholars/viewfeatured.aspx?id=6b7913cf-b136-41a8-9595-2d11e7ffbe04|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 26, 2008|title=Featured Profiles|publisher=A.B. Duke Foundation|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}</ref> At Duke he contributed photographs to a Save the Children Foundation project involving refugees from the [[Rwandan genocide]] and the war in Bosnia. Some of his work appeared in the publication ''Children in War: Community Strategies for Healing''.<ref>[http://www.eric.ed.gov/PDFS/ED412009.pdf ''Children in War: Community Strategies for Healing''], ed.gov; accessed May 11, 2017.</ref><ref name=Beacon />\n\nBefore graduating from Duke in 1996, Greitens was selected as a [[Rhodes Scholar|Rhodes]]<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1995/12/11/us/32-are-named-rhodes-scholars.html?scp=1&sq=greitens&st=cse 32 Are Named Rhodes Scholars] AP National Desk, nytimes.com, December 11, 1995.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/1995/12/two-receive-rhodes |title=Two receive Rhodes |date=December 11, 1995 |last=Allen |first=Misty |work=dukechronicle.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510212008/http://dukechronicle.com/node/107778 |archive-date=May 10, 2010 |accessdate=November 1, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and a [[Truman Scholar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.truman.gov/meet-our-scholars?Year=1995|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929033242/http://www.truman.gov/meet-our-scholars?Year=1995|url-status=dead|title=Meet Our Scholars, 1995 Truman Scholars|archivedate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> He went on to attend [[Lady Margaret Hall]], a constituent college of the [[University of Oxford]], where he earned a [[MPhil|master's degree in philosophy]] in development studies in 1998 and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|doctorate in philosophy]] in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|title=Public service focus of Greitens' talk|url=https://source.wustl.edu/2010/03/public-service-focus-of-greitens-talk/|date=March 17, 2010}}</ref> Greitens is a former Senior Fellow at the Harry S. Truman School of Public Affairs at the [[University of Missouri]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://truman.missouri.edu/People/EricGreitens|title=Archived copy|accessdate=May 24, 2011|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110324095601/http://truman.missouri.edu/People/EricGreitens|archivedate=March 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Athletics ===\nGreitens is a sub-three-hour marathon runner and a winner of Shamrock Marathon at Camp Fallujah, Iraq. A boxer, he won two Oxford University Boxing Blues and the gold medal at the British Universities Sports Association's National Boxing Championships.<ref name=\":2\" /> Greitens has a black belt in [[Taekwondo]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.navytimes.com/news/your-navy/2017/12/12/missouri-gov-eric-greitens-a-former-navy-seal-touts-his-physical-feats/|title=Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens, a former Navy SEAL, touts his physical feats|last1=Balantine|first1=Summer|date=December 11, 2017|newspaper=Navy Times|access-date=June 28, 2019|agency=Associated Press|last2=Stafford|first2=Margaret}}</ref>\n\n=== Humanitarian work ===\nGreitens has done international humanitarian work in Rwanda, Cambodia, Albania, Mexico, India, the Gaza Strip, Croatia, and Bolivia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bigthink.com/videos/eric-greitens-why-i-became-a-navy-seal|title=Eric Greitens: Why I Became a Navy SEAL|date=September 4, 2011|website=Big Think|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> During his 2016 campaign for governor, he said, \"I have worked in Cambodia with kids who lost limbs to land mines and are survivors of polio. I\u2019ve worked in Bolivia with children of the street. I\u2019ve worked in one of Mother Teresa\u2019s homes for the destitute and dying.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/883fae53a7864ae89abe1f5e9a9bb94a|title=Missouri gubernatorial candidates on social issues|last=Press|first=The Associated|date=October 9, 2016|website=AP NEWS|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFor six weeks as a college student, Greitens worked at two refugee camps, the Puntizela camp outside Pula, Croatia, and the Gasinci camp outside Osijek, Croatia. Both are described in his book. Refugee camps in Croatia were temporary homes for Bosnians crossing the border.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.columbiamissourian.com/news/politifact_missouri/fact-check-greitens-worked-with-bosnian-refugees-but-location-less/article_f1b362f0-85a8-11e6-917e-e386578ae76b.html|title=FACT CHECK: Greitens worked with Bosnian refugees but location less clear|last=Alamdari|first=Natalia|website=Columbia Missourian|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> Greitens also traveled to Rwanda and Zaire as a volunteer U.N. photographer.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==Career==\nGreitens has taught public service at the Truman School of Public Affairs and was an adjunct professor of business ethics in the MBA program at the [[Olin School of Business]] at [[Washington University in St. Louis]].<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|title=Eric Greitens |url=http://now.tufts.edu/commencement-2012/eric-greitens|work =Tufts Now|date=May 20, 2012|publisher=[[Tufts University]]|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Faculty News:Bookshelf|work=Olin Business |url=https://olin.wustl.edu/docs/Communication/OlinBusinessMagazine_2011.pdf|issue=Fall 2011|page=11|publisher=[[Olin Business School]]|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=records>{{cite news|title=Records shed light on Missouri candidate Eric Greitens' income, sources|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article111904197.html|author=Hancock, Jason |date=November 1, 2016|work =[[Kansas City Star]]|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Armed services===\nGreitens matriculated at the [[Officer Candidate School (United States Navy)|United States Navy's Officer Candidate School]] in [[Pensacola, Florida]], in January 2001, graduating in May of that year as an ensign in the [[United States Navy Reserve]].{{sfn|Greitens|2011|p=133}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.veteransadvantage.com/cms/content/herovet-eric-greitens|title=Eric Greitens profile|last=Asfar|first=Roy|date=April 1, 2011|publisher=Veterans Advantage|accessdate=April 28, 2014}}</ref> He then began [[Basic Underwater Demolitions/SEAL]] (BUD/S) training in [[Coronado, California]],{{sfn|Greitens|2011|p=143\u201345}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navyseals.com/life-service| title=Archived copy| accessdate=May 24, 2011|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722154323/http://www.navyseals.com/life-service|archivedate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> graduating with Class 237 in February 2002.{{sfn|Greitens|2011|p=201}}\n\nGreitens rose to be a [[lieutenant commander]] in the [[United States Navy Reserve]]. During his active duty career, he was deployed four times, to [[Iraq]], [[Afghanistan]], the [[Horn of Africa]], and [[Southeast Asia]]. He was the commander of a joint special operations task unit, a [[Mark V Special Operations Craft]] detachment,{{sfn|Greitens|2011|p=235}} and an al-Qaeda targeting cell.{{sfn|Greitens|2011|p=271}} He was awarded the [[Bronze Star]], [[Purple Heart]], and the [[Combat Action Ribbon]].<ref name=\"Beacon\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://now.tufts.edu/commencement-2012/eric-greitens |title=Eric Greitens |publisher=Tufts University |website=Tufts Now |access-date=April 13, 2018 |year=2012 }}</ref> In 2011 the Association of the U.S. Navy named Greitens its Naval Reserve Junior Officer of the Year.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://now.tufts.edu/commencement-2012/eric-greitens|title=Eric Greitens|date=October 16, 2013|website=Tufts Now|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe has criticized the [[Veterans Administration]], saying of its employees, \"Even if you\u2019re only 40 percent disabled, they\u2019ll give you 100 percent disability in some cases.\" \"You have to think about the incentives of government workers. Guys in the VA don\u2019t get paid to help veterans lead productive lives. Their metrics are on how many people sign up for benefits.\" He feels such overuse strains the VA system and prevents vets from reintegrating into general society.<ref name=\"Beacon\">[http://freebeacon.com/politics/the-great-jewish-hope/ The Great Jewish Hope], ''[[Free Beacon]]'', Bill McMorris, February 19, 2015. Retrieved April 12, 2018.</ref>\n\nDuring a deployment in Thailand, Greitens learned of drug use by Navy personnel and initiated an investigation that led to their removal. In the Philippines Greitens's crew effectively shut down a transit site for a terrorist organization, according to an evaluation report.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/76bc2050643a49edbef75bae6f8fedd5|title=Greitens' displayed ambition, from childhood through career|last=Lieb|first=David a|date=May 13, 2018|website=AP NEWS|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> Greitens spent three months in charge of a 50-person unit in Manda Bay, Kenya, near the Somali border. He left full-time active duty to take a one-year White House fellowship, where he developed a program to get architecture and engineering students involved in rebuilding efforts after Hurricane Katrina.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.columbiatribune.com/e6d628f8-08cb-568f-80ec-31b7fa4ff9b2.html|title=Military records laud Missouri Senate, governor candidates|website=Columbia Daily Tribune|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> Greitens simultaneously remained in the Navy Reserves, leading a program that recruited high-level advisers for special military operations around the world.<ref name=\":4\" /> After his fellowship, he volunteered for a six-month tour in Iraq that began in October 2006.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==== Fallujah truck bombing ====\nOn March 28, 2007, two suicide bombers detonated trucks carrying chlorine gas at the Fallujah government complex where Greitens and other military personnel were sleeping. The attack was the seventh [[Chlorine bombings in Iraq|chlorine bombing]] in the [[Al Anbar Governorate|Al Anbar]] province of [[Iraq]] by [[Al-Qaeda|al Queda]]. Greitens was among about 15 who were wounded.<ref name=\":5\" /> \"The attack began at 6:33 a.m. with mortar fire, followed by two truck bombs and small arms fire. Iraqi Police identified the first suicide attacker and fired on the truck, causing it to detonate before reaching the compound,\" according to a [[Multi-National Force West|Multinational Forces West]] press release. \"Iraqi Army soldiers spotted the second suicide truck approaching the gate and engaged it with small arms fire, causing it to also detonate near the entrance of the compound.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2007/03/fallujah_government.php|title=Fallujah government center struck by chlorine suicide attack {{!}} FDD's Long War Journal|date=March 28, 2007|website=longwarjournal.org|language=en-US|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> Greitens received a [[Purple Heart]] after sustaining injuries from the bombing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2017/05/29/greitens-explains-navy-seal-leadership-style-vs-political-leadership-style/|title=Greitens explains Navy SEAL leadership style vs. political leadership style|date=May 29, 2017|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===White House fellowship===\n[[File:Eric Greitens 2011-5.jpg|thumb|Greitens speaking in 2011]]\nIn 2005 President [[George W. Bush]] appointed Greitens as a [[White House Fellow]].<ref>[http://www.whitehouse.gov/fellows/alumni/2005-06.html White House Fellows: Class of 2005-2006\" Online Article] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080616101956/http://www.whitehouse.gov/fellows/alumni/2005-06.html |date=June 16, 2008 }}, WhiteHouse.gov, July 16, 2008.</ref> As a White House Fellow he worked in the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development|Department of Housing and Urban Development]] (HUD)<ref>Hinman, Kristen. [http://www.riverfronttimes.com/2008-04-09/news/navy-seal-eric-greitens-has-come-home-to-st-louis-to-help-fellow-iraq-vets \"Captain America\"], ''Riverfront Times'', April 9, 2008.</ref> and developed a new program to assist with rebuilding efforts after [[Hurricane Katrina]]: the Universities Rebuilding America Partnership (URAP),<ref>\"Volume 3 Number 5: Universities Rebuilding America\", PD&R Periodicals: Research Works, May 1, 2006.{{cite web|url= http://www.huduser.org/periodicals/ResearchWorks/may_06/RW_vol3num5t1.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=April 27, 2008|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080502214837/http://www.huduser.org/periodicals/ResearchWorks/may_06/RW_vol3num5t1.html|archivedate=May 2, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huduser.org/periodicals/ResearchWorks/may_06/RW_vol3num5t1.html|title=Internet Archive Wayback Machine |date=September 27, 2015|accessdate=May 18, 2017|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130504100943/http://www.huduser.org/periodicals/Researchworks/may_06/RW_vol3num5t1.html|archivedate=May 4, 2013}}</ref> a $5.6 million effort to engage architecture and engineering students in the continued effort to rebuild [[New Orleans]]. During his time as a White House Fellow he co-founded the President's Higher Education Community Service Honor Roll Program.<ref>[http://truman.missouri.edu/wp-content/uploads/eric-greitens-cv.pdf \"Profile: Eric Greitens\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220191347/http://truman.missouri.edu/wp-content/uploads/eric-greitens-cv.pdf |date=February 20, 2015 }}, The Truman School of Public Affairs webpage, February 20, 2015.</ref>\n\n===Nonprofit work===\nAfter returning from Iraq, Greitens used his combat pay and the disability pay of two friends to start [[The Mission Continues]], a nonprofit organization whose goal is to \"challenge veterans to serve and lead in communities across America\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.missioncontinues.org/About/About_Us|title=Archived copy|accessdate=May 23, 2011| url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110528042213/http://www.missioncontinues.org/About/About_Us|archivedate=May 28, 2011}}</ref> It encourages veterans to heal themselves through public service by engaging in volunteer organizations across the country.<ref>Klein, Joe [http://time.com/3707640/clay-hunts-legacy-for-veterans \"Clay Hunt's Legacy for Veterans\"], ''Time'', February 16, 2015.</ref><ref>Shane III, Leo [http://www.militarytimes.com/story/veterans/careers/civilian/2014/11/20/mission-continue-jobs/19320641 Study: Volunteer work could help vets' careers], ''Military Times'', February 16, 2015.</ref> In 2014 it won the CLASSY Award for its effectiveness in active-duty and veteran services.<ref>\"[http://www.classyawards.org/exchange/the-mission-continues-drives-progress-for-active-duty-veteran-services The Mission Continues Drives Progress for Active Duty & Veteran Services] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220191247/http://www.classyawards.org/exchange/the-mission-continues-drives-progress-for-active-duty-veteran-services/ |date=February 20, 2015 }}\", CLASSY Award, February 16, 2015.</ref> Greitens stepped down as CEO in July 2014 and resigned from the board of directors in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.missioncontinues.org/about/our-board|title=Our Board - Mission Continues |publisher= Mission Continues|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newprofit.com/cgi-bin/iowa/do/invest/37.html?page=leadership |title=New Profit Inc.: The Mission Continues|publisher= Mission Continues|accessdate=May 11, 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105211219/http://newprofit.com/cgi-bin/iowa/do/invest/37.html?page=leadership |archive-date=November 5, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.draperrichards.org/fellows/mission.html|title=Internet Archive Wayback Machine|date=September 28, 2015| accessdate =May 18, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120103015210/http://www.draperrichards.org/fellows/mission.html|archivedate=January 3, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.missioncontinues.org/About/OurTeam/details/11 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522084346/http://www.missioncontinues.org/About/OurTeam/details/11 |archivedate=May 22, 2011 |df= }}</ref><ref>Brennan, Vince [http://www.bizjournals.com/stlouis/news/2014/07/02/the-mission-continues-greitens-steps-down.html \"The Mission Continues' Greitens steps down\"], ''St. Louis Business Journal'', February 20, 2015.</ref>\n\nAs CEO of The Mission Continues, Greitens worked without a salary in 2007\u201308. Later he received compensation between $150,000 and $200,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/organizations/208742553|title=Nonprofit Explorer|work =ProPublica| accessdate= May 11, 2017}}</ref> Daniel Borochoff, president and founder of [[CharityWatch]], which evaluates nonprofit organizations, said that Greitens's wages \"seem within a reasonable range\"; the AP reported that his salary was about one-third higher than the $131,000 median compensation for chief executives of 237 medium-sized charities in the Midwest.<ref>[http://bigstory.ap.org/article/20824a15eb914e2694e1d4e102d909da/missouri-governor-candidates-salary-charity-questioned Missouri governor candidate's salary from charity questioned], [[Associated Press]], September 12, 2016.</ref> In a 2016 interview Borochoff cited Greitens's PhD and military experience as a possible reason for his slightly above-average salary. Borochoff said Greitens's wages \"seem within a reasonable range. The leaders of the Mission Continues have a big responsibility with this program, dealing with kind of a complicated population, so people shouldn't make that comparison to their own salary.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rebootcamp.militarytimes.com/education-transition/2016/09/08/the-mission-continues-founder-s-salary-questioned-amid-candidacy-for-missouri-governor/|title=The Mission Continues founder's salary questioned amid candidacy for Missouri governor|last=Lieb|first=David A.|date=April 2, 2018|website=Reboot Camp|language=en-US|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 [[New Profit Inc.|New Profit]] added The Mission Continues to its portfolio of the fastest-growing and highest-impact nonprofits in the sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.newprofit.org/amplify/honoring-the-mission-continues-on-veterans-day|title=Honoring The Mission Continues on Veterans Day|last=Admin|website=blog.newprofit.org|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> The [[Associated Press]] reported in March 2018 that Greitens had used the charity's email account to arrange political meetings about his intended gubernatorial campaign, which may not be allowed by federal tax law.<ref>[http://fox2now.com/2018/03/01/greitens-sent-political-invite-on-charity-email/ Greitens sent political invite on charity email], ''[[KTVI]]'', March 1, 2018. Retrieved March 20, 2018.</ref> He was also accused of using the charity's list of donors to raise money for his political campaign, a violation of campaign finance law.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news-leader.com/story/news/politics/2018/04/20/eric-greitens-indicted-again-he-suspected-stealing-charity-he-created/535650002/|title=Eric Greitens was indicted again. He is suspected of stealing from the charity he created.|work=Springfield News-Leader|access-date=September 9, 2018|language=en}}</ref> On December 28, 2018, the Missouri Attorney General informed The Mission Continues that, after a review of \u201chundreds of thousands of pages\u201d and several depositions, there was not enough evidence to support enforcement action against the nonprofit.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vockrodt |first1=Steve |title=Hawley drops Greitens-related investigations as he prepares to leave AG's office |url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article223692540.html |newspaper=Kansas City Star |accessdate=December 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018 The Mission Continues president Spencer Kympton posted an open letter informing its members that \"Regardless of someone's [Greitens's] history with The Mission Continues, we do not stand by actions that violate the core values we all strive to embody. And as uncomfortable as it may be, we must not fail to pronounce that.\" The letter also apologized to the volunteers and community leaders with The Mission Continues for any unwarranted attention from media and civic leaders they experienced.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.missioncontinuesblog.org/letter-veterans-thank-continuing-make-nations-communities-stronger/ |title=A Letter to Our Veterans: Thank You for Continuing to Make Our Nation's Communities Stronger |publisher=The Mission Continues |access-date=July 12, 2018 |date=July 10, 2018 |first=Spencer |last=Kympton }}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010 to 2012, [[Washington University in St. Louis]]'s [[Center for Social Development]], in collaboration with The Mission Continues, conducted a study involving nearly 500 veterans in more than 400 nonprofit organizations in 42 states. Its aim was to assess the perceived personal, social and family impacts of participating in the organization's Fellowship Program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://csd.wustl.edu/items/the-mission-continues-national-initiative-2/|title='The Mission Continues' National Initiative {{!}} Center for Social Development {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=csd.wustl.edu|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> \u201cThe results show that volunteering with The Mission Continues can help vets reengage in their communities and can increase their well-being,\" wrote Nancy Morrow-Howell, co-author and Faculty Associate, Center for Social Development, Washington University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://csd.wustl.edu/new-survey-shows-redeploying-veterans-to-serve-at-home-eases-reintegration-challenges/|title=New survey shows redeploying veterans to serve at home eases reintegration challenges {{!}} Center for Social Development {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=csd.wustl.edu|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Author===\n[[File:SD meets with Missouri governor 170327-D-GO396-222 (32870938313).jpg|thumb|left|Greitens with U.S. Secretary of Defense [[James Mattis]] in March 2017]]\nGreitens's first book, ''Strength and Compassion'' (2008), is a collection of photographs and essays with a foreword by Rwandan humanitarian [[Paul Rusesabagina]] and an introduction by [[Bobby Muller]], cofounder of the [[International Campaign to Ban Landmines]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.creativewell.com/pdf/muller.pdf|title=''Strength and Compassion''|publisher=creativewell.com|accessdate=May 11, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304074201/http://www.creativewell.com/pdf/muller.pdf|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Strength and Compassion: Photographs and Essays by Eric Greitens|date=September 23, 2008|isbn=978-0971007802|last1=Greitens|first1=Eric}}</ref> Photographs by Greitens were placed on display in the exhibition \u201cStrength and Compassion\u201d at the [[:fi:International Photography Hall of Fame and Museum|International Photography Hall of Fame]] (IPHF) in December 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/entertainment/arts-and-theatre/former-navy-seal-s-photos-come-to-international-photography-hall/article_7e960a88-fe17-5e83-80e0-38da5b8e968f.html|title=Former Navy SEAL's photos come to International Photography Hall of Fame|last=Miller|first=Sarah Bryan|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> ''Strength and Compassion'' was recognized as ''ForeWord'' magazine's Photography Book of the Year and the grand prize winner of the 2009 New York Book Festival.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOn April 11, 2011, [[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]] published Greitens's second book, ''The Heart and the Fist: The Education of a Humanitarian, the Making of a Navy SEAL''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.houghtonmifflinbooks.com/catalog/titledetail.cfm?titleNumber=1431563|title=Book Detail Page - HMH Books|work=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt |accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/39344692/Spring-2011-Adult-Frontlist-Catalog|title=Spring 2011 Houghton Mifflin Harcourt Adult Frontlist Catalog|publisher=scribd.com|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref> ''The Heart and the Fist'' is Greitens's memoir, featuring stories of his humanitarian work, his training as a naval officer and SEAL and the military experiences that led him to adopt the philosophy that one has to be strong to do good but also has to do good to be strong. The book ranked 10th on the ''New York Times'' bestseller list for hardcover nonfiction in May 2011,<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/22/books/review/InsideList-t.html?_r=1&ref=books|work=The New York Times|first=Jennifer|last=Schuessler|title=Inside the List|date=May 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2011-05-29/hardcover-nonfiction/list.html|work=The New York Times|first=Jennifer|last=Schuessler|title=Print & E-Books|date=May 29, 2011|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref> debuting on the St. Louis Independent Bookstore Alliance Best Sellers list at No. 1 for the week of April 17, 2011.<ref>[http://www.stlindiebook.com/node/41 \"St. Louis Independent Bookstore Alliance\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911121720/http://www.stlindiebook.com/node/41 |date=September 11, 2011 }}, stlindiebook.com; accessed May 10, 2017.</ref> The following year, Houghton Mifflin Harcourt also released a [[Young adult fiction|young adult]] edition, ''The Warrior's Heart''.<ref>Powers, Kevin, [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/11/books/review/the-warriors-heart-by-eric-greitens.html \"Acts of Valor\"], ''New York Times'', November 11, 2012; accessed February 18, 2015.</ref>\n\nIn March 2015 Houghton Mifflin Harcourt released Greitens's book ''[[Resilience: Hard-Won Wisdom for Living a Better Life]]''. It draws on letters Greitens wrote to a fellow SEAL struggling with [[PTSD]].<ref>Nelson, Marcia [http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/new-titles/adult-announcements/article/65354-spring-2015-announcements-lifestyle-death-and-dieting.html Spring 2015 Announcements: Lifestyle: Death and Dieting], ''Publishers Weekly'', February 16, 2015.</ref><ref>Naughton, Julie [http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/authors/interviews/article/65363-rising-after-a-fall-pw-talks-with-eric-greitens.html \"Rising After a Fall: PW Talks with Eric Greitens\"], ''Publishers Weekly'', February 16, 2015.</ref>\n\nAs an author and former SEAL, Greitens was a popular speaker before his political career.<ref name=\"records\" /> In 2016 an anonymous group charged in a [[YouTube]] video that he had exaggerated his record and was unduly benefiting from his time in the SEALs; Greitens responded to the claims by releasing his military records and publishing a video he uploaded to his channel with testimonials from SEALs and Marines with whom he had served.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/03/us/navy-seals-split-over-members-benefiting-from-hard-earned-brand.html|title=Rift Among Navy SEALs Over Members Who Cash In on Brand|date=April 3, 2016|work=The New York Times| accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Governor of Missouri==\nIn 2015, Greitens\u2014who was a Democrat in his early years\u2014wrote a [[Fox News]] editorial announcing that he had become a Republican. He said he had been raised in the tradition of [[Harry Truman]] and had even been recruited as a Democratic candidate for Congress, but was pushed rightward after seeing the [[Department of Veterans Affairs]] fail to help many of his brothers in arms. He recalled being angered at how the Democrats' only solution was to \"spend more money\" on the VA. \"The problem is that most Democrats seem to think more money and bigger government are the solutions to virtually every single problem,\" he wrote. He said he believed Democrats no longer had the right ideas to stand up for the middle class.<ref name=\"Fox News\"/>\n\n===2016 election===\n{{main|2016 Missouri gubernatorial election}}\n[[File:Eric Greitens for Governor.png|thumb|Gubernatorial election campaign logo]]\nOn September 26, 2015, Greitens announced his candidacy for [[List of Governors of Missouri|governor of Missouri]]<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/government-politics/article36693603.html|title=Former Navy SEAL Greitens running as Republican for Missouri governor|website=kansascity.com|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref> as a Republican.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/greitens-casts-himself-renegade-he-joins-gop-crowd-running-governor|title=Greitens casts himself as a renegade as he joins GOP crowd running for governor|author=Jo Mannies|work=stlpublicradio.org|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref> Shortly after a June 30, 2016, quarterly deadline for filing campaign contributions, he received the largest ever single contribution in a Missouri campaign, $1.975 million, which meant he did not have to reveal it until October, months after the primary. The source was a previously unknown [[Superpac]], \"SEALS for Truth\".<ref>[https://www.riverfronttimes.com/newsblog/2016/07/21/eric-greitens-nabs-single-largest-campaign-contribution-in-missouri-history Eric Greitens Nabs Single Largest Campaign Contribution in Missouri History], ''[[Riverfront Times]]'', Danny Wicentowski, July 21, 2016. Retrieved March 29, 2018.</ref> SEALS for Truth had received the money from the American Policy Coalition (APC), another Superpac, on the same day APC received the entire amount. Greitens had assured voters he intended to increase transparency while reducing corruption in state politics as a campaign focus.<ref name=\"Superpac\">[https://themissouritimes.com/34673/greitens-donors-donor-still-mystery/ Greitens donor\u2019s donor still a mystery], ''The Missouri Times'', Travis Zimpfer, October 17, 2016. Retrieved March 29, 2018.</ref> APC, about which there was almost no information online, was headed by Ohio lawyer David Langdon, who had incorporated it in Kentucky in 2015.<ref name=\"Superpac\" /> Between the 2010 election cycle and early 2015, at least 11 groups connected to Langdon spent at least $22 million on ballot initiatives against abortion and same-sex marriage and on federal and state elections around the country, as tabulated by the Center for Public Integrity.<ref>[https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2015/05/dark-money-ohio-elections-phantom-118268 Meet the Suburban Ohio Lawyer Behind the Right\u2019s Dark Money Machine], ''[[Politico]]'', Carrie Levine, May 26, 2015. Retrieved March 29, 2018.</ref> On March 12, 2017, the ''[[St. Louis Post Dispatch]]'' and ''[[The Kansas City Star]]'' editorial boards published a joint editorial criticizing Greitens for \"secret fundraising and secret spending\" and for tactics such as ordering that \"[s]ecurity staffers block reporters from getting close to him\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/opinion/columns/the-platform/editorial-attention-gov-greitens-our-joint-call-with-the-kansas/article_9a90c2e7-9aaa-5faf-886d-949420b1505c.html|title=Editorial: Attention, Gov. Greitens! Our joint call with ''The Kansas City Star'' for greater transparency, accountability|last=Star|first=the editorial boards of the St. Louis Post-Dispatch and The Kansas City|work=St. Louis Post Dispatch |accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref> In 2018 Missouri Attorney General [[Josh Hawley]], a Republican running for the U.S. Senate, announced the opening of an investigation of Greitens's 2016 campaign financing.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/23/mccaskill-missouri-greitens-republicans-senate-545393 |department=Elections |title='She's a lucky duck': GOP implodes again for McCaskill |newspaper=[[Politico]] |first=Daniel |last=Strauss |date=April 23, 2018 |access-date=April 30, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nGreitens won the August 2 Republican primary with 236,250 votes (34.6%) to businessman John Brunner's 169,425 (24.8%), Lieutenant Governor [[Peter Kinder]]'s 141,498 (20.7%), and former Speaker [[Catherine Hanaway]]'s 136,350 (19.9%).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kmbc.com/politics/eric-greitens-wins-missouri-gop-primary-to-face-chris-koster-in-fall/41023714|title=Eric Greitens wins Missouri GOP Primary, to face Chris Koster in fall|publisher=kmbc.com|accessdate=June 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/2016-election/results/map/governor/missouri|title=Missouri Governor Races Results|work=Politico|accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref> Democrat-turned-Republican Greitens faced Republican-turned-Democrat [[Chris Koster]] in the general election on November 8, 2016, and won with 51.3% of the vote to Koster's 45.4%.<ref name=\"General\">{{cite web|url=http://enr.sos.mo.gov/default.aspx |title=2016 General Election - Official Results |work=Missouri Secretary of State|date=November 8, 2016|accessdate=December 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 28, 2017, the Missouri Ethics Commission fined Greitens's campaign $1,000 for violating state campaign ethics rules regarding campaign disclosure. Greitens did not contest the fine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/in-latest-secrecy-issue-gov-greitens-is-fined-by-state/article_f08341ac-aea7-510e-b8fd-a1f5a872964e.html|title=In latest secrecy issue, Gov. Greitens is fined by state for undisclosed donor list|last=McDermott|first=Kevin|work=stltoday.com|accessdate=May 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title= 2016 Republican Primary for Governor of Missouri<ref>{{cite web |title=Missouri Gubernatorial Election, 2016 |url=https://ballotpedia.org/Missouri_gubernatorial_election,_2016 |website=ballotpedia.org |publisher=Ballotpedia |accessdate=November 18, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n |party = Republican Party (United States)\n |candidate = Eric Greitens \n |votes = 236,481\n |percentage = 34.56\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Republican Party (United States)\n |candidate = John Brunner\n |votes = 169,620\n |percentage = 24.79\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Republican Party (United States)\n |candidate = Peter Kinder\n |votes = 141,629\n |percentage = 20.70\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Republican Party (United States)|candidate=Catherine Hanaway|votes=136,521|percentage=19.95}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title= 2016 Missouri Gubernatorial Election<ref>{{cite web |title=2016 Missouri Governor Election Results |url=https://www.politico.com/2016-election/results/map/governor/missouri/ |website=politico.com |publisher=Politico |accessdate=November 18, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n |party = Republican Party (United States)\n |candidate = Eric Greitens \n |votes = 1,424,730\n |percentage = 51.3\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n |party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = Chris Koster\n |votes = 1,261,110\n |percentage = 45.4\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Cabinet===\n[[File:GreitensSEOC.jpg|thumb|Governor Greitens and DPS Director Drew Juden brief reporters during Winter Storm Jupiter at the State Emergency Operation Center on January 12, 2017.]]\nGreitens's cabinet began service on January 9, 2017, when he was inaugurated as the 56th governor of Missouri. Director of the Department of Corrections Anne Precythe was the first member of his cabinet, appointed on December 21, 2016. All but three members of his cabinet were confirmed by the Missouri Senate by the end of predecessor Jay Nixon's administration. Rob Dixon, Steve Corsi, and Anna Hui served as Acting Director of Economic Development, Acting Director of Social Services, and Acting Director of Labor and Industrial Relations, respectively, before being confirmed. The Greitens administration had a majority female cabinet.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Cabinet Position !! Name !! Appointment Date\n|-\n| Administrator of the [[Office of Administration]]||[[Sarah Steelman]]|| January 6, 2017\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Agriculture|Department of Agriculture]]|| Chris Chinn || December 27, 2017\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Corrections|Department of Corrections]]|| Anne Precythe || December 21, 2016\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Natural Resources|Department of Natural Resources]]|| Carol Comer || January 18, 2017\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Public Safety|Department of Public Safety]]|| Charles Juden || January 2, 2017\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Revenue|Department of Revenue]]|| Joel Walters || February 14, 2017\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Insurance, Financial Institutions, and Professional Registration]]|| Chlora Lindely-Myers || February 14, 2017\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Health and Senior Services|Department of Health and Senior Services]]||[[Randall W. Williams]]|| February 9, 2017\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Economic Development|Department of Economic Development]]|| Rob Dixon || June 2, 2017\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Social Services|Department of Social Services]]|| Steve Corsi || May 19, 2017\n|-\n| Director of the [[Missouri Department of Labor and Industrial Relations|Department of Labor and Industrial Relations]]|| Anna Hui || March 30, 2017\n|}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/whos-running-missouri-now-brief-look-greitens-cabinet-picks-date#stream/0|title=Who's running Missouri now? A brief look at Greitens' Cabinet picks to date|last1=Griffin|first1=Marshall|website=news.stlpublicradio.org|publisher=St Louis Public Radio|accessdate=November 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===First year===\n[[File:GreitensInaug.jpg|thumb|A B-2 stealth bomber flies over the Inauguration of Governor Eric Greitens on January 9, 2017 in Jefferson City, Missouri.]]\nGreitens took office as governor on January 9, 2017. His first two executive orders banned employees in the executive branch from accepting gifts from lobbyists and froze all new regulations through February 2017. He remained opposed to accepting a federal Medicaid expansion in Missouri.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/governor-elect-greitens-likely-to-make-missouri-a-right-to/article_678160f8-ceab-55da-9b94-28c643308b2e.html|title=Governor-elect Greitens likely to make Missouri a right-to-work state|first=Kevin|last=McDermott|publisher=stltoday.com|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref> In November 2018 a statewide referendum put heavy restrictions on lobbyist gifts, virtually banning them.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Griffiths |first1=Shawn |title=Missouri Voters Ban Most Lobbyist Gifts, Vote to End Gerrymandering |url=https://ivn.us/2018/11/07/missouri-voters-ban-lobbyist-gifts-vote-end-gerrymandering/ |website=ivn.us |publisher=IVN |accessdate=November 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn February 6, 2017, Greitens signed a bill making Missouri the 28th [[Right-to-work law|right-to-work state]].<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|last1 =Shaw| first1= Adam|title='Right-to-Work' Movement Claims Victory in Missouri, Eyes NH Next |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/02/06/right-to-work-movement-claims-victory-in-missouri-eyes-nh-next.html|date=February 6, 2017 |work=[[Fox News]]|accessdate=February 10, 2017}}</ref> In response, unions that opposed the law filed a referendum to overturn it,<ref>{{cite web |last1= Hancock| first1= Jason| title=Gov. Eric Greitens Signs Missouri Right-to-Work Bill, But Unions File Referendum to Overturn It|url =http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article130983664.html|date=February 6, 2017|work=[[The Kansas City Star]]|accessdate=February 10, 2017}}</ref> and on August 7, 2018, Missouri voters voted to overturn the right-to-work law.<ref name=\":15\">{{cite web|url=https://fox2now.com/2018/08/07/right-to-work-overturned-as-prop-a-fails/|title=Right-to-work overturned as Prop A fails|date=August 8, 2018|accessdate=August 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, 170 gravestones at the Chesed Shel Emeth Jewish Cemetery in [[University City, Missouri|University City]], [[Missouri]], were toppled and overturned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/02/21/us/jewish-cemetery-vandalized/index.html|title=Jewish cemetery vandalized; headstones damaged|author1=Dalila-Johari Paul |author2=Jason Hanna|website=CNN|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/02/22/politics/jewish-cemetery-muslims-fundraising-trnd/index.html|title=Pence, Missouri governor join cleanup at vandalized Jewish cemetery|author=Alexandra Larkin and Faith Karimi|website=CNN|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref> The vandalism drew national attention and occurred during a period when anonymous threats were being made against Jewish institutions nationwide.<ref name=\":0\" /> Greitens responded to the vandalism by announcing that he would lead a cleanup at the site. Greitens, who is Jewish, posted on Facebook a request for volunteers to help him clean up the cemetery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/EricGreitens/posts/10155034667679747|title=Eric Greitens|website=facebook.com|language=en|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref> On February 27, 2017, [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Mike Pence]] was already in Missouri for a small business roundtable, where he toured a small business in Fenton with Greitens, and he accepted Greitens's offer to join the cleanup efforts.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stljewishlight.com/news/local/pence-community-response-to-cemetery-vandalism-inspiring-the-nation/article_bd8b4474-f976-11e6-8ede-cf20a79c4c41.html|title=Pence: Community response to cemetery vandalism 'inspiring the nation'|last=Writer|first=Eric Berger, Staff|website=St. Louis Jewish Light|language=en|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref> The St. Louis Jewish Light reported, \u201cthe governor and vice president made their remarks atop a flatbed truck on a path inside the cemetery.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> CNN reported that President Trump called Greitens to \"thank the people of Missouri for standing up in the fight against anti-Semitism.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn August 22, 2017, Greitens granted a stay of execution to [[Murder of Felicia Gayle|Marcellus Williams]], who had been set to be executed that day. DNA tests, using technology unavailable at the time of the killing, on the knife used in the killing matched an unknown male, not Williams. Greitens appointed a board of five retired judges to investigate the case and recommend commutation or execution. The panel has no deadline for its report.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/greitens-stops-execution-after-questions-about-dna-evidence/article_edb01294-3d89-5bf6-823e-5a10f8747cc4.html|title=Greitens stops execution after questions about DNA evidence|last=Kohler| first= Jeremy| work=St. Louis Post Dispatch|access-date=August 22, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Missouri governor names panel to examine new DNA evidence in Marcellus Williams' case |url=http://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/missouri-governor-names-panel-examine-new-dna-evidence-marcellus-williams-case#stream/0|author=Mannies, Jo|date=September 12, 2017|publisher=stlpublicradio.org|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref>[[File:Mike Pence and Eric Greitens.jpg|thumb|Greitens meeting with Vice President [[Mike Pence]], January 2017]]On October 27, 2017, the governor's office announced that 30 women had been appointed to state boards and commissions, joining \"a majority-female cabinet\". First Lady Sheena Greitens had announced on October 3 that the Greitens administration would appoint 25 women in the next 25 days, in honor of the 25th anniversary of the Women's Foundation of [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Governor Greitens Appoints 30 Women to State Boards and Commissions|url=https://governor.mo.gov/news/archive/governor-greitens-appoints-30-women-state-boards-and-commissions|date=October 27, 2017|publisher=governor.mo.gov|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Judicial appointments====\nGreitens appointed Jackson County Circuit Judge W. Brent Powell to the Missouri Supreme Court in April 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/kansascity/news/2018/03/20/jackson-county-circuit-court-judge-cory-atkins.html |title=Greitens appoints 'Rising Star' as new Jackson County judge |newspaper=Kansas City Business Journal |date=March 20, 2018 |first=James |last=Dornbrook |access-date=August 13, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.joplinglobe.com/news/judge-w-brent-powell-appointed-to-missouri-supreme-court/article_8b4ef146-29e0-11e7-99ea-336e3939c698.html |title=Judge W. Brent Powell appointed to Missouri Supreme Court |date=April 25, 2017 |newspaper=Joplin Globe |first1=Summer |last1=Ballentine |first2=David A. |last2=Lieb |access-date=August 13, 2019 |agency=Associated Press }}</ref> He also made the following judicial appointments: Kevin Walden was appointed Circuit Judge for the 8th Judicial Circuit; Katherine (\"Katie\") M. Fowler as Circuit Court Judge for the 22nd Judicial Circuit; Lynne R. Perkins as Associate Circuit Court Judge for the 22nd Judicial Circuit; Brouck Jacobs as Circuit Judge for the 13th Judicial Circuit; and Melissa Lawyer as Circuit Judge for the 5th Judicial Circuit.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://themissouritimes.com/44913/greitens-announces-five-judicial-appointments/ |title=Greitens announces five judicial appointments |newspaper=The Missouri Times |date=October 13, 2017 |access-date=August 13, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n====Tort reform====\nIn 2017 [[Harris Insights & Analytics]] surveyed 1,300 corporate litigators and senior executives for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce's Institute for Legal Reform. Missouri's overall state liability system ranked 49th out of 50. As part of his \u201cMore Jobs, Higher Pay\u201d plan, Greitens pushed for more tort reform than any state in the country. In 2017 the [[American Tort Reform Association]] criticized St. Louis as the \"worst Judicial Hellhole\u2122\" in the country, and said \u201cjudicial hellholes\u201d like [[St. Louis]] are known for systematically misapplying the law in ways that expand liability and ratchet up the cost of doing business in the state. Greitens signed legislation that the Property Casualty Insurers Association of America said would help improve Missouri's legal climate by curbing abuses associated with \u00a7537.065 and the time-limited demand settlement process.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.insurancejournal.com/news/midwest/2017/07/13/457609.htm |title=Missouri Governor Signs Tort Reform Legislation |date=July 13, 2017 |journal=Insurance Journal |access-date=August 13, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nOther tort reform bills Greitens signed include:\n\nMissouri SB31, which makes changes to the collateral source rule (paid v. billed damages) so parties can introduce only evidence of the actual cost of the medical care rendered, not the value of that care.\n\nMissouri SB43, which brings standards for lawsuits in Missouri in line with 38 other states and the federal government. The bill requires the use of the \u201cmotivating factor\u201d standard for employment discrimination cases. The \u201cmotivating factor\u201d standard is used by the U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC) in analyzing claims under Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 (Title VII) and the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA).\n\nMissouri SB 88, which gives veterinarians the same malpractice coverage as doctors, dentists, and other medical professionals.\n[[File:GreitensRoyals.jpg|thumb|Greitens speaking to Fox 4 News at the 2017 MLB Opening Day for the Kansas City Royals in August 2017.]]\nMissouri HB 452, which says that, with certain exceptions, no healthcare provider shall be liable for the negligence of another entity or person who is not an employee of the healthcare provider.\n\nMissouri HB153, which creates a higher standard for expert evidence, improves the reliability of expert witness testimony, and puts Missouri in line with a majority of states regarding the standard used for expert testimony.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.news-leader.com/story/opinion/readers/2018/02/02/keep-reforming-missouri-lawsuit-abuse-2018/1087167001/ |title=Keep reforming Missouri lawsuit abuse in 2018 |newspaper=Springfield News-Leader |date=February 2, 2018 |first1=James R. |last1=Copland |first2=Rafael A. |last2=Mangual |access-date=August 13, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==== Ethics reform and government efficiency ====\nWithin an hour of his inauguration, Greitens signed an executive order banning state employees in his administration from accepting or soliciting gifts from lobbyists. The order also banned employees in the governor's office from lobbying the executive branch while Greitens was in office. The order was later loosened by Governor Mike Parson, who allowed gifts to members of the executive branch. As Lieutenant Governor, Parson received meals and gifts from lobbyists worth $2,752 in his first six months in office, the [[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] reported, citing Missouri Ethics Commission records.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox2now.com/2017/01/09/greitens-bans-lobbyist-gifts-to-executive-branch/|title=Greitens bans lobbyist gifts to executive branch|date=January 9, 2017|website=FOX2now.com|language=en|access-date=August 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFox 2 News St. Louis accused Greitens of \u201clashing out against two Republican senators who didn\u2019t vote against a pay raise for themselves and other elected officials.\u201d Only Republican State Senators Denny Hoskins and Paul Wieland cast votes to allow the raise to take effect, but six other senators recused themselves and didn't vote. Greitens had personally pressured lawmakers to vote down the raise. Hoskins and Wieland described their meetings with him as tense. Wieland described it as intimidation and said he felt insulted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox2now.com/2017/01/31/missouri-governor-slams-fellow-republicans-on-social-media/|title=Missouri governor slams fellow Republicans on social media|date=January 31, 2017|website=FOX2now.com|language=en|access-date=August 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGreitens approved a plan to reduce the number of people that can be appointed to political positions. A 2017 Boards and Commissions Task Force report outlined ways to eliminate 439 gubernatorial appointments and cut or merge numerous state boards and commissions, more than 200 of which currently exist. The recommendations aligned with Greitens's goal to make Missouri's government smaller and reduce state regulators' reach. The report included recommendations to cut more than two dozen commissions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news-leader.com/story/news/politics/2017/11/02/gov-greitens-gives-seal-approval-plan-eliminating-hundreds-missouri-appointees/822309001/|title=Gov. Greitens gives seal of approval to plan eliminating hundreds of Missouri appointees|last=Schmitt|first=Will|website=Springfield News-Leader|language=en|access-date=August 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring his 2017 State of the State address, Greitens announced: \"We found 30 cars the government didn't need, and we're getting rid of them. That's going to save Missourians over $500,000.\" Greitens sold one of the state's two passenger planes used by his predecessor, [[Jay Nixon]]. The 2018 [[Missouri Department of Public Safety|Department of Public Safety]] spending proposal called for a $37,000 reduction in aircraft maintenance costs due to the sale of the twin-engine, six-passenger plane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newstribune.com/news/local/story/2018/jan/14/state-cutting-30-vehicles-oa-fleet/708689/|title=State cutting 30 vehicles from OA fleet|website=News Tribune|access-date=August 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/missouri-governor-to-sell-one-state-airplane/article_ace2d746-f8c9-5964-adf7-a2f137ee5a77.html|title=Missouri governor to sell one state airplane|last=Erickson|first=Kurt|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=August 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGreitens released funding for biodiesel facilities that was originally withheld because of concerns that state revenues could fall short. The released $4 million was the amount necessary to pay off a backlog of subsidies called for under a 2002 state law that provided incentives for biodiesel plants that began operating by 2009. Fox 2 St. Louis reported that members of the soybean industry said that releasing the incentives \u201chelped launch the industry.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox2now.com/2018/05/17/missouri-governor-releases-final-biodiesel-subsidies/|title=Missouri governor releases final biodiesel subsidies|date=May 17, 2018|website=FOX2now.com|language=en|access-date=August 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Economic effect====\nOn November 21, 2017, Greitens announced that [[Sedalia, Missouri]], would be home to a $250 million [[Nucor]] steel-bar mill.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.komu.com/news/nucor-announces-new-steel-mill-in-sedalia/|title=Nucor announces new steel mill in Sedalia|website=KOMU|language=en|access-date=June 20, 2019|first=Mackenzie|last=Huck|date=November 21, 2017}}</ref> Missouri was chosen over Kansas, Nebraska, South Carolina and Florida for the facility, which created 255 jobs with a median annual salary of $65,000 in addition to 450 temporary construction jobs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/stlouis/news/2017/11/21/steel-company-picks-missouri-for-new-250-million.html|newspaper=St. Louis Business Journal|access-date=June 20, 2019|title=Steel company picks Missouri for new $250 million mill|first=Steph|last=Kukuljan|date=November 21, 2017}}</ref> Missouri moved up nine spaces, from 31st to 22nd, in [[CNBC]]'s annual list of America's Top States for Business published on July 11, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/07/11/top-states-for-business-22-missouri.html|title=22. Missouri|last=staff|first=CNBC com|date=July 11, 2017|website=www.cnbc.com|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref> In 2018 Missouri also had its lowest unemployment rate in 18 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/business/local/missouri-unemployment-drops-to-lowest-rate-since-june/article_01a69daf-6081-56d4-9f4d-963e722e85a2.html|title=Missouri unemployment drops to lowest rate since June 2000|last=Press|first=Associated|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Regulatory reform ====\nIn January 2017 Greitens signed Executive Order 17-03, which froze implementation of all new regulations for over 30 days and required each agency to review its rules and remove \"needless and burdensome regulations.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/greitens-signs-second-executive-order-freezing-new-regulations-for-businesses/article_2f0a09b8-c164-5021-8f69-f382d4586ca6.html|title=Greitens signs second executive order freezing new regulations for businesses|last=Bott|first=Celeste|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref> A 2017 audit of state regulations found more than seven million words of regulations on the books. Greitens declared plans to remove nearly one-third of these, equal to approximately 33,000 regulations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://krcgtv.com/news/local/gov-greitens-state-of-the-state-address|title=Gov. Greitens State of the State Address|last=Staff|first=KRCG 13 Web|date=January 10, 2018|website=KRCG|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGreitens signed into law a bill removing regulations on ride-sharing services like [[Uber]] and [[Lyft]], allowing them to work freely in Missouri. Uber said the legislation would lead to 10,000 additional jobs in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news-leader.com/story/news/politics/2017/04/24/greitens-signs-statewide-regulations-for-uber-lyft/100855590/|title=Greitens signs statewide regulations for Uber, Lyft|website=Springfield News-Leader|language=en|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref> Greitens posted on Facebook a video of himself signing the bill in a Lyft in a [[Taco Bell]] parking lot, which earned him a shout-out from Taco Bell.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article147109379.html|title=Greitens gets a shout-out from Taco Bell after his Chalupa bill-signing ceremony|last=By|website=kansascity|language=en|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSenior officials in Greitens's administration supported state and national agricultural advocacy groups\u2019 efforts to rewrite the Obama Administration's \"[[Waters of the United States]]\" (WOTUS) rule.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newstribune.com/news/news/story/2017/jun/28/missouri-leaders-applaud-epas-waters-change/679903/|title=Missouri leaders applaud EPA's 'waters' change|website=News Tribune|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref> Missouri [[American Farm Bureau Federation|Farm Bureau]] President Blake Hurst said, \"we appreciate Gov. Greitens' comments to [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] asserting that the WOTUS rule was too broad an interpretation of law and that it should be redefined.\"<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nIn March 2017 Greitens announced that the Missouri Board of Nursing approved the [[United States Air Force|Air Force]]'s practical nurse education program. He said the agreement, designed to allow military nurses to practice in the civilian sector following military service, would be the first of its kind in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://krcgtv.com/news/local/greitens-missouri-board-of-nursing-approves-air-force-practical-nurse-education-program|title=Greitens: Missouri Board of Nursing approves Air Force practical nurse education program|last=Dailey|first=Greg|date=March 22, 2017|website=KRCG|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:SteelMillRally.jpg|thumb|Hundreds of workers from southeast Missouri rally outside the Governor's Office in support of Greitens and the 2017 Steel Mill Bill.]]\n\n==== 2017 steel mill special session ====\nGreitens supported the Missouri Steel Mill Bill, legislation that allowed utility regulators to approve lower electricity rates for industrial companies using large amounts of energy.\n\nThe legislation was drafted in response to the March 2016 [[Noranda (mining company)|Noranda]] smelter closure, in which nearly 900 people lost their jobs and the average household income in [[New Madrid County, Missouri|New Madrid County]] fell by $6,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2018/09/26/theres-optimism-in-southeast-missouris-bootheel-about-jobs/|title=There's optimism in southeast Missouri's Bootheel about jobs|date=September 26, 2018|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref> During the final weeks of the regular 2017 legislative session, the Missouri House of Representatives passed an amendment by State Representative [[Don Rone Jr.|Don Rone]] designed to help bring industrial jobs to the state. The bill, however, was met with opposition in the Senate led by Senator Doug Libla, and ultimately failed. Greitens called a special legislative session in May 2017, bringing the Missouri General Assembly back to the Capitol one week after its regular session adjourned to pass the legislation.\n[[File:SenatorsDoor.jpg|thumb|Following a rally, Greitens led workers to the offices of state senators to urge them to pass the 2017 Steel Mill Bill.]]\n\u201cAnd people are sick of having to drive to Kentucky, having to drive to Tennessee, having to drive to Arkansas,\u201d Greitens said in an interview with MissouriNet. \u201cWatching their friends have to get in trucks and go across the border to find a quality job. And we promised during the (gubernatorial) campaign we were going to fight for them.\u201d<ref name=\"missourinet.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2017/05/22/missouri-legislatures-special-session-starts-monday-greitens-and-schaaf-clash-over-psc-language-issue/|title=Missouri Legislature's special session starts Monday; Greitens and Schaaf clash over PSC language issue|date=May 22, 2017|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter calling the session, Greitens held rallies in Southeast Missouri in [[New Madrid, Missouri|New Madrid]], [[Poplar Bluff, Missouri|Poplar Bluff]], [[Dexter, Missouri|Dexter]] and [[Sikeston, Missouri|Sikeston]] and hosted hundreds of Bootheel residents at the Capitol in Jefferson City for a rally urging lawmakers to approve the bill.<ref name=\"missourinet.com\"/> Following the rally, Greitens encouraged the crowd to join him in walking to every state senator's office. Participants taped messages to the doors of Senate offices, including phrases such as \u201cwe don\u2019t want welfare\u201d and \u201cbring back American jobs.\u201d<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2017/05/24/southeast-missouri-residents-rally-with-greitens-on-noranda-issue-rone-predicts-house-will-approve-bill-on-wednesday/|title=Missouri Bootheel residents rally with Greitens for jobs bill|date=May 24, 2017|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref> Rone praised Greitens, saying \u201cwe finally have a governor who knows where southeast Missouri is.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nUltimately, the General Assembly passed the legislation and Greitens signed the bill in to law on June 16, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.missouribusinessalert.com/industries/84500/2017/06/16/greitens-signs-steel-mill-bill/|title=Greitens signs steel mill bill passed in May special session \u2013 Missouri Business Alert|language=en-US|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref> Following the special session, Magnitude 7 Metals LLC announced that the firm would restart two of the plant's three production lines, which brought over 450 jobs to the region with an average salary of $95,000, with the potential for another 900 jobs in the future.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2017/05/25/missouri-house-approves-norandasteel-mill-bill-mccreery-describes-bill-as-giveaway-to-ameren/|title=Missouri House approves Noranda/steel mill bill|date=May 25, 2017|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.semissourian.com/story/2491628.html|title=Former smelter to reopen in May, plans to employ 450 people near term, as many as 900 with future expansions|last=Missourian|first=Mark Bliss ~ Southeast|date=March 10, 2018|website=seMissourian.com|language=en|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the announcement, Greitens accepted an invitation to meet with [[Donald Trump|President Donald Trump]] at the [[White House]] to discuss workforce development and job creation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2017/06/15/missouri-governor-signs-steel-mill-bill-heads-to-washington-to-talk-jobs/|title=Missouri governor signs steel mill bill, heads to Washington to talk jobs|date=June 15, 2017|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== 2017 pro-life special session ====\n[[File:ProLifeSession.jpg|thumb|Nearly a thousand supporters of the pro-life movement attend Governor Greitens' rally during the pro-life special session in June 2017.]]\nFollowing the extraordinary session on the Steel Mill Bill, Greitens called a second special session to pass pro-life legislation. He went on a statewide tour with former [[Arkansas Governor]] [[Mike Huckabee]] and said \"we had some radical politicians in St. Louis who passed legislation to make St. Louis an abortion sanctuary city, where it would make it illegal ... for organizations like Our Lady's Inn and other pro-life groups just to hire pro-life workers. So we're out here to protect pregnancy care centers.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/abortion-regulations-st-louis-anti-discrimination-law-focus-2nd-special-legislative-session|title=Abortion regulations, St. Louis anti-discrimination law focus of 2nd special legislative session|last2=Griffin|first2=Marshall|first1=Jo |last1=Mannies|website=St. Louis Public Radio|access-date=August 13, 2019|date=June 7, 2017}}</ref> The bill also required that doctors explain the risks of abortion to a patient 72 hours before performing an abortion, called for annual inspections of clinics, added new whistle-blower protections for clinic employees, and heightened requirements for pathologists who provide services to abortion facilities. Executive director of [[NARAL Pro-Choice America|NARAL Pro Choice Missouri]] Alison Dreith said the session was \"political theater.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/in-private-ceremony-greitens-signs-new-abortion-law/article_10c9ef36-688b-51c1-9aca-2386d9495187.html|title=In private ceremony, Greitens signs new abortion law|last=Erickson|first=Kurt|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|access-date=August 13, 2019|date=July 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn July 26, 2017, Greitens signed HCS SB 5, a wide-ranging pro-life measure, into law.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalrighttolifenews.org/2017/07/missouri-gov-greitens-signs-wide-ranging-pro-life-measure/|title=Missouri Gov. Greitens signs wide-ranging pro-life measure|last=Dave Andrusko|date=July 26, 2017|website=NRL News Today|access-date=August 13, 2019}}</ref> Missouri Right to Life said, \"We are especially grateful to Governor Greitens for calling this special session and for his support of this pro-life legislation.\" [[National Right to Life Committee|NRLC]]'s state affiliate called the measure \"one of the strongest pro-life bills to be passed by the Missouri Legislature in many years.\"<ref name=\":21\" />\n\nIn 2018 [[The Satanic Temple]] delivered oral arguments in front of the [[Missouri Court of Appeals|Missouri State Court Western Appellate District]] in an effort to challenge Greitens's pro-life legislation, claiming that it \"violated the religious beliefs of one of its members.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/satanic-temple-missouri-abortion-law_n_59bacd6de4b02da0e1403c82|title=Why The Satanic Temple Is Fighting Missouri's Restrictive Abortion Law|last=Blumberg|first=Antonia|date=September 14, 2017|website=HuffPost|access-date=August 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018 Greitens was featured in the [[Netflix]] documentary film \"''[[Reversing Roe]]''\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Reversing Roe (2018)|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt8948614/fullcredits|website=IMDb|access-date=August 13, 2019}}</ref>{{better source|date=August 2019}}\n\n==== Changes to Missouri's foster care system ====\n\nIn June 2017 Greitens signed Missouri's first Foster Care Bill of Rights, which outlined specific measures designed to improve the safety and quality of life of children in Missouri's foster care system.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/greitens-signs-foster-care-bill-rights#stream/0 |title=Greitens signs Foster Care Bill of Rights |publisher=St. Louis Public Radio |date=June 22, 2017 |first=Marshall |last=Griffin |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018 Greitens ordered that Missouri children in foster care no longer have to pay $15 to get copies of their birth certificates. The move was hailed as removing a key obstacle for many to apply for driver's licenses, jobs, or higher education. \u201cFor the children who are involved in this system, it\u2019s everything to them,\u201d said Colleen Polak, director of legal services for Voices for Children in St. Louis.<ref name=\"news.stlpublicradio.org\">{{cite news |url=https://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/missouri-foster-children-top-agenda-first-lady-sheena-greitens#stream/0 |title=Missouri foster children top agenda for first lady Sheena Greitens |date=January 3, 2018 |publisher=St. Louis Public Radio |first=Holly |last=Edgell |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017 Greitens appointed 27 advocates to the Child Abuse and Neglect Review Boards, Children's Trust Fund Board, and Missouri State Foster Care and Adoption Board. Many of those boards had been unable to operate because no one had been appointed to them to make quorum.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://themissouritimes.com/45902/greitens-appoints-27-members-to-child-protection-boards/ |title=Greitens appoints 27 members to child protection boards |date=November 17, 2017 |first=Benjamin |last=Peters |newspaper=The Missouri Times |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Sheena Greitens announced that the administration's Children's Division had enrolled in a new National Council For Adoption (NCFA) study of foster parent recruitment and retention. Its goal was to find ways to more effectively train and support foster parents.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.missourinet.com/2017/12/12/far-reaching-foster-care-study-announced-by-missouri-first-lady/ |title=Far reaching foster care study announced by Missouri First Lady |date=December 12, 2017 |first=Jason |last=Taylor |website=Missourinet |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref> Sheena Greitens also distributed over 3,200 books in state storage Missouri's foster families and foster children.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/stlouis/news/2018/01/30/q-a-with-sheena-greitens.html |title=Q&A with Sheena Greitens |magazine=St. Louis Business Journal |date=January 30, 2018 |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref> She then announced that Missouri had joined the National Electronic Interstate Compact Enterprise, a multistate collaboration designed to make adoption and fostering across state lines easier.<ref name=\"news.stlpublicradio.org\"/>\n\n==== Council of Governors ====\nIn May 2017 President Trump appointed Greitens to the Council of Governors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://themissouritimes.com/40176/greitens-named-council-governors-trump/|title=Greitens named to Council of Governors by Trump|date=May 2, 2017|website=The Missouri Times|language=en|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref> A bipartisan organization of state governors, the council advises on matters of national defense, the national guard and defense support to local authorities. Greitens served alongside [[Rick Scott]] of Florida, [[Bill Walker (American politician)|Bill Walker]] of Alaska, [[Mark Dayton]] of Minnesota, [[Steve Bullock (American politician)|Steve Bullock]] of Montana, [[Dannel Malloy]] of Connecticut, and [[Mary Fallin]] of Oklahoma. Greitens was the only newly elected governor Trump appointed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newstribune.com/news/missouri/story/2017/may/02/trump-intends-appoint-greitens-council-governors/672261/|title=Trump intends to appoint Greitens to council of governors|website=News Tribune|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Public safety and law enforcement support ====\n\nGreitens signed a \u201cBlue Alert\u201d law modeled after the Amber Alert system for missing children. He pursued the idea to allow public broadcasts with information that could assist in the apprehension of individuals who commit violence against police officers. The measure was part of a package of crime-related changes to state law the Missouri House and Senate approved in May 2017. It also enhanced penalties for assaults on law enforcement officers and created the crime of illegal re-entry. People deported from the United States for committing a crime who return and commit a felony would also be guilty of illegal re-entry in Missouri.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://themissouritimes.com/42367/greitens-signs-blue-alert-bill-into-law/ |title=Greitens signs Blue Alert bill into law |date=July 6, 2017 |newspaper=The Missouri Times |first=Benjamin |last=Peters |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.senate.mo.gov/17info/BTS_Web/Bill.aspx?SessionType=R&BillID=57095296 |publisher=Missouri State Senate |title=SB34 \u2013 Modifies and creates new provisions relating to criminal offenses |first=Scott |last=Svagera |date=July 6, 2017 |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nGreitens announced a special operations unit of the State Highway Patrol to target violent felons on interstate highways. The task force collected better intelligence to aid local police and pushed to stop drug trafficking. The Missouri Department of Public Safety worked with the FBI and the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration to go after violent criminals.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://fox4kc.com/2017/07/11/state-highway-patrol-to-help-address-violence-in-st-louis/ |title=State Highway Patrol to help address violence in St. Louis |agency=Associated Press |date=July 11, 2017 |publisher=[[WDAF-TV]] |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nGreitens changed the state's emergency response philosophy, adopting a \u201cgo early, go big\u201d approach in which the operating response was to go before disaster strikes and be overprepared throughout the emergency to minimize human casualties. He activated the State Emergency Operations Center prior to several major events, including instances of massive flooding, tornadoes, and winter storms. The center operates 24 hours a day to coordinate the response by the National Weather Service, The Department of Public Safety, the State Emergency Management Agency, Missouri State Highway Patrol, MoDOT, Electric Utilities and Power Companies/Power, and faith-based and volunteer response partners, including Convoy of Hope and the Red Cross.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.news-leader.com/story/news/local/missouri/2017/01/12/greitens-declares-state-emergency-winter-storm-approaches/96522264/ |title=Greitens declares state of emergency as winter storm approaches |date=January 12, 2017 |newspaper=Springfield News-Leader |publisher=USA Today Network |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nOfficials in the Greitens administration sent notices to 8,000 doctors who weren't following best practices for prescribing [[opioids]] within the state's Medicaid program, instructing them to change their prescribing patterns and consider referring people on long-term opioids to addiction programs. The ''Kansas City Star'' reported that Greitens also started filling vacancies on the medical licensing board with physicians who were \u201cwilling to get tough on colleagues who contribute to the opioid crisis.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/local/news-columns-blogs/the-buzz/article161759233.html |title=Gov. Eric Greitens orders prescription drug monitoring program for Missouri |date=July 17, 2017 |newspaper=The Kansas City Star |first1=Jason |last1=Hancock |first2=Andy |last2=Marso |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nGreitens issued an executive order to create a prescription drug monitoring program, addressing the concern that Missouri was the only state in the U.S. without a program. The order directed the Department of Health and Senior Services to build the database, which was designed to help identify suspicious patterns of prescriptions of controlled substances, including opioids.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/business/health-care/article203576419.html |title=Greitens announces opioid crackdown that could affect 8,000 Missouri doctors |date=March 5, 2018 |newspaper=The Kansas City Star |first=Andy |last=Marso |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nGreitens created the Firefighter Veterans Initiative to connect veterans to public safety careers. The program introduces participants to firefighting through physical skills training through basic classroom instruction and pairing students with mentors.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://krcgtv.com/news/local/photo-gallery-governors-initiative-trains-veterans-to-be-firefighters |title=Initiative trains veterans to be firefighters |date=February 18, 2018 |publisher=[[KRCG]] |first=Gabriella |last=Nu\u00f1ez |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Second year===\nOn February 24, 2018, Greitens declared a state of emergency and activated the Missouri National Guard in response to severe weather that began on February 23.<ref>{{cite web |title=Executive Order 2018-02 |url=https://governor.mo.gov/node/266 |website=governor.mo.gov |publisher=Missouri Governor |accessdate=November 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Tax reform====\n[[File:GreitensChiefs.jpg|thumb|Governor Greitens and Kansas City Chiefs Coach Andy Reid on the field at KC Chiefs Training Camp in St. Joseph, Missouri in July 2017.]]\nOn January 18, 2018, Greitens announced tax cuts to be proposed in the state legislature. More information on the cuts was released in the following weeks. The plan was to cut individual and corporate taxes by approximately $800 million. The overhaul would reduce the top individual income tax rate by 10% and the corporate income tax rate by nearly a third. The top individual income tax rate would drop from 5.9% to 5.3%. The proposal would also create a non-refundable state tax credit for low-income workers, which Greitens said would essentially eliminate income taxes for 380,000 people. He said the bill would drop taxes 51%, from $920 to $449 annually for a married couple with two children earning $40,000. Greitens also said the plan would drop taxes down 2.9%, from $6,917 to $6,716 annually, for a married couple with two children who earn $150,000. The plan also intended to cut corporate tax rates from 6.25% to 4.25%.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erickson |first1=Kurt |title=Greitens hopes $800 million in tax cuts will turbocharge the Missouri economy |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/greitens-hopes-million-in-tax-cuts-will-turbocharge-the-missouri/article_d6fbb4da-072f-5c40-a971-ce8a1995011f.html |newspaper=St Louis Post-Dispatch |accessdate=November 18, 2018 |date=January 30, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |title=Governor Greitens outlines principles for tax reform |url=https://themissouritimes.com/47460/governor-greitens-outlines-principles-for-tax-reform/ |newspaper=The Missouri Times |date=January 18, 2018 |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref> It simplified the tax code and eliminated special rules that rewarded companies that hired employees outside of Missouri. As a result, Missouri would have the country's second-lowest corporate tax rate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.columbiamissourian.com/news/state_news/greitens-plan-cuts-taxes-for-most-missourians/article_fa713de0-0527-11e8-ac09-6723216541b3.html|title=Greitens' plan cuts taxes for most Missourians|author=Missourian Staff|website=The Columbia Missourian|language=en|access-date=June 20, 2019 |date=January 29, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nGreitens's $28.8 billion fiscal 2019 budget proposal estimated a 2.5% growth rate in net general revenue, with 70% coming from personal income taxes. To balance the operating budget, Greitens also proposed changes to the tax code that would increase state revenue. One of these was removing the timely filing discount. The discount offers vendors up to a 2% discount for filing sales taxes on time. The Missouri Department of Revenue projected state savings of $57.4 million by eliminating the discount.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Henderson |first1=Matthew |title=Greitens proposes sweeping tax reform |url=http://sbj.net/stories/greitens-proposes-sweeping-tax-reform,57373 |website=sbj.net |publisher=SBJ |date=February 5, 2018 |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nGreitens signed legislation that simplified Missouri's tax code, eliminated special rules that rewarded companies that hired employees outside of Missouri, and reduced Missouri's business tax rate from 6.25% to 4.0%, making it the second lowest in the country.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.cchgroup.com/2018/06/05/missouri-enacts-corporate-tax-rate-cut-and-apportionment-changes/ |title=Missouri Enacts Corporate Tax Rate Cut and Apportionment Changes |website=CCHTaxGroup |date=June 5, 2018 |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==== ''Trinity Lutheran Church of Columbia v. Comer'' ====\nGreitens ended a longstanding state policy against using tax dollars to aid religious groups. His decision came a week before the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] heard arguments in the case of ''Trinity Lutheran Church of Columbia v. Comer''. The lawsuit challenged a 2012 decision by the Missouri Department of Natural Resources to deny the Columbia church a grant to replace the gravel on its playground with softer, safer material. Greitens instructed the Department of Natural Resources to allow religious organizations to apply for and be eligible to receive those grants.<ref>Greitens ended a long standing state policy of discrimination against religious organizations.  The policy prevented tax dollars from being used to aid religious groups. Greitens\u2019 decision came a week before the U.S. Supreme Court heard arguments in the case of ''Trinity Lutheran Church of Columbia v. Comer''. The lawsuit challenged a 2012 decision by the Missouri Department of Natural Resources to deny the Columbia church a grant to replace the gravel on its playground with softer, safer material. Greitens instructed the Department of Natural Resources to allow religious organizations to apply for and be eligible to receive those grants. {{cite news |url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article144497099.html |title=Gov. Greitens reverses state policy, allowing tax dollars to aid religious groups |newspaper=The Kansas City Star |date=April 13, 2017 |first=Jason |last=Hancock |access-date=August 12, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==== Jason Stockley protests ====\nOn September 15, 2017, St. Louis police officer [[Jason Stockley]] was found not guilty of first-degree murder for shooting [[Anthony Lamar Smith]] in 2011. Protests erupted in St. Louis. Prior to the verdict, a group of clergy publicly stated that an acquittal would result in \"mass disruption\" in the city. Greitens, who was openly critical of his predecessor Jay Nixon's response to the Ferguson unrest, preemptively activated the Missouri National Guard and scheduled 12-hour shifts for the St. Louis municipal police.\n\nBefore the judge's decision in Stockley's trial, Greitens and Smith's fianc\u00e9e, Christina Wilson, made a call for peace. \"If you feel like you want to speak out, speak how you feel and whatever comes to you,\"\n\nWilson said, \"Just do it in a peaceful way.\"<ref name=\"praises\">{{cite news |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/greitens-praises-police-response-to-st-louis-protests/article_4308bc80-da7d-5519-930a-d4645fd670ab.html |title=Greitens praises police response to St. Louis protests |newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=October 10, 2017 |first=Kurt |last=Erickson |access-date=August 13, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ksdk.com/article/news/local/gov-greitens-fiancee-of-anthony-lamar-smith-call-for-peace/63-474991744 |title=Gov. Greitens, fianc\u00e9e of Anthony Lamar Smith call for peace |publisher=KSDK |date=September 15, 2017 |first=Sam |last=Clancy |access-date=August 13, 2019 }}</ref> Greitens said, \"Whatever the verdict is, we will protect every single person's right to peacefully protest\". \"And whatever the verdict is, we will also protect people's lives, their homes and our communities.\"<ref name=\"praises\" /> Following the verdict, Greitens oversaw the Department of Public Safety's plan to protect city infrastructure like firehouses. After declaring the protests an \"unlawful assembly\", police officers were pelted with water bottles and rocks. Protesters also descended upon Mayor [[Lyda Krewson]]'s home, and threw bricks at and vandalized it. Police deployed tear gas to break up the crowd and two officers were injured by bricks thrown by protesters. Over the night, ten police officers were injured and 32 protesters arrested. Greitens said, \"In the past, our leaders let people break windows, loot, start fires. They let them do it. Not this time.\u201d Within 48 hours, major threats of violence were thwarted and it was reported that the St. Louis police made 300 arrests. Greitens garnered national attention for his response to the protest. \u201cWe had leaders who wanted to give people a safe space to loot and to burn,\u201d Greitens told Fox News. \u201cNow in Missouri if you loot the only safe space you\u2019re going to have is in a jail cell.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/gov-greitens-you-break-a-window-you-re-going-to/article_4e2ca012-aa46-50e8-a22e-37885318db8a.html |title=Gov. Greitens: 'You break a window, you're going to be behind bars.' |date=September 17, 2017 |newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |first=Erin |last=Heffernan |access-date=August 13, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==== Low-income housing tax credits ====\nIn 2017 the Missouri Housing Development Commission voted 8 to 2 to zero out the state's low-income housing tax credit for 2018.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/greitens-succeeds-push-halt-low-income-housing-tax-credits|title=Greitens succeeds in push to halt low-income housing tax credits|last=Griffin|first=Marshall|website=news.stlpublicradio.org|language=en|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref> Greitens phoned into the meeting and voted to zero out the tax credits while then Lt. Governor [[Mike Parson]] voted to keep them. Greitens said in a written statement that \"special interests abused low income housing tax breaks to make themselves rich.\"<ref name=\":13\" /> Following Greitens's appointments to the commission and the 2017 vote, Missouri did not issue $140 million in state low-income housing tax credits. The low-income housing tax credit program was cut from over $1.3 billion over the previous decade to zero. Greitens accused the low-income housing industry of conspiring to upend his political career though legal troubles and the threat of impeachment.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article232245482.html|title='Affordable housing crisis': Future of Missouri low-income tax credit still in flux|last=By|website=kansascity|language=en|access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref> It was later determined that a month after he orchestrated the demise of the tax credit, local newspaper publisher Scott Faughn paid $50,000 in cash to the attorney for the ex-husband of the woman who accused Greitens of sexual misconduct.<ref name=\":14\" /> ''[[The Kansas City Star]]'' reported on July 8, 2019, that Faughn eventually paid the attorney another $70,000 in cash, keeping the transactions secret for months while continuing to cover Greitens both in his newspaper and on his TV show, which is sponsored by Sterling Bank, a Poplar Bluff-based bank highly involved in low-income housing tax credits. When the payments were eventually revealed, Faughn fled the state to avoid a subpoena from Greitens's lawyers. The attorney who received the payments testified that he was told the cash came from a GOP donor who wanted to oust Greitens.<ref name=\":14\" />[[File:GreitensFire.jpg|thumb|Greitens training with firefighters at the St. Louis Fire Academy in February 2017.]]When Parson took over as governor following Greitens's resignation in June 2018, he was adamant that the $150 million program remain dormant until the legislature passed reforms. In May 2019, after the legislature was unable to reconcile differences between the two chambers in a bill to restart the program, Parson's office announced that he would consider restoring the credits without the legislature, but he ultimately decided against doing so.\n\n====Changes to the Missouri National Guard and veterans' rights ====\nOn June 14, 2017, Greitens signed legislation (S.B. 108) guaranteeing state and federal reemployment rights to Missouri employees who are members of any reserve component of the U.S. Armed Forces called to active duty. The law also extended reemployment rights to Missouri employees who are members of the National Guard of another state called to active duty in that state.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thinkhr.com/blog/missouri-employment-law-update-june-2017/ |title=Missouri Employment Law Update |date=June 19, 2017 |website=ThinkHR |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nOn October 10, 2017, Greitens announced the Missouri Army National Guard would add nearly 800 soldiers by 2019. The expansion brought units to Missouri from around the country. The new units' economic impact was estimated around $15 million, including direct payroll and access to benefits for healthcare and education for the soldiers.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article178264206.html |title=Gov. Greitens announces 800 new National Guard jobs |agency=Associated Press |date=October 11, 2017 |newspaper=The Kansas City Star |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Greitens announced that members of the Missouri National Guard would train with the [[Israeli Home Front Command]]. Missouri is one of four states\u2014along with Colorado, Illinois and Massachusetts\u2014to train with the command, a branch of the [[Israel Defense Forces]] that focuses on civilian protection during a war or crisis.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stljewishlight.com/news/local/gov-greitens-missouri-national-guard-troops-to-train-with-israelis/article_bf3fbe72-11bb-11e8-a64c-e304a2a51eee.html |title=Gov. Greitens: Missouri National Guard troops to train with Israelis |website=St. Louis Jewish Light |date=February 14, 2018 |first=Eric |last=Berger |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://fox2now.com/2018/02/09/missouri-to-partner-with-israeli-home-front-command/ |title=Missouri to partner with Israeli Home Front Command |date=February 9, 2018 |agency=Associated Press |website=Fox2Now |publisher=[[KTVI]] |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Greitens signed into law legislation allowing those in the Missouri National Guard and the armed forces reserves to deduct their military income from their state taxes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://fox2now.com/2018/04/19/missouri-bill-lowers-income-taxes-for-national-guard-and-reserves/ |title=Missouri bill lowers income taxes for National Guard and reserves |date=April 19, 2018 |agency=Associated Press |website=Fox2Now |publisher=KTVI |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nOn April 27, 2018, Greitens announced an initiative in the Department of Natural Resources to recruit and hire more veterans at Missouri State Parks. DNR began recruiting veterans to serve in the department in June 2017. That effort was expanded by opening additional positions to veteran recruits including Park Ranger, Park/Historic Site Specialist and maintenance classifications. In response to the initiative, the [[Missouri Department of Natural Resources]] developed a new website devoted to veteran recruitment.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.kfvs12.com/story/38063168/gov-greitens-announces-effort-to-hire-vets-for-mo-state-parks/ |publisher=[[KFVS]] |date=April 27, 2018 |title=Gov. Greitens announces effort to hire vets for MO state parks |first=James |last=Long |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Confide app ruling===\nIn December 2017, Democrats accused Greitens and senior members of his staff of subverting Missouri's open records laws after the ''[[Kansas City Star]]'' reported that they used [[Confide]], a messaging app that erases texts after they have been read, on their personal phones.<ref name=\"penchant\">{{cite news |title=Greitens' penchant for secrecy goes digital with messaging app that leaves no trace |url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article188405944.html|author=Hancock, Jason|date=December 7, 2017| work=[[Kansas City Star]]|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref> Attorney General Hawley at first claimed conflict of interest, but on December 20 announced his office would investigate, saying that the matter was legally complex because the state [[Sunshine Law]] \"was written decades and decades ago and has not been updated to take into account\" technological changes.<ref name=\"answers\">{{cite news|title=Greitens answers question about his use of secret texting app by attacking media |url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/local/news-columns-blogs/the-buzz/article189204289.html|author=Hancock, Jason|date=December 11, 2017|newspaper=[[Kansas City Star]]|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Missouri attorney general will investigate Gov. Greitens' use of secret texting app|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article190772809.html|author=Hancock, Jason|date=December 20, 2017|work =[[Kansas City Star]]|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"seeks\">{{cite news|title=New lawsuit seeks to stop Missouri governor from using secretive phone app| url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/new-lawsuit-seeks-to-stop-missouri-governor-from-using-secretive/article%E2%80%94b22e94c7-6546-5eff-a93e-43f33fa6978a.html |author=Erickson, Kurt|date=January 2, 2018|newspaper=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref> In March 2018, Hawley cleared Greitens, finding no evidence of wrongdoing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/hawley-s-office-subpoenaed-for-greitens-confide-investigation-records/article_d4ea77f9-b984-53c1-add0-a4bef6ef8ed0.html|title=Hawley's office subpoenaed for Greitens Confide investigation records|last=Suntrup|first=Jack|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn late December, two attorneys filed suit, claiming that use of such \"self-immolating\" apps by elected officials and government employees violates Missouri's public records laws.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lawsuit alleges Gov. Greitens conspired to violate Missouri open records laws |url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article192544944.html|author=Hancock, Jason|date=January 2, 2018|work=[[Kansas City Star]]|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Organization files lawsuit against Greitens over use of app |url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/national/organization-files-lawsuit-against-greitens-over-use-of-app/article_468329d1-a491-5148-bf1f-17198125f02b.html|date=January 2, 2018|newspaper=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref> On January 3, 2018, Rep. Gina Mitten filed House Bill 1817, which would ban use of apps like Confide in conducting public business, and Speaker Richardson told the ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'' that in its 2018 session the legislature might consider modernizing the state's current open records laws.<ref name=\"seeks\" />\n\nOn July 9, 2019, [[Cole County, Missouri|Cole County]] Circuit Judge Jon Beetem sided with Greitens, dismissing the claims that Greitens's office had subverted or violated any laws. Beetem also ruled that as a private citizen, Sansone cannot sue Greitens over alleged Sunshine Law violations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kshb.com/news/state/missouri/missouri-judge-sides-with-ex-gov-eric-greitens-in-lawsuit-over-message-deleting-app|title=Judge sides with ex-Gov. Greitens in Sunshine Law suit|date=July 9, 2019|website=KSHB|language=en|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Affair and invasion of privacy charge ===\nOn January 10, 2018, ahead of an investigative report released by St. Louis [[CBS]] affiliate [[KMOV]] the same evening, Greitens publicly disclosed that he had engaged in an extramarital affair with his hairstylist in 2015.<ref name=\"kmov.com\">{{cite news |url=https://www.kmov.com/news/blackmail-alleged-as-governor-greitens-admits-to-extramarital-affair/article_f4d77b48-9d65-5fbc-8511-84002622188d.html  |title=Blackmail alleged as Governor Greitens admits to extramarital affair |date=January 10, 2018 |publisher=[[KMOV]] |first1=Lauren |last1=Trager |first2=John |last2=O'Sullivan |access-date=September 18, 2019 }}</ref> Greitens and his wife issued a joint statement in which he acknowledged the affair, called it \"a deeply personal mistake\", and said that \"we dealt with this together honestly and privately.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-pol-missouri-governor-greitens-20180111-story.html|title=Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens' extramarital affair was 'the worst-kept secret in the world' |last=Pearce|first=Matt|date=January 11, 2018|work=L.A. Times|access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref> KMOV played a recording made by the hairstylist's then-husband in which she said that Greitens had invited her to his home, where she consented to having her hands taped to exercise rings above her head while she was undressed and blindfolded. In the recording, the hairstylist added that while she was blindfolded, Greitens took pictures of her without her consent and threatened to share them if she ever went public with the affair.<ref name=\"washingtonpost\">{{Cite news|first=Fred|last=Barbash|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2018/01/11/missouri-gov-eric-greitens-admits-extramarital-affair-but-denies-reports-he-blackmailed-woman/|title=Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens admits extramarital affair but denies reports he blackmailed woman with nude photo|work=[[Washington Post]] |publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|location=Washington DC|date=January 11, 2018|access-date=January 11, 2018|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\nGreitens denied the blackmail accusation.<ref name=\"washingtonpost\" /> After initially not commenting on the question, his attorney appeared to deny that any pictures were taken; in an email, he wrote, \"No violence. No picture taken. No threat of blackmail.\"<ref name=\"kmov.com\" /><ref>{{Cite news|first1=Kevin|last1=McDermott|first2=Jack |last2=Suntrup|first3=Celeste|last3=Bott|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/greitens-admits-affair-on-heels-of-television-report/article_b5f28d4d-72bd-512c-870b-da7dc7cd1fe3.html|title=Greitens admits affair, but denies allegation he blackmailed woman with photo |work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|publisher=[[Lee Enterprises]]|location=St. Louis, Missouri|date=January 11, 2018 |accessdate=February 24, 2018|quote=No violence. No picture taken. No threat of blackmail.}}</ref> Greitens also denied taking any such photos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/state-lawmaker-says-greitens-told-him-no-picture-ever-taken/article_13f90b72-a796-5cc5-a1b9-8b10f356d068.html|title=State lawmaker says Greitens told him 'no picture ever taken' of former lover|last=McDermott|first=Kevin|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=August 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter Attorney General [[Josh Hawley]]'s office said in a statement that it did not have jurisdiction to look into the matter, the [[district attorney|circuit attorney]] for the City of St. Louis opened an investigation into the blackmail allegations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fox4kc.com/2018/01/11/st-louis-circuit-attorney-launches-investigation-into-gov-greitens-following-affair-blackmail-allegations/|title=St. Louis circuit attorney launches investigation into Gov. Greitens following affair, blackmail allegations|last=Koch|first=Makenzie|date=January 11, 2018|access-date=January 11, 2018|publisher=fox4kc.com|agency=Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article194149869.html|title=Greitens faces criminal inquiry, calls for resignation after blackmail allegations|last1=Lowry|first1=Bryan|date=January 11, 2018|work=[[Kansas City Star]]|access-date=January 11, 2018|publisher=[[McClatchy Company]]|last2=Hancock|first2=Jason|location=Kansas City, Missouri}}</ref>\n\nOn January 20, 2018, [[CNN]] reported that two unnamed sources alleged that the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] was investigating Greitens. Following its usual practice, the FBI did not confirm or deny the existence of an inquiry, and the sources could not confirm whether the blackmail allegations were its focus.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Evan|last1=Perez|first2=MJ|last2=Lee|first3=Rebecca|last3=Berg|title=FBI opened inquiry into Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens|url=http://www.cnn.com/2018/01/19/politics/missouri-governor-eric-greitens-fbi-inquiry/index.html|work=[[CNN]]|date=January 19, 2018|accessdate=February 12, 2018}}</ref> In response, Greitens's attorney, Jim Bennett, said in an email that he and his colleagues had not seen any indication that an FBI investigation was underway. Bennett added that they saw nothing worthy of investigation, and that \"Governor Greitens has not been contacted at any time by the FBI and we are not aware of any interest by the FBI.\"<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news-leader.com/story/news/politics/2018/01/20/greitens-attorney-pushes-back-cnn-report-fbi-inquiry/1050784001/|title=Greitens' attorney pushes back on CNN report of FBI inquiry|last=Schmitt|first=Will|website=Springfield News-Leader|language=en|access-date=August 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n\"I have notified CNN that this story should be retracted,\" Bennett said. \"Without getting into the details, it is sufficient to say the named source has a history of profane and aberrant behavior toward people associated with Governor Greitens dating back to last year to such a degree that Governor Greitens\u2019 press secretary had to block his calls and other members of the Missouri Republican Party staff felt threatened to the degree that senior leadership attempted to intervene with his family.\" The named source was former Greitens supporter Eli Karabell.<ref name=\":20\" /> On January 20, 2018, Greitens told the AP he didn\u2019t know Karabell. Greitens\u2019s spokesman, Parker Briden, said Karabell was a \u201cserial liar\u201d who had called Briden multiple times \u201cacting crazy,\u201d including claiming he would donate millions to Greitens if he could meet with him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/4d51c51d43894faa994c71138a5bab07|title=Missouri governor: 'no blackmail,' 'no violence' in affair|last=Lieb|first=David a|last2=Ballentine|first2=Summer|date=January 20, 2018|website=AP NEWS|access-date=August 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Indictment====\nOn February 22, 2018, a St. Louis [[grand jury]] indicted Greitens on felony invasion of privacy charges.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=February 23, 2018|title=Missouri governor charged over nude photo|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-43164741|newspaper=BBC News|date=February 23, 2018}}</ref> He was released on [[personal recognizance|his own recognizance]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Missouri gov. indicted on invasion of privacy charge for allegedly taking compromising photo |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/eric-greitens-indicted-invasion-of-privacy-compromising-photo/|accessdate=February 27, 2018 |publisher=CBS News|date=February 23, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Kevin|last=Held|title=Gov. Eric Greitens indicted for invasion of privacy|url=http://fox2now.com/2018/02/22/gov-eric-greitens-indicted/|website=Fox 2 St. Louis|location=St. Louis, Missouri|date=February 22, 2018|accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref> and waived his first appearance.<ref>Joel Currier, [http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/greitens-waives-first-court-appearance-in-computer-tampering-case/article_0aa57c54-45dc-5999-ab32-473300365ca8.html Greitens waives first court appearance in computer tampering case], ''St. Louis Post-Dispatch'' (May 22, 2018).</ref> \n \nOn March 26, the judge denied defense motions to have a [[bench trial]] rather than a jury trial, refused to dismiss the assistant prosecutor, kept the jury trial date as scheduled, and refused to dismiss the indictment.<ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.nhregister.com/news/article/The-Latest-Judge-allows-charge-against-Missouri-12782763.php|title=The Latest: Judge allows charge against Missouri governor|date=March 27, 2018|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn April 9, 2018, ''Fox News'' reported that the woman with whom Greitens had the affair testified that she could not say whether she saw Greitens with a camera or phone on the day he allegedly took the photo. Court records say that the woman told prosecutors, \"I don't know if it's because I'm remembering it through a dream or I\u2014I'm not sure, but yes, I feel like I saw it after it happened, but I haven't spoken about it because of that\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/missouri-gov-greitens-ex-lover-said-illicit-photo-may-have-been-a-dream-documents-say|title=Missouri Gov. Greitens' ex-lover said illicit photo may have been 'a dream,' documents say|last=Chamberlain|first=Samuel|date=April 9, 2018|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn pre-trial depositions, William Tisaby, a former FBI agent who assisted Gardner with the Greitens investigations, affirmed to defense attorneys that he had taken notes during his interview of the woman. After attorneys pressed him to turn over the notes, he changed his testimony and asserted that he had not taken notes during the interview. Video footage, initially withheld from defense attorneys but later tendered, showed Tisaby taking notes during his interview with the woman while in Gardner's presence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/st-louis-prosecutor-s-investigator-greitens-case-charged-perjury-evidence-tampering|title=St. Louis Prosecutor's Investigator In Greitens Case Charged With Perjury, Evidence Tampering|last=Lippmann|first=Rachel|website=news.stlpublicradio.org|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 20, 2018, the circuit court attorney charged Greitens with a second felony for tampering with a computer in taking email and donor lists from The Mission Continues for fundraising purposes.<ref name=\"NewsTrib\">[http://www.newstribune.com/news/missouri/story/2018/apr/30/house-committee-release-supplemental-greitens-report/724225/ House committee investigating Greitens releases report comparing woman's testimony], ''[[Jefferson City News Tribune]]'', April 30, 2018. Retrieved May 1, 2018.</ref> The Associated Press first reported on the donor list in October 2016. Greitens initially denied using the list, but in April 2017 he acknowledged its use. Greitens said the list was provided by his then-campaign manager, but the former manager denied that.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/former-aide-says-greitens-relied-charity-donor-list-dark-money-kick-start-campaign |title=Former aide says Greitens relied on charity donor list, 'dark money' to kick-start campaign |first1=Jo |last1=Mannies |first2=Jason |last2=Rosenbaum |publisher=[[KWMU]] |date=May 9, 2018 |access-date=May 18, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n====Voluntary dismissal of criminal charges====\nBoth charges against Greitens were dropped in May 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Berg|first1=Rebecca|title=Charge dropped against Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/05/14/politics/eric-greitens-charge-dropped/index.html|work=CNN|date=May 14, 2018|accessdate=November 19, 2018}}</ref> Prosecutors withdrew the felony invasion of privacy charge on May 14, 2018, after investigators failed to find the alleged photo that formed the basis of the charge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2018/05/15/charge-against-missouri-gov-eric-greitens-is-dropped-but-prosecutors-plans-to-revisit/|title=Charge against Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens is dropped, but prosecutors plan to revisit|work=Washington Post|date=May 15, 2018|author=Samantha Schmidt}}</ref> The prosecutor's office agreed that if Greitens resigned, it would withdraw the felony charges relating to the charity email list.<ref name=\"The New York Times\">{{cite news |last1=Bosman |first1=Julie |last2=Smith |first2=Mitch |title=Gov. Eric Greitens of Missouri Resigns: 5 Takeaways |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/30/us/eric-greitens-missouri-takeaways.html |work=The New York Times |date=May 30, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Greitens resigned effective June 1, 2018.<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/embattled-missouri-gov-eric-greitens-says-he-will-resign/2018/05/29/5dc13386-6384-11e8-a69c-b944de66d9e7_story.html Embattled Missouri Governor Eric Greitens says he will resign], ''[[Washington Post]]'', Sean Sullivan, May 29, 2018. Retrieved May 30, 2018.</ref>\n\nThe circuit attorney referred the case to a special prosecutor, Jean Peters Baker of Kansas City. Baker declined to refile charges, citing the statutes of limitations and insufficient evidence.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vockrodt |first1=Steve |title=Baker declines to charge Greitens despite 'probable cause' for sexual assault |url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article212769354.html |newspaper=The Kansas City Star |accessdate=December 22, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.riverfronttimes.com/newsblog/2019/06/19/kim-gardner-cant-escape-the-shadow-of-greitens-investigation|title=Kim Gardner Can't Escape the Shadow of Greitens' Investigation|last=Wicentowski|first=Danny|website=Riverfront Times|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> ''The Kansas City Star'' confirmed that at the conclusion of Gardner's and Baker's investigations, evidence of an alleged photo was never produced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kansascity.com/opinion/editorials/article212861529.html|title=Jean Peters Baker declined to charge Greitens, but she did right by the victim|last=Sugg|first=Rich|website=kansascity|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn May 18, 2018, [[Cole County, Missouri|Cole County]] Prosecutor Mark Richardson announced he would not file any additional charges against Greitens, as suggested by Attorney General Hawley, related to how his gubernatorial campaign reported the receipt of a charity donor list used for political fundraising.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ksdk.com/article/news/local/missouri-prosecutor-says-he-wont-file-charges-against-governor-greitens/63-553896740 |title=Missouri prosecutor says he won't file charges against Governor Greitens |website=KSDK |language=en-US |access-date=May 18, 2018 |date=May 18, 2018 |agency=Associated Press }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/missouri-to-launch-special-session-on-greitens-allegations/2018/05/18/32580988-5a59-11e8-9889-07bcc1327f4b_story.html |title=Greitens won't be charged for finance report on donor list |last=Lieb|agency=Associated Press |first=David A. |date=May 18, 2018 |newspaper=Washington Post |language=en-US |access-date=May 18, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==== Special Investigative Committee report ====\nSeveral Republican members of the [[Missouri House of Representatives]] called on Greitens to resign after the allegations were made public.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Jack|last1=Suntrup|first2=Kurt|last2=Erickson|title=Missouri Republicans debate whether Greitens should stay or go|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/fourth-gop-house-member-says-greitens-should-resign/article_6838825d-5a63-5bfb-8d81-c17fb4c89ee4.html|work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|publisher=[[Lee Enterprises]]|date=January 17, 2018|accessdate=February 12, 2018}}</ref> Hawley, a Republican running for the U.S. Senate, called the situation \"very grave\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Benjamin|last=Peters |url=https://themissouritimes.com/49665/hawley-calls-situation-with-greitens-very-grave-in-fox-news-interview/|title=Hawley calls situation with Greitens 'very grave' in Fox News interview|work=The Missouri Times|publisher=Capitol Publishing Group |location=Jefferson City, Missouri|date=March 29, 2018|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> Illinois Governor [[Bruce Rauner]], a Greitens campaign contributor and ally, called on Greitens to resign.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/12/rauner-greitens-resignation-call-520858 |title=Illinois GOP governor calls for Missouri GOP governor to resign |newspaper=[[Politico]] |first=Natasha |last=Korecki |date=April 12, 2018 |access-date=April 30, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nOn April 11, 2018, a Special Investigative Committee (SIC) of the Missouri House of Representatives released an initial 24-page report detailing allegations against Greitens by the hairstylist with whom he had had an affair.<ref>{{cite report |title=Report of the Missouri House Special Investigative Committee on Oversight|publisher=Missouri House of Representatives |date=April 11, 2018}}</ref> The stylist accused him of unwanted kissing and sexual touching, violently slapping and spanking her, coercing her into performing oral sex on him, and threatening to blackmail her.<ref>{{cite news|first=John|last=Eligon |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/11/us/missouri-greitens-house-impeachment-inquiry.html|title=Sex Claims Against Missouri Governor Vividly Detailed in Report|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=New York Times Company|location=New York City|date=April 11, 2018 |accessdate=April 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Eli|last=Rosenberg |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2018/04/11/missouri-gov-eric-greitens-groped-and-initiated-unwanted-sexual-contact-with-woman-she-testifies/|title=Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens groped, hit and coerced woman into sexual contact, she testifies |work=[[Washington Post]]|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|location=Washington DC|date=April 11, 2018|accessdate=April 11, 2018}}</ref> In a four-page report issued on April 30, 2018 the SIC chair, Republican Representative Jay Barnes, said it found that the Greitens defense claims, that the woman's testimony was inconsistent, were groundless.<ref name=\"NewsTrib\" />\n\n====Impeachment session and resignation====\nOn May 3, the Missouri House and Senate collected enough signatures from members to call a special session to consider impeachment.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/05/03/politics/missouri-lawmakers-special-session-greitens-impeachment/index.html |title=Missouri lawmakers seeking special session for impeachment proceedings against Greitens |date=May 4, 2018 |first=Rebecca |last=Berg |access-date=May 5, 2018 |publisher=CNN }}</ref> House Speaker Todd Richardson, a Republican, said 29 senators and 138 House members, more than the three-fourths required in each chamber, supported convening a 30-day special session. It began on May 18, the last day of the regular session.<ref name=\"impeach\">[https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/03/eric-greitens-missouri-impeachment-special-session-568509 Missouri lawmakers agree to special session to weigh impeaching Gov. Eric Greitens], ''[[Politico]]'', Brent D. Griffiths, May 3, 2018. Retrieved May 7, 2018.</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://kcur.org/post/what-expect-during-missouri-s-special-session#stream/0 |title=Missouri's special session underway, here's what to expect |last=Griffin |first=Marshall |date=May 18, 2018 |work=[[KCUR]] |access-date=May 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn May 29, 2018, Greitens announced that he would resign effective June 1, 2018.<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\"/> The St. Louis prosecutor's office had made a deal with Greitens that if he resigned, it would withdraw the felony charges for using the veterans' charity email list in his campaign.<ref name=\"The New York Times\"/>\n\n====Aftermath====\nOn December 31, 2018, the Special Investigative Committee on Oversight that was investigating Greitens released its final report.<ref name=\"SuntrupReport\">{{cite web |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/committee-investigating-eric-greitens-releases-pages-of-documents-on-new/article_ec4525d1-f354-5729-860b-89821d75dd43.html |first=Jack |last=Suntrup |title=Committee investigating Eric Greitens releases 2,100 pages of documents on New Year's Eve |newspaper=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] |date=December 31, 2018}}</ref> The ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'' reported, \"Documents and testimony showed that Greitens ran an off-the-books gubernatorial campaign in 2014 and 2015, and lied about his campaign's acceptance of a charity donor list from the Mission Continues, a veterans charity Greitens founded in 2007.\"<ref name=\"SuntrupReport\" />\n\nOn July 18, 2019, [[KFVS-TV|KFVS]] televised an interview with Greitens about a leaked draft audit of former [[Missouri Department of Public Safety|Missouri Director of Public Safety]] Drew Juden by Democratic [[State Auditor of Missouri|State Auditor]] [[Nicole Galloway]], rumored to be planning a run for governor in 2020.<ref name=\":19\"/> Greitens can be seen leaving a building in his U.S. Navy uniform before changing clothes to speak to the station.<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kfvs12.com/2019/07/18/juden-defends-tenure-dps-draft-audits/|title=Juden defends tenure in DPS draft audits|last=Sweeney|first=Kathy|website=KFVS|access-date=July 24, 2019|date=July 18, 2019}}</ref> He appointed Juden in January 2017 as Director of Missouri Department of Public Safety. Governor [[Mike Parson]] announced that Juden would leave the department in August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2018/09/07/fired-missouri-official-takes-shots-at-parson-his-replacement/|title=Fired Missouri official takes shots at Parson, his replacement|date=September 7, 2018|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref> Shortly after the appointment of former State Patrol Superintendent Sandra Karsten as Juden's replacement, Auditor Nicole Galloway announced a departmental audit of DPS at Parson's request.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2018/11/28/galloway-to-audit-missouri-dps-directors-office-parson-and-karsten-called-for-audit/|title=Galloway to audit Missouri DPS director's office; Parson and Karsten called for audit|date=November 28, 2018|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref> KFVS's investigation found that Galloway's audit covered only Juden's time as Director.<ref name=\":19\" /> The first draft of the audit KFVS obtained alleged that Juden had taken unreported time off while Director.<ref name=\":19\" />\n\n===Final days in office===\nAt 508 days, Greitens's gubernatorial tenure is the 10th-shortest in Missouri history. Among elected governors, his tenure is the shortest of any Missouri governor since 1861, and the fourth-shortest overall (behind only [[Frederick Bates (politician)|Frederick Bates]], [[Claiborne Fox Jackson]], and [[Trusten Polk]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://editions.lib.umn.edu/smartpolitics/2018/05/31/eric-greitens-records-4th-shortest-tenure-by-an-elected-missouri-governor/|title=Eric Greitens Records 4th Shortest Tenure By An Elected Missouri Governor {{!}} Smart Politics|website=editions.lib.umn.edu|date=May 31, 2018|access-date=June 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the final days of his administration, Greitens signed 77 pieces of legislation into law. Among these was a bill that cut the corporate tax rate and changed how utility companies receive rate adjustments. He also signed a law making [[revenge porn]] illegal in Missouri. He banned lab-grown meats, provided a 5% rate reduction for utility companies, and allowed monopoly utility companies to increase fees for water services if they don't make the expected amount from utility rates. Greitens also signed bills to:\n\n* allow telephone companies to choose a different way to be taxed;\n* pare a program intended to entice developers to restore dilapidated buildings;\n* raise the minimum age to be tried as an adult from 17 to 18;\n* give state regulatory control over disposal of industrial waste;\n* codify consumer protections for Missourians to ensure they're not stuck with large bills for emergency services;\n* reclassify state workers as at-will employees;\n* allow businesses to grow and harvest hemp;\n* decrease the corporate tax rate from 6.25% to 4%; and\n* expand medicaid coverage for new mothers struggling with addiction.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erickson |first1=Kurt |title=Here are the bills Gov. Eric Greitens signed before leaving office |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/here-are-the-bills-gov-eric-greitens-signed-before-leaving/article_d2132b21-8db0-5d50-bed6-1d8ad4ec34b0.html |website=stltoday.com |publisher=St Louis Post-Dispatch |accessdate=November 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nGreitens also issued four commutations and five pardons.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greenwald |first1=Dan |title=Greitens issues several pardons and commutations on final day in office |url=https://www.kmov.com/news/greitens-issues-several-pardons-and-commutations-on-final-day-in/article_75ee3711-21e0-567c-a3bc-53ffe34db35e.html |website=kmov.com |publisher=KMOV4 |accessdate=November 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Pardon of Judy Henderson ====\nOn December 20, 2017, Judy Henderson was released from the Chillicothe Correctional Center in northwest Missouri after 35 years on Greitens's orders.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/nation-world/article215228235.html|title='I've not really talked about it.' Judy Henderson revisits Klein murder on crime show|last=Gutierrez|first=Lisa|date=July 21, 2018|website=The Kansas City Star|access-date=}}</ref> Greitens went to Chillicothe to meet with Henderson and sign the papers commuting her life sentence for her role in the July 1981 robbery-turned-murder of jeweler Harry Klein. Greitens's office said that Henderson could have been out of prison decades earlier.<ref name=\":17\" /> Following her release, the 68-year-old Henderson gave her version of the events on \"''The Real Story with [[Mar\u00eda Elena Salinas]]''.\"<ref name=\":17\" /> Authorities believe her boyfriend, Greg Cruzen, shot Klein and paid four witnesses to lie about Henderson's role, according to the ''[[Springfield News-Leader]]''.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news-leader.com/story/news/crime/2018/06/06/springfield-judy-henderson-eric-greitens-pardon-prison-release/559819002/|title=Eric Greitens still has fans, like the Springfield woman he pardoned after 35 years in prison|website=Springfield News-Leader|language=en|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref> At trial, Henderson and Cruzen were represented by the same defense attorney. \"I remember Jimmy McMullin, the attorney, telling us to not say a word, not to talk to anyone about anything. I was so confused, I felt like we were both going to be O.K. That's what Greg kept telling me,\" she told Salinas. Henderson claims she wanted to take the stand to defend herself \"but Jimmy McMullin said I cannot, and I did not know what my defense was until every witness walked in the courtroom and I would tell Jimmy when they would come in, I said, 'Who are they and why are they here?'\" She was found guilty. Cruzen was acquitted.<ref name=\":17\" />\n\nGreitens's office said it reviewed thousands of documents related to the case before Greitens commuted her sentence and subsequently pardoned her. She told the ''News-Leader'' that Greitens called her on his last day in office to tell her she was pardoned. \"The loss of a life and the pain that it caused his family is something that will stick with me for the rest of my life,\" Henderson said in June 2018.<ref name=\":18\" />\n\n===Appointment of special prosecutor to investigate St. Louis Circuit Attorney===\nFollowing the dismissal of all charges against Greitens, his defense attorneys filed a police report with the [[Metropolitan Police Department, City of St. Louis|St. Louis Metropolitan Police Department]] alleging criminal misconduct by Gardner's office in his case.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/stlouis/news/2018/05/15/greitens-lawyers-to-file-police-report-accusing.html|newspaper=St. Louis Business Journal|access-date=July 2, 2019|title=Greitens' lawyers to file police report accusing former lead investigator of perjury |date=May 15, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nOn June 29, 2018, St. Louis Circuit Judge Michael Mullen appointed Gerard Carmody as special prosecutor to investigate the alleged misconduct by Gardner's office.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kbia.org/post/special-prosecutor-appointed-william-tisaby-investigation|title=Special prosecutor appointed in William Tisaby investigation|last=Lippmann|first=Rachel|website=kbia.org|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/greitens-investigator-s-deposition-reveals-confrontation-confusion-but-did-he/article_a7250df9-7baa-5c9f-8e91-248406678286.html|title=Greitens investigator's deposition reveals confrontation, confusion. But did he commit perjury?|last=Currier|first=Robert Patrick, Joel|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> On June 17, 2019, a 7-count felony indictment of William Tisaby was unsealed. Tisaby had been charged with six counts of felony perjury and one count of felony tampering with evidence.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article231646258.html|title=Former FBI agent who investigated Greitens indicted for perjury, evidence tampering|last=By|website=kansascity|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> According to the ''St. Louis Post-Dispatch'', the 30-page indictment accused Tisaby of concealing a series of documents from defense attorneys and lying under oath during the deposition \u201cabout matters that could substantially affect, or did substantially affect, the course or outcome of the Greitens case.\"<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/former-fbi-agent-who-investigated-greitens-indicted-in-st-louis/article_147c2a69-b36e-5822-8e8c-e81ac81cfdf7.html|title=Former FBI agent who investigated Greitens indicted in St. Louis as part of perjury investigation|last=Patrick|first=Joel Currier, Robert|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> ''The Associated Press'' reported that Tisaby surrendered to authorities on the same day the indictment against him was unsealed. He pleaded not guilty at his arraignment and was released on his own recognizance on the conditions that he surrender his passport and inform a probation officer of any travel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/8172e48bb5f74427a315ab8322542338|title=Former Greitens' investigator indicted on 7 felonies|last=Hollingsworth|first=Heather|date=2019-06-17|website=AP NEWS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> In a press conference following Tisaby's release from custody on June 17, 2018, Tisaby's attorney, Jermaine Wooten, told reporters that \u201cMs. Gardner is probably the actual target here, not Mr. Tisaby.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox2now.com/2019/06/18/attorney-gardner-is-probably-the-actual-target-here-not-mr-tisaby/|title=Attorney: 'Gardner is probably the actual target here, not Mr. Tisaby'|date=June 18, 2019|website=FOX2now.com|language=en|access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe indictment also lodged a series of claims against Gardner, stating \"that she failed to correct Tisaby\u2019s lies, failed to report them to police, and made incorrect statements to defense lawyers and the judge.\" The alleged misconduct in the unsuccessful prosecution of Greitens has placed Gardner at risk of losing her law license and facing criminal charges.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nOn July 10, 2019, the grand jury that indicted Tisaby disbanded without any other indictments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/grand-jury-disbands-without-charging-st-louis-circuit-attorney/article_e0894ff8-d44d-553c-8cb6-7822076aa626.html|title=Grand jury disbands without charging St. Louis Circuit Attorney|last=Currier|first=Joel|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref> The next day, Gardner held a press conference outside the St. Louis Circuit Attorney's Office denying any wrongdoing in Greitens's case. The press conference marked Gardner's first public statement on the matter since the appointment of the special prosecutor, as a gag order had been placed on the case for the duration of the grand jury. Fox 2 Now reported that Gardner claimed that it was time for the city to \"move on\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox2now.com/2019/07/11/after-grand-jury-term-ends-gardner-says-its-time-for-the-city-to-move-on/|title=After grand jury term ends, Gardner says it's time for the city to move on|date=July 11, 2019|website=FOX2now.com|language=en|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref> Following the press conference, Carmody took the unusual step of putting out a statement clarifying that the grand jury disbanded not because the investigation was complete but because it had reached its expiration and its term could not be extended.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://molawyersmedia.com/2019/07/16/investigation-involving-st-louis-prosecutor-kimberly-gardner-is-ongoing-2/|title=Investigation involving St. Louis prosecutor Kimberly Gardner is ongoing|last=Salter|first=Jim|date=July 16, 2019|website=Missouri Lawyers Media|language=en-US|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref> \u201cNotwithstanding the expiration of that Grand Jury\u2019s term, the investigation into possible criminal activity will continue,\u201d Carmody said in the statement.<ref name=\":16\" />\n\nDuring an August 15, 2019 hearing, Carmody said the ongoing probe was focused on the failed prosecution of Greitens and confirmed that Gardner was under \"active criminal investigation.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ksdk.com/article/news/local/criminal-investigation-into-failed-prosecution-of-former-missouri-governor-eric-greitens-remains-active/63-a23813c9-e272-4f63-b918-5f918214bc43|title=Criminal investigation into failed prosecution of former Missouri Governor Eric Greitens remains 'active'|website=KSDK|access-date=August 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation and conclusion==\n\nIn February 2020, after a nearly 18-month investigation into Greitens's 2016 gubernatorial campaign, the Missouri Ethics Commission (MEC) \"found no evidence of any wrongdoing\" by him, but required the campaign to update its reports with in-kind contributions from two groups, and to pay the commission about $178,000 in fees. In a statement, Greitens called the result an exoneration and vindication.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/13/politics/eric-greitens-no-wrongdoing-investigation-missouri/index.html |title=Investigation into former Missouri governor who resigned finds 'no evidence of any wrongdoing' |date=February 13, 2020 |first=Rebecca |last=Buck |publisher=CNN |access-date=February 14, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://krcgtv.com/news/local/no-evidence-of-any-wrongdoing-former-gov-eric-greitens-fully-exonerated|title=UPDATE: State ethics fines Greitens campaign $178,000 for failing to report contributions|date=February 13, 2020|publisher=KRCG|access-date=February 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nGreitens spoke publicly for the first time since his resignation with [[KTVI|Fox 2 St. Louis]]' Chris Hayes on February 13, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox4kc.com/news/no-evidence-of-any-wrongdoing-former-governor-eric-greitens-fully-exonerated-of-campaign-misconduct/|title='No evidence of any wrongdoing': Former Gov. Eric Greitens fully exonerated, campaign to pay $38k|date=February 13, 2020|website=FOX 4 Kansas City WDAF-TV {{!}} News, Weather, Sports|language=en-US|access-date=February 24, 2020}}</ref> Greitens claimed that the investigation was a result of \"false allegations made by a lawyer politician,\" presumably former State Rep. Jay Barnes, who filed the complaint. Barnes served as the Chairman of the Missouri House Special Committee on Oversight responsible for investigating the allegations against Greitens. Barnes publicly accused Greitens of running a \"criminal enterprise\" and of having committed \"literary fraud\" relating to Greitens' best-selling book, ''Resilience''. The MEC found no evidence to support Barnes' claims.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox2now.com/2020/02/13/were-fighting-back-eric-greitens-on-new-ethics-report-on-his-campaign/|title='We're fighting back' \u2013 Eric Greitens on new ethics report on his campaign|date=February 14, 2020|website=FOX2now.com|language=en|access-date=February 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn February 20, 2020, Greitens appeared on several radio shows to discuss a resolution introduced in the [[Missouri House of Representatives|Missouri House]] by Rep. Justin Hill calling on [[United States Attorney General|U.S. Attorney General]] [[William Barr]] and the [[Department of Justice]] to investigate several cash payments totaling $120,000 paid to witnesses in the Greitens case in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://971talk.radio.com/blogs/the-marc-cox-morning-show/former-missouri-governor-eric-greitens-on-federal-investigat|title=Greitens endorses call for federal investigation|date=February 20, 2020|website=FM NewsTalk 97.1|language=en|access-date=February 24, 2020}}</ref>  Hill, a former police officer with experience on a DEA task force responsible for large currency investigations, appeared on The Marc Cox Show prior to Greitens. Hill characterized the cash payments delivered by convicted felon and Missouri journalist Scott Faughn as a \"criminal effort to un-elect a duly elected Governor.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://971talk.radio.com/blogs/the-marc-cox-morning-show/missouri-rep-justin-hill-on-governor-eric-greitens|title=Rep Justin Hill wants AG Barr to investigate the Greitens take down|date=February 19, 2020|website=FM NewsTalk 97.1|language=en|access-date=February 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Post-gubernatorial career==\nOn June 2, 2019, the ''St. Louis Post-Dispatch'' reported that Greitens had returned to the U.S. Navy as a Naval Reserve Officer. Since leaving office, he has worked on a book about his Jewish faith.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/getting-his-sea-legs-back-after-resigning-from-office-greitens/article_0b797d35-842b-56aa-ad2f-77f046890dd4.html|title='Getting his sea legs back.' After resigning from office, Greitens tries to steady his life \u2014 in private|last=Suntrup|first=Kurt Erickson, Jack|website=stltoday.com|language=en|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== COVID-19 Response ====\nDuring a [[Fox News]] interview on [[America's Newsroom]], Greitens called the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] outbreak a \"serious issue\" and said that \"fear is also contagious\", calling for a level-headed response from elected officials.<ref>{{Citation|title=America's Newsroom|url=https://www.facebook.com/EricGreitens/videos/1396498820558747/|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, 2020, Greitens solicited donations and then purchased $80,000 worth of [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE) for first responders in the [[Greater St. Louis|St. Louis]], [[Kansas City metropolitan area|Kansas City]], and [[St. Joseph, Missouri|St. Joseph]] areas. He provided nearly 15,000 protective masks to numerous agencies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kmox.radio.com/articles/news/former-gov-eric-greitens-delivers-masks-to-first-responders|title=Former Gov. Eric Greitens delivers $80,000 protective masks to St. Louis first responders|date=2020-03-30|website=KMOX-AM|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox2now.com/news/missouri/former-missouri-governor-gets-donors-to-raise-money-for-masks-for-first-responders/|title=Former Missouri governor gets donors to raise money for masks for first responders|date=2020-03-30|website=FOX2now.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Sheena Greitens.jpg|thumb|upright|Sheena Greitens in 2017]]\n[[File:Inauguration of Eric Greitens 12.jpg|thumb|Eric and Sheena Greitens dancing at the inaugural ball]]\nGreitens's marriage to his first wife ended in divorce in 2003.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article194096374.html|title=Gov. Greitens admits to extramarital affair, denies threatening to blackmail the woman|work=The Kansas City Star|date=January 10, 2018|first=Jason|last=Hancock|access-date=January 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe married Sheena Elise Chestnut on August 7, 2011, in [[Spokane, Washington]],<ref name=\"nyt1\" /> and they have two sons.<ref name=\"MizzStateU\">[http://publicaffairs.missouristate.edu/Convocation/Eric-Greitens.htm 2014 Convocation Lecture] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220191705/http://publicaffairs.missouristate.edu/Convocation/Eric-Greitens.htm |date=February 20, 2015 }} February 16, 2015</ref><ref>Hollerman, Joe [http://www.stltoday.com/lifestyles/columns/joe-holleman/stl-s-eric-greitens-steps-down-as-veterans-group-chief/article_1efe6a36-7515-5ac0-bd7d-8fc111c83c55.html STL's Eric Greitens steps down as veterans group chief], ''St. Louis Post-Dispatch'', February 16, 2015.</ref><ref name=\"nyt1\" /> Sheena Greitens is an [[assistant professor]] of [[political science]] at the [[University of Missouri]], focused primarily on China and North Korea.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ksl.com/article/46234810 |title=Missouri governor admits having affair but denies blackmail |first1=Summer |last1=Ballentine |first2=Jim |last2=Salter |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=January 11, 2018 |access-date=February 28, 2019 |website=[[KSL.com]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Greitens had an extramarital affair with his hairstylist.<ref name=\"kmov.com\"/>\n\nThe first Jewish governor of Missouri, Greitens attends the Reform B\u2019nai El synagogue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/meet-the-first-jewish-governor-of-missouri-a-former-navy-seal/|title=Meet the first Jewish governor of Missouri, a former Navy SEAL|last=Friedman|first=Gabe|website=timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stljewishlight.com/news/local/q-a-with-eric-greitens-who-will-be-first-jewish/article_2201014b-2727-5f86-b345-130fa9837055.html|title=Q&A with Eric Greitens, who will be first Jewish governor of Missouri|last=JTA|first=Gabe Friedman|website=St. Louis Jewish Light|language=en|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, before Greitens took office, Sheena Greitens was robbed at gunpoint at a St. Louis-area coffee shop. She was unharmed. Three suspects, ages 14, 15 and 19, were arrested a short time later. Eric Greitens said at the time that he was glad \u201cthe men and women of law enforcement found these young men before I did.\u201d<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/4416854ada4f4957ba61e514b8ede13c|title=3 in custody in robbery of wife of Missouri governor-elect|last=Salter|first=Jim|date=2016-12-06|website=AP News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> After the incident, [[Missouri State Highway Patrol]] Captain John Hotz said the patrol would begin providing security for Sheena Greitens. The patrol provided security for the governor-elect immediately after the election, but Hotz said security detail for the spouse typically begins only after a governor takes office.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n==Honors and awards==\nOn October 3, 2008, [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush]] awarded Greitens the [[President's Volunteer Service Award]] outside [[Air Force One]] at [[Lambert International Airport]] in St. Louis, Missouri, for his work at [[The Mission Continues]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/greitens-said-it-memorable-quotes-that-marked-his-candidacy-governorship/article_aa4c6678-2482-56ff-af43-c7c13ec8cfe4.html |title=Greitens said it: Memorable quotes that marked his candidacy, governorship |date=June 1, 2018 |newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |access-date=February 28, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://latimesblogs.latimes.com/washington/2009/01/post-1.html |title=Who were those unfamiliar audience faces at Bush's farewell address? |date=January 15, 2009 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |access-date=February 28, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Greitens received the HOOAH Award, commissioned by the Major George A. Smith Memorial Fund and presented by the [[National Conference on Citizenship]] to recognize \"a notable veteran who defines their citizenship through service to our country\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncoc.net/index.php?tray=content&tid=top45&cid=2kc27|title=Presentation of the HOOAH Award to Lt. Eric Greitens |publisher=[[National Conference on Citizenship]]|access-date=April 28, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100929060411/http://www.ncoc.net/index.php?tray=content&tid=top45&cid=2kc27 |archive-date=September 29, 2010 |date=October 2, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.slideshare.net/civicvoice/ncoc-event-program-2009 |title=Event Program: HOOAH Award |date=September 9, 2009 |publisher=[[National Conference on Citizenship]] |at=slide 5 |via=[[SlideShare]] |access-date=February 28, 2019 }}</ref> He was also named the 2010 Reader of the Year by ''[[Outside (magazine)|Outside]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nyberg|first=Justin|url=http://outsideonline.com/outside/culture/200912/altruism-all-stars-eric-greitens.html|title=Adventure Altruism All-Stars|work =Outside Online |date=December 3, 2009|accessdate=April 28, 2014 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110507012215/http://outsideonline.com/outside/culture/200912/altruism-all-stars-eric-greitens.html|archivedate=May 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=Sam|last1=Moulton|first2=Kyle|last2=Dickman|first3=Justin |last3=Nyberg|first4=Ryan|last4=Krogh|first5=Abe|last5=Streep|url=http://www.outsideonline.com/1874971/adventure-altruism-all-stars |title=Adventure Altruism All-Stars|work=[[outside (magazine)|Outside Online]]|publisher=Mariah Media|location=Santa Fe, New Mexico |date=December 2, 2009|accessdate=May 24, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2010, [[Major League Baseball]] and ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' announced Greitens as a winner in ''People's All-Stars Among Us'' competition. He was selected to represent the city of St. Louis and the Cardinals at the 2010 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] in [[Anaheim, California]].<ref>[http://newyork.yankees.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20100601&content_id=10674702&vkey=pr_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl \"MLB, ''PEOPLE'' Magazine & Cardinals announce three finalists for 'People All-Stars Among Us' national campaign\"], New York Yankees, June 1, 2010.</ref><ref>[http://mlb.mlb.com/peopleallstarsamongus \"People All-Stars Among Us\"], MLB.com, June 20, 2010.</ref>\n\nOn May 20, 2012, Greitens was awarded an honorary Doctor of Humane Letters degree from [[Tufts University]] when he gave the commencement speech at the school's 156th commencement.<ref>[http://now.tufts.edu/articles/meaningful-adventure \"A Meaningful Adventure\"], Tufts University, May 20, 2012.</ref> That same year he received the Bronfman Prize, which recognizes dynamic leaders whose innovation and impact serve as inspiration for the next generations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecharlesbronfmanprize.com/recipients/2012-eric-greitens|title=Eric Greitens profile|work=Charles Bronfman Prize|date=February 16, 2015|accessdate=April 11, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807065905/http://thecharlesbronfmanprize.com/recipients/2012-eric-greitens|archive-date=August 7, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn April 18, 2013, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' named Greitens to its list of the 100 Most Influential People in the World.<ref name=TIME>{{cite magazine|first=Mike|last=Mullen|url=http://time100.time.com/2013/04/18/time-100/slide/eric-greitens|title=The 2013 TIME 100: Eric Greitens|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|location=New York City|date=February 18, 2015 |accessdate=April 11, 2018}}</ref> In 2014 ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' featured him as one of the World's 50 Greatest Leaders.<ref>{{cite web|first=Geoff|last=Colvin|url=http://money.cnn.com/gallery/leadership/2014/03/20/worlds-best-leaders.fortune/38.html|title=Eric Greitens - Fortune ranks the World's 50 Greatest Leaders|work=[[CNNMoney]]|publisher=[[CNN]] |date=March 20, 2014|accessdate=April 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Military award ribbons and badges ===\n\n[[File:United_States_Navy_Special_Warfare_insignia.png|200x200px]]\n\n[[File:United_States_Navy_Parachutist_Badge.png|200x200px]]\n\n[[File:NavySmallBoatOfficerPin.jpg|alt=|100x100px]]\n\n[[File:Bronze_Star_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Bronze Star Medal]]\n\n[[File:Purple_Heart_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Purple Heart]]\n\n[[File:Joint_Service_Commendation_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Commendation Medal|Joint Service Commendation Medal]]\n\n[[File:Navy_and_Marine_Corps_Commendation_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Commendation Medal|Navy and Marine Corps Commendation Medal]]\n\n[[File:Combat_Action_Ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Combat Action Ribbon|Navy Combat Action Ribbon]]\n\n[[File:Us_jointservachiev_rib.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Achievement Medal|Joint Service Achievement Medal]]\n\n[[File:Navy_and_Marine_Corps_Achievement_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Achievement Medal|Navy and Marine Corps Achievement Medal]]\n\n[[File:National_Defense_Service_Medal_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[National Defense Service Medal]]\n\n[[File:Afghanistan_Campaign_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Afghanistan Campaign Medal]]\n\n[[File:Iraq_Campaign_Medal_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Iraq Campaign Medal]]\n\n[[File:Global_War_on_Terrorism_Expeditionary_Medal_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary Medal]]\n\n[[File:Global_War_on_Terrorism_Service_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]]\n\n[[File:Sea_Service_Deployment_Ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Sea Service Deployment Ribbon|Navy Sea Service Deployment Ribbon]]\n\n[[File:ResMedRib.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Armed Forces Reserve Medal]]\n\n[[File:Outstanding_Volunteer_Service_ribbon.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Military Outstanding Volunteer Service Medal|Outstanding Volunteer Service Medal]]\n\n[[File:United_States_Navy_Rifle_Marksmanship_Ribbon_with_expert_device.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Marksmanship Medal|Navy Expert Rifleman Medal]]\n\n[[File:United_States_Navy_Pistol_Marksmanship_Ribbon_with_expert_device.svg|border|55x55px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Marksmanship Medal|Navy Expert Pistol Shot Medal]]\n\n==Publications==\n*{{cite thesis|type=AB|last=Greitens|first=Eric R.|date=1996|title=On Courage|publisher=Duke University|degree=|url=https://find.library.duke.edu/catalog/DUKE002133696|doi=}}\n*{{cite thesis|type=M.Phil|last=Greitens|first=Eric R.|date=1998|title=Intervening on Behalf of Children in War: Challenges for Humanitarian Assistance|publisher=Oxford University|degree=|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Intervening_on_Behalf_of_Children_in_War.html?id=-qhEPAAACAAJ|doi=}}\n*{{cite thesis|type=PhD|last=Greitens|first=Eric R.|date=2000|title=Children First: Ideas and the Dynamics of Aid in Western Voluntary Assistance Programs for War-Affected Children Abroad|publisher=Oxford University|degree=|url=https://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?uin=uk.bl.ethos.365669|doi=}}\n*{{Cite book| last=Greitens| first=Eric|title=Strength & Compassion: Photographs and Essays|publisher=Leading Authorities Press|year=2008|isbn=978-0971007802}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Greitens|first=Eric|title=The Heart and the Fist: The Education of a Humanitarian, the Making of a Navy SEAL|publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]]|year=2011|isbn=978-0547424859|ref=harv|location=New York|url=https://archive.org/details/heartfisteducati0000grei|url-access=registration}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Greitens|first=Eric|title=The Warrior's Heart: Becoming a Man of Compassion and Courage|publisher=[[HMH Books for Young Readers]]|year=2012|isbn=978-0547868523|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/warriorsheartbec0000grei}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Greitens|first=Eric|title=Resilience: Hard-Won Wisdom for Living a Better Life|publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]]|year=2015|isbn=978-0544323988|title-link=Resilience: Hard-Won Wisdom for Living a Better Life}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{C-SPAN|ericgreitens}}\n* {{Charlie Rose view|15618}}\n* {{Worldcat id|lccn-n2008-39452}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dave Spence]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[Governor of Missouri]]|years=[[2016 Missouri gubernatorial election|2016]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jay Nixon]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Governors of Missouri|Governor of Missouri]]|years=2017\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mike Parson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of Missouri}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Politics|War}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Greitens, Eric}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American male taekwondo practitioners]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:American military writers]]\n[[Category:American Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:Angier B. Duke Scholars]]\n[[Category:Duke University alumni]]\n[[Category:Governors of Missouri]]\n[[Category:Jewish American military personnel]]\n[[Category:Jewish American state governors of the United States